<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS' CHANGE REFLECTS LAVIN'S
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA has won five consecutive Pacific-10
basketball games for the first time since 1997, when it won eight
straight and the conference title.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins believe their success, now as then, reflects coach
Steve Lavin's attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last few weeks, his demeanor has been as close to 1997 as
it's been in four years,'' assistant coach Michael Holton said.
``It's his demeanor in practice more than anything, his firmness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no coincidence that the players have responded. Coach
Lavin has been extremely firm in what he's demanded of them. And
when I think back to '97, what I remember was his heavy hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Lavin hasn't noticed a change in his demeanor, but he did
acknowledge a different approach. Because the Bruins finally
understand the new offense, he's explaining less and demanding
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going at a faster clip in practice,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Earl Watson noticed a difference in Lavin after the
disastrous weekend in Arizona, when the Bruins lost two games by 44
points.
</P>
<P>
   They haven't lost since.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way coach has managed practice has been amazing the last
couple weeks,'' Watson said. ``It's his control of practice. He's
definitely been firmer. There's been a lot of discipline. The
transition from drill-to-drill is amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   The goodbye guy: The Bruins will honor their lone senior,
forward Sean Farnham, during today's season finale against
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Long a fan favorite, Farnham is averaging 1.4 points and 1.3
rebounds, but statistics have never been his thing. Instead, he'll
be remembered for his indefatigable spirit, charm and work ethic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have a lot of emotions, obviously,'' he said. ``It'll bea
great day and a sad day. It'll be everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing is that I'm leaving on a higher note than it
looked like I would three weeks ago,'' when postseason prospects
were dim.
</P>
<P>
   Most likely, Farnham will start today: in the last two years,
the Bruins are 13-1 with him in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Prime material: Forever in search of perspective, Lavin listed
all the national upsets on the greaseboard in UCLA's lockerroom -
South Carolina over Tennessee, Penn State over Ohio State,
Georgetown over Syracuse - and then warned the Bruins that they are
not immune.
</P>
<P>
   ``I showed them that's what can happen when one team is
physically and mentally fatigued and the (underdog) is loose and
relaxed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One upset meant more to Lavin than any other: St. Louis over
Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   The Billikens are coached by Lorenzo Romar, the former UCLA
assistant and Pepperdine boss and a longtime friend to many
involved with the Bruins basketball program. ``It's great,'' Lavin
said. ``I've left Lorenzo a couple voice-mail messages, one after
their first-round game and one after Cincinnati.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis beat Tulane on Friday and is one victory from the
Conference USA title and an NCAA bid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
