<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS AND NOTES FROM AROUND THE NATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS first item to report Gore's planned meeting with Ventura.)  
 (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE DEMOCRATS
</P>
<P>
   GORE ON THE TRAIL
</P>
<P>
   In his continuing effort to woo independent voters, Vice
President Al Gore was planning to meet in Minneapolis on Saturday
morning with Jesse Ventura, the very independent governor of
Minnesota. Gore, who campaigned Friday night in Bloomington, Minn.,
picked up the endorsement of Sen. Paul Wellstone, the Minnesota
Democrat who had supported former Sen. Bill Bradley. Gore called
Ventura on Air Force II on his way to Minnesota to line up the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, in a speech in Albany, N.Y., Gore gave a
glimpse of his coming campaign against the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't let those Confederate-flag-waving, Bob-Jones-embracing,
right-wing extremists divide us!'' Gore called out as he addressed
Puerto Rican and Hispanic members of the state Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Delivering much of his speech in Spanish, he added: ``We are the
party of hope, not anger or exclusion. We are the party of the
people, and not the powerful. We're the party of the future and not
the past.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH CAROLINA CAUCUS
</P>
<P>
   A few hours after Bill Bradley dropped out of the Democratic
presidential race Thursday, 172 people who deeply admired him
showed up at the party caucuses in South Carolina to give him their
votes. The display of die-hard loyalty was not quite enough,
however, to counterbalance the 8,864 people who voted for Vice
President Al Gore in a preview of one-sided primaries to come. Even
before Bradley quit, the Democratic caucuses had already been
declared essentially irrelevant, in comparison with the hotly
contested Republican primary in February that drew a record 573,000
voters.
</P>
<P>
   THE VOTERS
</P>
<P>
   YOUTH CONVENTION
</P>
<P>
   Before Philadelphia plays host to the Republicans this summer, a
less well-publicized convention will be held there.
</P>
<P>
   In April the Generation X convention, a nonpartisan meeting of
voters ages 18 to 35, will consider issues like Social Security,
the environment, and First Amendment rights and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting will be sponsored by the Foundation for Individual
Responsibility and Social Trust, a nonprofit group that promotes
civic engagement among younger people. The foundation has extended
invitations to all the presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're really trying to court the young vote,''
Melinda Scott, 29, the associate director of the foundation, said
of the candidates. ``We're the swing vote.''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting will be held at the University of Pennsylvania and
Drexel University April 14 to 16, and the foundation is hoping that
1,000 people will attend. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS
</P>
<P>
   CANDIDATE COMEDY
</P>
<P>
   It's Alan Keyes? The voluble Keyes, the lone remaining
challenger to Gov. George W. Bush for the Republican presidential
nomination, is set to appear in a skit on ``Saturday Night Live''
this weekend, say aides and NBC officials. The details of the skit
are closely held and are still subject to last-minute negotiations.
But Connie Hair, a spokeswoman for Keyes, said that he would appear
on the ``Weekend Update'' segment of the show and planned to make
``merciless fun'' of the media.
</P>
<P>
   THE HOUSE
</P>
<P>
   GUNS AND MONEY
</P>
<P>
   Mark Detro, one of six Republican candidates in Oklahoma's 2nd
Congressional District race, wants to run a ``pro-gun donation
drive'' to raise campaign money and increase public awareness about
the right to bear arms. Campaign contributors would participate in
a lottery for two Ruger firearms donated by a gun broker.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be a few bad apples,'' Detro, 32, said, ``but the
way the media distorts some of the school shootings and always
looks at the worst-case scenario, you'd never know that 99 percent
of the gun owners in America are law-abiding citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Federal Elections Commission approved the plan, he
says, Oklahoma state officials have objected because of the state's
anti-gambling laws. ``We're trying to work something out with them
now,'' Detro said. He said that about 25 people had called since he
announced the lottery, asking how to send checks to his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   THIS WEEKEND'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: Saturday: Austin, Texas Sunday: Plant City,
Fla., and Knoxville, Tenn. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: Saturday: Minneapolis, Chicago and Houston. Sunday:
Houston, Dallas and Miami.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
