<SLUG> BC-RAMPART-STATS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GANG-RELATED CRIMES RISE IN POST-SCANDAL RAMPART DISTRICT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG GITTRICH  
 and BETH BARRETT 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; L &LR; OS ANGELES _ With the Los Angeles Police Department's
Rampart Division crippled by scandal, gang violence on the streets
around the station house has soared - nearly 40 percent during this
year's first two months.
</P>
<P>
   Graffiti and other signs of street thuggery also have been
creeping back into the community, undermining a long-fought battle
against the notorious 18th Street gang, whose members were the
targets of many of the abuses allegedly committed by officers in
the anti-gang CRASH (Community Resources Against Street Hoodlums)
unit.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the disturbing rise in gang crime in the low-income
community located between Hollywood and downtown is directly linked
to the scandal and the city's related decision to suspend gang
injunctions is the subject of debate in law enforcement circles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be a blip, or it could be that gang members are being
more brazen since the injunctions have been lifted,'' said LAPD
Capt. Robert Hansohn. ``It also could be some gang fight beneath
the surface.''
</P>
<P>
   Hansohn was put in charge of the division in August 1998, two
weeks before Internal Affairs investigators arrested rogue cop
Rafael Perez at the station house for stealing eight pounds of
cocaine from the evidence room.
</P>
<P>
   Perez has told investigators that he and other dirty cops shot a
suspect, planted drugs and guns on several suspects and repeatedly
committed perjury to send innocent people to jail. The
vigilante-style law enforcement tactics led to a large number of
arrests and intimidated those in the neighborhood, at least
partially contributing to the fall in crime.
</P>
<P>
   At his sentencing hearing last month, Perez explained: ``The
lines between right and wrong became fuzzy and indistinct. The 'us'
against 'them' ethos of the overzealous cop began to consume me and
the ends seemed to justify the means.''
</P>
<P>
   The rogue actions by Perez and other officers he has implicated
forced the suspension of gang injunctions, a major tool used by the
LAPD to fight gang-related crime.
</P>
<P>
   The Rampart anti-gang CRASH officers had provided sworn
declarations used in court by the City Attorney's Office to get
injunctions imposed to limit the activities of local street thugs.
With the cops' credibility undermined, the city had no choice but
to suspend the injunctions last year. One injunction had been in
place since August 1997; another since June 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Since the two injunctions were lifted, gang-related violent
crimes - which include homicides, rapes, assaults, kidnapping,
robbery, witness intimidation, extortion and carjacking - have
jumped noticeably.
</P>
<P>
   Through last month, 151 gang-related violent crimes were
recorded by police, compared with 108 for the same period last year
- a 39.8 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``It points out that gang injunctions work. They are very
effective,'' said City Attorney Jim Hahn, who has spearheaded the
implementation of 11 gang injunctions across the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``As this investigation continues, we are still not in a place
where we could say which declarations can be relied on. It may be a
few more months. Injunctions are a tool ... Other methods are
available to suppress gang crimes. This is by no means a green
light for gang activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Ted Hunt, president of the Police Protective League, predicted
gang-related crime will continue to rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the sanctions were lifted, the gang members who
terrorized the community before now feel they've been given the
green light to go back and terrorize people - and it's going to get
worse,'' the union leader said.
</P>
<P>
   Under increased pressure to prevent problems similar to those
that poisoned the Rampart Division, LAPD Chief Bernard C. Parks has
ordered the city's elite anti-gang Community Resources Against
Street Hoodlums units to be disbanded Sunday. Officers will be
reassigned to patrol details for the next month, and gang details
will be reorganized within normal patrol units.
</P>
<P>
   With many officers in the Rampart CRASH unit under investigation
and on administrative leave, the division's patrol officers have
faced the fallout of the scandal on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (problem) people are gone, but people still want to focus
on the station,'' said Sgt. S. Britt-Nickerson, driving her black
and white police car past a television camera crew, a common sight
in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to deal with the aftermath. It's hard. The bad element
in Rampart is really using this to their advantage, they're being
more brazen than they would have been.''
</P>
<P>
   Without the injunctions, gang members from outside Rampart are
beginning to return to the neighborhood, she said. If suspects are
arrested, many are emboldened to threaten officers with false
claims, such as evidence-planting.
</P>
<P>
   And while the new crop of Rampart officers prides itself on
doing a professional job, Hansohn and other officers said the
scandal might have made some officers overly cautious.
</P>
<P>
   Still, during the first week of March, the division led the
department in arrests, Hansohn said.
</P>
<P>
   Detective Danny Burzumato said it's common now for suspects to
say, ``I know you're from Rampart, so I won't get convicted.''
</P>
<P>
   The rising gang violence statistics underscore the need for good
police work that prioritizes problems, Hansohn said. The captain
added that throughout the scandal the community generally has
backed the police.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are in tune,'' Hansohn said. ``It's bothersome to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Several people interviewed in the community, the most crowded in
the city, said they were concerned about the possibility of
increased gang activity but had not seen evidence of it in their
own lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hard problem,'' said David Lopez, who assembles
vertical blinds in a shop near the Rampart station on Temple
Street.
</P>
<P>
   After a pause, Lopez said: ``You have to look at the future.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
