<SLUG> BC-HEASTER </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL DEBT ISN'T ALL NEGATIVE 
</HEADLINE>
 COL.-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A lot of people smart enough to know better buy the theory that
paying off the national debt is one of the best things America
could do for itself.
</P>
<P>
   What everyone should be clear on, however, is that nobody is
talking about paying off all the debt. They're only talking about
retiring the publicly held portion of the federal debt.
</P>
<P>
   The debt has two components. One is the bills, notes and bonds
held by individuals, banks, institutional investors and foreigners.
This is the marketable debt, which is almost 60 percent of what
Uncle Sam owes. The other component is the nonmarketable debt,
which could be called the money government owes itself. Most of
this debt is Treasury IOUs credited to various trust funds. These
funds exist as parking places for excess revenues from taxes levied
for specific purposes. The Social Security trust fund is the
largest and best known, but many others exist for purposes as
varied as funding highway and airport construction and harbor
maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   The trust funds get these IOUs in the form of nonmarketable
securities because all of the tax money collected for specific
purposes isn't spent as intended. The unused revenue goes to
finance general budget outlays and the fund gets a redeemable
credit.
</P>
<P>
   It's important for Americans to understand the national debt's
bifurcated nature. Otherwise, they can be easily deceived. Although
the Treasury has been paying down public debt for more than a year,
the non-public portion of the debt has been rising even faster than
the public portion is being retired.
</P>
<P>
   If the U.S. pays off all of the publicly held debt but allows
the debt ``we owe ourselves'' to grow even faster, Americans will
end up with the worst of all worlds. The federal government would
still be obligated to redeem trust fund debt as needed, but
domestic and global financial markets would be denied the market
for public Treasury debt that is so necessary to maintaining an
orderly financial system.
</P>
<P>
   Without Treasury's publicly held debt, for instance, the Federal
Reserve won't be able to manage monetary policy nearly as
efficiently. Regardless of what you think of the Fed, this would
risk destabilization of the financial system.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar's status as the world's reserve currency also would
be jeopardized, economist Larry Kudlow explained recently in an
analysis for Investor's Business Daily. This would undermine U.S.
economic health because foreigners' willingness to invest in
dollar-denominated assets has been key to financing big trade
deficits without sacrificing prosperity. Treasuries are often
foreign investors' asset of choice because they are super safe.
Foreign interests now hold about 40 percent of the marketable debt,
or double the total of just five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Without a Treasury market, investors also couldn't hedge or
avoid risk during market turmoil by purchasing super-safe
Treasuries. The damage this would do to market stability both at
home and abroad is incalculable.
</P>
<P>
   Americans have long been told debt is bad. Not necessarily so.
Unmanageable debt is bad, but the U.S. debt situation has always
been manageable. What probably won't be as manageable is a
financial world without Treasury securities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
