r a BC-FETALTISSUE-KAN &LR;      03-11 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FETAL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI IN KANSAS CITY OPENS INVESTIGATION INTO FETAL TISSUE INDUSTRY
 
</HEADLINE>
 TISSUE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The FBI in Kansas City opened an investigation
Friday into whether anyone violated federal law in removing and
marketing tissue from fetuses at an Overland Park clinic where
abortions are performed.
</P>
<P>
   The probe will be carried out by the health care fraud unit of
the FBI in cooperation with the U.S. attorneys' offices in Kansas
and Missouri, Special Agent Jeff Lanza said.
</P>
<P>
   Members of a congressional subcommittee on Thursday called on
Attorney General Janet Reno and FBI Director Louis Freeh to launch
an inquiry at a hearing on the fetal tissue industry.
</P>
<P>
   The Health and Environment Health Subcommittee cited documents
and interviews raising questions about fees charged by a company
run by a Lee's Summit pathologist.
</P>
<P>
   The pathologist, Miles Jones, told an undercover reporter with
ABC News that organs such as livers, hearts and brains are in high
demand and that researchers ``will pay whatever you ask.'' Jones
had a price list for organs.
</P>
<P>
   Jones has not returned numerous calls for comment on his work.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, tissue and organs can only be donated, not
sold. Reasonable fees are allowed for removal services and
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Laws also prohibit women from being persuaded to prolong their
pregnancies, so organs are more developed and valuable, and it
prohibits altering normal abortion procedures in order to harvest
tissue.
</P>
<P>
   Lanza said the FBI would look into fees as well as into abortion
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Fetal tissue is important to researchers seeking cures for
several diseases, from Parkinson's disease to juvenile diabetes.
Some fear that the current controversy, raised by abortion foes,
could set back such efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Congress lifted a ban on fetal-tissue research in 1993 but made
it a felony to purchase or sell fetal tissue for profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am concerned that in attempting to enforce the
laws...Congress may unnecessarily over-restrict fetal tissue
research,'' said Samuel Cohen, a University of Nebraska Medical
Center pathologist, at the hearing Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Many opposed to abortion say they agree with the importance of
such research, but strict procedures must be followed or
profiteering will encourage more abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Another witness, medical technician Lawrence Dean Alberty Jr. of
Lee's Summit, said he once saw twin fetuses, used for organ
donations, moving and breathing in a pan of blood and that another
fetus moved its eyes.
</P>
<P>
   But Alberty acknowledged in a sworn affidavit that he was not
qualified to judge fetal viability, did not know if procedures had
been altered and was unaware if a fetus had come from a woman who
had an abortion to save her own life.
</P>
<P>
   Alberty also admitted that he accepted more than $10,000 from an
anti-abortion group for secretly gathering information and that he
lied to the group about some of what he had witnessed. He said,
however, that his testimony Thursday was accurate.
</P>
<P>
   Alberty was employed by Anatomic Gift Foundation Inc., an organ
harvesting firm, and later worked for Jones' company, Opening
Lines.
</P>
<P>
   Anatomic Gift and Opening Lines were under contract in the mid-
to late 1990s to remove fetal tissue at Comprehensive Health, an
Overland Park clinic affiliated with Planned Parenthood of Kansas
and Mid-Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Planned Parenthood terminated both agreements after concerns
arose over some business practices, said Peter Brownlie, president
and chief executive officer of Planned Parenthood. Brownlie said he
supported the federal inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Jones failed to respond to a subpoena to testify to the House
subcommittee on Thursday. The subcommittee, which serves under the
Commerce Committee, voted to hold him in contempt of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   For him to be charged with contempt and arrested, the Commerce
Committee and the full House would have to vote for contempt and
the Justice Department would have to indict him, House lawyers said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Records show that Jones has held a medical license in at least
16 states and the District of Columbia since he got a medical
degree from Howard University in Washington, D.C., in 1977. He got
a license in Missouri in 1997 and in Kansas in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Jones listed his other state licenses when he applied for a
license in Rhode Island in 1998, said Milton Hamolsky, chief
administrative officer of the Rhode Island Board of Medical
Licenses and Discipline.
</P>
<P>
   Hamolsky said it is not unusual for certain specialists, such as
pathologists and radiologists, to be licensed in many states
because their practices often involve filling in for doctors on
vacations and leave.
</P>
<P>
   In a related move Friday, Missouri Gov. Mel Carnahan announced
creation of a 15-member task force to review Missouri's 1969 law on
organ and tissue research.
</P>
<P>
   ``The task force will work to ensure that this important
research is not marred and exploited by someone seeking to make a
profit,'' Carnahan said.
</P>
<P>
   The task force will include physicians, organ-donation
specialists, individuals who have received organ donations, family
members of organ donors, lawmakers and others. The group will
review medical, legal and ethical opinions regarding fetal tissue
and organ donation.
</P>
<P>
   A Kansas House committee Thursday introduced a bill to require
tracking of fetal tissue and monitoring of fees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
