r a BC-EVOLUTION-KAN &LR;      03-11 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVOLUTION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLL FINDS PREFERENCE FOR TEACHING EVOLUTION RATHER THAN CREATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE BEEM  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most Americans want evolution, not creation, taught in public
schools, according to a poll released Friday by the People for the
American Way Foundation, a liberal watchdog group.
</P>
<P>
   About 83 percent of those polled favored the teaching of
evolution _ the theory that living things have changed through time
_ over biblical creation.
</P>
<P>
   About 70 percent see no conflict between the two ideas,
according to the poll.
</P>
<P>
   ``The poll shows most Americans believe God created evolution,''
said Ralph G. Neas, president of People for the American Way
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-seven percent of respondents classified creation as an
accurate account of how humans developed..
</P>
<P>
   The People for the American Way Foundation commissioned the
Washington firm DYG Inc. to conduct the poll. Telephone interviews
with 1,500 randomly selected persons were conducted in early
November. The poll has a margin of error of 2.6 percentage points
at a 95 percent confidence level. That means that if the study were
repeated 20 times, the results would be within 2.6 percentage
points 19 of the 20 times.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty percent of those polled disagreed with the Kansas Board of
Education's decision last August to de-emphasize evolution in new
state science standards.
</P>
<P>
   That is similar to results of a poll conducted last October by
The Kansas City Star and the Wichita Eagle. In that poll of 604
Kansans, 52 percent of respondents disagreed with the state board.
</P>
<P>
   The People for the American Way Foundation's poll results also
are similar to those of a Gallup Poll released in August.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Holloway of Shawnee has heard all this before. She said
she suspects the poll results could be skewed by the way questions
were phrased.
</P>
<P>
   The question on whether respondents agreed with the state
board's decision is one example, Holloway said: Pollsters told
respondents the state board deleted evolution from the new science
standards, which isn't exactly true. Still present in the science
standards is microevolution, or change within species. The board
deleted macroevolution, or change from one species to another.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's leading the answer,'' Holloway said.
</P>
<P>
   She also noted that the poll results were being released months
after the dispute was at its peak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why now? Why Kansas?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Because it's an election year, Neas said, and because those who
disagree with the state board need a wake-up call to realize how
hard its supporters will work to maintain the ground they've
gained.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very determined, tenacious minority,'' Neas said.
</P>
<P>
   The People for the American Way Foundation also commissioned the
poll to gauge how Americans, not just Kansans, view the state
board's decision. Since August, local and state school boards in
states from Kentucky to Oklahoma to New York have tinkered with
state standards and local classroom guidelines as they struggle to
determine what to teach in science classes, Neas said.
</P>
<P>
   The poll also found:
</P>
<P>
   - Although 95 percent of respondents have heard the term
``evolution,'' only 42 percent said they are ``very familiar'' with
the concept. Thirty-two percent incorrectly believe evolution means
humans developed from apes over millions of years. (The correct
definition is that humans developed from less advanced forms over
millions of years.)
</P>
<P>
   - Most Americans do not favor teaching only evolution or
creation. Forty-six percent say students should either discuss
religious explanations for origins in other classes or discuss
creation as a belief, not a scientific theory, in science class.
</P>
<P>
   - Sixty-six percent said the issue of whether to teach evolution
in public schools is too important to leave to individual school
boards or schools to decide.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway found that part of the foundation's poll intriguing
because it points to support for a national curriculum, something
the public has repeatedly rejected, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't they think the people closest to the children should
know what they want them to learn?'' Holloway said. ``How arrogant
and elitist.''
</P>
<P>
   John Morris, a geologist and president of the Institute for
Creation Research in San Diego, agreed. It's a common tactic and
somewhat Marxist, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The People for the American Way has this hidden agenda to use
their power base to infiltrate Kansas and take the (control) from
the local district,'' Morris said.
</P>
<P>
   Neas agreed that the Kansas controversy goes to the heart of
People for the American Way's mission. Changing the science
standards spoke to issues of quality education, freedom of speech
and the separation of church and state, Neas said.
</P>
<P>
   The poll results prove there's strong bipartisan support for the
foundation's position, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Molleen Matsumura of the National Center for Science Education
in Berkeley, Calif., said the results show something else, too.
Since August, Kansas has been the butt of jokes on late-night
television, in academic journals and in editorial cartoons. But the
results of the recent poll and earlier polls show that the opinions
of most Kansans aren't that different from those of their neighbors
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``People all over the country have been poking fun at Kansas.
People don't want to be like Kansas'' said Matsumura, whose
organization advocates the teaching of evolution. ``Guess what,
folks. You probably are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-00 0040EST &QL; 
