<HEADLINE>
SPORTS  
</HEADLINE>
 2TAKES-KAN  
 NCAA's QUEST TO ENFORCE RULES ON AMATEURISM UNSETTLES COLLEGE (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS, KATIE FUNK, HOWARD RICHMAN  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ NCAA suspensions of big-time college
basketball players over violations of amateurism rules is roiling
the basketball world, angering coaches and even helping create a
new players association.
</P>
<P>
   Labeled a ``witch hunt'' and ``crackdown'' by some, the NCAA
finds itself with few defenders.
</P>
<P>
   Temple's longtime coach John Chaney fumed after the NCAA
suspended center Kevin Lyde last week for one game because an
amateur coach paid for a summer course when Lyde was in high
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is truly unbelievable,'' he told reporters. ``Why don't
they go back to the crib? Why don't they go back and see if the kid
changed his diapers in the crib. I don't understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   Driven by anonymous tips and information from a federal
investigation based in Kansas City, the NCAA this season slapped
temporary suspensions on eight players at schools from Los Angeles
to Queens, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the suspensions involved players' accepting tuition
money to pricey East Coast prep schools to hone their skills before
entering college. Others involved players who accepted money or
shoes from summer league coaches and even from professional agents.
</P>
<P>
   NCAA officials say that despite some new wrinkles in the recent
cases, they're merely enforcing long-standing rules designed to
ensure an athlete's amateur status.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cases we've been seeing since late last year are cases
that have come to the attention of the NCAA,'' said spokeswoman
Jane Jankowski. ``We have not changed the way we investigate these
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The wave of suspensions began when the NCAA penalized three
players who were high school stars in the Kansas City area:
Oklahoma State's Andre Williams, for accepting tuition payments;
UCLA's JaRon Rush, for accepting money from an amateur coach and an
agent; and Missouri's Kareem Rush, for accepting impermissible
benefits from the same summer-league coach.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, DerMarr Johnson at Cincinnati, Jamal Crawford
at Michigan, Chris Porter of Auburn and Erick Barkley at St. John's
were hit with similar suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   The recent suspensions have made one thing clear: An athlete's
tuition to a prep school better be paid by a parent or guardian.
And an athlete should be careful, very careful, about taking money
from amateur coaches and others.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime observers question whether the NCAA is prepared to
suspend every player who ever violated such amateurism rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's confounding to me because this has been going on for
years,'' said Bob Gibbons, a recruiting analyst. ``If you or I want
to pay for a young man to go to school, what's wrong with that?''
</P>
<P>
   Annoyed with the suspensions, an Overland Park association that
represents college basketball coaches has helped organize the
Student Basketball Council to give players a voice.
</P>
<P>
   The fledgling group's chairman, Duke junior forward Shane
Battier, left little doubt as to its top priority: ``We are
immediately concerned and highly disappointed about the image that
a lot of players are getting, due to perceived violations of NCAA
rules.'' More questions than answers
</P>
<P>
   School tuition or summer league spending money is all the same
to the NCAA: They're benefits or services received solely because
of the individual's athletic reputation or skill, and they're
against the rules.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the NCAA has permitted some payments by friends or
benefactors if they had a long-standing personal relationship with
the players.
</P>
<P>
   As JaRon Rush prepared to choose a university in 1996, the man
who had paid his tuition at Kansas City's Pembroke Hill School,
businessman Tom Grant, informed the NCAA, which did not object.
</P>
<P>
   But earlier this year, the NCAA learned of a similar
relationship between Grant and Oklahoma State's Williams, and
tuition payments to a Maine prep school. Williams was suspended for
five games and ordered to repay $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   The differences in the two cases are difficult to see. The NCAA
will not discuss the details of individual cases. But after
Oklahoma State beat Kansas on Friday in the Big 12 Tournament,
Williams said he wasn't surprised more cases came to light after
his suspension and the suspensions of the Rush brothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's too much out there not to look at it deeper,''
Williams said.
(MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-00 0042EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
