r a BC-PREP2TAKES-KAN &LR;      03-11 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PREP </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS  
</HEADLINE>
 2TAKES-KAN  
 NCAA's QUEST TO ENFORCE RULES ON AMATEURISM UNSETTLES COLLEGE (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS, KATIE FUNK, HOWARD RICHMAN  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ More such cases could emerge, even as the
NCAA prepares for this year's national championship tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star surveyed the top 25 men's teams on the Jan.
17 Associated Press poll. Of about 350 players on those teams, 35
had attended prep schools or private high schools recognized for
their basketball programs.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the colleges contacted _ including top-ranked Cincinnati
_ did not return phone calls when they learned The Star wanted to
speak with players who had attended prep schools. In other
instances, spokesmen refused to set up interviews with such
players.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA's vigilance also opens questions for players now in
prep schools.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City's Shaun Dunson, a former Pembroke Hill School
basketball player and 1999 graduate, is being recruited by several
big-time schools, according to his father.
</P>
<P>
   Like Williams and the Rush brothers, Dunson knows Kansas City
businessman Grant, who paid his tuition to Maine Central Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Dunson said recently he is not concerned because his
relationship with Grant goes back to when he was 10 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Caron Butler, one of the nation's top prep school players, who
signed to play at defending national champion Connecticut, could
soon find himself in the NCAA's headlights.
</P>
<P>
   The Bray Center, a private non-profit community center in
Racine, Wis., partly financed Butler's tuition at Maine Central
Institute, said Jameel Ghuari, the center's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   Ghuari said the Bray Center had paid part of Butler's tuition
last year, but that its auditors said it couldn't help one person
without offering help to others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how Caron is paying this year. Bray Center isn't
contributing money,'' Ghuari said. Prep school defenders
</P>
<P>
   Much of this year's drama has focused on the role of expensive
prep schools, which can enforce academic discipline on a poor
student and expose a promising athlete to top competition.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors that help such students need to be encouraged, said
Gibbons, the recruiting analyst.
</P>
<P>
   ``Truth of the matter is this nation's public school system is
not working properly, and some aren't meeting the requirements of
NCAA standards,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ghuari said prep schools are important to big colleges because
they deliver players with four years of eligibility, rather than
the two years that a player retains after attending junior college.
</P>
<P>
   After prep school, he said, ``kids have four years to play, five
years to get a degree.''
</P>
<P>
   Max Good, once the head coach at Maine Central and now an
assistant coach at Nevada-Las Vegas, bristles when critics describe
Maine Central as a ``basketball factory.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here for social growth and academic growth,'' Good said.
``We (would not) take kids just to have a good basketball team.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Tolliver, who wants to play big-time ball after
finishing at Virginia's Fork Union Military Academy, has found the
prep-school experience valuable. His tuition was paid for by a
partial scholarship and contributions from the nearby West Bottom
Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   Tolliver said he wears a uniform every day: gray pants, brown
shirt, black jacket, gray hat and black gloves. Students march for
an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to go to (Fork Union) because I wanted to get better
by going against the best competition,'' Tolliver said. ``This is
pretty much like a college.''
</P>
<P>
   Jankowski of the NCAA said that ``with the heightened
attention,'' schools might want to work with the NCAA to make
certain the players they're recruiting will be eligible. In search
of fairness
</P>
<P>
   Jankowski acknowledged the NCAA has broken some new ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's different is the complex nature of these cases,'' she
said. ``They involve sums of money and other individuals who have
been involved which we haven't seen a lot of. I'm referring to
outside individuals that a prospective athlete is not legally
dependent on.''
</P>
<P>
   Ghuari, who has coached traveling summer teams with shoe company
sponsorship, has a solution.
</P>
<P>
   He'd like to see youth league coaches who develop the athletes
to be among those who pull down big money in college basketball,
like CBS and the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   Without top-quality athletes, he argues, there would be no $6
billion TV contract with CBS for March Madness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about money and power,'' Ghuari said.
</P>
<P>
   But through a survey of its members last year, the NCAA made it
clear that it wants to reduce the influence of summer league,
non-scholastic coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the NCAA is conflicted about its role.
</P>
<P>
   Made up of member universities and governed by college
presidents, the NCAA has charged its staff to enforce the
amateurism rules as they are now. But in the coming months, the
NCAA will consider revamping those rules, even to the point of
allowing players to return to the college game after playing a year
of pro ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all this publicity, it's possible the membership might
want to look at this,'' Jankowski said.
</P>
<P>
   But one reason for the publicity and hot comments from coaches
and others may stem from a change in philosophy by NCAA enforcers,
records in the Williams case show.
</P>
<P>
   In a Jan. 13 letter to the NCAA, Oklahoma State's Gerald Lage
argued that the NCAA had changed its view of existing relationships
without notifying Grant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fairness mandates that consideration be given to the
reasonableness of Mr. Grant's reliance on the actions (or
inactions) of the enforcement staff,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Fairness. That's what everybody wants.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent web chat by the basketball coaches association
Oklahoma coach Kelvin Sampson said:
</P>
<P>
   ``We opened Pandora's Box. I don't know if we have the time or
the enforcement staff to investigate every kid that goes to prep
schools. Are we going to legislate for prep schools or against
them? That is the question.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
