<SLUG> BC-MILLIONAIRE-NOPE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAME SHOW CONTESTANT MISSES $125,000 GUESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIK NELSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  LOS ANGELES _ It was an expensive lesson in classical music
one that cost him $93,000 - but Shane Demmitt of Northridge still
felt rich Friday after appearing this week on ABC's wildly popular
quiz show, ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?''
</P>
<P>
   It was Demmitt's final answer - and ultimate decision to bypass
his last lifeline - that cost the Loyola Law School student much of
his $125,000 prize money when he missed a question about composers
of requiem Masses. The result? He walked away with a paltry
$32,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to try for the $1 million because it's a
once-in-a-lifetime opportunity,'' Demmitt said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the four composers that he had to choose from - Brahms,
Mozart, Rossini and Verdi - Demmitt guessed it was Guiseppe Verdi
who had never written a requiem Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that your final answer?'' asked host Regis Philbin. The
correct answer is Rossini.
</P>
<P>
   Philbin reminded the 28-year-old second-year law student that he
had a remaining ``lifeline'' that would allow him to eliminate two
of the choices for the $250,000 question, but Demmitt declined.
</P>
<P>
   He could have stopped. He could have walked away with the
$125,000. He knew he didn't know beans about composers. Why take a
$93,000 guess?
</P>
<P>
   Despite the doubts of mystified viewers, Demmitt said there was
a method to his apparent madness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wanted to take a shot at the million because a lot of
things had been going right,'' Demmitt said Friday. He believed the
final lifeline would not have helped, and thought it better to save
it for one of the final two questions for $500,000 and $1 million,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played it up to that point the way I was planning to play
it, to get in position for the million,'' he explained. ``Had that
question come up one question later, I would have walked.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the plan: If he made it to a quarter-million, he would
quit and keep the money if the questions looked too difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Demmitt, the contestant's sister, had nothing but praise
for her brother's shot at the big money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really impressed with the outcome ... he just put it so
eloquently: He didn't look at it as losing $93,000, he looked at it
as gaining $32,000,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Demmitt, his sister and his girlfriend, Jenni Mischel, watched
the show with friends at Demmitt's Northridge condominium Thursday.
Other than Mischel, no one knew the outcome of the game, which was
taped in New York on Feb. 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I was, like, leaning into the TV,'' said Susan Demmitt.
On the last question, ``when his answer lit up, I thought he got it
right, then I saw the other answer in green, and I was just
devastated. I was, like, oh, God, because it was, like, so much
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the many events that boosted Demmitt's confidence was his
winning the ``fastest finger competition,'' which requires 10
potential contestants to arrange four items in a certain order.
</P>
<P>
   For Demmitt, he had to list heist movies in the reverse order of
their release. The film buff correctly guessed ``Entrapment,''
``Dead Presidents,'' ``A Fish Called Wanda'' and ``Oceans 11,'' and
did it in the fastest time possible.
</P>
<P>
   To reach that point, he had to answer similar questions by
phone. He guessed at some questions, which prospective contestants
answer by punching telephone buttons at home.
</P>
<P>
   In the first round, which he qualified for by repeatedly dialing
the show's toll-free number, he was faced with organizing sandwich
spreads according to their introduction on the market. Heinz
ketchup was first, he reasoned, because he remembered seeing a date
on a bottle, then Welch's Grape Jelly because, well, wine-making
had been around for centuries. Then it was between Jif and Skippy
peanut butter, and he figured that Jif was a more modern-sounding
name.
</P>
<P>
   On the final question that he missed, Demmitt had to do a
similar set of calculations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking that the answer was probably one of the two
Italians,'' in part because their culture had advanced more quickly
and he believed their art would be more secular in nature.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was up to one of his five pre-picked ``phone-a-friends''
to bail him out. He chose Robert Nissenbaum, director of the law
library at his own Loyola School of Law in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shane didn't really have a classical music buff on his list,''
Nissenbaum said. ``In my mind it was Verdi or Rossini, and I
flipped a coin in my head.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end it didn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   After the taping, ``my dad told me, '$125,000 isn't a
life-altering amount of money, but $1 million is,''' Demmitt said.
``Hell, I'm in law school, maybe I'll be making that $93,000 when I
get out.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
