<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOLS-CHANCELLOR-375&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERIM CHANCELLOR IS GAINING SUPPORT FOR PERMANENT JOB, OFFICIALS
SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After just seven weeks at the helm of the New York
City school system, interim Chancellor Harold O. Levy has emerged
as the front-runner for permanent chancellor, and would win the
support of a majority of the Board of Education _ if he wants the
job, high-level education officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   They said that in a short period, Levy had embarked on an
ambitious agenda _ setting tougher standards for the performance of
superintendents, vowing to move more quickly to remove incompetent
teachers and taking aim at the unwieldy central bureaucracy. By
doing so, he has convinced at least four of the seven board members
that he has the management ability it will take to turn around the
ailing school system.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Harold wanted the job, he would be the instant
front-runner,'' one top Board of Education official said. ``We
could put a 4-3 vote together.''
</P>
<P>
   Levy has been coy about his intentions, and refused to comment
again Friday on whether he would be a candidate for the permanent
job.
</P>
<P>
   To seal his hold on the job, Levy would probably need the
blessing _ or at least the neutrality _ of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
Giuliani vociferously opposed Levy's interim appointment and has
not yet spoken with him. But, behind the scenes, the mayor's aides
have opened lines of communication with Levy and have expressed
approval of some of Levy's initiatives. When told of comments by
Board of Education officials that Levy had a good shot at the
permanent chancellorship, the mayor's office said diplomatically
Friday evening that it would have no comment.
</P>
<P>
   And despite Giuliani's persistent public attacks on the Board of
Education, there are signs that he and Levy have found ways to work
together.
</P>
<P>
   The strongest indication, officials said, is their tentative
agreement to allow Randy Levine, until recently a deputy mayor and
still a trusted confidant of Giuliani, to negotiate the school
system's labor contract with the United Federation of Teachers.
</P>
<P>
   And opposition from Giuliani might not kill Levy's chances. The
limits of the mayor's power became clear in January, when Levy's
supporters managed a surprise defeat of Giuliani's candidate for
interim chancellor, by a 4-3 vote.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There have been a raft of other indications that Levy is no
ordinary temporary chancellor, biding his time until a permanent
successor is chosen. He has won favorable notices from the
editorial boards of all four of the city's major daily newspapers.
He has not been shy about appearing in public in his new role, much
as a candidate might campaign for public office. In the next few
weeks, he has scheduled speaking engagements with influential civic
and business groups.
</P>
<P>
   William C. Thompson Jr., president of the board, said Friday
that the board had no intention of anointing Levy and that it would
be up to him to come forward as a candidate if he wanted to stay
past June.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at the beginning of a search process,'' Thompson said.
``If Harold said, `Gee, I would like to be considered,' we wouldn't
stop that process. Then it's a question of whether the board would
want to interview Harold and put him into that process.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, just that willingness to consider the possibility of a
Levy candidacy is a shift. Until now, Thompson has insisted that
Levy was chosen as an interim chancellor, and that it would be
far-fetched to imagine him as anything more. Under the new
thinking, Levy could count on the same four votes he got in
January, including Thompson's. Education officials added, however,
that a strong challenger to Levy could still emerge.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also said that whatever Levy's thoughts, it would do
him little good to express them: if he says he wants the job this
early in the game, it may sound like hubris; if he doesn't, he
becomes even more of a lame duck.
</P>
<P>
   But some education officials have wondered all along why Levy
would have taken an expensive leave of absence from his job as a
corporate lawyer and manager for Citigroup if he did not have
longer-term aspirations to the job.
</P>
<P>
   Because he lacked formal education experience, Levy was required
under state law to get a waiver from the state education
commissioner to become chancellor. Although the contract granted to
him by the Board of Education in January is good for only six
months, the waiver is permanent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
