<SLUG> BC-BANKROB-LAPD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY GETS SHOOTOUT CASE: POLICE CONDUCT CALLED ATROCIOUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY ANDERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; L &LR; OS ANGELES _ After the ``worst bank robbery in the history
of the world,'' police in effect got away with murder by allowing
the gunman in the 1997 North Hollywood shootout to bleed to death,
an attorney told a federal jury Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Stephen Yagman said police allowed Emil Matasareanu,
30, to die a ``tortured, prolonged death'' as officers told a
paramedic to get out of the area and lit up what appeared to be a
cigar.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two Los Angeles Police Department officers have
figuratively gotten away with murder so far,'' Yagman said in
closing arguments of the civil rights lawsuit brought by
Matasareanu's children. ``Their conduct was atrocious.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys for retired policemen John Futrell and James
Vojtecky said some of the 17 victims wounded in the shootout had to
wait up to 2 hours to get help and the available paramedics treated
those with the most serious wounds who they thought would survive.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Bradley C. Gage, who is representing Futrell, said
officers and paramedics waited to treat or move Matasareanu because
he had 29 bullet holes in him, weighed 280 pounds, bled more when
he moved and had what appeared to be a ``booby trap'' belt on.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the worst bank robbery in the history of the world
and that changes everything,'' Gage said. Officers were reluctant
to call medical personnel to the scene because of police radio
reports of a third masked gunman in the area, Gage said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Yagman said he believes six people were involved
and four took part in the robbery. He said they were working for
the Montana Militia.
</P>
<P>
   After nine hours of closing arguments Friday, the case was sent
to the six-man, six-woman jury. They begin deliberations Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The bank robbery took place on Feb. 28, 1997, when Matasareanu
and Larry Eugene Phillips, 26, used automatic weapons to hold off
police for nearly an hour as they tried to get away. The gun battle
spilled onto residential streets and was televised live to a
national audience.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether 17 people, including 11 officers, were wounded and
the two gunmen died.
</P>
<P>
   Yagman said the jurors must decide if the officers showed
``deliberate indifference'' to the plight of Matasareanu.
</P>
<P>
   But Assistant City Attorney Donald Vincent, who represents
Vojtecky, said that of the 26 witnesses in this case, none proved
allegations of deliberate indifference.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-00 0121EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
