<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3856 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-METEORS-EVOLUTION-SFC     03-11 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METEORS-EVOLUTION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSCOPIC BEADS SUGGEST METEOR BOMBARDMENT PLAYED ROLE
IN  EARTH'S ABUNDANCE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN  
 c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tiny glass-like beads that formed millions of years ago when
comets and meteors gouged deep craters on the moon and Earth have
revealed a surprising role those bombardments played in the
emergence of Earth's abundant life, a team of scientists from
Berkeley, Calif., suggests.
</P>
<P>
   The glassy objects _ so tiny that only microscopes can reveal
their details _ were brought back from the moon by Apollo
astronauts 30 years ago when manned space flight was in its
infancy.
</P>
<P>
   Four Berkeley scientists using new techniques to date the
objects have found that both the Earth and moon came under a
suddenly intensified bombardment just as a burst of diversified
plant and animal life on Earth began about 500 million years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The emergence of widely varied primitive life forms is known as
the ``Cambrian explosion.'' The fossil record indicates it
continued to produce more and more newly evolved plants and animals
_ the ancestors of all life on Earth today _ for about 10 million
years.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of the bombardment on the Earth's environment might
have been so severe, researchers speculate, that it could have
caused major changes in the climate that forced some organisms to
disappear, while others adapted and diversified.
</P>
<P>
   The research was reported Friday in the journal Science by a
group headed by Paul Renne, director of the Berkeley Geochronology
Center, an independent research center, and three colleagues on the
University of California campus, where Renne is an adjunct
professor.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the glassy beads, known as spherules, were formed by
cratering impacts on the Earth and moon about 4 billion years ago,
when all the newly made planets were under constant bombardment by
meteoroids and comets.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of those violent crater-forming impacts have long since
vanished from the Earth's surface as upheavals of new continents,
volcanic eruptions and earthquakes churned the surface of the young
planet again and again.
</P>
<P>
   But on the sterile, quiescent lunar surface the craters are
still a major feature of the moonscape. The Berkeley team's
analysis of 155 tiny spherules in moon rocks carried home by the
Apollo 14 crew have revealed two major episodes of crater-forming
bombardments from space.
</P>
<P>
   The first began during the early days of the solar system about
4.5 billion years ago. The impacts continued for nearly a billion
years before they waned _ just at the time when life first emerged
on Earth, Renne noted.
</P>
<P>
   By dating spherules from some of the moon's younger craters, the
researchers have concluded that the crater-forming bombardments
increased unexpectedly again about 500 million years ago and
continued through the time of the Cambrian explosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``So life may have arisen on the Earth many times, to be wiped
out each time by the cratering impacts, and then may have arisen
again,'' Renne speculated in an interview. ``But just what role
those impacts played in evolution is still open to question.''
</P>
<P>
   Other members of Renne's team are Richard Muller, a UC physicist
at the Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory who conceived the idea
of using the spherules to calculate the timing of intense
bombardments from outer space; Timothy Culler, Muller's former UC
graduate student; and Timothy Becker, the manager of Renne's
Geochronology Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``The increase in cratering was roughly coincident with the
Cambrian explosion of complex life on Earth,`` Muller said
Thursday. ``As Darwin originally conceived evolution, survival of
the fittest meant superiority in conflict with other species. But
an increased crater rate also increases the stress on species to be
able to survive catastrophe. It is conceivable that this increased
stress helped drive evolution toward species with greater
adaptability and flexibility, away from instinct and toward greater
intelligence.''
</P>
<P>
   Muller is the physicist who has proposed what he calls the
``Nemesis Hypothesis,'' a theory that an unknown ``companion star''
orbits the sun every 26 million years from a distance of about 3
light years, or 18 trillion miles.
</P>
<P>
   Muller said he hoped to find evidence in the spherule ages of a
26 million-year period of increased cratering impacts that might
have been triggered by his ``Nemesis'' star.
</P>
<P>
   So far, he said, the accuracy of the spherule age dates is not
precise enough to support his hypothesis, although refining the
technique and analyzing more spherules may help. In the meantime,
he said, his own research group is in the process of building and
testing a new telescope that will soon be moved to a mountaintop
near Monterey, where it will hunt for the ``Nemesis'' star.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-00 0125EST &QL; 
