r a BC-CLEMENCY-DEATHROW-SFC     03-11 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLEMENCY-DEATHROW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CLEMENCY DENIED FOR KILLER OF 3 WOMEN AND GIRL  &HT;     By HARRIET CHIANG 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Declaring that convicted murderer Darrell Rich acted in an
``almost unbelievably brutal manner,'' California Gov. Gray Davis
denied clemency Friday for the serial killer who is scheduled to be
executed next week.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's decision leaves the Cottonwood man with little
hope of avoiding a lethal injection in San Quentin's death chamber.
</P>
<P>
   His execution, set for 12:01 a.m. Wednesday, will come 19 years
after he was convicted of murdering three women and an 11-year-old
girl in Shasta County. He also was convicted of sexually assaulting
five other women during a grisly rampage in the summer of 1978.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Rich acted in a callous and almost unbelievably brutal
manner,'' Davis said in a statement accompanying his clemency
decision. ``There is absolutely nothing about Mr. Rich's brutal
behavior that warrants clemency,'' he concluded. ``Clemency is
denied.''
</P>
<P>
   Rich's lawyer, Jim Thomson of Berkeley, called the governor's
decision ``morally and legally unsupportable.''
</P>
<P>
   In the clemency request, lawyers for the condemned man urged
Davis to follow the lead of Illinois Gov. Governor  &LR; George Ryan,
who imposed a moratorium in January on all executions until reforms
are made to the state's current death penalty system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. Davis had the opportunity to lead this state out of the
19th century and into the 21st,'' Thomson said, ``and leading us
away from state-sanctioned killing that has been questioned and
repudiated throughout the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomson also was dismayed that the governor summarily rejected
Rich's argument that he is a changed man with an exemplary prison
record who has discovered his Indian heritage while behind bars.
Rich, who has adopted the name Young Elk, is one-quarter Cherokee.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer said that every time he visits Rich, the inmate
expresses remorse for his grisly crime spree. ``This stuff haunts
him,'' Thomson said.
</P>
<P>
   Shasta County District Attorney McGregor Scott said he was
gratified by the governor's decision. ``If the death penalty is not
appropriate in this case, what case is it appropriate for?'' the
prosecutor said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's decision comes four days after relatives of some
of Rich's victims implored Davis not to spare the inmate's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our lives have been changed forever,'' Twyla Yates cq &LR;  told
the state Board of Prison Terms at Monday's clemency hearing.
Yates's daughter Linda Slavik, a 28-year-old wife and mother, was
kidnapped, raped and shot to death by Rich. Her body was left in a
garbage dump along with another of his victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``The execution of the animal who caused so much heartache will
finally bring closure,'' she told the board.
</P>
<P>
   The board voted unanimously to recommend that the governor deny
Rich's clemency request.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the state filed a petition yesterday arguing against
Rich's request that he observe last rites at a Native American
sweat lodge on prison grounds. In a lawsuit he filed in federal
court, Rich said the ceremony represents his only opportunity to
make ``amends with those he has wronged and with his Creator.''
</P>
<P>
   But in its response, the state yesterday filed a declaration
from a Cherokee Nation official, who called Rich's argument
``hogwash.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can say with assurance that it has no religious significance
to the Cherokee people,'' Richard Allen said in court statement. A
judge will rule on Rich's request Monday.
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle staff writer Chuck Squatriglia contributed to this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
