<SLUG> BC-SHOWEST-VEGAS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEATER OWNERS GET BOOST FROM STARS, THEIR STUDIOS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARLA MATZER ROSE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _  &LR; He may have gotten snubbed by Academy of Motion
Picture Arts and Sciences voters, but theater owners love Jim
Carrey.
</P>
<P>
   So making like an overly sincere beauty queen, Carrey vowed to
``strive to complete (his) duties as Star of the Year over the next
12 months.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrey reeled off a list of things he would do to be more
``star-like,'' such as getting his teeth capped and his face
lifted, ``so I look more star-like.'' It doesn't matter that his
acceptance speech came at the annual theater owners convention
Showest awards banquet at Las Vegas' Paris Hotel. An award is an
award.
</P>
<P>
   And the winners aren't surprised when their names are announced:
That's known well in advance.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a lively affair nonetheless, as stars let down their
hair with the folks who actually support those big paychecks of
theirs: theater owners.
</P>
<P>
   This year's event was hosted by the dryly witty Martin Mull, who
lampooned star-struck attendees by asking to have his picture taken
with the audience and joked that he was often up for the same roles
as winners Ving Rhames and Hilary Swank.
</P>
<P>
   After Comedy Star of the Year Drew Barrymore gushed that she
tried to be ``reincarnative'' of grandfather John Barrymore, Mull
quipped that he wondered if reincarnative was really a word - but
that he would never forget Barrymore saying, ``I live to please
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the statues were handed out by powerful
behind-the-scenes Hollywood folks you won't see on your standard
awards show. Supporting Actor of the Year Rhames received his
statue from Paramount Pictures Chairwoman Sherry Lansing. She
managed to find several opportunities to mention Rhames' role in
the upcoming ``Mission Impossible T2.''
</P>
<P>
   Producer of the Year Armyan Bernstein (``End of Days,'' ``The
Hurricane'') was introduced by Ron Meyer, president of Universal
Studios.
</P>
<P>
   This was a business convention, after all. Studio executives
want theater owners to know they are appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the female winners - Annette Bening, Swank and Angelina
Jolie - are considered Oscar front-runners, which often translates
into additional revenue for the people who show the films.
</P>
<P>
   Despite hectic and well-compensated work schedules, all showed
up - even Bening, named actress of the year, who was radiant and
very, very pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hesitant to fly here. But now that I've experienced this
moment, I'm so glad I did,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dreamworks' ``American Beauty,'' considered a leader in the race
for the Best Picture Oscar, was the only film to spawn two winners:
Bening and screenwriter Alan Ball.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-00 0130EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
