<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 01:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3859 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-GOP-PROCHOICE-SFCHRON     03-11 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-PROCHOICE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 AT S.F. MEETING, PRO-CHOICE GOP WOMEN LAMENT THEIR BITTER DILEMMA  &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ State Assemblywoman Sue Jackson from Monte
Sereno put it best Friday when she described what it's like to be
pro-choice and a Republican in the election year of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you like to have things thrown at you?'' she said with a
wry laugh.
</P>
<P>
   But for Jackson and a corps of Republican women who sat at the
annual Power of Choice luncheon Friday, sponsored by the National
Abortion Reproductive Rights Action League in San Francisco, the
joke is more than painful.
</P>
<P>
   The NARAL gathering brought together nearly 1,000 pro-choice
women _ Republicans and Democrats alike _ to assess the 2000
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   And with Texas Gov. George W. Bush now the presumptive nominee
of the Republican Party, those GOP pro-choice women _ politically
active, educated and willing to write campaign checks _ appeared
especially frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   They say that in his haste to seize the anti-abortion mantle and
court the Christian right in the primaries just past, Bush has made
them unwelcome in their own party. And they fear he has irrevocably
damaged the GOP's presidential chances in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republican women, if they really vote their conscience, they
will have to go with Al Gore,'' said Dagmar Dolby, one of the
nation's leading abortion rights activists and an influential
Republican voice in San Francisco. Dolby _ the wife of sound
pioneer Ray Dolby _ said that although she has proudly held to the
GOP since 1982, when she became a citizen, she recently took the
step, for the first time, to register as an independent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can no longer be part of the party,'' said Dolby this week.
``It's not just the choice issue. It's the whole social agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   At the NARAL lunch, Dolby told the gathering of women that,
sadly, '`reproductive rights have been made into a political
football.''
</P>
<P>
   And she was hardly alone in her anger on that front.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; California's Gender Gap
</P>
<P>
   In California, the abortion issue holds enormous sway among
women who have provided a crucial ``gender gap'' margin-of-victory
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Seven in 10 Californians support abortion rights, a factor that
played heavily in the 1998 governor's race. Republican candidate
Dan Lungren learned that firsthand when he paid for ads that
outlined his anti-abortion position to state voters _ and went down
to a historic landslide defeat to Democratic Gov. Gray Davis, a
supporter of abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the 2000 election approaches and with Bush having
wrapped up the GOP nomination, many Republican women worry that the
party is simply hitting the rewind button on the issue all over
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just handed the election to Al Gore,'' said Honor
Bulkley, a Republican supporter of the ``Wish List,'' the GOP
version of EMILY's list, an organization that raises money for
pro-choice female candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Bulkley said that although she couldn't bring herself to vote
for Gore, she is seriously considering the other alternative _
sitting out the presidential vote altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Many who said they voted for John McCain _ who reached out to
pro-choice women better than Bush, in their eyes _ said they will
now reassess their options.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; A Promise to Fight
</P>
<P>
   And Jackson, one of the rare pro-choice GOP women who has been
elected to office in California, is one who said she doesn't intend
to give up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be damned if they'll take my party away from me,'' she
said. ``We will fight this on to Philadelphia,'' where the GOP will
hold its national convention in July.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson and many others of the GOP women said the state of the
party today is particularly painful because at the start of his
presidential run Bush appeared on the right track.
</P>
<P>
   He said then that Americans were unlikely to support a
constitutional amendment to outlaw abortion, and he stressed that
he hoped to bring Americans together, even while they may not agree
on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   But the Texas governor faltered, they said, when he began
stepping to the right to win voters in Iowa and South Carolina,
saying that the Supreme Court's Roe vs. Wade decision legalizing
abortion was ``a reach'' and that he supported the GOP platform on
abortion, which makes no exceptions even in cases of rape and
incest.
</P>
<P>
   ``If George Bush wanted to, he could get rid of the whole GOP
platform altogether,'' said Carol Mayer Marshall, a former member
of the administration of Bush's father, former President George
Herbert Walker Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But in November 2000, she said, ``I don't see how (George W.)
will win California. Gore will be all over the choice issue.''
</P>
<P>
   On this, Democrats agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bay Area has become a Republican free zone, because not
only are the Democrats and independents voting heavily democratic,
but many of the Republicans have had it with their party's
opposition to choice,'' said Bob Mulholland, campaign strategist
for the state Democratic Party. ``In 1996, the Republicans were in
a circle shooting each other on the issue. (Now) it's the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Kate Michelman, who heads NARAL, lauded the GOP women for
continuing to fight for the issue, though their party _ and their
presumptive nominee _ seems not to hear. ``I hope to the GOP will
come back to its roots ... of respecting individual freedom, and
keeping government out of individual lives,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And Michelman said her organization will now pay for a series of
advertisements to remind women _ Republican and Democrat alike _
what's now at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is for four years,'' she said. ``The Supreme
Court is for decades to come.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-00 0132EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
