<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 01:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3881 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-WESTERN-PRIMARIES-2ND     03-11 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WESTERN-PRIMARIES-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE AND BUSH FIND CONTINUED SUCCESS IN WESTERN PRIMARIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to update voting results.)  
(ART ADV: A photo, NYT10, has been sent to New York Times photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The emphatic success that Vice President Al Gore and
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas enjoyed in the Super Tuesday primaries
removed almost all relevance from Friday's balloting in Colorado,
Utah and Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   Any that was left dissipated on Thursday when their chief
competitors, former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey and Sen. John
McCain of Arizona, called an end to their White House pursuits.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Gore and Bush won easily in Colorado and in Utah.
</P>
<P>
   In Colorado, the Democrat piled up 71 percent of the vote and
the Republican 65 percent, with 100 percent of the precincts
reporting.
</P>
<P>
   With 98 percent of the precincts reporting in Utah, Gore had
polled 81 percent of the vote; for the Republicans, Bush had 63
percent and Alan Keyes 20 percent. It was Keyes' best outing.
</P>
<P>
   In Wyoming, Republicans overwhelmingly supported Bush in a
nonbinding straw poll. He received 78 percent with 22 of the 23
county caucuses reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who swept all the Democratic contests on Tuesday, did not
campaign in Colorado or Utah this week. As the winner in all but
four of 13 Republican contests on Tuesday, Bush did, appearing at
rallies in Denver, Provo, Utah and Cheyenne, Wyo., where he struck
his familiar themes of tax breaks, strengthening the military and
criticizing Gore for his fund-raising practices.
</P>
<P>
   In each state, Bush was joined by the governor, Republicans all,
who were among his campaign's earliest supporters: Bill Owens of
Colorado, Michael O. Leavitt of Utah and Jim Geringer of Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until late Thursday that it became clear that Bush
would have the three states, as well as the rest of the country, to
himself without another major challenger.
</P>
<P>
   Freda Poundstone, McCain's Colorado coordinator, said she had
been expecting the senator to appear at rallies in Denver and
Colorado Springs, but then had to notify supporters that he was
withdrawing. The turnabout came too late for the campaign to pull
advertisements on Denver television stations, which ran late into
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Not that McCain's decision seemed to matter much to voters
casting ballots Friday. In Colorado, for example, a poll published
in The Denver Post on Sunday showed Bush with the support of 55
percent of registered Republicans, compared with 29 percent for
McCain. The margin of error was plus or minus 6 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, too, had been a heavy favorite in Colorado over Bradley,
by 66 percent to 24 percent in the same poll. It mattered less how
he stood in Utah and Wyoming even though he was the favorite in
both. They are heavily Republican states, and, like many other
Western states, are expected to support Bush in November.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-00 0145EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000311.0032 </DOCNO>
