<HEADER>
A3884 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-HORNETS-     03-11 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-HORNETS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORNETS BEAT CLIPPERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A rotten week rerun is nothing new for the Los
Angeles Clippers, who've been working on their sequel to
``Groundhog Day'' for about three months.
</P>
<P>
   But their five-day run of serial disaster is remarkably
grotesque - even by franchise standards.
</P>
<P>
   Monday was Shaquille O'Neal's birthday massacre. Wednesday was
death by Vince Carter. Thursday was relatively safe practice time
for the NBA's pre-draft-lottery favorites, who learned that Kenyon
Martin - the top suspect to be the No. 1 pick - achieved a broken
leg. TGIF, in this instance, represents ``Thank God It's Fibula,''
because a knee injury could be far worse.
</P>
<P>
   Friday produced nothing more than a blown 20-point,
third-quarter lead, a disturbing turnaround that enabled the
Charlotte Hornets to finish off the Clips, 118-101, before 15,362
at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   It's high time for ``Headband Night'' at Staples, a promotion
that would enable Clipper fans to use this freebie to cover their
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The home team managed to go 3 for their last 35 games in the
usual way - have a swell first half that includes early foul
trouble for Michael Olowokandi, flirt with victory for a portion of
the second half, then disintegrate.
</P>
<P>
   Their latest disgusting performance featured the aforementioned
20- point, third-quarter (ahem) cushion that was erased by
Charlotte (34-28) before the fourth period began. Riding the end of
pencil was rookie point guard Baron Davis (19 points), who narrowly
avoided employment on Planet Clipper when Charlotte passed on
selecting Lamar Odom in last summer's draft.
</P>
<P>
   The Clips (12-50) played without lame duck Maurice Taylor, who
called in sick. His power forward gig was taken by mighty Pete
Chilcutt (8 points, 8 rebounds).
</P>
<P>
   With Taylor at home, Tyrone Nesby (20 points) became the
self-designated trigger man, and produced 13 points in the first
quarter. The Clippers committed no turnovers and shot 52.6 percent
from the field to lead, 32-26, going into round two.
</P>
<P>
   Round two yielded another victory for the Clippers, who led by
as many as 11 points three times. Two of those advantages were
earned on 15-foot jumpers by CBA evacuee point guard Jeff McGinnis.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Anderson (24 points) finished the half with 18 points to
lead the Clippers, who made 54.5 percent of their field-goal
attempts and held a 52-46 edge. Odom (10 points, 10 assists, 10
rebounds) didn't scratch in the first half, but did hand out 7
assists.
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Coleman (31 points) had 17 to pace the Hornets. Former
Laker hero Eddie Jones (21 points) made just 1 of 8 shots to slow
down the Hornets.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers started pouring it on in the third, Odom's 3-point
shot boosting the lead to 69-49 at the quarter's 9:50 mark.
</P>
<P>
   Led Davis, the Hornets rallied, closing to within six at 77-71
with 4:31 before the fourth quarter. Davis, who abandoned UCLA
after two seasons, had 8 points in that run.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers continued to crumble, and Jones scored on a
fast-break layup to put the Hornets ahead for the first time,
82-81, at 1:11 of the third. Davis scored after slick crossover
dribble with two seconds left in the period to give himself a dozen
points in the quarter and provide Charlotte with an 86-83 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth quarter was amazing 12 minutes of garbage time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
