<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGSNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANTHERS CLAIM KINGS' BARRIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Len Barrie, the journeyman center recalled in
November when the Los Angeles Kings' first line was wiped out by
injuries, was claimed on waivers on Friday by the Florida Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   Barrie, 30, did not score much in 46 games with the Kings, just
five goals and 13 points. However, he did provide grit to the third
and fourth lines after Jozef Stumpel returned to the first unit.
</P>
<P>
   His spot was vacated in the event the Kings are able to make a
trade by Tuesday's deadline. However, coach Andy Murray said that
is unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very disappointing day for me; very sad,'' Barrie
said before boarding a flight to South Florida. ``We were building
something special here. I will miss them and I think they will miss
me, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrie was placed on waivers Wednesday and the club was hoping
he would clear during the 48-hour waiver period. But he was picked
up by the Panthers, a club he spoke to last summer before signing
with the Kings after playing two years in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess if there is an upside, it is that I am going from one
playoff team to another,'' Barrie said. ``I played for (Panthers
coach)Bryan Murray so I know what to expect. But you really want to
finish what you started.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings were the fourth club for Barrie, whose up-and-down NHL
career began in 1989-90 with Philadelphia. He played briefly for
the Panthers in 1993-94 and also the Pittsburgh Penguins.
</P>
<P>
   He opened the season with minor-league Long Beach and was the
leading scorer in the International Hockey League at the time of
his recall. Barrie was a gifted scorer in the minors, but he had
difficulty taking his game to the next level.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't going to start on either of our first two lines, but
he worked well on the third and fourth lines and was a great guy to
have on a hockey club,''said Andy Murray, who met with Barrie at
the club's El Segundo practice facility before preparing the Kings
for tonight's game against the Calgary Flames. ``Lennie helped
create a chemistry in the dressing room and that is something we
are going to miss.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Barrie rarely scored, he did have his moments. On
Jan.6, he scored two goals in a 4-2 victory over Florida and said
later there was an added incentive playing against a team that
snubbed him during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Feb 25, before 35 friends and family members from his
home in nearby Victoria, B.C., Barrie scored the first goal in a
5-2 victory against the Vancouver Canucks.
</P>
<P>
   Quick whistles: Barrie is a free agent at the end of the season
and said the Kings would be the first team he'll contact....
Goaltender Stephane Fiset, sidelined since last Saturday with a
strained right groin, hopes to resume workouts Monday and could be
ready to return to action by the end of next week.... General
manager Dave Taylor sent faxes to the other 27 clubs notifying them
that disgruntled winger Donald Audette has requested a trade.
Taylor said he has not received any replies and expects Audette to
remain with the club. Audette returned to the second line Thursday
after a two-game benching and had an assist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-00 0156EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
