r s BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN     03-11 0465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS STREAK PUT INTO PERSPECTIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Lakers' latest flirtation with
history is being treated much the same as their prior ones - with a
smile and not much else.
</P>
<P>
   Their 17-game winning streak is tied for sixth-longest in the
NBA record books, second longest in Lakers lore. But if it means
anything to him,Kobe Bryant isn't letting on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just got 17 wins in a row. We have a lot of room for
improvement, so we don't have time to really sit back and think
about what we're doing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When might the Lakers sit back and be impressed with the
achievement?
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the season,'' said Bryant, ``when we're popping
champagne.''
</P>
<P>
   A victory Sunday against the visiting Sacramento Kings, and the
Lakers would match the 1995-96 Chicago Bulls' 18-game streak, which
preceded a championship.
</P>
<P>
   Two more wins after that - at Denver and Washington - would move
the Lakers into truly select company.
</P>
<P>
   Only two teams have ever won 20 or more in a row - the 1970-71
Milwaukee Bucks, who won 20, and the 1971-72 Lakers, who won an
NBA- record 33.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams won the championship.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Harper was part of the Bulls' 18-game streak, so the Lakers'
run ``doesn't faze me at all. I mean, this is a long year. It's
nice we get these 17 games in a row things, but the main priority
is to play later on this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Phil Jackson not only coached that Bulls' streak, but he
was alsoa member of the 1969-70 New York Knicks team that won a
then-record 18 in a row on the way to the championship.
</P>
<P>
   He called the Lakers' 17-game run ``nice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a big number. I was in the league when 18 was the
largest number, and we used to think that was an incredible number
of games won. But then the Lakers in '71-72 just blew it out. It's
incredible to run up this number of wins, because it says that we
haven't been defeated now in almost six weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' last loss was Feb. 1, at San Antonio. Their last
home loss was Jan. 22, against Portland.
</P>
<P>
   How does the streak compare to the Bulls'?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like this,'' Jackson said. ``We were playing a little
bit higher intensity, perhaps. This is a team that can grind things
out, very economically, actually, if they want to.''
</P>
<P>
   Fading Blazers: Portland is still the Lakers' closest rival, but
the margin is 4 games in the wake of the Lakers' streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an awesome thing for them,'' Jackson said. ``I know it's
affecting their morale a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant said the extra breathing room is ``nice, but as far as
thinking about where their mentality is and where their head is, I
don't really care.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-00 0157EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000311.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 02:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3887 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BRUINS-HURRICANES-BOS     03-11 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRUINS-HURRICANES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS BEAT HURRICANES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. _ The winds of change, blowing with hurricane
force these days around the Bruins, roared again Friday night with
news here, following Boston's 5-3 win over Carolina, that Rob
DiMaio was traded to the New York Rangers for strapping right wing
Mike Knuble.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaio, a top checker and grinder for the Bruins the last four
seasons, will fly to Pittsburgh this Saturday morning and is
expected to suit up for the Blueshirts Saturday night against the
Penguins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really hasn't hit me yet,'' said a somewhat stunned but
upbeat DiMaio, exchanging farewell handshakes with his teammates as
they boarded a bus that transported them to a charter flight to
Montreal. ``It's part of the game, I guess, just the way things
work. Things are happening around here fast and furious. I guess
this is just part of the job.''
</P>
<P>
   For two of his seasons in Black and Gold, DiMaio was a key
contributor on a third line with center Tim Taylor. He now will be
reunited with Taylor in New York, presumably again on the No. 3
line, assigned to cover the top scoring trios among the rest of the
Original 28.
</P>
<P>
   The 27-year-old Knuble, ex- of the University of Michigan, began
his career with the Red Wings, who made him the 76th pick in the
'91 draft. He won a Stanley Cup with the Red Wings in the 1997-98
season and then was swapped to the Blueshirts for a draft pick Oct.
1, 1998. A potential power forward, if he can pick up his
intensity, the 6-foot-3-inch Knuble likely will be in Montreal
Saturday night when the Bruins face the Canadiens.
</P>
<P>
   The move was made, from strictly a personnel standpoint, for
size. The 32-year-old DiMaio is only 5-10, but plays an aggressive
game that most nights makes him look 4 or 5 inches taller. He backs
down from no one. He and defenseman Don Sweeney have been the
club's two grittiest and most consistent performers this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knuble's big, I like his size,'' said coach Pat Burns. ``We
need that.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMaio also has been blunt, and that made him a more likely
candidate to get the gate. In the hours leading up to and after Ray
Bourque's trade to Colorado, DiMaio once more expressed his concern
(i.e. dismay) over management's failure to fill out the roster and
make the Bruins legitimate contenders. It wasn't quite akin to Adam
Oates's outburst prior to his being dealt in '97, but it was blunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just being honest, that's all,'' said DiMaio, asked
again about those comments as he exchanged farewells. ``I certainly
wasn't trying to burn bridges or anything. I hope it's not the
reason I was traded, but who's to say? Boston was a great city for
me. I loved my time there. I had great teammates, great coaches. It
was just a great experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he felt his comments ultimately were the reason he was
shown the door, DiMaio said, ``Hey, I didn't say anything that no
one else has said. I reiterated some things that others have said,
and some of those have been reiterated to the public of late.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMaio was referring, of course, to Bourque's comments in
Tuesday's Lawrence Eagle Tribune, when he warned that his trade was
``just the start'' of things to come and that players around the
league no longer wanted to play in Boston. Bourque soon backed off
those statements, but only slightly, and Boston president/general
manager Harry Sinden said he didn't believe Bourque made those
comments.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaio, hindered with a hand injury the last two weeks, did not
play in the victory here. He said the hand has healed, will not
need surgery (once a prospect), and he intends to suit up Saturday
night. It will be his second tour in the New York metropolitian
area, having begun his career with the Islanders as a 1987 draft
pick.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-00 0212EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000311.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3888 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BULLS-CELTICS-BOS     03-11 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BULLS-CELTICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELTICS BURY BULLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This was how the Celtics thought it would be against the Bulls.
They played some role reversal with Chicago in their first two
meetings, but Friday night, the planets were in order and
everything went according to Hoyle.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls, of course, are thinking about next August, which
makes games in March somewhat problematic and inherently difficult.
The Celtics are still thinking about making the playoffs, which
makes it a lot easier. It showed. They wanted this one. The Bulls
didn't care. They were in ``warm up the plane'' mode for the final
36 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a thorough 104-74 drubbing that was over in the
first half. That is the harsh truth, harsher still given the
Celtics' affinity for blowing late, 20-something leads at home.
Boston led by 11 after one, 21 at the half, 28 after three and,
really, it was all ceremonial the rest of the way. Pervis Ellison
even got in the game for 11 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing I like about this game is that when we got the
lead, we stayed with it, stayed aggressive all night,'' said Paul
Pierce, who had 15 points. ``We got the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   The win was the Celtics' third straight and kept them three
games (in the loss column) out of the coveted No. 8 playoff spot.
They got some help from Indiana, which beat Cleveland, and from the
Nets, who beat the Bucks. Orlando was idle.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics felt they were owed this one. ``We let two games
against them get away,'' said Kenny Anderson, who had a team-high
16 points. ``We had to take advantage this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Antoine Walker, who had 9 points, 8 rebounds, and 5 steals
in 28 minutes, ``This was definitely revenge. We wanted to make a
statement that we are tough and that the other two games were a
fluke.''
</P>
<P>
   You know it's a long night when Bulls coach Tim Floyd has to go
to his bench _ and his bench is as good (or bad) as his regulars.
Even celebrated rookie Elton Brand was in a funk; he had a
rotisserie 16/9, but was 6 of 19 from the field and was kept off
the offensive glass, where he has made a nice living this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were coming out at me a lot,'' said Brand. ``They really
came at me tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, the Celtics spread the wealth like Marxists with
eight players scoring between 8 and 16 points. They didn't shoot as
well as they might have liked _ 45 percent _ but it hardly matters
when your opponent shoots worse (38 percent), can't handle the ball
(26 turnovers leading to a whopping 32 points), can't pass (14
assists), and missed all four of its 3-point attempts. Other than
that, the Bulls were luminous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really disappointed with the effort,'' said Floyd, who
had every right to be. ``That was a ridiculous performance. There
are no excuses. Guys come. Guys go. At this level, you're supposed
to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics, looking for payback and to stay in the playoff
frame (as opposed to picture), dominated from start to finish. They
never trailed, led by 15 before the game was nine minutes old, by
23 in the second, and by a comfy 37 midway through the fourth.
Chicago trailed by 28 after three and opened the fourth by missing
six shots, turning it over three times, and scoring a single point
in the first five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   It was what we've come to expect of the Bulls, who entered the
game having lost nine of 10 and with the worst record in the
conference. They had lost two nights earlier in Orlando by 36, and
have now lost 18 games by 15 or more points and 13 by 20 or more.
This one was their third worst of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Where to begin? The Celtics led, 13-10, and then scored 11
unanswered points, starting with an Anderson hoop. Chicago had four
turnovers in the run, which featured 4 points from Pierce (5 of 11
in 30 minutes). Danny Fortson (14 points, 7 rebounds, 6 fouls in 25
minutes) finished it off with a pair of free throws.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics got the lead to 15 before a pair of hoops by
legendary Celtic-killer Chris Anstey brought Chicago back to within
31-20 after one. That margin would look mighty good to Chicago in a
few minutes. Over the final 36 minutes, it never got closer than
that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
