<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICAL TIME FOR BELTRE TALKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ On the eve of possibly signing a three-year
contract that could pay him anywhere between $5 and $10 million,
Los Angeles Dodgers third baseman Adrian Beltre admitted feeling
anxiety about possibly ending the five-month soap opera that has
surrounded him.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers managing general partner and CEO Bob Daly and Scott
Boras, Beltre's agent, worked deep into Friday night, trying to
resolve the issue before today's soft deadline imposed by both
sides. Today also is the major-league-mandated deadline to renew
the contracts of players with three years or less of service time,
or lose them to free agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little anxious about it, a little nervous,'' Beltre
said. ``I want to know what's going to happen. Sometimes at night I
think about it a little bit. But when I'm on the field and playing,
it doesn't bother me at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly and Boras spoke each of the past few days in an attempt to
reach an agreement. The Dodgers are willing to pay Beltre $5
million, but Boras is asking for nearly $10 million, baseball
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Though both sides are hoping a deal is struck, neither said one
was imminent. Still, those familiar with the situation believe a
deal, worth $6 to $7 million, will be made today. If not, the
Dodgers will renew Beltre's contract for one season for
approximately $275,000. He made $220,000 last season.
</P>
<P>
   But renewing the contract could make the issue more complex.
Though Boras and Daly could continue to negotiate afterward, both
sides said that would be much more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre, 20, was signed by the Dodgers at age 15, which violates
baseball's rules. Daly learned of the issue in October, papers were
filed with baseball in November and commissioner Bud Selig denied
Beltre's request for free agency in December. The players
association filed a grievance in January, but a hearing date is yet
to be set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know it was going to be this long,'' Beltre said.
``It should have been for two days, and then it was four, and six,
and you see how far it goes. Nobody knows what's going to happen. I
actually don't know what's going to happen. Nobody knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Say Uncle: When Dodgers left fielder Gary Sheffield was growing
up in Tampa, Fla., he remembers an uncle of his blowing pitches by
the neighborhood kids on the sandlot. That uncle was Doc Gooden,
and after years of being dominated by him, Sheffield finally has
something to talk about.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield homered in the first inning Friday against Gooden, who
is trying to make Houston's rotation. It was Sheffield's first
homer of the spring, and first off Gooden.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're a kid and your uncle is dominating grown-ups, and
everyone else around the neighborhood, and everybody was
overmatched ... it took me 31 years to get to the point to where I
could hit the ball, and feel comfortable doing it,'' Sheffield
said. ``He was mad at me. I can't tell you what he was calling me
when he went in to do his sprints.''
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Manager Davey Johnson said right-hander Mike
Fetters is about a week away from pitching in a game. Fetters, who
strained his left quadricep, is having trouble covering first and
fielding bunts, Johnson said.... The Dodgers tried to get down to a
workable number of players in camp. They assigned Apostol Garcia
and Hiram Bocachica to Triple-A Albuquerque and sent Randy Galvez,
Geronimo Gil, Julio Vinas, Luke Allen and Chris Ashby to
minor-league camp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
