<SLUG> BC-FBC-USCNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC GETS COMMITMENT FROM UPLAND DEFENSIVE END
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Jason Wardlow, a defensive end from Upland High,
has become the first high school junior to commit to USC for next
year's recruiting class.
</P>
<P>
   Wardlow (6-foot-3, 225 pounds) selected USC while visiting the
school last weekend on its academic day. He had 17 sacks last
season and is projected as a defensive end in college.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans are eager for early commitments from players like
Wardlow, because current defensive ends Sultan Abdul-Malik,
Shamsud-Din Abdul-Shaheed and Matt Childers will all be seniors
next season.
</P>
<P>
   Early impression: By the conclusion of the first practice, it
was apparent junior college transfer cornerback Chris Cash would
immediately challenge for a starting position. He intercepted a
pass, and broke up another that looked like a sure catch for wide
receiver Steve Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like him,'' USC coach Paul Hackett said. ``He really has
picked up stuff fast. I'm pretty pleased. We have great
expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   If Cash does start, the Trojans would likely move junior Kris
Richard to free safety and keep Antuan Simmons as the other
cornerback. Simmons is sitting out spring drills while he recovers
from back surgery he had last November.
</P>
<P>
   Where's the shotgun?: After criticism last season that the
Trojans did not use the shotgun offense, Hackett vowed to install
some parts of it for next year. The first steps should be taken in
spring drills, although Hackett was not sure when he would start to
implement the passing formation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will at some point look at the shotgun,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   New tight ends coach Brian Schottenheimer might help, since he
previously coached with Steve Spurrier at Florida, well known for
its use of the shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   Higher expectations: Quarterback Carson Palmer feels this year's
spring practices are more important than last year's, and not just
because he needs to get back in football shape after missing nine
games with a broken collarbone.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, we have a chance to do a lot more than last year
because we have a better team,'' Palmer said. ``We're going to the
Kickoff Classic and have a chance to have a really good season.''
</P>
<P>
   Ready for a challenge: Hackett said he believes playing Penn
State in the Kickoff Classic is not a mistake, although some have
second-guessed the move, especially because the Nittany Lions
defeated USC 24-7 in the 1996 Kickoff Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we aspire to be the best, we need to play against the
best,'' Hackett said. ``I don't think USC ever turns down a game
like that. Are we up to the task? We're going to find out.''
</P>
<P>
   On track: Wide receiver Marcell Allmond, cornerback Darrell
Rideaux and offensive lineman Lucais MacKay all missed the first
two days of drills to participate in a track meet. They will join
the football team when practices resume March 23.
</P>
<P>
   Position change: Sophomore tight end Scott Huber asked Hackett
this week if he could switch to defensive end, and will try the
position in spring drills to see if he can make the move
permanently.
</P>
<P>
   Polamalu out: Sophomore safety Troy Polamalu missed the first
two days of spring practice because of a sore hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   Extra scholarship: Hackett said the Trojans have an available
scholarship and could still sign a punter or kicker for next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
