<P>
   BOSTON-BIG-DIG (Boston) _ It's as if a tunnel had collapsed on
top of James J. Kerasiotes and he were digging himself out of the
debris with his bare hands, all the while calling up through the
settling dust, ``Even so, everybody, really, this project is a
success!'' What has collapsed is, thank goodness, not a real,
physical tunnel, not part of the monumental Boston highway
construction project known as the Big Dig, of which Kerasiotes, as
chairman of the Massachusetts Turnpike Authority, is the Biggest
Digger. Rather, it is the political and public relations debacle
that has crashed down around him for more than a month, ever since
he acknowledged that his past vehement assertions to the contrary,
the dig _ billed as the biggest civil works endeavor under way in
the country and the most complex American urban infrastructure
project ever _ was over budget. By Carey Goldberg.
