   MACBETH-OPERA-REVIEW (New York) _ Updating an opera from its
historical setting to the approximate present can often represent
lazy thinking on the part of a director, a gimmicky way to make an
older work seem relevant. But the director Graham Vick's production
of Shostakovich's great tragi-satirical opera, ``Lady Macbeth of
the Mtsensk District,'' unveiled at the Metropolitan Opera in 1994,
demonstrates that the right kind of updating concept can be
revelatory. The production returned to the Met on Thursday night,
vividly conducted by Valery Gergiev, with the soprano Catherine
Malfitano in an arresting portrayal of the title role. By Anthony
Tommasini.
