<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS STRIVE TO SETTLE EDMONDS, ANDERSON SITUATIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ The Anaheim Angels are determined to make every
effort to settle their situations with free-agents-to-be Jim
Edmonds and Garret Anderson before opening night against the
Yankees on April 3 in Anaheim, a source said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The club does not want to begin the season distracted with trade
rumors involving the two players, particularly Edmonds, whose name
comes up the most and who could attract a better return package.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' goal is to re-sign or trade the outfielders, though
it is unlikely they would trade both. It's also doubtful they will
re-sign Edmonds, although the relationship between the two sides
has improved of late.
</P>
<P>
   Camp has gone so well for the first three weeks the club is
intent on keeping that feeling going into the season. Both Edmonds
and Anderson also would like to have their situations settled by
the time the season begins.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds has said that he does not want to go to a team with
which he wouldn't re-sign because he'd still be trade bait. He
would prefer to go to a team that would immediately begin working
on signing him to a contract extension, or even agree to a deal in
advance of a trade.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees remain the team most likely to land Edmonds because
of their needs, their financial ability to pay him, and because
they have the most to offer in return, most notably pitcher Ramiro
Mendoza.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an abundance of outfielders and if we'd get ourselves
in position to get appropriate returns for our assets, it's
something we'll look at,'' Angels president Tony Tavares said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Short stint: Troy Percival made his first appearance of the
spring Friday, but those who blinked might have missed it.
</P>
<P>
   Percival started the Angels' Cactus League game against the
Padres and his day's work was short and sweet: one inning, three
outs, eight pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Percival has been recovering from shoulder surgery, which
included the removal of a large bone chip that was buried in muscle
and shaving loose fragments from his collarbone. The pain got so
bad last season that he had trouble holding his newborn baby, and
he was shut down by the club two weeks before the season ended.
</P>
<P>
   He's spent spring training building up strength in the shoulder,
and Friday was his first opportunity to test himself in a real
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``During my bullpens (workouts) I'm worried about mechanics,
worried about my arm,'' Percival said. ``When I get in the game,
all I want to do is go out and throw. Today I was pain-free. I
can't remember the last time I felt like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Normally, Percival is aware of his velocity, which typically
ranges from 93-97 mph. But now he is more concerned with simply
being able to throw over the top without pain and pitch like he did
in 1995 and '96.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea how hard I'm throwing, which is unusual for
me,'' Percival said. ``All I want to do is go out there and throw
strikes. I know I was throwing good enough to get it by people. I'm
not throwing 100 mph, but I should be at 95 by the start of the
season. Getting my arm angle up was effortless. I didn't feel I was
trying to throw hard at all.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For where Troy is now I don't think any of us could be
happier,'' manager Mike Scioscia said. ``He showed his arm is sound
and it's going to get stronger. That's a big first step he took.''
</P>
<P>
   Percival has been working on a split-finger pitch this spring
and plans to use it often, along with his curveball, which he threw
once Friday for a called strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saw the one (curveball) I used last year - it bounced in
the on-deck circle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides getting his shoulder cleaned out, Percival also got in
shape, losing 20 pounds and getting down to 220.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got too heavy at the end of last year,'' he said. ``It's a
lot easier to go up than down.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercker struggles: Kent Mercker, competing for a spot in the
starting rotation, followed Percival and gave up five runs (two
earned) and seven hits in 2 innings. The Angels, however, beat the
Padres 9-5. Bengie Molina went 2 for 3 with a home run, and Darin
Erstad and Scott Spiezio had two hits apiece.
</P>
<P>
   In a split-squad game in Peoria, the Padres beat the Angels 4-3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
