<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BROWN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESSURE IS OFF DODGERS' BROWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ Had Kevin Brown won all 35 of his starts last
season, thrown about five no-hitters, and had his tutoring of
younger pitchers translated into four 20-game winners, maybe the
expectations heaped upon him would have been fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, none of that happened. The hoopla surrounding
Brown at this time last season was engulfed by midseason thanks to
a Los Angeles Dodgers team that imploded time and again.
</P>
<P>
   A year after the initial whirlwind swirling around Dodgertown,
Brown remains the highest-paid pitcher in baseball. It's just the
interest is very different.
</P>
<P>
   And Brown, no longer besieged by reporters every day because of
his industry-rocking contract, is experiencing the kind of spring
training he craves.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's nice and relaxed,'' Dodgers catcher Todd Hundley said.
``Obviously, coming in last year, there was a lot of pressure on
him. I think he handled it great. I think he's able to relax a
little more this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The day-to-day pressures, including dissections of his every
move, are gone. He's also comfortable in returning to a clubhouse
in which he's known, and in which he knows most others. And the
talk of Brown being the guy to return the Dodgers to glory is gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be easier for me this year,'' Brown said. ``I'm not
coming in starting from square one. I know people here. I know the
coaching staff. I know the players. It's easier, certainly.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Dodgers agreed to pay Brown $105 million over
seven years because he could handle such pressure. But one thing
Brown can't do is start every other day, turn double plays, hit
behind runners, provide depth in the bullpen (though he tried to at
times) and be a versatile player off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Brown can do a lot of things, but filling other gaping holes
isn't in his repertoire. Even so, Brown did very little wrong last
year for a club that made it a habit of doing the wrong thing. He
was 18-9 with a 3.00 ERA for a team that won 77 games. He tied a
career high with 35 starts and was consistent and quiet amidst a
sea of controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Brown admitted he forced a few conversations with teammates in
trying to live up to the role of leader, and manager Davey Johnson
said numerous times last season that Brown may have put too much
pressure on himself early.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may have tried to make sure I was trying to talk to some of
the guys instead of letting it happen,'' Brown said. ``I really
didn't feel any adverse effect from anything. I know that those
things come about because of the things I need to do. The
leadership role, that's not a tag I put on myself.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's a tag everyone else wanted to put on Brown. From the
moment he was introduced as a Dodger, management talked about
Brown's unmistakable intangible qualities - his work ethic, his
intensity, his leadership.
</P>
<P>
   As the season developed, those attributes became more clear.
After a one of his few strong outings, a win against Atlanta,
Carlos Perez remarked how sitting next to Brown on the bench during
games was helpful.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Dreifort talked about watching Brown's daily work routine
and learning from it. Brown's known for bearing down even more in
tight situations, and Dreifort frequently mentioned that when
talking about his run of strong pitching performances last season.
</P>
<P>
   And Chan Ho Park is perhaps Brown's biggest admirer. After Park
was pounded during a start last season on the road, Brown came to
Park's hotel room. The two talked for a few hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``That meant so much to me,'' Park, 26, said. ``He came to me
and told me about how he went through the same kind of things when
he was my age. I didn't know that. I thought he was always a great
pitcher like he is now. I didn't know he had the same problem. He
said he was just like me. That made me feel really good.''
</P>
<P>
   That's where Brown's inherent value lies.
</P>
<P>
   Brown wins more than nearly everyone else - only Greg Maddux's
71 wins are more than his 69 since he joined the National League in
1996. He's a workhorse who chews up innings with quality starts and
gets better as seasons progress.
</P>
<P>
   It's just that even though Brown pitched markedly better after
the All-Star break last season, going 9-3 with a 2.41 ERA, the team
digressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that was different than I hoped was we didn't
win,'' Brown said. ``You get used to winning. It's hard to go
back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-00 0221EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
