<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CSUN-MONTANA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE WINS, REACHES FOR SKY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MISSOULA, Mont. _ The late show was a great show for the Cal
State Northridge men's basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   Television forced the Matadors' Big Sky tournament semifinal
against host Montana to a 9:30 p.m. local time slot, and Northridge
proved to be ahit, beating the Grizzlies 76-65 in front of 5,038 at
Dahlberg Arena Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Northridge (20-9) advanced to meet Northern Arizona for the
conference title tonight at 7:30. The winner gets an automatic bid
to the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN went six minutes without a basket in the second half but
never gave up the lead. Hewitt Rolle's putback with 7:52 left put
Northridge up by nine (55-46) and Marco McCain's 3-pointer made it
58-46 at the 7-minute mark.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's steal and layup just before halftime gave CSUN a 35-28
halftime lead. McCain also had a pair of baskets in an 11-0
Matadors run earlier in the half that led to a 33-25 Matadors lead,
and the 6-3 junior guard had nine points in the first 20 minutes,
tying Carl Holmes for the team lead.
</P>
<P>
   Northridge shot 55 percent (16 of 29) in the first half, and
Montana struggled from the floor (39 percent). But the Matadors
only made one of eight 3-point attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Montana, the tournament host for the first time since 1992, took
advantage of sloppy play by the Matadors early and took a 15-7 lead
on Shane Christensen's 3-pointer. Christensen made a combined four
of 17 shots in the teams' two regular-season games.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Arizona 82, Eastern Washington 65: The Lumberjacks shot
61 percent to advance to their third consecutive tournament final.
</P>
<P>
   Ross Land (24), Cory Schwab (20) and Adam Lopez (15) combined to
almost outscore the Eagles (15-12) by themselves for third-seeded
NAU (18-10).
</P>
<P>
   ``Ross, Adam and Cory really got their feet set and got some
good shots,'' NAU coach Mike Adras said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-00 0243EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
