<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CSUN-MONTANA-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE BEATS MONTANA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MISSOULA, Mont. _ Almost a month ago, Carl Holmes stood in a
hallway in this arena and said he believed the Cal State Northridge
men's basketball team was the class of the Big Sky Conference.
</P>
<P>
   One more win, and his teammates will prove Holmes right.
</P>
<P>
   Fifth-seeded CSUN took a lead late in the first half, never
relented and beat tournament favorite Montana 76-65 Friday night to
advance to the conference championship game tonight against
Northern Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The winner gets an automatic bid to the NCAA Tournament.
Northridge, enjoying its finest season at the Division I level,
improved to 20-9. The top-seeded Grizzlies ended their season
17-11.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a dream come true,'' Holmes said after scoring a
team-high 21 points and grabbing seven rebounds. ``This is a great
experience. We're 40 minutes away from going to the NCAA
Tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN coach Bobby Braswell, who has guided the Matadors to two
conference tournament finals in four seasons, said: ``We've had an
up-and-down year. Right now we're playing good basketball and we're
playing unselfishly.''
</P>
<P>
   Montana led 25-24 with 6 minutes, 25 seconds left in the first
half. A layup by Brian Heinle made it 26-25 and the Grizzlies never
led again. CSUN led 35-28 at halftime, 49-43 with 10 minutes left
and 63-49 at the five-minute mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all had one goal in mind and that was to stay on top,''
Heinle said. ``We knew we would do it with defense, and that's what
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Northridge !ital!had!off! to win with defense. The Matadors went
six minutes between field goals in the second half but never
buckled.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got (the lead) down to three or four or five ... we
broke down and turned it over and didn't make a stop on defense,''
said Montana forward Matt Williams, who had 22 points and 10
rebounds in his final game. ``That really hurt us.''
</P>
<P>
   What also hindered the Grizzlies was the shooting of CSUN
reserve guard Marco McCain, who made 7 of 12 shots and had 17
points in only 19 minutes. McCain made three 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   ``At different times we've had different people step up for
us,'' Braswell said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams fouled out with a little less than two minutes left and
CSUN comfortably ahead. He was one of two Grizzlies to foul out;
CSUN had Heinle, Andre Larry and Jeff Parris foul out of its 73-70
overtime loss here on Feb. 17.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Holmes made his declaration. He wasn't being cocky
or petulant, just stating what he believes is fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been working hard all season long to get to this
point,'' Holmes said after Friday night's game. ``Right now our
minds are on winning this tournament. I said before we left
Northridge, we're not coming home with anything less than the
tournament trophy. We're 40 minutes away.''
</P>
<P>
   Third-seeded Northern Arizona (18-10) advanced with an 82-65 win
over No. 2 seed Eastern Washington in the early semifinal. The
Lumberjacks shot 61 percent and got 24 points from senior Ross
Land.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know each other so well,'' NAU coach Mike Adras said about
facing CSUN tonight. ``There won't be any surprises. We're travel
partners. We're even staying in the same hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   The CSUN men join the Matadors women on championship Saturday.
The women, who won the tournament last year, take on No.1 seed
Montana in the final at 1 p.m. Montana, ironically, was the last
school to win the men's and women's title in the same year (1997).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
