<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 10:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3918 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-CZECH-ALBRIGHT-REVIEW     03-11 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CZECH-ALBRIGHT-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO SAY NO IN CZECH: DIPLOMACY OF THE ABSURD 101 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRAGUE, Czech Republic _ From the Annals of Diplomacy (Personnel
Department):
</P>
<P>
   It was March 2000. In 10 months, Madeleine Albright, first
female secretary of state of the United States, would be out of a
job.
</P>
<P>
   So what was a friend to do? As an admirer and what passed in
those days as a philosopher, Vaclav Havel had an idea: Albright
should succeed him as the president of the Czech Republic, her
birthplace.
</P>
<P>
   And as an absurdist playwright, Havel had no intention of taking
no for an answer.
</P>
<P>
   When the idea first floated up from the diplomatic universe of
leaks and hints, two weeks before, Albright scotched it, saying
that however flattered she might be, her loyalties lay with her
adopted country, the United States, which she was serving.
</P>
<P>
   Legally, of course, it was problematic for a government official
to entertain job offers while in office. It was doubly problematic,
then, for a secretary of state, the chief foreign-policy official
of her government, to express any interest in serving another
government, let alone in running it.
</P>
<P>
   After all, what could seem a conflict of interest in some lower
apparatchik might be construed as treason in a secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   But Havel, a patient man with his own domestic political
difficulties, seemed entirely serious _ and unbendingly persistent.
With Albright standing beside him at a memorial to the Czechs'
first democratic president, Thomas G. Masaryk, Havel, the second
democratic president, again pressed Albright to consider becoming
the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally would consider it excellent because, into this
rather stale provincial environment, this would bring an
international spirit,'' Havel told Czech Television in response to
a question that he himself had planted with a reporter covering the
ceremony. ``Someone who knows the world well would come to the
Czech Republic, already understands it, and would be able to act
here with regard to all broader world circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright, clearly not taken by surprise, said nothing. But the
next day she planted a question of her own with a reporter so that
she could utter another polite refusal of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, she had plenty of time to change her mind, with Havel
not scheduled to leave office until 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Still, however tempted she might have been, she did not suggest
that Havel try to succeed President Clinton in the interests of
bringing a new spirit to the ``rather stale, provincial
environment'' of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   She remained too much of a diplomat for that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-00 1057EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000311.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 10:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3820 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-CZECH-ALBRIGHT-REVIEW     03-11 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CZECH-ALBRIGHT-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO SAY NO IN CZECH: DIPLOMACY OF THE ABSURD 101 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
