<HEADER>
A3919 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKE     03-11 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Primary Loser Who's Something of a Winner &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley is going on vacation. John McCain is going back to
the Senate. And Americans who were energized and entertained by
their candidacies have gone into mourning.
</P>
<P>
   That includes the national press corps. ``I now think of John
McCain as `Uncle Fun,''' said Jonathan Alter, the Newsweek writer
and NBC News commentator, after the Super Tuesday drubbings, from
Maine to New York to Ohio to California, that forced McCain and
Bradley out of the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley withdrew from the race Thursday morning, and McCain did
the same an hour later, as he stood in the brilliant sunlight of
Sedona, Ariz. Which was entirely apt, because of the two, McCain
cast the broader shadow. The unlikely coalition he mobilized, of
independents, moderate Republicans and disaffected Democrats, now
constitutes a crucial swing block in the general election, a group
over which the presumptive nominees, Gov. George W. Bush and Vice
President Al Gore, are now expected to wage a fierce contest.
</P>
<P>
   Although neither of the vanquished contenders offered a ringing
endorsement of the survivors, it was McCain who at week's end was
playing the harder to get. Bush, seeking a rapprochement, sent out
feelers; Gore went out of his way to acknowledge McCain and invite
the senator's fans into his tent.
</P>
<P>
   The finality of Super Tuesday, with 16 states voting the closest
the country has come to a national primary, paved the way for a
long general election campaign. With their war chests all but
depleted _ some $200 million was spent on the primary campaign _
and the polls showing a virtual dead heat, Gore and Bush stand
shoulder to shoulder at the starting line.
</P>
<P>
   That, say analysts across the political spectrum, could make
McCain a de facto kingmaker. ``McCain has lost the Republican
nomination,'' said the conservative pundit William Kristol, ``but
he and what he stands for remain the central issues in the
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By PETER MARKS
</P>
<P>
   The 50-Year-Old Man and the Sea
</P>
<P>
   Normally, when crossing an ocean, a traveler might focus on
having enough legroom. Does it concern Remy Bricka? Nah! As he
crosses the Pacific, he'll have all the room he needs. He's
walking.
</P>
<P>
   No, this is not some loopy gimmick. Bricka, for whatever reason,
has done this sort of thing before. His walk across the Atlantic in
1988 landed him in the Guinness Book of World Records.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe ``walk'' isn't the right word. Bricka, a 50-year-old
French entertainer, has mini-canoes on his feet, a paddle and,
behind him, a catamaran for provisions and naps. Presumably he
doesn't have e-mail, but, yes, there is a Web site
(www.stoeffler.com) that, for French speakers, helps track
``l'homme qui marche sur l'eau.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoeffler, a French food company, is sponsoring Bricka's
7,800-mile, six-month slog from Los Angeles to Sydney. The company
provided 22 pounds of sauerkraut.
</P>
<P>
   How did Bricka explain his quest? ``Our time goes quickly,'' he
said. ``I will use my time to realize my dream.'' How did
bystanders react? ``He's crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   Dow Takes a Sharp Drop While Nasdaq Hits a New High  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The tale of two stock markets continued to confound investors.
It was the best of times for the Nasdaq Composite, which surpassed
the 5,000 mark for the first time on rising technology stocks. But
the more established companies in the Dow Jones industrial average
fell, bringing the average down to 9,796.03 on Tuesday. The split
in the two markets reflects investors' ardor for so-called new
economy stocks, thought to be immune to the ill effects of rising
interest rates. But market strategists doubt that hot technology
companies can remain a safe haven forever.
</P>
<P>
   _ By GRETCHEN MORGENSON
</P>
<P>
   The Price for Taking Bribes
</P>
<P>
   China executed Hu Changqing, a former provincial vice governor,
for taking $600,000 in bribes. The government is seeking to
demonstrate its resolve in cracking down on high-level corruption,
which is damaging the Communist Party's reputation. Hu was the
highest official ever put to death for corruption. An investigation
has already linked dozens of relatively high-level local officials
with a $10 billion smuggling ring in Xiamen in southern China. But
many Chinese are skeptical that China's leaders will pursue the
campaign to the top party ranks. When the Xiamen investigation was
about to implicate the wife of the Beijing party chief, Jia
Qinglin, party propaganda departments sprang to life, professing
her innocence.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL
</P>
<P>
   Gassing Up Goes Up
</P>
<P>
   American drivers will have plenty of gasoline this summer, say
Energy Department analysts. And they'll pay plenty for it: a
national average $1.56 for a gallon of regular unleaded, much more
in high-cost areas like New York City and California. By 2001,
prices will be on their way down, the analysts said, assuming that
oil countries step up production, as expected, and that there is no
war in the Middle East. Those are big ifs.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID STOUT
</P>
<P>
   Police Torture Verdict, Part 2  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Three New York City police officers were found guilty of
covering up the vicious assault on Abner Louima in the restroom of
a Brooklyn station house three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The officers _ Charles Schwarz, Thomas Bruder and Thomas Wiese _
were convicted of obstructing justice by lying about Schwarz's role
in the attack. At a previous trial last year, Schwarz was found
guilty of restraining Louima while another officer, Justin A.
Volpe, sodomized him with a broken broomstick.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ALAN FEUER
</P>
<P>
   Sinkhole, Boston Style  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boston's ``Big Dig,'' the monumental project to sink the city's
raised Central Artery underground, is presenting even more of a Big
Bill than expected. Its overseers were grilled by lawmakers about
why the federal- and state-financed project will cost at least $12
billion, not the supposedly set-in-stone $10.8 billion, and why
they did not reveal the overrun earlier. They responded that not
everything is controllable when an undertaking is the most complex
urban infrastructure project in the country's history. They have
until Wednesday to come up with a plan to pay for the overrun.
</P>
<P>
   _ By CAREY GOLDBERG
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
