<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 11:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3921 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      03-11 1545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(lh) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, March 12:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POLITICS (Mexico City) _ For months, Mexico's
presidential race seemed headed inexorably toward a 14th
consecutive victory by the governing party. Suddenly, it has turned
into a real race, because Vicente Fox has made advances that give
him a better chance at the presidency than any other opposition
figure since the Mexican revolution. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   PERU-POLITICS (Tacna, Peru) _ There are eight candidates in the
race against President Alberto K. Fujimori. But their standing is
low. This is in part explained by Fujimori's lasting popularity,
particularly among Peru's large Indian population, which credits
the president with defeating two terrorist groups and ending years
of hyperinflation. But the opposition candidates have also had
trouble gaining traction because, in their view, they are competing
on a tilted playing field. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-PARAMILITARY (Bogota, Colombia) _ His private army has
killed thousands of people in the past decade, making him perhaps
the most feared man in this violent country. But a decision to
submit to a grilling on television early this month has allowed the
paramilitary leader Carlos Castano to come out of the shadows and
present himself as one more victim of the violence he had
previously been seen as personifying here. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DILEMMA (Washington) _ Nine months after they declared
victory in the war over Kosovo, Washington and its NATO allies are
now fighting among themselves over how to prevent a deteriorating
situation in the Serbian province from spinning out of their
control. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-U.S. (Berlin) _ The fiasco over the appointment of a new
managing director for the International Monetary Fund has caused
serious damage to the critical German-U.S. relationship and
revealed deep personal rifts within the governing coalition of
Gerhard Schroeder, the Social Democratic chancellor. By Roger
Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-VOTE-BUYING (Chin Jin, Taiwan) _ Taiwan's voters will
elect a new president on March 18 to succeed Lee Teng-hui. With the
three main candidates locked within a few percentage points of one
another in the polls, party officials are girding themselves for a
spree of vote buying, and opposition and election officials fear
that the practice could play a substantial role in determining the
winner. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN-POLITICS (Madrid, Spain) _ What incumbent would not envy
Spain's prime minister, Jose Maria Aznar? During his four years in
office, Aznar surprised many doubters by successfully guiding Spain
into the European monetary union. And Spain's economy is booming.
Unemployment has dropped to 15 percent from 23 percent. But if
Aznar is the victor in Sunday's elections, it will probably be by a
hair. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   SWISS-CITIZENSHIP (Geneva) _ This weekend, in what some view as
a worrying trend that may fan right-wing xenophobia in Switzerland
and neighboring Austria, voters in an industrial suburb of scenic
Lucerne will get to decide in the most personal way just who should
be a Swiss citizen. Every eligible voter in Emmen has received a
booklet containing family photographs and intensely personal data
on tax status, salary, background and hobbies for each of the 56
people in the town seeking naturalization. By Elizabeth Olson.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-U.N.-DUES (United Nations) _ A long, hard battle to lower
U.S. payments to the United Nations begins next week, and diplomats
from a wide cross-section of nations say there is no guarantee that
the issue will be resolved. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-WORLD-CUP (Johannesburg, South Africa) _ South Africa
kicked off a campaign this week to hold the most important sporting
contest in the country's history when it welcomed a delegation of
international soccer officials who will decide on the country's bid
for the 2006 World Cup. By Henri E. Cauvin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FLA-WATER-SHORTAGE (Land O'Lakes, Fla.) _ There may be water,
water everywhere, but as remarkable as it may seem in Tampa Bay,
there is not enough to drink. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVELING-HABERDASHER (Fairfield, Iowa) _ As the sun rose over
slumbering Iowa cornfields, Tim DeFord rambled along Interstate 80
in an old station wagon stocked with men's suits and shirts.
DeFord, a haberdasher who makes house calls, caters to customers in
little Midwestern towns that no longer have a men's shop. By Dirk
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   GUN-INITIATIVES (Denver) _ Frustrated by their legislatures'
unwillingness to pass new gun-control measures, citizen groups in
three Western states are collecting signatures to put the issues
before voters this fall as ballot initiatives. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   CRAFT-NETWORKS (Honaker, Va.) _ Phyllis Street is about to
plunge into the global economy. The coal miner's widow, who turned
for survival to the quilt maker's arts that run two centuries deep
in her family, will leave her home on Monday for the first airplane
trip of her life. It will be to London, where she will be a star
entry in the Ideal Home Show, Europe's premier exhibition for the
booming crafts industry. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   LEE-HOME (Alexandria, Va.) _ Unable to pay for the upkeep of a
museum, a Civil War historical preservation group has sold the home
where Confederate Gen. Robert E. Lee grew up to a couple who intend
to turn it into their own.
</P>
<P>
   FIREFIGHTER-RAMPAGE (Memphis, Tenn.) _ As funerals began
Saturday for victims of an off-duty firefighter's shooting spree
here on Wednesday, authorities said the alleged gunman has not yet
explained exactly what drove him to murder his wife, a deputy
sheriff and two fellow firefighters who came to his home to put out
the blaze he had set there. By Emily Yellin.
</P>
<P>
   OCEAN-WALKER (Los Angeles) _ The journey of an Alsatian man who
intended to walk cross the Pacific Ocean from Los Angeles to
Sydney, Australia, came to a rapid end about 30 miles off the coast
of Los Angeles this week, when his sleeping quarters were destroyed
by debris in a storm.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   OIL-POLITICS (Washington) _ Republicans in Congress have begun
to blame the Clinton administration generally and Vice President Al
Gore in particular for the recent jump in the price of gasoline,
and that seems sure to become a hot issue in the presidential race.
By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   NOMINATION-SYSTEM (Washington) _ This year's primary season was
far more competitive, far more engaging to the voters and far more
compelling a story than almost anyone expected. There is just one
problem, critics of the nominating system say. It is, essentially,
over, even though more than half of the states have yet to hold
nominating contests for one or both parties. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-VOTERS (Seattle) _ The McCain voter is America's hottest
political quarry these days. But while the bloc has come to be
hugely significant in electoral terms, interviews with dozens of
such voters here in Washington state, and in Michigan,
Massachusetts and California, vividly confirmed what polls have
suggested from the outset: beyond their allegiance to McCain and a
somewhat vague banner of reform, there seemed to be virtually
nothing that amounted to a common bond in their political views. By
Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   GORE (Dateline TK) _ An exclusive interview.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-BRIEFS _ The early line for vice presidential
nominees; Waiting for Perot may be in vain; Falwell's crusade:
Voter registration; One candidate's way of getting attention. By B.
Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Message in a Viagra Bottle. By Maureen
Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   KRUGMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Are we scamming ourselves? By Paul
Krugman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS-BUDGET _ A rundown of sports stories will move by 1 p.m.
ET.
</P>
<P>
   AM-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ A description of the front page layout of the
first edition of The New York Times will move at 12 p.m.
