with Syria to provide a mechanism and cover for the withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   It was revealing that instead of unalloyed satisfaction at the
prospect of seeing the back of retreating Israeli soldiers,
Lebanese and Syrian officials reacted to the news with immense
pique.
</P>
<P>
   The view in Israel, expressed with no lack of self-satisfaction,
is that Syria has now lost a bargaining chip in its dealings with
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   If there are no more Israelis to kick around in southern
Lebanon, this reasoning goes, it will be too risky diplomatically
and militarily for Syria to allow Hezbollah to continue its
attacks, because the only Israeli targets would be in Israel
itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Syrians want a deal, then unilateral withdrawal will
facilitate it,'' said Foreign Minister David Levy last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli move also undercuts the unusual outbreak of Arab
solidarity that emerged in the last three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the Hezbollah attacks in the security zone in
southern Lebanon, in which seven Israelis were eventually killed,
Israel mounted fierce bombing raids on Lebanese civilian targets.
The destruction of Lebanese electrical generating plants galvanized
the Arab Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Within a week, senior Arab officials were making the pilgrimage
to Beirut to pledge solidarity with Lebanon against Israel and its
occupying force. Even Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, a staunch
advocate of reconciliation between Arab states and Israel, flew to
Lebanon to show his support _ the first time he had ever visited.
</P>
<P>
   It was the greatest display of Arab unity in more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Yet with a single vote in the Cabinet, Israel cracked the common
front. Although nearly all of Israel's neighbors in the Middle East
expressed reservations about a unilateral withdrawal from southern
Lebanon, none could complain too loudly after so forcefully and
recently calling for an end to the Israeli occupation.
</P>
<P>
   Rearranging the board, however, is not all to Israel's
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah remains a political force in Lebanon, one that might
become especially emboldened after an Israeli withdrawal to demand
a bigger role in the political and military life of the country. Or
a unilateral Israeli pullout could be followed by still more
attacks and counter-attacks that might escalate to involve Syria or
destabilize Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   A fractured Lebanon is a frightening prospect. For the many Arab
states, it evokes the long civil war that, in 1989, prompted them
to invite Syria to enter Lebanon to bring order. And for Israel,
instability in Lebanon was the justification for invading the
country in 1982, the beginning of the nightmare that is ending only
now.
</P>
</TEXT>
