<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Sunday, March 12. The N.Y. Times News Service supervisor is
Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927; e-mail:
lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DILEMMA (Washington) _ Nine months after they declared
victory in the war over Kosovo, Washington and its NATO allies are
now fighting among themselves over how to prevent a deteriorating
situation in the Serbian province from spinning out of their
control. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 2 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POLITICS (Mexico City) _ For months, Mexico's
presidential race seemed headed inexorably toward a 14th
consecutive victory by the governing party. Suddenly, it has turned
into a real race, because Vicente Fox has made advances that give
him a better chance at the presidency than any other opposition
figure since the Mexican revolution. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 1 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   OIL-POLITICS (Washington) _ Republicans in Congress have begun
to blame the Clinton administration generally and Vice President Al
Gore in particular for the recent jump in the price of gasoline,
and that seems sure to become a hot issue in the presidential race.
By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 2 p.m. ET in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   FLA-WATER-SHORTAGE (Land O'Lakes, Fla.) _ There may be water,
water everywhere, but as remarkable as it may seem in Tampa Bay,
there is not enough to drink. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 2 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-VOTERS (Seattle) _ The McCain voter is America's hottest
political quarry these days. But while the bloc has come to be
hugely significant in electoral terms, interviews with dozens of
such voters here in Washington state, and in Michigan,
Massachusetts and California, vividly confirmed what polls have
suggested from the outset: beyond their allegiance to McCain and a
somewhat vague banner of reform, there seemed to be virtually
nothing that amounted to a common bond in their political views. By
Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 2 p.m. ET in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   TRAVELING-HABERDASHER (Fairfield, Iowa) _ As the sun rose over
slumbering Iowa cornfields, Tim DeFord rambled along Interstate 80
in an old station wagon stocked with men's suits and shirts.
DeFord, a haberdasher who makes house calls, caters to customers in
little Midwestern towns that no longer have a men's shop. By Dirk
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 1 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   IMMIG-EDUC (New York) _ It is the second week of school, and
Kathleen Sampson has been presenting the same lesson for several
days: ``Amina is from Somalia. Somalia is in Africa. Da Quan is
from China. China is in Asia.'' She builds sentences using facts
about the students in the classroom, repeating them over and over.
This is not first grade, but ninth grade at Liberty High School in
Manhattan, with immigrants 14 to 17 years old. These teen-agers
have arrived from all corners of the earth with one thing in
common: little or no education. By Karen W. Arenson.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 2 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
