<DOCNO> NYT20000311.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 11:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3829 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-GEFFEN-BIO-REVIEW-NYT     03-11 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEFFEN-BIO-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GEFFEN BIOGRAPHY: NOT READY FOR HIS CLOSE-UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ He had a quick temper, and friends found it ugly. He
was profane, rapacious and Machiavellian _ a brilliant strategist
who rarely took a step without anticipating the consequences. He
wept easily _ but one film director said he fed on other people
with the hunger of a praying mantis.
</P>
<P>
   These harsh comments were made about the legendary Hollywood
moguls David O. Selznick, Harry Cohn and Louis B. Mayer. Compared
with these men _ whom he idolizes _ David Geffen, the billionaire
entertainment mogul, seems almost benign. Yet Geffen is outraged
and depressed about a new biography, ``The Operator,'' published by
Random House last week, that depicts him as _ surprise! surprise! _
smart, ruthless, abrasive, calculating, generous and complicated.
</P>
<P>
   What especially disturbs Geffen is that he handpicked his
biographer, Tom King. King believes he was chosen because he is a
reporter with The Wall Street Journal and because, like Geffen,
he's gay. What Geffen wanted was a book that treated him like the
Omaha investor Warren Buffett _ another idol. But his personality
is more colorful than that of Buffett, who never wanted to marry
Cher or pal around with Calvin Klein.
</P>
<P>
   So Geffen got a warts-and-all biography that, while hardly
flattering, is not quite as brutal as he says it is. The book
details Geffen's climb from an unhappy Brooklyn boyhood to the
pinnacle of Hollywood success in the music business and, currently,
as a partner at DreamWorks SKG. Along the way, his relationships
soured with several artist-clients and music executives, and he is
portrayed, at worst, as a bully willing to sacrifice friends to
achieve enormous wealth.
</P>
<P>
   ``David very much wanted a serious book about him,'' King said.
``I think he was bowled over by the notion that a Wall Street
Journal reporter would spend two years examining his life.'' King
said it was ``enormously brave'' of Geffen to open virtually every
door to him, including interviews with a psychiatrist the mogul saw
as a child and several former lovers. ``Even though David withdrew
his cooperation roughly halfway through,'' he said, ``to my
knowledge he didn't once tell people after that point that they
shouldn't talk to me.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the Geffen book follows two biographical
traditions. One is of the well-known, powerful and controlling
subject seeking a respectable biographer _ but then not wanting
candor. The most recent example is Edmund Morris' biography of
Ronald Reagan, ``Dutch'' (Random House, 1999). Morris, a Pulitzer
Prize winner who was handpicked by the Reagans, spent 10 years
researching the former president's life and created a bizarre
biography, using fictional devices. The portrayal was extremely
harsh.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the Hollywood tradition of biographies _ often
by writers who are either flattered and intimidated by their
subjects or come to loathe them. ( King seems neutral about
Geffen.) Certainly Geffen took an unusual risk that other Hollywood
moguls, like Michael Ovitz and Michael Eisner, avoided. He sought a
serious biographer who controlled what he wrote. Compare that with
Ovitz, whose pallid biography in 1997 never caused a stir. Or
compare it with Eisner, whose autobiographical book, ``Work in
Progress'' (Random House, 1998), was criticized for its lack of
candor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Biographies here tend to be simplistic, veering from
hagiography to portrait of the devil as a young man,'' said Robert
Bookman, a top literary agent at Creative Artists Agency. ``They're
often either black or white, as opposed to a more complex and
realistic portrayal.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeanine Basinger, chairman of the film studies department at
Wesleyan University and author of several scholarly books about
Hollywood, put it another way: ``There's sort of an attitude _
everyone hates a mogul. If you write a nasty book about a star,
half the people out there may be fans who won't like it and won't
buy it. But if you write about a mogul, no one cares. No one
defends moguls. They don't have fans. They're guys who care about
money and power.''
</P>
<P>
   Geffen cares, most certainly, about money and power. But he is
not quite in the same league as the great moguls of the 1930s and
'40s whose power and cultural influence _ far more than he has ever
had _ were matched by outsized, often savage personalities. In his
book ``An Empire of Their Own'' (Crown, 1988), Neal Gabler called
Jack Warner, who founded Warner Brothers with his brother, Harry,
``crude, vulgar, shallow, flashy, contrary and galling.'' ( Geffen
purchased Harry Warner's 13,600-square-foot mansion in Beverly
Hills, and all its contents, for $47.5 million in 1990.)
</P>
<P>
   The brilliant but irascible Harry Cohn, who built a movie empire
as president of Columbia Pictures, kept a photo of Mussolini in his
office. ``He was the meanest man I ever knew _ an unreconstructed
dinosaur,'' Budd Schulberg, the writer, once said.
</P>
<P>
   Cohn provoked perhaps the most famous quotation ever made about
a Hollywood mogul. His funeral in 1958 included some of the biggest
stars in town. Mourners packed two studio sound stages. After
attending the funeral, the comedian Red Skelton said, ``Well, it
only proves what they always say _ give the public something they
want to see, and they'll come out for it.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Geffen, the archetype of the contemporary mogul, is
complex, benevolent at times with his money and even a bit
vulnerable. But a mogul is a mogul. ``None of these guys got to be
moguls by being a boy scout,'' King said. On that point, Geffen
would probably agree with his biographer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-00 1137EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
