<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000311.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 12:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3937 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-TRAVELING-HABERDASHER     03-11 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVELING-HABERDASHER-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN RURAL MIDWEST, THE SUIT GOES SHOPPING FOR THE MAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients. A map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAIRFIELD, Iowa _ As the sun rose over slumbering Iowa
cornfields, Tim DeFord rambled along Interstate 80 in an old
station wagon stocked with men's suits and shirts. A haberdasher
who makes house calls, DeFord caters to customers in little
Midwestern towns that no longer have a men's shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can size a guy up over the phone,'' said DeFord, 43,
reaching under the car's front seat for a metal box that held the
names and addresses of his far-flung customers. ``I ask their
height and weight. And if a guy says, `Oh, I guess I weigh about
210, maybe 215,' I write down 230.''
</P>
<P>
   DeFord owns Lord's Fine Men's Wear in Perry, about 30 miles
northwest of Des Moines, a store that would have closed long ago,
meeting the fate of so many small-town shops, if DeFord did not
keep his business alive by traveling to customers in places where
men's shops have disappeared, towns like Indianola and Keosauqua,
Webster City and Oskaloosa.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, stores of all kinds on Main Street have been dying,
as shoppers have turned to big shopping centers and outlet malls,
even if it means a long drive. But for men's shops, it is not just
the competition that has changed, but the customers. Americans have
gone to casual attire.
</P>
<P>
   Workplaces now routinely allow employees to ``dress down.''
Principal, a big insurance company in Des Moines, has adopted a
policy of letting workers dress informally. In the computer field,
a suit is about as common as a manual typewriter. When they go to
the opera or to church, people wear blue jeans and T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go into some of these places, and there aren't 25 men in
town who wear a suit to work,'' said DeFord, who carries brands
like Austin Reed, Christian Books and Warren Sowell. ``But for
those 25 guys, somebody's got to sell them a suit.''
</P>
<P>
   From Interstate 80, DeFord turned off at Oskaloosa, passing
Happy Joe's ice cream parlor and the A.D. Gun store, then turned
off on a hilly country road just west of Ottumwa, before cruising
past faded barns and grain elevators into Fairfield, a town of
10,000 people, where his first customer of the day, Stew Gaumer,
54, was waiting for the clothier at Agri-Industrial Products.
</P>
<P>
   ``Got some nice slacks, Stew,'' DeFord told Gaumer, after a
handshake, some pleasantries and a word about the balmy weather.
</P>
<P>
   The two men retreated to a conference room for privacy, as
DeFord laid out six pairs of trousers on a table. Gaumer, a
53-year-old salesman, slipped off his pants to try on a new pair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cuff or plain hem, Stew?'' DeFord asked, bending to his knees
to measure the fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cuff,'' Gaumer replied.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the slacks on the table, Gaumer chose three: navy,
khaki and olive.
</P>
<P>
   ``That'll do it,'' said Gaumer, who was in a hurry to catch a
plane for a business trip to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   As he wrote a check, Gaumer talked about the convenience of this
style of shopping.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could drive 60 miles to a mall in Iowa City and waste half a
day,'' Gaumer said. ``Here we started at 10 minutes to 10. Now
we're all done, and it's not even 10 o'clock yet.''
</P>
<P>
   DeFord, a tall, angular man with reddish hair graying at the
temples, hurried back to his station wagon, fired the engine and
drove off to his next stop: Henderson's frame shop and gallery.
</P>
<P>
   At the store, Don Henderson shouted a friendly greeting, but
pointed to a line of customers and lifted his palms to the sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm awful busy right now,'' Henderson said. ``Can you come
back later?''
</P>
<P>
   DeFord nodded, then headed back to the car, and drove a few
blocks to Central Valley Bank, just to chat for a minute with Greg
Lowenberg, an old customer, about his latest fishing exploits.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Back out on the sidewalk of Burlington Avenue, DeFord was
stopped by a woman who shouted, ``Hey, you're the traveling clothes
man.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Rose Kennedy, who runs a real estate office in downtown
Fairfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband bought a pair of pants from you last summer,''
Kennedy explained. ``Well, he's quit smoking and gained some
weight. So he needs to have them let out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is he around?'' DeFord asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's down at the carwash now,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we'll try him later,'' the clothier assured her.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Then it was on to another bank, the Iowa State Bank &AMP; Trust,
where Jerry Green, 43, was waiting for his new suit.
</P>
<P>
   On an earlier trip, Green had selected a swatch of clothing for
a custom-made suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``That feels right,'' Green said, as he slipped on the trousers
in a basement meeting room, ``as long as I don't gain some
weight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Want some more room?'' DeFord asked him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah,'' he replied, ``I'd just fill it up.''
</P>
<P>
   As soon as he measured the fit, DeFord tried to make another
sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Want to look at some ties?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' Green said, a bit apologetically.
</P>
<P>
   DeFord slapped down a dress shirt on the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real dress, French cuffs,'' DeFord told him. ``I'd really
like to get your shirt business.''
</P>
<P>
   Green told him he would think about it.
</P>
<P>
   Next it was back to Don Henderson's store, where his wife,
Donna, explained that he had run out on a key job, part of his
locksmithing sideline in the frame business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry,'' she said, ``he'll be back in the late afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
   On every road trip to Fairfield, which DeFord makes once or
twice a week, he makes time for a retired clothier, Ralph Perry,
who ran the finest men's shop in town for 30 years until retiring
in 1981. In almost every town, DeFord calls on the retired
haberdashers, partly for advice, partly for leads on customers.
</P>
<P>
   Green, 81, who favored skinny long brown cigarettes and long,
colorful stories, took a seat in a rocking chair and thanked DeFord
for the visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' he said, ``I tell people around here that they can
trust you.''
</P>
<P>
   DeFord nodded appreciatively.
</P>
<P>
   Perry quickly moved to one of his favorite topics, the
unpardonable dressing habits of Americans today. The leisure suit,
as he recalls it, was the beginning of the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd go to a funeral and see pallbearers wearing leisure
suits,'' he said, grimacing as if he had just bit into a lemon.
``It was a disgusting development.''
</P>
<P>
   DeFord said he knew too well about the changed dressing habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could put my inventory on the sidewalk with a sign that says
`free' and half the people in the town would walk right past it,''
he said. ``They'd think, `Now what would I want to put that in my
closet for?'''
</P>
<P>
   Perry told him that all was not lost. There were still some
people out there with taste and standards in dressing themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've got a group of people you enjoy pleasing,'' Green
said, ``gosh that's dandy.''
</P>
<P>
   The protege and the mentor shook hands and said goodbye until
the next time.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Back on the road, DeFord headed to a newer neighborhood of
Fairfield, turned down a winding street and pulled into the
driveway.
</P>
<P>
   Standing at the front door, Leland Gookin waved the clothier
inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're talking thunderstorms,'' Gookin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ground needs the moisture,'' the clothier said.
</P>
<P>
   The two men nodded. Then it was time to get down to business.
</P>
<P>
   Gookin was not an easy fit for a sport coat: size 46 short.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take a look at this,'' DeFord said, holding up a sport coat
for Gookin to inspect. ``It's got some blue in it, some tan, maybe
some olive. You could wear it all year round.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I don't know,'' Gookin said. ``I just don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Go look in the mirror, Leland,'' the clothier said. ``Give it
a look.''
</P>
<P>
   Gookin walked to a mirror, then returned to the living room,
where DeFord waited with hope for a sale on the $240 coat.
</P>
<P>
   But Gookin was still uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   It was time for more small talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``How's that Mercury of yours?'' asked DeFord, who knew how
Gookin loved his 1957 vintage automobile, the one in a framed
photograph in the living room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Got it stored in the garage uptown for now,'' Gookin answered,
as he turned back to the sport coat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't I leave it here for your wife to look at it when she
comes back,'' DeFord said as he lay the sport coat on the couch.
``She's your fashion adviser, right.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Out in the car, DeFord said he knew it would be a struggle to
make a sale without a woman on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys of a certain generation,'' he said, ``they've never
bought clothes by themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As the clock neared noon, DeFord drove to a Hardy's restaurant,
his usual stop in Fairfield, and ordered lunch. Wearing a dark
suit, crisp white shirt, print tie and tassled loafers, the
clothier had a hamburger and a carton of milk.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in my business are better off if they don't have a
memory,'' he said, talking about earlier times, when people dressed
to the nines. ``The old days are gone, and they're not coming
back.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon, DeFord made his third trip to Henderson's
frame shop.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the store, the salesman admired some prints on the wall
and waited, until Henderson, 53, who was working behind the
counter, called out: ``I guess I'm ready.''
</P>
<P>
   The two men retreated to a back room, and DeFord laid out eight
or nine shirts and a handful of ties on a work table.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson, who said he counted on DeFord to ``keep my colors a
little bit coordinated,'' considered his choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a wedding coming up,'' he said, ``so I need a good
summer shirt.''
</P>
<P>
   DeFord pointed to a tie with a Norman Rockwell print.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kind of neat for a guy in a gallery, don't you think?'' the
salesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson was not convinced.
</P>
<P>
   But he did like two of the dress shirts, especially after his
wife, Donna, said she liked them.
</P>
<P>
   ``That should fit the bill,'' Henderson said as he hurried back
to wait on a customer at the counter.
</P>
<P>
   It was past nine o'clock that night by the time DeFord had seen
his last customer of the day. He got a room at the Super 8 motel,
and prepared to get up early for the next day's rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't worry about the competition,'' DeFord said. ``Nobody
is going to work this hard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
