</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-PRINCES-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM THE RULING CLASS, MEET THE NEXT PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(DUPLICATION NOTICE: Also filed in `a' category) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of them was born just a dozen blocks from the White House
and reared, at least when Congress was in session, in a hotel set
amid the embassies of Washington. The other knew 1600 Pennsylvania
Avenue as the place where his father worked for a dozen years in
successive jobs: vice president of the United States for two-thirds
of that time, president for the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Their parallel paths of privilege took them past landmarks that
were different in name but identical in spirit: St. Albans School
and Harvard University for one, Phillips Academy and Yale
University for the other.
</P>
<P>
   And politics pumped so strongly in their blood that one of them
first ran for a seat in the House of Representatives _ the same
seat his father had once occupied _ in 1976, at the age of just 28.
(He won.) The other lagged only two years behind, making his own
bid for Congress in 1978 at the age of 32. (He lost.)
</P>
<P>
   Now, despite all the primary-season chatter about giving
Americans a new kind of politics, despite the tussles in both
parties over which presidential contender could bring a fresh and
unjaded perspective to governing, the contest has narrowed to these
two: Albert A. Gore Jr. and George W. Bush, a former senator's only
son and a former president's firstborn _ namesakes and political
princes with dissimilar styles but astonishingly similar
inheritances.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential historians and political analysts said they could
not recall a previous election in American history when the
nominees (presumptive, for now) of both major parties were not only
such prominent political heirs but also from such similar stations
and members of the same generation.
</P>
<P>
   That equivalence could simply be accidental, the analysts said,
but several said it speaks in part to the state of politics and the
mood of the electorate. It also imbues this year's presidential
race with an unusual and fascinating dynamic: among the challenges
facing both Vice President Gore and Bush, the Texas governor, is
how they relate to their political ancestries, particularly the
degree to which they reap the benefits of their backgrounds while
avoiding the drawbacks. That balancing act has been a theme in both
men's careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think either of them is going to have a slogan of
`Vote for me, keep the tradition alive,''' said Bill Carrick, a
Democratic strategist, adding that such bald elevations of pedigree
over merit would surely invite rejection.
</P>
<P>
   But to some extent, he and other political analysts noted, the
Democratic voters who backed Gore and the Republican voters who
supported Bush were indeed choosing to keep certain traditions
alive.
</P>
<P>
   In Gore's case, the more relevant tradition may have been the
last seven years of the Clinton administration. But in the cases of
both candidates, voters were choosing someone with an almost
congenital grasp of politics, all the social and material
advantages that went along with that life style and milieu and a
relative unfamiliarity with hardship or tests of character on the
scale of Sen. John McCain's five and a half years as a prisoner of
war in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bush both dealt with that war in a way that reflected
their memberships in a younger, more coddled generation. Gore went
to Vietnam, but only briefly, and as an Army journalist. Bush got a
coveted spot as a pilot in the Texas Air National Guard and was
able to stay close to home.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were in a recessionary period, where class distinctions
are more on the surface, there might have been more of a dialogue
about that,'' said Don Sipple, a Republican strategist. Similarly,
he said, if the nation were in the grip of a crisis, voters might
reject any semblance of the status quo and seek someone who seemed
just a bit more idiosyncratic and adventurous, a bit less destined.
</P>
<P>
   A brief period of economic fright yielded the man from Hope,
Bill Clinton. A nationally devastating corruption of the public
trust yielded the man from Plains, Jimmy Carter. With the world
relatively peaceful and the nation phenomenally prosperous, there
is no such invitation this time around for a slightly unusual
upstart or self-styled maverick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Bradley or McCain understood that,'' said
Celinda Lake, a Democratic pollster. ``There's sometimes an
assumption that Americans are risk-takers in good times. But
Americans are really only risk-takers in bad times. There's a real
interest out there in finding someone who is going to preserve what
we have, someone who knows the ropes.''
</P>
<P>
   Lake said that in some focus groups she has conducted, voters
expressed both an assumption that Bush might call his father at
crucial times and a sense of comfort _ not alarm _ in that
likelihood.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, Bush and their supporters say it is the men's
accomplishments that have made them credible presidential
contenders. But their ancestries undeniably helped start and guide
them on their way in politics, providing them with networks, access
to money, instantly high profiles and other tactical advantages.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, their fathers' careers _ especially their failures
_ taught them valuable lessons, some reflected in their current
campaigns. When Albert Gore Sr.'s many distinguished years as a
senator from Tennessee ended with his defeat at the polls in 1970,
one reason was his Republican rival's nasty and negative approach,
which Gore did not match. His son exhibited no such reticence in
taking on former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey over the last nine
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``His father's political demise was as instructive to him as
anything that his father did while in office,'' said Bill Turque,
author of a recent biography of the vice president, ``Inventing Al
Gore'' (Houghton Mifflin). ``It taught him the power of attack
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has a similar reference point: his father's failed bid for
a second term as president in 1992. President Bush ran a campaign
more responsive than assertive and hampered by dissension and
disloyalty in the ranks. His son sought to avoid those mistakes,
quickly putting McCain on the defensive and entrusting his effort
to a tightly knit circle of longtime political allies.
</P>
<P>
   And yet both candidates' relationships to their patrimony are
more complicated. They recognize that if they seem to be trading
too heavily on their backgrounds, it could turn off voters. They
also realize that their backgrounds inform and play into some of
their most potent liabilities: in Gore's case, that his life and
world view are utterly circumscribed by politics; in Bush's case,
that his late-blooming political prominence is the result of his
father's connections, not his own talents and toilings.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the years between 1992, when Gore won the vice presidency and
his father said publicly that ``we raised him for it,'' and 1998,
when his father died, Gore's advisers sometimes sought to steer
reporters away from his dad.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Gore almost constantly invokes Albert Gore Sr. on
the campaign trail, but largely to emphasize what a self-made man
his father was. He mentions that his father was poor and had to
attend law school at night. The vice president need not worry that
voters will think he is trying to trade on Americans' affection for
his father, because only older voters in Tennessee would have the
requisite memory of the man.
</P>
<P>
   Former President George Bush, by contrast, is keenly remembered
_ he left office only seven years ago _ and that creates both an
added impetus for his son to mention him and a greater danger that
some voters will raise an eyebrow when he does so. So the Texas
governor is artful and sparing about it.
</P>
<P>
   For much of last year, Bush's stump speech included a passage in
which he acknowledged that the leap from governor to president
would be a big one. ``But,'' he added, `'I've had some pretty good
training.''
</P>
<P>
   He then went on to talk about running Texas, but the pauses he
took before and after that line, and the applause it reliably
elicited, left no doubt about its intent. Bush was saying, without
quite saying, that being his father's son should give Americans
some reassurance.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the New Hampshire primary, Bush and his advisers
abandoned such subtlety, putting the governor's parents on a stage
with him. The event was deemed by many to be a disaster, signaling
to voters that a torch was being passed, rather than earned.
</P>
<P>
   It was odd, because Bush usually goes out of his way to avoid
that impression. His almost strenuously folksy side _ the cowboy
boots he sometimes wears, the hyper-informal manner that recently
prompted him to address several of the physicians at a recent
campaign event as ``Doc'' _ seems like a self-conscious purging of
the blue in his blood.
</P>
<P>
   Gore takes his own stabs at a common touch. Did you know that he
once lived in a trailer park? That he likes and watches ``The
Simpsons''? Voters at his town hall-style meetings do, because Gore
has made a point of telling them.
</P>
<P>
   It promises a somewhat surreal spectacle between now and
November: two candidates whose life stories could not be more
entwined in establishment politics, and whose current situations
owe a great deal to those circumstances, competing to convince
Americans that they have just the right distance from it all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
