A3950 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-F16-SALES-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      03-11 0399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-F16-SALES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHICH ONE HAS THE EXTRA LEGROOM? 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When the United Arab Emirates bought 80 Block 60
F-16 fighter jets from Lockheed Martin Corp. in February, it got
special fuel tanks above the wing, a new color cockpit display, a
forward-looking infrared targeting system and a radar dish in the
nose cone.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the emirates are an oil-rich ally, and the United
States wants them to have a robust (and expensive) air defense.
</P>
<P>
   The F-16 is among the world's most sophisticated fighter jets.
Lockheed Martin has sold 3,992 of them since production began in
1978, for more than $50 billion. Foreign nations bought 1,686 of
those. Over the past 10 years F-16s have been purchased by Egypt,
Israel, Turkey, South Korea, Bahrain, Greece and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   Each of these sales must be approved by the State Department,
which determines just how sophisticated these planes should be. The
department must ask the following questions: Does Washington trust
the purchasing government? Does it have nearby enemies? Is it an
enemy of one of America's friends? Depending on the answers, the
purchaser may, like the emirates, get the highest performing
machine money can buy. Or something less.
</P>
<P>
   For example, when Washington allowed Block 50 model F-16s to be
sold to Greece and Turkey, there was just enough difference between
the two planes to maintain something like a strategic balance
between those rivalrous nations.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey got the basic model with night-time capability, use of
precision weaponry and the exterior lantern system for targeting
and navigation. Greece, with a much smaller fighter fleet, bought
the Block 50 plus model, with greater range and an internal
electronic warfare system that could presumably confound Turkey's
radar system.
</P>
<P>
   When Taiwan bought some F-16s several years ago, the United
States, to calm China, would only approve sales of the older Block
20 model. But they also quietly approved the latest onboard
avionics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-00 1221EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000311.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 12:21 </DATE_TIME>
