<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, March 12, moved Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   This final budget adds F16-SALES-REVIEW and eliminates
HEALTHCARE-PERKS-REVIEW.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-PRINCES-REVIEW (Undated) _ Despite all the
primary-season chatter about a new kind of politics, the contest
has narrowed to these two: Albert A. Gore Jr. and George W. Bush, a
senator's only son and a president's firstborn, and their
respective namesakes. They are political princes with dissimilar
styles but astonishingly similar inheritances. Historians and
political analysts cannot recall an election when both nominees
came of age in the same generation and circumstances. By Frank
Bruni. (`a' category)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-PUTIN-PETER-REVIEW (Undated) _ A portrait of Peter the
Great hangs in the office of Vladimir Putin. Those who have heard
Putin's paeans to free enterprise and democracy will find this
heartening, invoking an image of Peter as the Westernizing reformer
and the scourge of Russia's xenophobes. Others, who have nervously
watched Putin destroy Grozny or have sensed his belief in a
powerful Russian state, might find the identification alarming,
recalling Peter's singleminded pursuit of a mighty empire. So it
may be helpful to look back at who Czar Peter I really was. By
Serge Schmemann. (`i' category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moved in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH-POLITICS-REVIEW (Atlanta) _ The South was once solidly
Democratic, then began to shift toward being solidly Republican.
But for now, it seems to be a region where, depending on the place,
the year, the candidates, their resources, the economy and the
issues, either party can prevail. Because the South is more
conservative than other regions, it poses a challenge for Democrat
Al Gore. But in the last two years, Southern Democrats have managed
to stall the GOP advance, and some believe this offers hope for
Gore. If he can split the South, as Bill Clinton did by winning 4
of 11 states in 1992 and 1996, Gore is likely to follow his mentor
to the Oval Office. By Kevin Sack. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-APOLOGY-REVIEW (Undated) _ Pope John Paul II's apology for
historical transgressions committed in the name of the Catholic
Church is remarkable but should be viewed within its theological
context _ it will, after all, take place during a Mass and is
consistent with the Christian requirement of repentance for
misdeeds. In an ecumenical sense, the apology is the dramatic
culmination of an unusual period of public penance by major
Christian groups. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   GEFFEN-BIO-REVIEW (Hollywood) _ Entertainment mogul David Geffen
is angry about a new biography, ``The Operator,'' that depicts him
as smart, ruthless, abrasive, calculating, generous and
complicated. But while hardly flattering, it's not quite as brutal
as he says it is. It follows two biographical traditions: that of a
famous and powerful subject seeking a respectable biographer _ but
then not wanting the author to probe too deeply _ and that of the
traditional Hollywood biography _ often by writers who are either
flattered and intimidated by their subjects or who have come to
loathe them. By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   HACKER-HANDLES-REVIEW (Undated) _ The fascination with malicious
hacker culture has spawned a profusion of wannabes who tend to be
adolescent denizens of online chat rooms and Internet junkies who
assume nicknames meant to convey tough-guy personas with super-hero
powers but whose actual intimidation factor is closer to Super
Nerd. Indeed, their real threat to national security might be
starting a run on acne medication, but judging from their online
handles, you'd think some of these pretenders could wipe out the
Kremlin with a keystroke while bench-pressing Rush Limbaugh. By
Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-INSULTS-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ Hand-wringing aside,
negative campaigning has been shown to work. But what more can
George W. Bush and Al Gore say after they've called each other a
fool, a liar, a bigot and worse? Plenty, one suspects. As a public
service, here is a trove of insults that can be adapted phase by
phase as the campaign takes off.
</P>
<P>
   F16-SALES-REVIEW (Washington) _ A look at issues involved in
U.S. sales of F-16 fighter aircraft to other countries. By
Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
