<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 12:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3965 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NOMINATION-SYSTEM-NYT     03-11 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOMINATION-SYSTEM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH THE RACES OVER, A QUESTION REMAINS: DID THE SYSTEM WORK ? 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ROBIN TONER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ This year's primary season was far more
competitive, far more engaging to the voters and far more
compelling a story line than almost anyone expected.
</P>
<P>
   There is just one problem, critics of the nominating system say.
It is, essentially, over. Even though more than half of the states
have yet to hold nominating contests for one or both parties. And
more than half of the delegates in both parties have yet to be
chosen. And fewer than half of the Americans surveyed last week by
Harvard's Shorenstein Center said they had even settled on a
favorite candidate in the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, nobody quite knows what will happen to voter interest
and engagement in the five-month lull between the de facto end of
the primaries and the party conventions, which traditionally kick
off the general election campaign. But the sense of
disenfranchisement in the states that have not yet held primaries
or caucuses is likely to be strong, and some analysts predict that
turnout, which set records this year on the Republican side, will
plummet.
</P>
<P>
   In Illinois, which holds its primary March 21, Jack Tatooles,
co-chairman of the John McCain for President campaign, said simply,
``It's just not fair.''
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, some politicians and analysts say, the primary
system worked well for the two parties this year, settling on the
two candidates, Vice President Al Gore and Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas, who had the deepest support among the party establishment.
``Having said that,'' said William E. Brock, who is heading the
Republican Party's Advisory Commission on the Presidential
Nominating Process, ``the process, I think, argues even more
strongly for some remediation, some improvements.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is, I think, fair to say that the nominations are over
before the great majority of Americans even focused on the
question. We had, almost, a national primary, and yet well over
half the American people had no voice,'' said Brock, a former
senator and chairman of the Republican National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Andrew, national chairman of the Democratic National
Committee, said, ``The real answer is we don't know yet how it
worked, and ultimately I don't think we'll know until we see what
turnout looks like in the fall, because our ultimate goal is
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, both parties say they are pushing ahead with their
efforts to explore a major restructuring of the primary system,
although no decisions have yet been made. (The nominees themselves,
of course, will play a major role in party affairs.) The
Republicans are under the greatest time pressures, because their
party's rules require that any changes to the system for 2004 must
be approved at this summer's convention.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Nicholson, chairman of the Republican National Committee,
said that without some action, more states will inevitably move
their primaries earlier on the calendar to have more of an
influence, putting the party ``on a trail inexorably to a national
primary day, and I think that's bad.''
</P>
<P>
   What many students of the nominating system prefer is some
system that gives lesser-known insurgent candidates at least a
chance to build support, gives various regions of the country a
fair shot at seeing the candidates, and occurs over a long enough
time frame that voters not only get to know the candidates and
their positions, but also have enough time for second thoughts and
buyer's remorse.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts argued that the truncated nature of this year's
primary campaign meant the only things truly debated were tactics
and endorsements, at least when the average voter was beginning to
tune in. William Galvin, the Massachusetts secretary of state and
the head of the National Association of Secretaries of State's
committee on presidential primaries, argued: ``If this had been
extended over maybe two months instead of six weeks, there would
have been an opportunity for more substantive discussions. They had
just about talked out Bob Jones University.''
</P>
<P>
   In several respects, of course, this year's primary season
confounded the conventional wisdom about problems in the nominating
system: Bush, the darling of party leaders and fund-raisers, did
not have a painless glide to the nomination. Turnout soared in the
fractious Republican contest, despite the maxim that negative
campaigns keep voters at home. And John McCain showed that powerful
insurgencies are still possible, even in an exceedingly compressed
calendar that puts a premium on money and name recognition.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts say it is increasingly apparent how much this
heightened participation was a function of the McCain candidacy,
and they worry that the collapse of that candidacy will lead to
further disillusionment.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Shorenstein Center poll, conducted March 1-5,
showed deep discontent with the way politics is practiced, with 87
percent of the respondents agreeing that ``most politicians are
pretty much willing to say whatever it takes in order to get
themselves elected.'' But 41 percent said there was an exception to
that rule this year, and McCain was the exception most frequently
cited.
</P>
<P>
   The poll also asked if the nominating system was ``fair to all
candidates,'' and found that a majority of McCain's supporters felt
it was not, while a majority of Bush's felt it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our polls showed that one of the things that was driving down
interest and essentially keeping people out of the process was this
sense of, `I just don't like what's been happening in politics, I
just don't like it,''' said Thomas E. Patterson, a Harvard
professor and co-director of the poll.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was able to tap into that discontent, Patterson said,
adding that the question now is whether his defeat feeds his
supporters' disillusionment or makes them realize how much is
possible.
</P>
<P>
   The next five months, though, may not be the most edifying in
politics, if history is a guide. ``If the Clinton election of '92
or '96 is any indicator, you'll see candidates lobbing grenades
across the fence with almost no communication,'' Brock said. ``It's
a long-distance artillery barrage, a lot of it based on attack ads.
Not very illuminating stuff.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-00 1249EST &QL; 
