<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-PARAMILITARY-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARAMILITARY LEADER IN COLOMBIA SPEAKS OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia _ His private army has killed thousands of
people in the past decade, making him perhaps the most feared man
in this violent country. But a decision to submit to a grilling on
television early this month has allowed the paramilitary leader
Carlos Castano to come out of the shadows and present himself as
one more victim of the violence he had previously been seen as
personifying here.
</P>
<P>
   The 90-minute interview was not Castano's first appearance on
Colombian television. In the past he has occasionally been shown
with his back to the camera or with sunglasses and a fake beard to
disguise his features. But never before had the main leader of the
country's right-wing death squads discussed his philosophy and
background in such detail or with such startling candor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that what I do violates international law, but the
violation of international law is inherent in a guerrilla war,'' he
said, adding, ``Wars are to be won, period'' and ``Our methods
produce excellent results.'' At another juncture, he maintained,
``I'm an extortionist, just like the guerrillas, but with more
delicacy,'' and warned, ``If an enemy has to be killed, then I say
kill him.''
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the interview suggests that Castano has been
attentive to the shifting political currents here. His mortal
enemies on the left, the guerrilla group known as the Revolutionary
Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC, toured Europe in February with
Colombian government peace negotiators, and their stature grew as a
result.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the Colombian United Self-Defense, as Castano's
private 5,500-member army is called, has been described as a band
of murderous thugs in human-rights reports published in the last
month by the U.S. State Department, the United Nations and the
private monitoring group Human Rights Watch.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the State Department is seeking to have Castano's
group added to its list of terrorist organizations along with the
likes of Osama bin Laden, who is accused of blowing up U.S.
embassies.
</P>
<P>
   During the interview on the private network Caracol, Castano,
wearing a blue dress shirt and matching tie that made him look like
a young executive, expressed hurt at being cast in such a role. ``I
am a patriot, not a bandit,'' he said indignantly, adding that his
group acts on behalf of ``the middle class, which has no one to
defend it,'' because the armed forces and police are too busy
defending ``the oligarchy.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, a damaging new report from the government
ombudsman's office here blames paramilitary death squads for the
execution of 902 people in 155 ``massacres'' last year. So Castano
was under pressure to do something to ``consolidate his status as
chief of a counterinsurgency project'' and ``paladin and defender
of property,'' as the country's main daily, El Tiempo, put it, and
to dispel the notion that he is a mere butcher and drug trafficker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the country to know Carlos Castano, and my sons their
father,'' he said. ``I don't want my sons to have to do this. It is
very difficult and cruel.''
</P>
<P>
   If Castano's strategy was to appear more human, it seems to be
succeeding. In an opinion poll published on Thursday by El Tiempo,
38 percent of those questioned said their image of Castano had
improved as a result of the interview, and 72 percent said the
government should bring his group into peace negotiations now under
way with left-wing guerrillas.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I saw that he is not the monster I had always thought him to
be,'' said Alba Rosa Guerrero Castro, a 46-year-old waitress. ``He
has done many bad things, but he has suffered a lot in this war
too, maybe even more than most people.''
</P>
<P>
   In a biographical sketch published in 1996, Castano explained
that his hatred of the country's various leftist insurgencies dates
back to September 1981, when he was 15 years old and a leftist
guerrilla unit kidnapped his father. When the family was unable to
come up with the ransom the guerrillas were demanding, the father
was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the family has waged a campaign of vengeance aimed
at anyone thought to be supplying the guerrillas, or to even be
sympathetic toward them. Four of Castano's brothers have been
killed in clashes with guerrilla groups, he said in the television
interview, and a sister was killed during a bungled kidnapping
attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result of this interview, Castano has undergone a
surprising metamorphosis,'' the columnist Maria Isabel Rueda wrote
in the weekly news magazine Semana. ``Overnight he manages to
transform himself from a barbarian with hands stained with blood
into a father forced to live apart from his children as the result
of a patriotic mission that obliges him to commit atrocities only
because it is necessary to halt the guerrillas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
