<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 13:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3970 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SPAIN-POLITICS-355&AMP;AD     03-11 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPAIN-POLITICS-355&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPAIN TURNS COOL TO PRIME MINISTER WHO ENGINEERED ITS BOOM 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain _ At a campaign rally in the bull ring in the
Mediterranean port of Valencia recently, the band played, the
crowds cheered and Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar boasted of his
record before being deluged with confetti.
</P>
<P>
   What incumbent would not envy Aznar? Most everyone here agrees
that they are better off today than in 1996. During his four years
in office, Aznar surprised many doubters by successfully guiding
Spain into the European monetary union. And under his conservative
policies, Spain's economy is booming. Unemployment has dropped to
15 percent from 23 percent. Spain has created as many new jobs in
the last four years as the rest of the European Union put together.
</P>
<P>
   But if Aznar is the victor in Sunday's elections, it will
probably be by a hair. Despite the clamor in his stronghold of
Valencia, recent polls show Aznar's center-right Popular Party
ahead of the Socialists by just four percentage points, a very
small margin in a country that is notoriously difficult to survey.
In 1996, Aznar's party held a seven-point lead in the polls going
into the elections and won with a 1.1 percent lead.
</P>
<P>
   Spanish politics always include a heavy dose of insult. And this
year is no different. Aznar, who brought the center-right back to
power after 14 years of Socialist rule that ended in multiple
scandals, has said voters had a right to ask whether his opponent
``had an idea in his head.''
</P>
<P>
   The Socialist candidate, Joaquin Almunia, has called Aznar ``a
right-wing big mouth'' and ``a puppet'' of the corporate world.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the contest has turned bitter with each side
accusing the other of false promises while engaging in tit-for-tat
campaign pledges. Barely had the Socialists, for example, produced
a proposal for a windfall profit tax on newly privatized companies
and a one-time bonus for pensioners of about $165 than the
government proposed to lower taxes and to increase the number of
people eligible for pensions.
</P>
<P>
   But this could hardly be called a hot-blooded campaign. With the
economy in good shape, neither side is suggesting big changes.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And neither candidate is capable of whipping up a crowd. At an
event in downtown Madrid last week, the prime minister, his
forehead shining with sweat, never cracked a smile or deviated from
a prepared text. His only nods to the rules of good delivery were
the occasional robotic turns to the left, right and center.
</P>
<P>
   Almunia is hardly more expressive. It remains to be seen whether
large numbers of Spaniards will even come out to vote. Polls
indicate that as many as 30 percent of Spain's 30 million voters
are undecided or may not vote at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a pretty flat campaign,'' said Victor de la Serna,
who writes a political column for Madrid's conservative daily El
Mundo. ``It's hard to think of anything to write about. Imagine if
you have Al Gore on the Socialist side and Al Gore on the
government side. That's what it's like here.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent terrorist bombings have given the contest an edge of
danger. Police officers are swarming all over Madrid's streets, and
access to campaign events is restricted. But few political analysts
believe that the resurgence of violent tactics by the Basque
separatist organization, known as ETA, will have much impact on the
election. Traditionally, Spain's mainstream parties have tried to
present a united front on terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   One new element in the political lineup is the French-style
cooperation pact between the Socialists and their long-time
enemies, the United Front, led by the Communists. But analysts say
this may be something of a desperate gamble. Already, relations
between the two seem strained. When the Socialists announced the
$165 bonus for pensioners, the Communist leader, Francisco Frutos,
suggested that the program smacked of vote buying. Frutos has also
been heard grumbling that the Socialist platform did not include
several Communist-backed programs including a 35-hour work week.
And analysts say that the coalition could actually drive some
Socialists away.
</P>
<P>
   In campaigning for another four years in office Aznar, a
47-year-old former tax collector, keeps warning of a return to the
country's Socialist years _ his code for heavy taxes and bloated
bureaucracies. But he is battling entrenched voting patterns.
Surveys show that after decades under the dictatorship of Francisco
Franco, who died in 1975, the majority of Spaniards still lean to
the left.
</P>
<P>
   And beyond his lack of charisma, Aznar has what many Spaniards
consider a suspicious past. As a young man, he wrote articles
against the constitution. Since then, he has worked hard to
disassociate himself from the far right. This time, he has
campaigned under the slogans, ``Compromise of the Center,'' or
``Let's go for more.'' Still, he is often seen as a man who
inclines toward the rich. The Socialists' most successful campaign
ploy has apparently been their attempt to paint his friends as the
primary beneficiaries of Spain's extensive privatization program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of my generation, we were anti-Franco, so it seems
unthinkable to vote for the right,'' said Javier Tosell, 57, a
professor of contemporary history at the University of Madrid.
``The polls are hard to do because I think we have a lot of closet
Socialists. Spain is doing well so they are too embarrassed to say
they will vote against Aznar. But in the voting booth they may.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spain is doing well, but Aznar is not doing so well. He is too
much to the right. When he speaks he still sounds like that.''
</P>
<P>
   One asset for the Socialists is that Almunia, 51, has a clean
record. Despite a long ministerial career _ at 34, he became the
youngest member of the Socialist Cabinet _ he has never been
tainted by any of the numerous scandals that brought down the
Socialists.
</P>
<P>
   However, he was not even the Socialists' first choice. Two years
ago, Almunia organized a primary election to become the Socialists'
candidate for prime minister _ only to lose. He got the nomination
back last year when the man who beat him withdrew. And his
ground-breaking deal with the Communists was less than a total
triumph. The Socialists had hoped that the United Front candidates
would step aside in certain contests, enabling the Socialists to
win those seats. But that did not happen.
</P>
<P>
   In the last elections in 1996, Aznar's party won 38.8 percent of
the vote, the Socialists 37.7. To form his government, Aznar joined
forces with the moderate Catalan party, a partnership which may
well be needed again.
</P>
<P>
   Many Spaniards say that this year's political scene leaves them
cold.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Vincente Maria, who has been driving a taxi since being
laid off from a factory job eight years ago, says business has
never been better, the city is booming and he has a brand new
subway stop near his house. A lifelong supporter of the left, he
was disgusted by all the scandals and says he would probably vote
for Aznar, if he voted at all. But he doubts he will make it to the
polling booth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really sick of politics,'' Vincente said. ``Almunia
doesn't have much to say and doesn't have good people around him.
Aznar doesn't have much to say, or can't get it out. And in the
end, I just can't be bothered with all of them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
