<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3974 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TAIWAN-VOTE-BUYING-AR     03-11 1276
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-VOTE-BUYING-ART-435&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN'S OPEN WALLETS BRING FEAR OF A BOUGHT PRESIDENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHIN JIN, Taiwan _ Three days before Taiwan held its last
presidential election in 1996, the local boss of this busy fishing
village in southwestern Taiwan called on Yang Cheng-ho. After
shooting the breeze a bit, he got down to business: the Nationalist
party hoped it could count on Yang's vote, and to show its
gratitude, the boss thrust a wad of bills into his hand.
</P>
<P>
   Yang, 61, who sells cigarettes and betel nuts, pocketed the
money. But he still voted for the candidate of the opposition
party. ``People have gotten smarter,'' he said with a devilish
grin. ``They'll take the money, but that doesn't mean they'll vote
for the candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's voters will elect a new president March 18 to succeed
Lee Teng-hui. With the three main candidates locked within a few
percentage points of one another in the polls, party officials are
girding themselves for another spree of vote buying, and opposition
and election officials fear that the practice could play a
substantial role in determining the winner.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Taiwan has never seen an electoral cliffhanger like
this one. In the last opinion polls, the three principal candidates
_ Vice President Lien Chan of the Nationalists, or Kuomintang; Chen
Shui-bian of the Democratic Progressive Party; and James Soong, an
independent _ each had about 25 percent of the vote, with the rest
undecided. Taiwan law bars the publication of new polls in the last
two weeks of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Not all attempts at vote buying are as brazen as that
experienced by Yang, who said he had not yet been approached this
year. As democracy takes root in Taiwan, the practice of handing
over cash is gradually waning. But more subtle attempts to bribe
voters are proliferating.
</P>
<P>
   From free dinners and junkets to vinyl jackets and scented soap,
Taiwan's 15 million registered voters can board a gravy train that
runs night and day from now until the vote. Most of the largess is
courtesy of the Nationalist party, which is in danger of losing
power for the first time in five decades.
</P>
<P>
   After so much time in power, the Nationalists have amassed one
of the greatest war chests of any political party in the world, as
well as assembling a formidable machine to mobilize voters.
Political analysts here said the party has set aside more than $60
million to get out the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are always thieves in society, so vote buying exists,''
said Huang Shih-chen, the chairman of Taiwan's Central Election
Commission. ``My personal view is that the dead-heat competition in
this election has raised the incentive for vote buying.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   With the race so tight, the Democratic Progressive Party
contends that the election could hinge on 200,000 or 300,000 votes.
It also believes that about 500,000 people _ mostly poor and living
in rural areas of central and southern Taiwan _ are ripe targets
for manipulation.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan has taken steps to stamp out vote buying, outlawing the
practice in 1985 and threatening violators with jail sentences of
up to five years. It also offers $500,000 for information leading
to the conviction of vote buyers. But Huang, the election official,
conceded that convictions were rare, in part because many of the
recipients of gifts regard the practice as customary.
</P>
<P>
   ``In traditional Chinese culture, people view gifts as a gesture
of respect for their act of voting,'' said said Bau Tzong-ho, a
professor of political science at National Taiwan University.
</P>
<P>
   An afternoon in Chin Jin illustrates why vote buying is so
deeply rooted. Although the nearby port city of Kaohsiung is a
stronghold of the Democratic Progressive Party, Chin Jin votes
reliably for the Nationalist party, local officials said, because
its fishermen depend on the state for access to fishing grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole district has been bought and paid for the KMT,''
said Chuang Ming-tsong, 53, a restaurant owner and opposition
supporter, using the acronym for the Kuomintang.
</P>
<P>
   Some political analysts doubt the impact of vote buying in a
presidential election, saying the practice works best in local
races, where people know the candidates personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's impossible to buy votes successfully in a national
election,'' said Lee Fu-hsing, a spokesman for Lien's campaign in
Kaohsiung, as he sat next to a bank of ringing phones. ``A
vote-buying operation of that scale would be too big for anybody,
even the KMT.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the opposition parties say the Nationalists will be careful
about handing over cash, for fear of getting caught. But they say
the party has developed more sophisticated strategies. The latest
craze in Kaohsiung and other cities is gambling parlors, which
opposition officials contend are linked to the governing
Nationalist party. People place bets on the candidate they believe
is favored by the owner, and if that candidate wins, they receive a
large payout.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Hsieh, the mayor of Kaohsiung and a Democratic
Progressive, said the system is a disguised form of vote buying and
has asked the local police to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   The Nationalists said Chen, the Democratic Progressive
candidate, was harping on the issue of vote buying to damage Lien.
And besides, they said, Chen gives away free dinners and campaign
souvenirs to supporters. ``It's the pot calling the kettle black,''
Lee Fu-hsing said.
</P>
<P>
   But critics of the Nationalists say it is a matter of degree. In
the days leading up to a ballot, according to the China Times
newspaper, the party will deploy 70,000 people to knock on doors,
hand out jackets and caps, and serve up dinners at party-run
banquet halls around the island.
</P>
<P>
   On Election Day, the Nationalists will post thousands of
monitors at voting booths throughout Taiwan _ as many as 40 or 50
per station, the Democrats say. Each person is paid $100 for his or
her efforts, guaranteeing a fresh stream of votes.
</P>
<P>
   The police force is another arrow in the Nationalists' quiver.
Chen Pi, the former chief of police for Taiwan Province, said that
85 percent of police officers are party members. Chen, who was
recently expelled from the party for supporting Soong, said those
officers would seek to persuade voters on their beats.
</P>
<P>
   Wang Jin-pyng, the president of Taiwan's legislature, said:
``The KMT has a powerful organization, even in the most remote
villages. These people can be mobilized to win over votes for
Lien.''
</P>
<P>
   Wang has the quiet confidence of a Nationalist heavyweight. He
estimates that once the party machine is running full tilt, the
Nationalists will be able to convert 8 percent of the electorate.
Given that Lien is lagging by less than 3 percentage points in most
polls, Wang said he could not conceive of the Nationalists losing.
</P>
<P>
   But just in case, the party is spending heavily to insure its
primacy in another type of campaign hucksterism. It pays taxicab
unions $50 for each driver they persuade to fly a flag with Lien's
campaign symbol of butterflies. The union passes along $43 to the
driver, but keeps $7 as profit. At one of Taipei's largest taxicab
unions, 300 of the 500 drivers are flying butterflies on their
hoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Chen Shui-bian,'' said Liu Shing-ming, the secretary of
the union. ``He came from a poor background, so working people are
comfortable with him. But this is a business decision.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
