<TEXT>
<P>
   Hand-wringing aside, negative political campaigning has been
shown to work. It's only March and already the presidential
candidates have spent vast sums of money on ads vilifying their
opponents. Still, as Jimmy Durante used to hoot, ``You ain't seen
nothin' yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, strategists for both Vice President Al Gore and Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas predicted that the campaign is only now
starting to heat up. But what more can the candidates say after
they've called each other a fool, a liar, a bigot and worse?
</P>
<P>
   Plenty, one suspects. As a public service, here is a trove of
insults that can be adapted phase by phase as the campaign careens
to its bitter end in November.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JOE SHARKEY
</P>
<P>
   Phase 1 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Even the nastiest campaigns usually start
out with high-toned sniping. What better source than Shakespeare, a
master of insult? The Shakespearean Insult Kit, available at
www.crinos.com, offers a mix-and-match list of choice words and
phrases from his works that can be fused at random with the click
of mouse. Now, for example, the literary politician can label his
opponent . . .(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   A swag-bellied malt-worm.
</P>
<P>
   A surly, dizzy-eyed ratsbane.
</P>
<P>
   A craven hedge-born lewdster.
</P>
<P>
   An errant pottle-deep pignut.
</P>
<P>
   A fawning toad-spotted scut.
</P>
<P>
   A spongy flap-mouthed lout.
</P>
<P>
   A mewling, clay-brained maggot-pie.
</P>
<P>
   A paunchy, rude-growing flap-dragon.
</P>
<P>
   Phase 2 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) By summer, it will be time for more pointed
remarks, along the lines of Winston Churchill's description of a
rival as ``a modest man with a lot to be modest about.'' One
Internet site, www.corsinet.com, has a section called Brain Candy
that features a large collection of famous putdowns: (END ITALICS
HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``A $400 suit on him would look like socks on a rooster.''
</P>
<P>
   _ _ Former Louisiana Gov. Earl Long &QR;
</P>
<P>
   ``His face is livid, gaunt his whole body, his breath is green
with gall; his tongue drips poison.'' _ John Quincy Adams
</P>
<P>
   ``I never forget a face, but in your case I'll make an
exception.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Groucho Marx
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do you sit there looking like an envelope without any
address on it?'' _ Mark Twain
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were married to you, I'd put poison in your coffee.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Lady Astor to Winston Churchill &QR;
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were my wife, I'd drink it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Churchill's reply
</P>
<P>
   ``He can compress the most words into the smallest idea of any
man I know.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Abraham Lincoln
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't you get a haircut? You look like a chrysanthemum.''
</P>
<P>
   _ P.G. Wodehouse
</P>
<P>
   ``He inherited some good instincts from his Quaker forebears but
by diligent hard work, he overcame them.'' _ James Reston on
Richard Nixon
</P>
<P>
   ``When he does smile, he looks as if he's just evicted a
widow.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Mike Royko on Bob Dole &QR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Compared to the Clintons, Reagan is living proof that a
Republican with half a brain is better than a Democrat with two.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The humorist P.J. O'Rourke &QR;
</P>
<P>
   ``If ignorance ever goes to $40 a barrel, I want drilling rights
to George Bush's head.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The humorist and Texas politician Jim Hightower &QR;
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) And from ``The Book of Classic Insults,''
edited by Tom Steele (Morrow, 1999): (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``Harding was not a bad man, he was just a slob.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Alice Roosevelt Longworth on Warren Harding
</P>
<P>
   ``Calvin Coolidge didn't say much, and when he did, he didn't
say much.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Will Rogers
</P>
<P>
   ``If Gladstone fell into the Thames, that would be a misfortune,
and if someone pulled him out, that, I suppose, would be a
calamity.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Disraeli, asked to distinguish between a misfortune and a
calamity
</P>
<P>
   ``She probably thinks Sinai is the plural of sinus.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The British politician Jonathan Aitken on Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Clinton's foreign policy experience stems mainly from
having breakfast at the International House of Pancakes.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Patrick Buchanan
</P>
<P>
   ``Nixon is the kind of politician who would cut down a redwood
tree and then mount the stump to make a speech for conservation.''
_ Adlai Stevenson
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my God, look at you. Anybody else hurt in the accident?''
</P>
<P>
   _ Don Rickles
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the kind of guy who can brighten a room by leaving it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Milton Berle
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed talking to you. My mind needed a rest.'' _ Henny
Youngman
</P>
<P>
   Phase 3 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) By late summer, the gloves will start
coming off. Here are some possible one-liners from a comedian named
Butch Fisco on his Web site, www.insults.com: (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``Nice suit! Somewhere there's a Pinto without upholstery.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you put your brain in a bird, it would fly backwards.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Vice President Gore: Nice hair! What is that, Rayon?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Gov. Bush, nice suit! There's a family in Tijuana right
now saying What happened to our kitchen curtains?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just got back from (Texas/Tennessee). It's nice to see people
with teeth again.''
</P>
<P>
   Phase 4
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) During debate season in the fall, regional
insults can easily be employed to win over undecideds. After all,
the presumed nominees of both major parties are from the South,
where, according to ``Redneck Classic'' (Longstreet Press, 1995),
by Jeff Foxworthy, you can be called a redneck if . . . (END
ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``You think the last four words of the National Anthem are
`Gentlemen start your engines.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Your wife has said, `Come move this transmission so I can take
a bath.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Your good deed for the month was hiding your brother for a few
days.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You stare at a can of frozen orange juice because it says,
`Concentrate.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can entertain yourself for more than an hour with a fly
swatter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to check your shirt to spell your name.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You refer to the fifth grade as `my senior year.'''
</P>
<P>
   Phase 5
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) As Election Day nears, the rhetoric is
bound to descend to the level of ``Liar, liar, pants on fire!''
James Percelay, Stephan Dweck and Monteria Ivey, in ``Double
Snaps'' (Morrow, 1995) have some useful last-minute barbs for
desperate candidates: (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``You're so dumb, on the way to the airport you saw a sign that
said `Airport Left,' so you went home.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're so ugly you can't get a date off a calendar.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If ugliness were an album, you'd go platinum.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Your father is so dumb he stole a car and kept up payments.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-00 1325EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
