<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-WATER-SHORTAGE-ART-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAMPA BAY LOOKS TO THE SEA TO QUENCH ITS THIRST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Calif.)  (ART ADV: Graphic and map are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAND O'LAKES, Fla. _ There may be water, water everywhere, but
as remarkable as it may seem in Tampa Bay, there is not enough to
drink.
</P>
<P>
   Blessed by abundant rainfall, the region has for decades drawn
all of its water from a network of inland wells. But spreading
development along roads with names like Progress Parkway,
stretching north all the way to Land O'Lakes, has finally overrun
what those ground-water well fields can safely produce.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, the verdant landscape here, some 30 miles north of
downtown Tampa, is dotted with small lakes. But in its search for
new sources of water, Tampa Bay is looking in another direction. To
help meet the needs of the area's 2.3 million residents, it plans
to desalt the sea.
</P>
<P>
   Never before has a large American urban area bet so heavily on
sea water desalination for fresh water. If approved by state
environmental officials, a plant to be built on the shores of Tampa
Bay would become the largest desalination plant this side of Saudi
Arabia by the end of 2002.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when other American coastal communities are bracing
for water crises, the effort by the Tampa Bay Water authority may
serve as an important test. Rejected for years as too expensive,
desalination is winning converts as the price of the process begins
to drop, but it still faces skepticism, even in Tampa Bay, where
some fear that the desalination plant could cause environmental
damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``How we resolve the problem in Tampa Bay could very well set
the mold, the blueprint for other parts of the country,'' said E.D.
Vergara, executive director of the Southwest Florida Water
Management District, the regulatory agency that was the driving
force in persuading Tampa Bay to change course.
</P>
<P>
   The outlines of Tampa Bay's problem can be seen in three
dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   One is demographic, after 50 years that have seen a fivefold
population increase in the Tampa Bay area, which includes the
cities of Tampa, St. Petersburg and Clearwater, and the counties of
Pinellas, Hillsborough and Pasco.
</P>
<P>
   The second is environmental _ depleted aquifers, dry wetlands
and fallen trees, all casualties of pumping water from the ground
to supply rapidly growing communities, often carried out with
little heed for the consequences.
</P>
<P>
   And the third is a clock that began to tick in 1995, when the
Tampa Bay Water authority submitted to years of pressure from state
regulators and agreed to cut back sharply on pumping ground water,
and to look elsewhere for new water sources.
</P>
<P>
   In its new plan for the decade ahead, Tampa Bay now envisions
desalted sea water providing about 10 percent of the region's
freshwater needs. Water from other newly developed sources, rivers
and a new reservoir, would account for about 25 percent of the
need, with the balance to be made up by highly restricted flows
from ground-water well fields.
</P>
<P>
   A Tampa Bay water timetable shows that without the 25 million
gallons of fresh water a day that the new plant is supposed to
produce, the area would face a major water shortage by early 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are where we are because of the travesty of development in
Florida,'' said Jerry L. Maxwell, who as general manager of Tampa
Bay Water has become a leading advocate of the desalination plan.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, American coastal cities have generally steered clear
of sea-water desalination. The main reason has been the cost,
usually many times more than that of conventional water sources,
like ground aquifers, lakes, rivers, streams and reservoirs.
</P>
<P>
   Sea-water desalination has been given a leading role in
overcoming water poverty only in parts of the world where such
alternatives are all but nonexistent, particularly in the wealthy
desert kingdoms of the Arabian peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, only two American cities have invested in
full-fledged sea-water desalination plants _ Key West, Fla., in the
early 1980s, and Santa Barbara, Calif., a decade later. Notably,
both cities mothballed their operations soon after they began,
having managed to line up less-expensive alternatives; the plants
are now maintained to provide emergency alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still cheaper for us to pump fresh water 130 miles down
here from the mainland than to make it from sea water,'' said Jim
Reynolds, deputy executive director of the Florida Keys Aqueduct
Authority.
</P>
<P>
   But a more basic form of desalination, aimed at brackish ground
water, has made major inroads in the United States, with plants now
operating along the coasts of Virginia, North Carolina, Florida,
Texas and California.
</P>
<P>
   Brackish water is much less salty than the sea, so cleaning it
is much less expensive, making the process more attractive. To
remove the salt from sea water usually requires that the water be
passed through synthetic membranes at exceedingly high pressures,
making the process more energy intensive and thus particularly
costly.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Tampa Bay is not the only place whose problems have sunk
to the level that serious thought is being given to drinking from
the sea.
</P>
<P>
   In Monterey County, Calif., which faces a severe water shortage,
public discussion about sea-water desalination has rumbled for
years, despite the voters' narrow rejection of it in the early
1990s. The water authority there proposed, instead, a new dam on
the Carmel River, but that plan has met with even more opposition.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, a turn to sea-water desalination is seen by some
experts as inevitable, unless the federal government and Florida go
forward with a multibillion-dollar plan to reclaim the Everglades
through a project that would help restore the flow of scarce
surface water to Miami-Dade County.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For Tampa Bay, sea-water desalination was made more feasible by
the terms of a bargain that was struck in 1995, when the local
water authority agreed to cut back on ground-water pumping.
</P>
<P>
   As a sweetener, state regulators promised to help pay for the
cost of creating new water resources, and under that formula, the
Southwest Florida Water Management Agency will use tax money it
collects to underwrite all but 10 percent of the $95 million cost
of building the desalination plant.
</P>
<P>
   The Tampa Bay Water authority awarded the construction contract
last year to an affiliate of the Stone &AMP; Webster Engineering Corp.
under terms that require the plant to begin operations by Dec. 31,
2002.
</P>
<P>
   Initial estimates by water officials in Tampa had projected the
cost of water produced by the plant to average $4 to $6 per 1,000
gallons, within the rough range of the costs in Key West and Santa
Barbara. But they said that technological advances had already
driven the projected costs down substantially. Under the terms of
the contract, the price the Tampa Bay Water authority itself will
pay for the desalted water will average $2.08 per 1,000 gallons
over the next 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   But that is nearly four times what the authority now pays for
water from some of the rural wells.
</P>
<P>
   This, in turn, will drive up the costs the municipal governments
pay the authority for water. For an ordinary household, it is
likely to translate into a monthly increase of about $7.50 on the
water bill.
</P>
<P>
   That prospect has generated little public complaint, and in
fact, the switch to more expensive sources of water has been loudly
welcomed in the parts of Tampa Bay that have suffered most from
ground-water pumping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it's not even safe to walk across your yard anymore
because the oak trees are shedding foot-thick limbs in order to
survive,'' said Gilliam Clarke, of Wesley Chapel, Fla., who lives
just outside the Cypress Creek well field, a once-isolated tract
that is one of 11 set aside long ago to feed the region's demands.
</P>
<P>
   To the south, however, some residents who benefited from the old
system have begun to mobilize in opposition to the new arrangement,
on grounds that the shift toward desalination might simply produce
a different environmental harm.
</P>
<P>
   A recent public meeting held in Tampa to review the proposed
plan attracted some 700 people, and all but one of those who spoke
expressed strong opposition to the idea of the desalination plant.
</P>
<P>
   The featured guest, David Struhs, who is the state's top
environmental official and who has yet to approve construction of
the water plant, was greeted on arrival with signs saying things
like ``Too Much Salt Kills'' and ``If I wanted the Dead Sea, I'd
Live in Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   The critics' worry is that the desalination plant would result
in a saltier Tampa Bay, with possible harm to water life, including
some fish and perhaps the manatee, an endangered marine mammal. The
bay would have to absorb the main byproduct of desalination, a
briny concentrate twice as concentrated as the sea.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa water officials say that the concern is misguided. The
concentrate would be heavily diluted, they say, before it reached
the open water, mixed with the sea-water outflow from the Tampa
Electric Co.'s Big Bend plant, with which the sea-water
desalination plant would share a site. The mixing formula calls for
a gallon of concentrate for 70 gallons of sea water from the
electric company.
</P>
<P>
   A study commissioned by Tampa Bay Water found no reasonable risk
that salinity in the bay would build up over time, said Anthony
Janicki, an environmental consultant who conducted the project. The
research found that the estuary into which the outflows would be
pumped already flush naturally, and it pointed out that native
species of fish and sea grass are already accustomed to salinity
variations.
</P>
<P>
   But some independent experts have been more skeptical, saying
that any salinity problems caused by a desalination plant might be
compounded by Tampa Bay's parallel plans to draw from new surface
water sources that now flow into the bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be no problem at all, but there needs to be more
study,'' said Holly Greening, a marine scientist who works for the
state-supported Tampa Bay Estuary Program.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, some Tampa Bay officials have become so confident of
solving the region's water problems that they have begun talking
about building a second sea-water desalination plant, this one
north of Clearwater, on the Gulf of Mexico, to help meet demand
after 2008.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have these counties done anything to control their growth?''
asked Steve Simon, a Pasco County commissioner who is a member of
the Tampa Bay Water board. ``No. So the question is how to provide
the water, and as I see it, desal is the only answer.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
