<P>
   RUSSIA-OLIGARCHS _ MOSCOW _ While experts agree that Russia's
popular acting President Vladimir Putin could be the runaway winner
in this month's presidential elections, many experts warn that none
of his efforts will matter unless he does what his predecessor
Boris Yeltsin failed to do: rein in Russia's oligarchs. Reform or
no reform, they say that Russia's woes will continue while the
robber barons retain their power. But while Putin would certainly
win about 100 percent of the vote if he did crack down on these
moneyed plutocrats, he would lose their financial backing _ crucial
to his success. (Coke, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH box attached to end of story.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Friday, March 10.
</P>
<P>
   COX-LATAM-MCKAY _ WASHINGTON _ The view from Buddy MacKay's
office is of the White House. Behind his desk is a map stretching
from the southern United States to the tip of South America. This
is MacKay's world. For the past year, the former Florida governor
has been President Clinton's special envoy to the Americas _ a
territory covering the entire Western Hemisphere, including Canada.
The job has taken MacKay, 66, to an average of two countries a
month _ listening to their leaders and communicating their problems
on at least a weekly basis to the president of the United States.
Sometimes, communications break down. (Lipman, Cox News Service).
WITH PHOTO.
</P>
