<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4009 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-McCAIN-VOTERS-ART-110     03-11 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-McCAIN-VOTERS-ART-1105(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Mich., Mass., Calif.)  
 DEVOTEES OF McCAIN WONDER WHICH WAY TO TURN  
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Holly Hamilton, a high school English teacher in
suburban Seattle, had never voted for a Republican _ until the
recent presidential primary, when she almost giddily marked her
ballot for John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still kind of shocked at myself,'' she said with a laugh
the other day as she was out walking her dogs, Nick and Winnie. She
said she did not agree with some of his positions, but admired the
way he wanted to ``shake things up.'' And now that McCain has
suspended his campaign? ``Oh, I'll wind up voting for Gore, I
guess. He certainly doesn't do a whole lot for me, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Another ardent McCain supporter, Joyce Maund, from West Seattle,
has voted for plenty of Republicans and, with her man out, Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas ``would probably be an acceptable second
choice for me.'' Bush could seal the deal if he could talk McCain
into being his running mate, Maund said. ``I know that's unlikely,
their being so different and all. But you know the saying _ variety
is the spice of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Kris Lenning, a phone company technician and
two-time Ross Perot voter, another passionate McCain supporter who
said she saw ``not a dime's worth of difference between Bush and
Gore.'' She said she wanted McCain to bolt his party and run as an
independent or a Reform Party nominee. If he did not, she said: ``I
really don't have any idea what I'd do in November. My vote's
completely up in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Lenning, Troy Miller, a purchasing agent who supported
McCain, said he was dismayed to be stuck now with ``two
establishment candidates.'' His vote? ``I'll listen to what they
have to say over the next several months, but if I had to vote
right now, I think I'd write in somebody like Pat Paulsen _ I'm
totally serious about that.''
</P>
<P>
   The McCain voter is the United States' hottest political quarry
these days _ the large swing bloc that is being assiduously courted
by Vice President Al Gore and Bush, and whose decision on a
second-choice candidate, if their man remained out of the race,
could well be the deciding factor in November's election.
</P>
<P>
   But while the bloc has come to be hugely significant in
electoral terms, interviews with dozens of such voters in
Washington state, and in Michigan, Massachusetts and California,
vividly confirmed what polls have suggested from the outset: Beyond
their allegiance to McCain and a somewhat vague banner of reform,
there seemed to be virtually nothing that amounted to a common bond
in their political views.
</P>
<P>
   If either Gore or Bush somehow managed to project himself as
``the real reformer'' in a two-man race, to use the mantle that the
Bush campaign has already put on its candidate, it seemed clear
that a significant majority of McCain voters could wind up being
theirs on Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   But it also seemed possible that the two candidates could end up
simply splitting much of the bloc roughly down the middle, with the
remaining McCain voters either not voting or voting for third-party
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The passion of many McCain voters for their candidate was
clearly deep, with many using words like ``honest,''
``straight-shooting,'' ``genuine human being,'' and even
``incredibly interesting,'' to describe him, and then going further
to express their opinion that these are qualities neither Gore nor
Bush has.
</P>
<P>
   But far from having a set of issues that united them, the McCain
voters seemed all over the political map on some of the central
questions these days, including the environment, gay rights and
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the only one who really came out and said he was
pro-life,'' said an admiring Art Majkowski, a retired Ford Motor
Co. worker in Centerline, Mich., who described abortion as the most
important issue to him in the election.
</P>
<P>
   But Melissa Price, an accountant in Seattle for Alaska Airlines,
said she thought that McCain paid lip service to conservative views
on the issue while ``in reality, he's a lot more open-minded on a
question like that. He's really more of a libertarian on it, I
think.''
</P>
<P>
   These comments also point to another distinguishing
characteristic of the McCain campaign: Many voters seem to have
projected their own personal views onto McCain, believing that he
shared them no matter what his public pronouncements were.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, while many solid Republicans spoke approvingly of McCain
calling himself a ``proud Ronald Reagan Republican,'' many
Democrats dismissed such remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just something he had to say to try to get some
Republican votes,'' said 20-year-old Edgar Klepers, a computer
sales clerk and student at South Seattle Community College, who
voted for McCain partly because he thought it would be
``interesting and fun'' to have him as president. ``He's clearly
really much more of an independent.''
</P>
<P>
   In the long term, McCain's campaign may end up helping to weaken
both political parties.
</P>
<P>
   In some states, longtime Democratic voters switched their party
status to vote for the Arizona senator. James W. Hennigan III, 44,
an insurance broker from the West Roxbury section of Boston, became
officially unenrolled to vote for McCain, and while he is leaning
toward Gore in a Bush-Gore match-up, he said he was in no hurry to
reclaim his old party affiliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have myself positioned right there in the middle,'' said
Hennigan. ``I still feel like a Democrat. It's an interesting
position now because I intentionally say I'm going to stay here in
the middle and decide what happens. Since I made the move, I said,
`I'm just going to sit on this unenrolled thing for a while.'''
</P>
<P>
   For many McCain supporters, the next logical step for their
candidate would be to jump back into the race as an independent
candidate, much as former Rep. John Anderson of Illinois did in
1980. That is an idea that clearly has wide support among many
McCain voters, but others said such a candidacy would be fruitless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think McCain running as an independent makes much
sense,'' said Anne O'Shea, 40, a former prosecutor who lives in
Alameda County, Calif. ``It sounds great, but he wouldn't have the
support of any leadership in the country. And I think the reason
why it was so difficult for him in this race is it's very clear
that you need the support of the GOP or the Democratic Party, and
if you don't have it, they will cremate you.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in addition to feeling bitter that their candidate had
fallen short, many McCain voters also said the experience confirmed
their belief that anybody who posed a true challenge to the
country's power structure could not be elected.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, by Bush winning, it really showed the whole thing is
skewed,'' said Michael Hansen, 32, a bank manager in West Seattle.
``The people really don't have a voice.''
</P>
<P>
   And Bart Ferko, of Oakland Township, Mich., a dance-studio
owner, said he had concluded that a real rebel like McCain could
not be elected president. ``Obviously if you're not part of the
network, you're out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if many of these voters expressed contempt for both Gore
(``plastic,'' ``detached,'' ``a bore'' were some of their
descriptions) and Bush (``an airhead,'' ``out of his depth,''
``unqualified''), they also typically said they were likely to vote
in November, and to choose one or the other.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for Bush is that some McCain voters grudgingly
admit that they now think Bush is tough enough to be president.
``This whole thing did show that he didn't crumble under pressure,
that's for sure,'' said Lynn J. Turk, a career foreign-service
officer who is now a business consultant in Redmond, Wash. ``He
showed he could organize a counterattack.''
</P>
<P>
   And for Gore, the bright spot in the temporary ``McCain Mutiny''
of many Democrats is that such voters hardly seem to have
permanently abandoned their party. ``I'm going out to get a Gore
bumper sticker to put over my McCain bumper sticker,'' said James
M. Marshall, a Seattle lawyer who described himself as a Democrat,
albeit one who could never bring himself to vote for Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall said he was planning to send some money to the Gore
campaign, though he cautioned that he had a remarkably unsuccessful
track record for backing presidential candidates: Anderson, Walter
Mondale, Michael Dukakis, George Bush (in 1992), and Bob Dole.
``Given my history of contributing to losers,'' he said, ``maybe
Gore won't even want my money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
