<HEADER>
A4011 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-RESPIRATORS-NYT &LR;      03-11 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-RESPIRATORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIMITING AIR FROM RESPIRATORS CAN SAVE LIVES, STUDY SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: this story, sent and held Friday, is now restored.) 
(bl) 
 By GINA KOLATA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A large new federal study shows that doctors can save certain
patients' lives in the intensive care unit if they set their
respirators so that less air is delivered than many doctors had
thought necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The study involved patients with acute respiratory distress
syndrome, a condition in which the lungs are partly filled with
fluid, making it impossible for patients to breathe without
respirators. The condition can occur with pneumonia but it also
occurs in trauma patients, including people who have been in
automobile accidents or who have had major surgery.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 100,000 Americans of all ages develop the disorder
each year, medical experts said. If they recover, most have no
lingering symptoms. But nearly half die.
</P>
<P>
   To determine how best to keep these patients alive with
respirators while their lungs recover, the National Heart, Lung and
Blood Institute sponsored a study that enrolled 861 patients across
the country. They were randomly assigned to one of two treatment
strategies. The results showed that death rates from the disease
could be cut by nearly 25 percent, a result so decisive that the
study ended last March, nine months ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   One of the principal investigators, Dr. Roy G. Brower of Johns
Hopkins University, announced the findings at a medical meeting in
April and began preparing a paper for publication. That paper was
accepted about two weeks ago by The New England Journal of
Medicine, and an edited version was completed last week, Brower
said. The journal deemed the results so important that it released
the paper Friday, posting it on its Web site (www.nejm.org),
although the paper will not formally appear until the issue dated
May 4.
</P>
<P>
   One of the treatment strategies was to push large volumes of air
into patients' lungs, at high pressure. The advantage was that
sufficient oxygen got into patients' blood. But the concern was
that the high pressures would damage the fragile lung tissue,
slowing healing or making it impossible.
</P>
<P>
   The second strategy was for the respirators to provide less
oxygen, even though many patients would become ``air hungry'' _
wanting more breath. In addition, Brower said, with less oxygen
going into the lungs, carbon dioxide can build up in the blood,
causing its own problems and making patients feel worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``If carbon dioxide accumulates, it contributes to the distress
the patient feels,'' Brower said. ``It can make the heart beat
faster, sometimes fast enough to make it a concern.'' Frantic for
breath, with pounding hearts, some patients have to be sedated, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the study showed that while nearly 40 percent of the
patients who received large volumes of air died, just 31 percent of
those receiving less air died.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is massively important,'' said Dr. Thomas Stewart, the
director of the intensive care unit at Mount Sinai Hospital in
Toronto, who did not participate in the Federal study. Family
members, he said, should be aware ``that the way their physicians
are managing the patients makes a difference to their outcomes.''
They need to be sure that the doctors are setting the respirators
to provide less air and gentler pressure in the lungs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never, ever, had any family member come and talk to me
about that,'' Stewart said. But, he added, ``now they will.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-00 1423EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000311.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4012 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-DODGERS0312-COX     03-11 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS0312-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    L.A.: No early contention(s)
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kissimmee, Fla. _ No one is sure about the shortstop, or the
bullpen or even the bottom of the rotation, all of which this
spring seem to be fine. The Los Angeles Dodgers are willing to
exhange all those uncertainties for something far greater, a
commodity missing throughout last year.
</P>
<P>
   Silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot going on,'' manager Davey Johnson said, ``in a
very quiet spring.''
</P>
<P>
   General manager Kevin Malone, whose ``New Sheriff's In Town''
pronouncement last spring rang a battle cry through the NL West, is
almost sullen, guarding his comments in every press encounter.
Outfielder Raul Mondesi, having punctuated his Dodger career with
wishes to be traded, got his wish.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Green arrived from Toronto to replace him and, having
heard what a snake pit the Dodgers operation had become, says he
has found the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're going to have a really good team,'' Green said.
``People said there were problems in the clubhouse last year but I
don't see them this year. Everything's been real quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fox Group needed a Maalox dispenser in the boardroom during
its initial foray into baseball ownership. Everything the Dodgers
had cultivated for a half-century in Los Angeles _ pride,
traditionalism, savvy public relations _ collapsed in 1999. A 38-38
second half became a monumental achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Kevin Brown hit Vero Beach last month and declared, ``I
think it's the situation now where it's time to keep your mouth
shut and let's do it all on the field, instead of talking about it
and giving it mouth and lip service.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone and new team CEO Bob Daley had facilitated that process
over the winter by bringing home native Southern Californian Green
and then tying down first baseman Eric Karros to a three-year $24
million contract.
</P>
<P>
   But the addition was not as critical as the subtraction.
Mondesi's welcome had become worn. Pitcher Ismael Valdes, who had
once fought in the shower with Karros over his selfishness, and
second baseman Eric Young, who clashed with Johnson, were sent to
the Chicago Cubs. Clubhouse tension was promptly reduced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether that (perception) applies to the guys they got rid of,
that's how you've got to take it as _ that Mondesi was an
individual, I was an individual, Valdes was an individual,'' Young
said. ``I just feel like they're still barking up the wrong tree.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking back at what 1999 became, Johnson said, ``I didn't know
what to expect. You can read the numbers and look at the players
but you don't really know an organization until you work in it. I
got a better understanding of where our strengths are and where our
weaknesses are, how we fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sheffield had seen enough to threaten to retire last
summer. This spring he said he wants to play until he's 40, meaning
nine more years.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's great to hear, because if he's feeling like that, he's
really locked in and determined to do everything he can for the
Dodgers,'' Malone said. ``I think he has peace of mind, and this
sure makes it sound like that.''
</P>
<P>
   With such a mood swing, the personnel incidentals seem smaller.
Johnson is waiting for Alex Cora to settle in at shortstop, despite
an offseason scare with an irregular heartbeat and a 0-for-9 start
this spring. Eric Gagne, Carlos Perez and Orel Hershiser are
angling for the last two spots in a rotation that includes Brown,
Chan Ho Park and Darren Dreifort.
</P>
<P>
   There still might not be enough on the roster to challenge the
Arizona Diamonbacks, which won the West by 14 games, 23 games ahead
of third-place L.A. The Dodgers payroll will exceed $90 million
after third baseman Adrian Beltre's new contract gets worked out.
</P>
<P>
   Fox will not again pay the NL's top payroll for another 1999,
which could cost Malone his job if the Dodgers aren't contending at
the All-Star break. As quick start is almost impossible. Fourteen
of the team's first 20 games are on the road. The Dodgers face
perennial contenders in the Mets, Giants, Braves and Astros 18
times in April.
</P>
<P>
   But this year is already far removed from last.
</P>
<P>
   Said Green, ``I think people aren't expecting as much,'' which
after last summer, can be a beautiful thing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
