<HEADER>
A4013 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CRAFT-NETWORKS-ART-NY     03-11 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRAFT-NETWORKS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPALACHIA'S TREASURES GO ON THE GLOBAL MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONAKER, Va. _ Phyllis Street, of all people, is about to plunge
into the global economy.
</P>
<P>
   The coal miner's widow, who turned for survival to the quilt
maker's arts that run two centuries deep in her family, will leave
her home here on Big A mountain on Monday for the first airplane
trip of her life. It will be to London, where she will be a star
entry from the suddenly less remote back hills of Appalachia in the
Ideal Home Show, Europe's premier exhibition for the booming crafts
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may turn out to be more than this gal can handle,'' said
Street, a virtuoso of quilting, hardly shying from this creative
breakthrough in which Appalachian planners have begun marketing the
best of their tradition-steeped crafters by way of international
trade shows and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   New networks of backwoods co-op businesses and community craft
makers are taking a giant marketing leap beyond the Appalachian
remoteness that long has frozen local economic opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   In leaving just as spring limns the gritty hill country, Street,
a painstaking maker of one-of-a-kind quilts that have come to be
priced at $1,000 and more in the competitive market, is an eager
pioneer. She relishes the venture for celebrating her flinty,
beautiful home region as much as her careful old way with
techniques like reverse applique, echo quilting, cross hatch
bordering, wire-edged ribboning, tendril embroidering and
``ruching'' _ an Old World word surviving here to describe a
particularly artful puckering of fabrics.
</P>
<P>
   The London show will hardly be another weekend at the flea
market. Committees of local craft masters have set firm product
standards so that there can be no gimcrack stereotyping of
Appalachia's best. Market connoisseurs can tell a hurried knock-off
from a quilt that takes Smith a year or more to create.
</P>
<P>
   The London marketing venture is to be conducted at the weeklong
show from a log-cabin pavilion made by Tennessee crafts people. It
is expected to produce an estimated $25 million in sales for 170
artisans and small businesses in 11 states of Appalachia, extending
from central Alabama to southern New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is kind of a watershed event for us, to have some of our
best people under an Appalachia umbrella at that important show,''
said Jesse L. White Jr., the federal co-chairman of the Appalachia
Regional Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is a state and federal venture charged with
nurturing economic and social improvements in the region, which has
been chronically battered by the fading of large-scale mining,
textile and tobacco industries.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the commission has been emphasizing the best hope
in small-business development for the burgeoning export economy.
</P>
<P>
   The London expedition shows once more that Appalachia, too long
prized as a campaign stop for politicians to show off their
empathy, is resilient. It remains pocked with poverty but studded
with master talents in traditional craft making.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the London exhibitors, like Katie McLaughlin, a
``sheep-to-shawl'' weaver and sheep herder from Tazewell, are also
involved as teachers of residents leaving the welfare roles to find
meaningful work. The new marketing for the global economy offers an
enormous window to another cottage-industry exhibitor, Debbie
Pierce and her five children, whom she schools at home in
Jonesville, where they all produce prized wall hangings and table
runners.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a whole new thing for me; we'll see what's going to
happen,'' said Smith, a quilter who works in a painterly fashion,
jotting her thoughts in notebooks and snatching together delicate
swatches and tattered scraps and appliques from the palettelike
shelves of her workroom. She produces such deeply personal works as
``Memories of Mother,'' a rich elegy of a quilt dedicated to the
woman who taught her the homespun craft that has become the
daughter's ticket to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
   Here on the eve of this bit of a breakout for Appalachia,
Phyllis Deel and Jeannie Stanley-Mullins, two organizers from a new
Virginia marketing operation known as PACE (Purely Appalachia Craft
Empowerment), roamed the hill towns. They saw to final details of
the show's entries from 25 contributors chosen in the state's seven
most southwestern coal counties.
</P>
<P>
   The cornucopia includes Larry Counts' handmade brooms, Lee
Osborne's weather vanes rendered from original drawings, the
heirloom needlework of Linda Mullins' infant clothing, plus a score
of other offerings, ranging from traditional slab pottery to
hardwood bowls and rocking horses, and from rag rugs to
apple-butter soap.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the rest of the world is going to be very interested
in what we have to offer,'' Deel proudly declared, driving
switchback up Big A mountain.
</P>
<P>
   What the craft masters are marketing to acquisition-hungry
collectors is a tradition of quality rooted in the very back-hollow
remoteness that has been both bane and blessing to Appalachia's
creative people.
</P>
<P>
   ``My very first remembrance of quilting is being just a tiny
little thing and playing in the pile of scraps my mother always
had,'' said Street, who recently sold a quilt for $3,500 to a woman
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mother quilted to keep us warm,'' she said, noting how much
even the world of Appalachia is changing. ``I loved that pile. I
just watched her at it; that's how I learned. Use-it-up, we called
that pile.''
</P>
</TEXT>
