<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: PESTERED IN PARADISE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By MAUREEN DOWD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Republican Establishment has spent an exhausting winter
luring a pouty W. out of his room. Now it must spend an exhausting
spring luring a pouty John McCain out of his room.
</P>
<P>
   The party elders know they have a dicey task ahead of them. How
can they con the idealistic Arizona senator into believing that
they are riddled with moral anxiety about the impact of money on
American electoral politics, even as W. and Gore begin the biggest
race for money since money was invented?
</P>
<P>
   McAchilles is sulking in his tent. But unless the GOP can get
him to lend his voltage to W., it may have its third presidential
debacle in a row.
</P>
<P>
   The exsurgent has fled on vacation to the South Pacific, to wash
that Bushman right out of his hair. He's eating mahi-mahi in
Bora-Bora, where he can escape Maria Shriver, the Establishment,
the Reform Party, cajoling cell phone calls and placating e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   Picture it:
</P>
<P>
   As McCain walks along the beach one morning, a bottle, an old
Viagra vial, washes up with a message: ``John: Bob Dole says suck
it up. There's life after losing. Lucrative commercials, too.
Besides, Junior won't put Elizabeth on the ticket unless you throw
a fit. You owe Bob Dole. Bob Dole sent you a check for your
campaign last fall while Bob Dole's wife was still in the race. Bob
Dole got sent to the woodshed. Bob Dole was sad. Sincerely, Bob
Dole.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, McCain lounges under a palm, sipping a brightly colored
drink with a little umbrella. He looks up to see the wicked Mitch
McConnell flying in a plane, skywriting: ``Surrender, Dorothy!''
</P>
<P>
   John and Cindy head off to a deserted island for a picnic.
Suddenly, they are stunned at the sight of a parachute opening. A
75-year-old man in a flight suit plummets down into their coconut
tarts. ``Third party,'' Poppy says, shaking his head. ``Wouldn't be
prudent. Message: I care about my boy.''
</P>
<P>
   The McCains make their getaway on a glass-bottom boat. They are
enjoying the exotic fish when a man in a mask and flippers swims
up. With horror, they realize it's none other than W., holding a
hand-lettered sign. ``Don't you judge my heart, Mutiny Man! Got any
more of that reform talk I can use? People seem to go for it.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain storms back to the privacy of his thatched hut. But soon
he is disturbed by the rhythm of Polynesian drums. He realizes they
are pounding out a message from the White House switchboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this Senator McCain? We have the vice president for you,
sir,'' the drums say. Then Al Gore comes on the drum. ``John, you
won't be able to beat me like a drum now. Ha! Ha! But don't cave to
those Bush weasels. Don't believe their promises. They will never
let you be secretary of defense. They think you're crazy as a loon.
I've promised Janet Reno her pick of anything in my cabinet. And my
pal Maria Hsia has her heart set on Treasury. That's the least I
can do for those gals. But we'll find a spot for you, Secretary
McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   The senator gives up hiding and goes back out for a sunset
snorkel. He sees some natives paddling up in a catamaran. As they
draw closer, he recognizes his campaign aides Mike Murphy and John
Weaver, wearing grass skirts. Murphy shouts: ``Stay angry!
G-r-r-r-r-r! Remember the phony veteran! Remember Pat Robertson!
Remember the breast cancer ads! We want a third party! Stay bitter!
Indulge those recriminations!''
</P>
<P>
   As McCain splashes away, he is frightened by the sight of a
dorsal fin. But when the fin surfaces, it turns out to be attached
to the head of Trent Lott.
</P>
<P>
   ``Howdy, John. All is forgiven,'' the majority leader says. ``We
don't think you're crazy anymore. Just plucky. Come home to the
Senate and we'll help you pass your bill to get more flights out of
Reagan Airport. We'll call it the `McCain Straight Flight Express
Act.' ''
</P>
<P>
   McCain darts behind a sand dune. Flying through the dusk, a
carrier cockatoo with a message strapped to its leg lands on his
head. He unrolls the message. It's on MSNBC stationery, from Chris
Matthews, Brian Williams, Jonathan Alter and Don Imus: ``Get back
on that bus! Don't leave us with those two phony princelings. Our
ratings are dropping. Please help us! Yours adoringly, the
Communist Pinko Trotskyites.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
