</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOR GORE, SPEAKING 'FROM THE HEART' WAS KEY TO VICTORY
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore believes the turning point
in his presidential campaign was his decision last summer to halt
constant calculations about what was best for the Clinton
administration and to start speaking ``straight from the heart.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a big change in my priorities,'' Gore said in an
interview Friday night in which he took stock of his campaign for
the Democratic nomination and his general election strategy against
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall campaign, Gore said, he will tout the economic
successes of the Clinton-Gore administration. He said he was
unconcerned about ``Clinton fatigue,'' as pollsters have described
the American public's dismay over President Clinton's personal
failures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the country shifted many months ago into what you
might call Clinton fatigue fatigue,'' he said with a laugh. ``They
wanted to focus on the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also dismissed suggestions that Sen. John McCain's campaign
against Bush failed because his message had little appeal. ``The
need for reform in our system is demonstrated in part by the
support he did receive,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president said that in the general election, ``I'm
certainly going to do my best to raise that banner even higher than
before.''
</P>
<P>
   He repeated his challenge to Bush to renounce the use of both
unregulated ``soft money'' donations to political parties and ads
bought by independent groups of supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Gore said, he and Bush should hold two debates a week.
``If he will agree, we can start next week,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore compared his commitment to campaign finance reform to
McCain's, saying that like the Arizona senator, ``I bring the
commitment born of personal experience to the battle.''
</P>
<P>
   For McCain, the experience was the ``Keating Five'' scandal, in
which five senators faced an ethics investigation after intervening
on behalf of a savings and loan executive who was a campaign
contributor. For Gore, it was his visit to a fund-raising event at
a California Buddhist temple that led to the conviction of a
longtime Gore fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned from my mistakes,'' he added, and suggested that
Bush has not.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to list Bush's mistakes, he said, ``I think it was a
mistake to raise $70 million outside the campaign finance limits. I
think it was a mistake to have secretly financed special-interest
attack ads come in at the last minute against John McCain in the
key primary. And I think it's a mistake to be opposed to campaign
finance reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Reviewing the past year, Gore said his political approach
shifted late last summer, when his campaign seemed uninspiring in
contrast to the growing excitement surrounding his Democratic
challenger, former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to the realization that it's a lot more important to be
a candidate for president than to be the best vice president you
can be to the nth degree,'' Gore said in the interview, conducted
by telephone from Air Force Two. ``That shift in priorities caused
me to understand why my strengths as a vice president had become my
weakness as a presidential candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pausing to reflect for a split second in response to
every question and challenge to ask myself, 'How can I move the
administration's agenda forward, how can I help the Clinton-Gore
administration?' he said. ``I realized that in order to ask the
people of this country for leadership, you have to respond
spontaneously and directly, straight from the heart, and not in any
other way.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said his new approach ``changed everything,'' leading him
to recognize the need to move his campaign headquarters from
Washington to his home state of Tennessee, to shed the trappings of
his office, to begin open meetings with ordinary people, and to
become ``totally immersed in the dialogue with the voters.''
</P>
<P>
   It worked.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, just one week after a clean sweep of 15 states in
the ``Super Tuesday'' primaries, Gore is expected to win the
``Southern Tuesday'' primaries in Florida, Louisiana, Mississippi,
Oklahoma, Tennessee and Texas. That would give him enough delegates
to win the Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Although the South has grown increasingly Republican in
presidential elections, Gore said he is not willing to cede the
South to Bush this year.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he can win anywhere in the South beyond his home state
of Tennessee and Clinton's home state of Arkansas, Gore cited
Georgia. He corralled 84 percent of the Democratic voters there,
his largest victory margin in any of last week's primaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a neighbor to Georgia, I was particularly gratified by
that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the controversy in Florida over Gov. Jeb Bush's
efforts to end affirmative action gives him a political opening
there, Gore said, `` I think the importance of that issue
transcends politics. What the governor of Florida is trying to do
is just plain wrong. ... Regardless of that issue, I am going to be
working hard in Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he does not know Bush personally, having met him only
two or three times. ``I've spent no more than 30 seconds in brief
exchanges,'' he said. ``So I don't really know him other than what
I've seen on television.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president also said he had not yet assessed Bush as a
politician. ``I haven't focused on the Republican contest very
much,'' he said. ``I've been focused on my nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gore said knows enough about the positions Bush has taken on
issues and about his record as governor of Texas to challenge him
on taxes, gun control, abortion rights and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he plans to attack Bush's proposal for a large tax cut
with an argument similar to the one he made against Bradley's call
for universal health care coverage _ that it will wipe out the
federal budget surplus, shred social safety net programs and
jeopardize the strong economy.
</P>
<P>
   He quoted McCain's criticism that Bush's tax cuts would
``clearly put Social Security at risk.'' And he charged that the
wealthy contributors to Bush's campaign are the ones who would
benefit the most from Bush's tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Gore, a key foreign policy player in the
Clinton administration, also plans to place a heavy emphasis on
foreign policy, perhaps Bush's biggest political weakness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to be talking about foreign policy a good bit in
the campaign because I think it should be discussed in a
presidential campaign,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Told that Bush is planning trips abroad to improve his foreign
policy credentials, Gore quipped, ``I hope they're long trips.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
