u i BC-SWISS-CITIZENSHIP-660     03-11 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISS-CITIZENSHIP-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWISS VOTING ON RESIDENCY RAISES FEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ This weekend, in what some view as a worrying trend
that may fan right-wing xenophobia in Switzerland and neighboring
Austria, voters in an industrial suburb of scenic Lucerne will get
to decide in the most personal way who should be a Swiss citizen.
</P>
<P>
   Every eligible voter in Emmen, population 27,000, has received a
booklet containing family photographs and intensely personal data
on tax status, salary, background and hobbies for each of the 56
people in the town who are seeking naturalization.
</P>
<P>
   Small though Emmen is, its vote on future citizens is in some
ways casting a larger shadow than other referendums in Switzerland
on Sunday on issues like introducing quotas to ensure that there
will be more women in top political posts, and stiffening the
already strict Swiss laws against artificial reproduction.
</P>
<P>
   Critics are alarmed that the process, which had a test run last
fall when a Yugoslav family of four was rejected by Emmen voters,
appears to be gaining ground.
</P>
<P>
   In the far larger cities of Zurich and Bern, the local branches
of the right-wing and anti-immigrant Swiss People's Party are
proposing a popular vote on citizenship. Their message carries
distinct echoes of the Austrian right-winger Joerg Haider and his
Freedom Party, which entered government in Vienna last month to
widespread disgust and dismay in the rest of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Swiss people feel danger because there are always more and
more strangers here,'' said Urs Ischi, a member of the increasingly
popular People's Party and an Emmen-based wholesaler who pushed the
town to adopt its system for reviewing citizenship applications.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Grundberg, head of Switzerland's SOS Racism, countered:
``It's a terrible thing that's happening in Emmen. It's been a real
tradition to vote in the villages, where people know each other.
It's another thing to do it in a city.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote in Emmen reflects Switzerland's struggle with one of
Europe's highest percentages of foreigners. Of its 7 million
residents, some 1.4 million, or 20 percent, are from other
countries, particularly workers from Italy, Portugal, Spain and the
countries that once made up the larger Yugoslavia. They were
recruited mostly during labor shortages in the 1960s and 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Now that these workers have been here for decades, many would
like to adopt Switzerland as their country, but they are running up
against resistance, especially in German-speaking central and
eastern Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to have a real identity,'' said Gonne Ganejaj, 21, who
along with her twin, Lily, has been rejected three times for
citizenship by local authorities in Beromunster, a town north of
Lucerne. ``I feel Swiss, but I can't prove it.''
</P>
<P>
   The sisters, who were born in Switzerland after their father
migrated from Kosovo and met the 12-year residency requirement,
were given no reason for the refusal. They are part of the 30
percent non-Swiss population of the canton _ or state _ of Lucerne,
bolstered by the influx of foreign workers filling numerous
factories.
</P>
<P>
   Many foreign workers' children have been born here, but they are
not automatically citizens. A nationwide effort several years ago
to make it easier for them to obtain Swiss passports failed.
</P>
<P>
   Citizenship is not a right but a touchy political decision,
because it has to do with the autonomy of individual communities,
which enjoy almost hallowed status in Switzerland, said Doris
Angst, head of the federal commission against racism. Each
community has a say at the beginning of the three-step citizenship
process. Its approval is followed by review at the cantonal and
federal levels.
</P>
<P>
   In Emmen and its sister suburb, Emmenbrucke, which are
administered together, voters agreed last June that becoming Swiss
would be decided by popular ballot. Voters received applicants'
photographs and personal information down to the number of children
in each family and the amount of individual savings.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's right,'' Mileva Cvitic-Vikalo said of the
display of these details. Her family moved from Croatia 30 years
ago, and her sons, 18 and 14, were born in Emmen.
</P>
<P>
   A glance at their page in the booklet for voters reveals that
her husband, Janko, earns $45,000 a year at the town's central
heating plant, likes to play soccer in his spare time and has no
savings. Her older son has his own page because after age 18 a
decision on citizenship must be made separately.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are also foreigners in Croatia now,'' Cvitic-Vikalo said
when asked why her family was seeking Swiss nationality. She seemed
resigned to rejection, saying, ``I'm not sure if we will succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   The odds are against her family, because they are from one of
the countries that used to be part of Yugoslavia, whose citizens
are widely blamed for increased crime and drug dealing in
Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Central European mentality is OK with the Swiss mentality,
but some mentalities aren't _ the people from the Balkans are too
far from our thinking,'' Ischi said, apparently differentiating
between Czechs, who settled in Switzerland in large numbers after
the Soviets invaded their country in 1968, and former Yugoslavs.
</P>
<P>
   But Ischi denied that the Yugoslav family was rejected last fall
because of their origin, even though Italian and Spanish candidates
succeeded. The family members ``weren't integrated'' and did not
speak Swiss-German after 18 years in Switzerland, he maintained.
The family could not be located for an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an odious system and it will allow racism to spread,''
Nils de Dardel, a Socialist Party lawmaker from Geneva, said of
Emmen's system. ``If you're French or Italian, it's fine, but if
you're Yugoslav, you don't have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   De Dardel and others point to a recent vote in the upscale town
of Baar, in a nearby canton, where 14 of 26 applicants for
citizenship were rejected. Eleven were from the Yugoslavia cluster
and three were from Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Baar, down-at-the-heels Emmen is struggling with the loss
of 5,000 jobs at its textile and steel factories in recent years.
Last year its 8 percent unemployment was more than double the
national level. Today it is around 4 percent, still higher than the
Swiss average.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are feeling insecure in a very new globalized world,
and they have a feeling that being isolated makes them more
secure,'' said Rosemarie Simmen, director of the Swiss foreigners
commission, which is starting a study of the naturalization
process. ``But you can't make a decision like this with 30,000
people who don't even know each other.''
</P>
<P>
   For Ischi, the popular vote ``gives gives back the right to the
people to give out a Swiss passport.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The people here,'' he said, ``have the right to the last
word.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
