<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICA, ONCE OUTCAST, SEEKS SOCCER'S PRIZE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Great Britain, Germany, Brazil)  (DUPLICATION WARNING: Also filed in `i' category.) 
(mk) 
 By HENRI E. CAUVIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ South Africa kicked off a campaign
last week to hold the most important sporting contest in the
country's history when it welcomed a delegation of international
soccer officials who will decide on the country's bid for the 2006
World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Banned from international competition for many years because of
its apartheid policies, South Africa is making its first
application for the soccer showcase, which is staged every four
years and is arguably the world's pre-eminent sporting event.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil, Britain, Germany and Morocco are also in the running.
But Africa is the only continent where the tournament has never
been held, and South Africa's supporters say it is time for that to
change.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa is one of only a few countries on the continent
that has the resources and facilities for the World Cup, which
draws hundreds of thousands of fans, players and journalists and
makes enormous demands on the host country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we can host this event,'' said Irvin Khoza, the
chairman of the country's campaign, in welcoming the committee from
FIFA, soccer's governing body.
</P>
<P>
   Morocco, one of the few other African nations with the resources
even to consider seeking the tournament, is making its third try.
And so far, it has ignored pleas to withdraw its application and
support South Africa's.
</P>
<P>
   The other three nations have experience in their favor, each
having held a World Cup tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The six-day stop in South Africa, which began Thursday, is the
inspection team's last in a series of visits to the bidding
nations. In July, after reviewing the findings of the inspections,
FIFA will decide which country should hold the event.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa was the site of the 1995 Rugby World Cup, the 1996
African Cup of Nations soccer tournament and the 1999 All-Africa
Games, but the World Cup dwarfs them all in the challenges it would
present here.
</P>
<P>
   Safety tops the list. South Africa has one of the highest rates
of violent crime in the world, and its beleaguered national police
force would almost certainly be pushed to its limits in protecting
the thousands of international visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation is another big question because South Africa's
cities have limited public bus and rail systems, and the country
would have to build, virtually from scratch, suitable networks for
moving visitors around the host cities.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the state of soccer in South Africa. Popular
as ever, the sport has nonetheless been racked by a string of
problems in the past several months. Joe Ndhlela, the chief
executive of the leading league, was suspended after being indicted
on fraud charges, several teams are being investigated for tax
evasion, and accusations of match-fixing have been leveled by a top
referee.
</P>
<P>
   The key figures in the sport, along with the minister of sport,
have been under pressure to correct any irregularities, and FIFA
will almost certainly be trying to judge the commitment to that
effort.
</P>
<P>
   As important as all of those questions will be, the inspection
team is looking hardest at the intangibles as it tours the country,
takes in a match and talks to fans, said Alan Rothenberg, an
American heading the six-member inspection committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things we want to do is really get a feel for the
people's support, that this is not a top-down bid but is something
that everyone is committed to,'' said Rothenberg, who was the chief
organizer of the 1994 World Cup, the first staged in the United
States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
