<HEADLINE>
ROBERT E. LEE'S CHILDHOOD HOME IS SOLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)  (jw) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALEXANDRIA, Va. _ Unable to pay for the upkeep of a museum, a
Civil War historical preservation group has sold the house where
Gen. Robert E. Lee grew up to a couple who intend to turn it into
their own home.
</P>
<P>
   The new owners, Mark Kington, a managing director at a venture
capital firm, and his wife, Ann, quietly acquired the dignified
brick town house with white trimming for $2.5 million from the
nonprofit Lee-Jackson Foundation. But the attorney general of
Virginia, Mark L. Earley, has asked that no money from the sale be
disbursed and no renovations on the house be made until his office
has reviewed the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   There were no competing bids on the house, and the deal was
never brought to the attention of the public real estate market.
</P>
<P>
   Listed on the National Register of Historic Places, the house is
characteristic of the Federal and Georgian architectural styles.
Robert E. Lee, the Confederate leader, lived there with his father,
Henry Lee III, a Revolutionary War cavalryman known as Light-Horse
Harry for his adroit horsemanship, and his mother, Ann, from the
time he was 5 until he entered West Point in 1825.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of this Washington suburb and Civil War historians
said they were surprised by the sale, which was prompted by the
foundation's inability to finance the 205-year-old house's
structural repairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a loss to our community,'' said Kristen Miller, the
director of the Lee-Fendall Museum, across the street from Robert
E. Lee's boyhood home. Miller was notified of the sale on the
afternoon of March 3, the day the Lee-Jackson Foundation and the
Kingtons signed a contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were absolutely astonished,'' said Col. Thomas Taylor, the
director of Stratford Hall, the 1,600-acre plantation in Montross,
Va., where Lee was born.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said he had received a letter from the Lee-Jackson
foundation saying the sale was in the ``best interest of the
preservation of the house'' because the Kingtons would care for it
well.
</P>
<P>
   Proceeds from the sale will go toward the Lee-Jackson
Foundation's college scholarship fund for Virginia high school
students.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
