<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-ISRAEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEIRUT SEEKS TO USE PULLOUT BY ISRAELIS AS LEVERAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JOHN F. BURNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ After 22 years of having Israeli troops
occupying part of its territory, Lebanon is only four months away
from the deadline Israel has set for withdrawing the troops. But
instead of celebrating the prospect of regaining 10 percent of its
territory, Lebanon has balked, setting terms of its own for the
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   The Lebanese position is part of a wider strategy that has been
closely coordinated with Syria, its much larger neighbor, which
exercises an effective overlordship in Lebanon through the 35,000
troops it has stationed here. In effect, diplomats say, Lebanon and
Syria see the Israeli commitment to withdraw as a chance to exact
additional concessions from Israel on other long-running issues.
</P>
<P>
   Israel, anticipating these demands, has said it is prepared to
complete its withdrawal without prior commitments to Israel's
future security, although it has said that it would prefer to have
agreements in place with its two neighbors before the pullout. The
issue was given added urgency when the Israeli cabinet endorsed the
July withdrawal last Sunday, making an official government policy
of what had previously been an election pledge by Ehud Barak,
Israel's prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from assuaging domestic political pressures, Barak sees
the withdrawal as a means of stripping Syria of a bargaining chip
in the negotiations over the Golan Heights, the strategic territory
seized by Israel during the 1967 Arab-Israeli war. The Lebanese and
Syrian demands for additional concessions amount to an attempt to
trump Barak, by warning that a unilateral withdrawal _ without
prior negotiations with Beirut and Damascus _ could lead to a new
conflict, with Palestinian refugees in Lebanon using the vacated
territory as a springboard for attacks on Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``An Israeli unilateral withdrawal will not work,'' Lebanon's
president, Emile Lahoud, said in an interview published Saturday in
Al-Hayat, a London-based newspaper. ``It will lead to another
war.''
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats see it as no coincidence that Lebanon and Syria have
pushed their demands before this weekend's biannual summit meeting
of Arab foreign ministers. The meeting, which began here Saturday,
has been billed as an occasion for the 22-member Arab League to
show a rare common front on the Middle East peace talks, and to
underline its backing of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   The first of the demands on Israel concerns Syria's insistence
on the return of the Golan. In January, Syria's demand for a prior
Israeli commitment to the handover of the territory led to the
suspension of Israeli-Syrian peace talks. Now, diplomats say, Syria
sees Israel's interest in completing its withdrawal without threat
of attack by the Lebanese guerrillas of Hezbollah as a means of
pressuring Israel over the Golan.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Lebanon appears determined to use the Israeli
withdrawal to press its longstanding demand for Israel to accept
the repatriation of the Palestinian refugees who migrated to
Lebanon during the wars of 1948 and 1967. The Lebanese government
numbers these refugees at 360,000, but some experts say that
migration since the battles of the 1980s has reduced the population
to no more than 200,000.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the figure, Lebanon has refused to accept the
Palestinians as citizens, and has confined most of them to pitiable
refugee camps. Now, Lebanon is demanding that Israel and the United
States, as the prime mover in the Middle East peace effort, accept
the right of the Palestinians to return, which in many cases would
mean moving to what is now Israel, or to the West Bank. The United
States has said the question should be settled separately.
</P>
<P>
   The demand is one that Israel, as well as Yasser Arafat's
Palestinian authority, has rejected. But after a telephone
conversation last week with Syria's president, Hafez el-Assad,
Lahoud, put it on the table as a condition for Israel's demand for
security guarantees after its pullout from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Lahoud then raised the stakes by warning of a possible
resumption of attacks on Israel by the Lebanon-based Palestinians,
the issue that precipitated Israel's invasion of Lebanon in 1978.
``How would it be possible to guarantee Israel's borders when
thousands of armed refugees are present in the Palestinians camps,
demanding the right to return amid a total absence of any answers
about their fate and future?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another issue that Lebanon could raise with Israel involves the
border between the two countries. Some Lebanese politicians have
said that they will not accept an Israeli withdrawal to the
frontier that existed before the 1978 invasion, but only to what
they call ``the internationally recognized border.'' These
politicians claim that a pullout back to the 1978 frontier would
involve Israel annexing about 46 square miles of land that was
Lebanon's before 1948.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
