<HEADLINE>
ALSATIAN MAN ENDS WALK CROSS PACIFIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The journey of an Alsatian man who intended to
walk across the Pacific Ocean from Los Angeles to Sydney,
Australia, came to a rapid end about 30 miles off the coast of Los
Angeles this week, when his sleeping quarters were destroyed by
debris in a storm.
</P>
<P>
   Remy Bricka, 50, intended to spend six months crossing the
Pacific on pontoonlike skis while towing a catamaran behind him
with food and sleeping quarters, but the adventure lasted less than
a day. Bricka said in an interview on Friday that he hit stormy
weather and 18-foot swells early Sunday in the first night of his
journey.
</P>
<P>
   The catamaran, which was being towed by friends on a boat who
had agreed to see him through the first 100 miles, was hit by wood
debris in the storm, and the capsule where Bricka slept and kept
computer, electronic and communication equipment was filled with
water.
</P>
<P>
   The boat that was towing him then blew out an engine, and the
U.S. Coast Guard had to rescue the party.
</P>
<P>
   Bricka said he hoped to replace his equipment at a cost of as
much as $40,000 and try again in April.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
