<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, March 12, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   A band of wet snow will linger Sunday morning from western
Pennsylvania to northern parts of New York and New England as
breezes from the north draw chilly air into a developing storm
system. Locally heavy snow and sleet will occur in the mountains of
northern New England. Rain will fall elsewhere in New England as
the low-pressure center moves across these regions. Rain will taper
to drizzle during midday and afternoon in southern New England, but
rain and some snow in northern sections will persist in Maine for
most of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The Southeast will turn breezy and cooler. A few showers will
dampen areas near the Carolina coast early Sunday, but ample
sunshine will cover most of the region by midday. Most of Florida
will be cooler than recent days; however, scattered thundershowers
will occur in the warmer air near the southern coast.
</P>
<P>
   A broken area of light snow and flurries will occur in the
chilly air north of a weak low-pressure area as it moves from the
central Dakotas to the northern Mississippi Valley. Farther south,
plentiful sunshine over the central and southern Plains will mix
with patchy clouds later in the day. Afternoon temperatures will be
a bit above the seasonal average.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Western states will be dry. Abundant sunshine will
boost temperatures above normal from the deserts of the Southwest
to the southern California coast. In the Northwest, a few rain
showers will brush the Olympic peninsula while scattered snow
showers occur in the Bitterroot Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Spring Floods
</P>
<P>
   Spring is a time of heightened concern about floods. In a
typical year, melting snow can conspire with increased rainfall to
make river flooding a threat. Sometimes, in northern areas, ice
jams exacerbate the floods on swollen rivers. This year spring
flooding will be much less than normal. The exceptionally mild
conditions in the Northern states mean that water locked in the
remaining snow cover is scant. The flood risk is so low in the Red
River Valley of the Dakotas that the National Weather Service has
canceled the flood outlooks that are normally issued at this time
of year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
