<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIREFIGHTER-RAMPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUNERAL HELD FOR SLAIN MEMPHIS FIREFIGHTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn.)  (jw) 
 By EMILY YELLIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEMPHIS _ As funerals began Saturday for the victims of a
shooting rampage in which a firefighter is accused, law-enforcement
authorities said they had not yet learned what prompted the
slayings of the firefighter's wife, a deputy sheriff and two fellow
firefighters who came to his home to put out the blaze he is
accused of setting.
</P>
<P>
   Frederick Williams, 41, was charged with four counts of
first-degree murder, one count of attempted murder and one count of
arson.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Williams confessed to the killings from his hospital
bed in an hourlong interview with officers on Thursday. He is
recovering from a broken leg caused by bullets police fired to
subdue him during his rampage, they say.
</P>
<P>
   The police director, Walter Crews, said Williams had given no
reason for his actions in his confession but had clarified for
investigators how events unfolded on Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   According to investigators, Williams told police officers that
he used a shotgun in his suburban home to kill his wife, Stacey
Williams, 32, a letter carrier, at about 12:30 p.m. Wednesday, just
after she got home from work. The couple had been married only
three weeks before, on Valentine's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Then, according to the police report, Williams, who had called
in sick to the fire department that morning, said he had set a
bedroom on fire and left the house. Outside, using the same gun, he
fired one shot at Rupert Peete, 45, a deputy sheriff sitting in his
squad car.
</P>
<P>
   Peete, who had been on his way to another call when a neighbor
of Williams' had diverted him to the Williams home, died instantly
and his car crashed into a fence.
</P>
<P>
   The same shot also injured, but did not kill, Deborah Gatewood,
the neighbor who had alerted Peete that Williams was wielding a gun
outside the burning home.
</P>
<P>
   Then, according to the report, Williams fired at, but did not
hit, neighbors who tried to come to Gatewood's aid.
</P>
<P>
   Two fire engines arrived, and one firefighter, Javier Lerma, 41,
got out to take a look at the fire. Williams told the police he
then shot Lerma in the head, killing him.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is also charged with shooting and killing William
Blakemore, 48, another firefighter, who was inside one of the fire
trucks. Crews, the police director, said that Blakemore had been on
duty substituting for Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Police arrived at the scene and shot Williams in the leg and
arrested him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears as though this is a culmination of a domestic
violence situation that erupted into a violent rage for anyone
around, which included people he worked with,'' Crews said. ``
Blakemore had been detailed to the engine house where this man
worked to take his place on the job that day. It just compounds the
tragedy of it all.''
</P>
<P>
   The shootings have left the Memphis Fire Department and many
others in the city stunned, and funds have been set up for the
families of the victims.
</P>
<P>
   Lerma was buried Saturday after a funeral at St. Francis of
Assisi Catholic Church in Memphis. Firefighters, police officers,
friends and church members paid their respects. For the Lerma
family, the funeral was a familiar rite. Lerma's father, also a
firefighter, had died while fighting a fire in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Funeral services for Blakemore and Peete were scheduled for
Monday and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Information on Williams' funeral has not been released.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
