<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BLAIR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTIN, IN MEETING WITH BLAIR, DOES NOT YIELD ON CHECHNYA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ At his first meeting with a Western leader since he
became Russian head of state, Acting President Vladimir Putin told
Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain on Saturday that he was
willing to give human rights organizations more access to the war
zone in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   But with Russian troops fighting some of the bloodiest battles
of the five-month war, Putin, the certain favorite in Russia's
March 26 presidential elections, gave no ground as Blair pressed
for peace talks with Chechen rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The two men, both lawyers by training, both of the same
generation, met in the imperial splendor of Petrodvorets, the
seaside palace built by Peter the Great, the czar whose portrait
hangs in Putin's office in homage to his role as state builder and
Westernizer.
</P>
<P>
   Blair, who was accompanied by his wife, Cherie, was later given
a whirlwind cultural tour of the old imperial capital, which also
happens to be Putin's hometown. The setting added symbolism to a
visit that Putin clearly hopes will set the tone for relations with
his Western counterparts as he establishes his identity in the club
of world leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper Segodnya on Saturday recalled Boris Yeltsin's
penchant for no-tie get-togethers and his habit of meeting world
leaders in sweaters and slacks, commenting that Putin prefers a
more imperial style.
</P>
<P>
   Facing down criticism at home for meeting a leader responsible
for a war notable for its brutality, Blair seemed set Saturday to
establish a working relationship with Russia's new leader, and to
keep the dialogue with Moscow open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to say how much I enjoyed the dialogue, which was a
very good omen for the future,'' Blair said after his first meeting
with the Russian acting president, in a comment that seemed to take
for granted Putin's victory in the upcoming election.
</P>
<P>
   Putin acknowledged Blair's concerns about the Russian military
campaign, which has been repeatedly criticized in the West for its
violence, particularly against the civilian population. Putin said,
``The Russian leadership, and I personally, must understand what
lies behind this position'' of Blair. ``I must admit that Russia is
making adjustments after such meetings. Russia is paying particular
attention to the opinion of its foreign partners, especially such
esteemed politicians as Tony Blair.''
</P>
<P>
   Sergei Prikhodko, a top Kremlin foreign policy adviser,
described the meetings between Blair and Putin as a very energetic
and open conversation between two very energetic and open leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Putin gave Blair a tour of the Hermitage, the fine arts
museum housed in the czars' Winter Palace, and in the evening, both
men and their wives, as well as James Wolfensohn, chairman of the
World Bank, attended a gala premiere of ``War and Peace,'' an opera
by Sergei Prokofiev.
</P>
<P>
   In his role as presidential host, Putin set a sharp contrast
with Yeltsin, who in his last years in office often stumbled at
public ceremonies, or made gaffes that made Russians wince in
shame.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, the year before he became the Soviet Communist Party's
general secretary, Mikhail Gorbachev, then a member of the
Politburo, traveled to Britain with his wife, Raisa, for an
informal meeting with Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher. Thatcher
afterward proclaimed Gorbachev to be a man she could do business
with, a comment that set the tone for the new Soviet leader's
reception abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The Chechen war and Putin's past as a KGB agent have raised
concerns both in the West and among members of Russia's small
liberal elite about his commitments to a free press, political
pluralism and other democratic standards.
</P>
<P>
   A Council of Europe parliamentary delegation flew to Grozny,
Chechnya's devastated capital, on Saturday to investigate reports
of atrocities and rights abuses by Russian forces.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Putin's administration has sent mixed signals. On
Saturday, a top military official, meeting with representatives of
Human Rights Watch, an organization that has documented cases of
atrocities committed by Russian troops in Chechnya, did not dispute
their facts and agreed that the mentality of the Russian military
must be changed.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Russia's top military prosecutor told the
press Saturday that the crime rate among troops fighting in
Chechnya was only one-fourth of that among troops posted elsewhere,
because soldiers were too busy fighting to commit crimes.
</P>
<P>
   In Chechnya on Saturday, battles raged in the villages in the
foothills of the Caucasus mountains, as Russian troops fought to
push out rebel guerrillas who have held on to their positions,
defying Russian predictions of victory. Russian officials
acknowledged Friday that 156 servicemen had been killed in the past
week, one of the bloodiest of the war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
