<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4047 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-ART     03-11 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: MADNESS AND SADNESS AT ST. JOHN'S 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Who is Erick Barkley playing for? This is the
million-dollar question that the wiry St. John's point guard will
contemplate for the next three weeks as March Madness _ the men's
and women's college basketball tournaments _ begins.
</P>
<P>
   Is Barkley playing for himself and his family? For his
teammates? Is he playing for St. John's University?
</P>
<P>
   Barkley made a short-term decision around midnight Friday.
Somewhere in the fever pitch of the Red Storm's Big East tournament
semifinal game against Miami at Madison Square Garden, Barkley
decided that he had had enough.
</P>
<P>
   Weakened by a stomach virus, scarred by the news that the
National Collegiate Athletic Association was extending its
investigation into his academic life at Maine Central Institute and
possibly upset by tension within the team, Barkley said he wasn't
playing for anyone.
</P>
<P>
   After the exhilarating one-point victory, Barkley, dejected and
near tears, told reporters he was taking a leave of absence. Leave
of absence? On the eve of the Big East championship game? Had
Barkley taken leave of his senses?
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came as a shock to everyone. Coach Mike Jarvis,
who was initially caught off guard by Barkley's independent act,
put his point guard's decision in a larger context.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are things sometime that are bigger than wins,'' Jarvis
said, ``and it's time for people to understand that. We're talking
about dealing with a young man who is first of all a very proud
human being, who has a great mother and family and who has been
through a tremendous amount.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis left the door wide open for his star point guard to
return. ``He's entitled to whatever thoughts he has at the time,''
Jarvis said, meaning that he would be welcomed back whenever he
decides to play. ``It's all part of being a human being.''
</P>
<P>
   Usually, the beauty of a sport like basketball _ sports in
general _ is that there are clear-cut winners and losers, goats,
heroes and heroines.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of St. John's and Erick Barkley vs. the NCAA, there
are no clear-cut good guys and bad guys, nor a lot of innocent
guys.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA enforcement staff has been criticized, even from
within, for applying narrow interpretations to archaic rules
governing amateurism and extra benefits. In its dispute with St.
John's, the NCAA has locked itself in a combative box from which
there can now be no graceful escape.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's has not been forthcoming with information and has
thrown annoying barriers across the road to keep the NCAA off the
trail. The university continues to hide behind the reputation of
the Riverside Church while refusing to acknowledge that the
church's high-powered basketball program is a de facto feeder
system from which St. John's has richly benefited over the years.
Ernie Lorch, the program's founder, is a St. John's supporter.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley is no innocent guy either. Like most star players at
nearly any university, in any sport, Barkley has profited _ even if
the profit was no more than having his prep school tuition paid.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA suspects that there may be more. There may have been an
ingrained system of gifts and perks that violated NCAA regulations.
The rules may be silly, arcane and hypocritical, but these are the
rules of the organization to which St. John's belongs; this is an
affiliation that allows the university to pay Jarvis hefty
compensation to coach.
</P>
<P>
   The team is built on precision, passing and chemistry, and now
that chemistry has been disrupted. There were reports of a
locker-room altercation between Barkley and his teammate Bootsy
Thornton at halftime of Friday's game, with Barkley apparently
injuring his left arm. The NCAA investigation might have
contributed to the tension of the moment, although most members of
the team have cited Barkley's problems with the NCAA as a unifying,
rather than a divisive, factor.
</P>
<P>
   From a basketball perspective, the shame of all this is that
Jarvis has St. John's playing well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're probably passing better this year than last year,'' the
junior guard-forward Reggie Jessie said. ``Last year we give it to
him; he sets something up and everything revolves around him. This
year everyone knows their role, and they're playing their role.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis, criticized last month for harsh comments comparing the
NCAA to the Gestapo and its investigation to rape, gave a more
tempered criticism Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next thing you know, they'll want to check his birth
certificate to see if he's a U.S. citizen,'' Jarvis said, ``and if
he's not, maybe they'll deport him.''
</P>
<P>
   Was the NCAA being vindictive?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if vindictive is the right word,'' Jarvis said.
``You can probably take a hundred words. But obviously we need to
continue to look at what's going on and we need to continue to ask
the hard questions. We need to maybe start looking at what's going
on the other side of the fence, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis added: ``I marvel at how much he's been able to endure so
far. But I'm still betting on Erick Barkley.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe St. John's has outgrown the need for the NCAA. Maybe the
next step is for a number of players, coaches and administrators to
take Barkley's lead and sit this tournament out, let the networks
televise reruns of tournaments past.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to change,'' Jarvis said. ``I hope that a lot of
people will finally get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Here we are at tournament season, and the NCAA's shining moment
is tarnished. One young man must determine for whom and for what is
he playing. Erick Barkley is certainly no longer playing for the
good and glory of the NCAA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
