<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAFEAT0312-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Worm deftly pulled
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The notice came over the Internet, which should
surprise no one because Mark Cuban made his billions that way. The
Dallas Mavericks' owner-to-be had tired of Dennis Rodman, and he
gave the Weird One the boot.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of letting public relations people handle it, Cuban sent
an e-mail to the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some proactive data on the Mavs releasing Dennis,'' is what
Cuban's e-mail said at the top. This is unique, to say the least.
Cuban, who'll shortly be approved by the NBA Board of Governors as
the Mavericks' owner, made the rounds during the NBA All-Star game
in February, shaking as many hands as possible.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, the billionaire e-mails a writer, saying he's glad
they met. This, again, is unique, for in the stuffy world of NBA
ownership, getting an owner to return a call is a major chore. To
get an unsolicited greeting and then receive a question-and-answer
e-mail from Cuban (again unsolicited) is unprecedented.
</P>
<P>
   But back to the Weird Worm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did we release him?'' Cuban wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got Dennis for a run at the playoffs. We obviously were not
successful in making that run. Rather than sitting Dennis on the
bench to give the other guys more time on the court, we decided it
would be better to release him. This at least gives him a chance to
get picked up by another team, even though he would not be elgible
to play in the playoffs,'' Cuban answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was it for basketball-related reasons, or because of his
recent comments about you and the team?'' Cuban asked, this time
posing a question as if a reporter asked him. Hey, the guy's
creative.
</P>
<P>
   He answered his own question: ``The comments had nothing to do
with it. We all are upset about losing. I would do this all again
and sign Dennis in a heartbeat. It was the right move, we just
didn't get the wins we wanted. I would also tell you that if we
were three games out of a playoff position, we would not be
releasing him. This has to do with creating playing time for the
younger guys and creating continuity for next year. We just didn't
think it would serve Dennis or the Mavs well if we just sat him
down and didn't play him.''
</P>
<P>
   More Cuban interviewing himself:
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you still consider him a friend?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely. I think the world of Dennis.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think he can still play?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No question about it. He is a great competitor and rebounder.
I think any team looking at a run for the playoffs in the Eastern
Conference, or not remaining on our schedule should definitely pick
him up.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not end the missive with a ``So long, Mark.'' But the
feeling was that he'll be heard from again.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
