<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4051 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     03-11 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: NFL NEEDS TO SOFTEN ITS CAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In pro football, the best players now resemble the cost of
lobsters on a fancy menu. Just put ``market price'' next to their
names.
</P>
<P>
   More and more with those players, it's not whether you win or
lose, it's how you play the market _ the free-agent market or the
renegotiated-contract market. And unless the National Football
League finds a way to soften its salary cap so a franchise can keep
its best players at market prices, that cap will continue to
sabotage the essence of pro football and of any other popular
spectator sport _ the fans' loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   To lessen the movement of ``market-price'' players, let every
team pay its own players above and beyond the NFL salary cap, which
is now as hard as a helmet, especially for players a team has
drafted and developed.
</P>
<P>
   In all the talk about the New York Jets' suddenly shopping
Keyshawn Johnson, the problem isn't so much that he wants to
renegotiate his contract as it is the Jets' inability to fit a new
deal under the $62.172 million cap.
</P>
<P>
   The irony of the Jets' success under Bill Parcells, like that of
other successful teams, is that the Jets now have so many quality
players, they can't pay all of them the quality salaries that the
market has set.
</P>
<P>
   If the Jets or any other team drafts and develops good players,
it should be rewarded. Instead, it's punished. The salary cap, no
matter how much it increases every year, allows only so much for a
team's payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Keyshawn Johnson and his agent, Jerome Stanley, are
blameless. Their complaint is that the two-time Pro Bowl wide
receiver is underpaid in today's market, that he will collect only
$1.74 million in basic salary in the 2000 season. They conveniently
forget that as a rookie he signed a six-year, $15 million deal,
including a $6.5 million bonus, when he had not yet proved he was
worth all that money.
</P>
<P>
   That's the one-way street too many players and agents live on
now. And too often that one-way sign points out of town.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the St. Louis Rams stopped celebrating their Super
Bowl victory, the ``market price'' had eroded their roster of four
players, notably tackle Fred Miller and center Mike Gruttadauria,
just as it had eroded the Super Bowl depth of the 49ers and Cowboys
after the salary cap was created in 1994. Once a quality player is
an unrestricted free agent, another team can always afford to offer
him more money to jump ship.
</P>
<P>
   That's how the New York Giants lost Chad Bratzke, now a Pro Bowl
defensive end with the Indianapolis Colts. Under the old system,
the Giants would have been set at defensive end for a decade with
Michael Strahan and Bratzke, but under the cap, they could afford
to pay only one of them market price. They preferred Strahan, the
right choice as the better of the two at the time, but Bratzke's
departure depleted the defense as last season's Giants finished
7-9.
</P>
<P>
   Bratzke's departure also depleted some Giants fans' loyalty. He
had been drafted (in the fifth round in 1994) and developed by the
Giants, just as Johnson had been drafted (with the very first
choice in 1996) and developed by the Jets, the way a fan likes to
see it happen. But Bratzke is gone, just as Johnson might be gone.
That's the way it is with every NFL team, where the salary cap is
never enough to afford all of a good team's quality players.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that way in the National Basketball Association; its
salary cap allows a team to pay its own players exorbitant money
that doesn't count against the cap. That's why Michael Jordan never
left the Bulls; that's why Patrick Ewing, Karl Malone, John
Stockton, Hakeem Olajuwon and David Robinson have played with only
one NBA team.
</P>
<P>
   With so much more movement by quality players in the NFL than
the NBA, more and more pro football fans feel betrayed by
unrequited love. They are reluctant to become devoted because that
quality player isn't likely to be as loyal to the franchise as the
fans are. It's difficult for fans to become attached to a player
when they know that, as soon as he's a free agent, he's likely to
be playing for another team for more money.
</P>
<P>
   But the ultimate problem is that the NFL is reluctant to soften
its cap. Under its collective bargaining agreement, the players
receive 63 percent of the gross income. Counting benefits, it's
almost 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   If the NFL were to allow a team to pay its own players a certain
amount above and beyond the cap, that percentage to the players
would increase in direct proportion to the decrease in the owners'
profits. But the NFL needs to come up with something to help a team
keep its own players, especially those whom the team has drafted
and developed.
</P>
<P>
   In the shake-up of the ``Monday Night Football'' telecast,
Howard Katz, the president of ABC Sports, talked about how the
production had developed a ``sameness.'' But maybe that's because
the NFL has developed a sameness, too. Too many players with the
same ``market price'' next to their names.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
