<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 15:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4053 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-NBANOTES0312-COX     03-11 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES0312-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The power struggle: top teams in the eastern and western
conferences
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   EASTERN CONFERENCE
</P>
<P>
   1. Indiana Pacers. They continue to establish themselves as the
class of the conference. To win at home over Portland without Jalen
Rose showed Larry Bird's group just might be primed to make a title
run.
</P>
<P>
   2. Miami Heat. Almost by default, the Heat land here. Miami has
done nothing to really establish itself lately, which speaks for
the weak competition in the East.
</P>
<P>
   3. Philadelphia 76ers. Toni Kukoc and Allen Iverson are learning
to play together, and with their defense, the Sixers could be real
trouble in the playoffs. They still need one more scorer.
</P>
<P>
   4. Toronto Raptors. With Vince Carter playing on an entirely
different level from most everyone else in the league, the Raptors
are growing immensely. They're winning in close games and on the
road, thanks largely to Carter, which should help in the
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   5. New York Knicks. Maybe the return of Charlie Ward and pending
return of Marcus Camby can inject some consistent life in this
uneven club. Right now, they are dry.
</P>
<P>
   WESTERN CONFERENCE
</P>
<P>
   1. Los Angeles Lakers. A classic case of a coach making a
difference. Phil Jackson has the team functioning as a team, and
with the talent the Lakers have, that's significant.
</P>
<P>
   2. Portland Trail Blazers. Speaking of talent, Portland has had
much of it playing poorly lately. Steve Smith and Scottie Pippen
have been average, and so the team dropped three in a row for the
first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   3. Utah Jazz. It seems there's nothing that can derail Karl
Malone and John Stockton from getting it done. They continue to
show the value of experience.
</P>
<P>
   4. Phoenix Suns. Penny Hardaway finally has realized the team
needs him to score, and he's getting it done. And the firepower
Rodney Rogers provides has been outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   5. San Antonio Spurs. Tim Duncan's back, and so are the
champions. Soon Sean Elliott will join the club, and if he regains
his old form, they'll be formidable again.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE RISE
</P>
<P>
   Toronto forward Vince Carter. He's hotter than a comet. His
confidence is in the stratosphere, which showed big-time on his
buzzer-beating three-pointer to down the Los Angeles Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles center Shaquille O'Neal. He's been so good that it
has become routine for him to dominate. No one's better this
season, and O'Neal continues to show it in guiding the Lakers to 17
consecutive victories.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana's Mark Jackson. The unselfish point guard never
complains about having his minutes split with Travis Best. And
against Portland on Thursday, Jackson had 23 points, including 10
in overtime, nine assists and no turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   FREE-FALLIN'
</P>
<P>
   Hawks guard Isaiah Rider. He can't make it to games on time, and
he has made no positive impact in the team's latest slide.
Suspension likely is coming for tardiness.
</P>
<P>
   Portland's Scottie Pippen. He wanted out of Chicago and then
Houston, and now, when the Trail Blazers go through a rough
stretch, Pippen hardly has been the effective player the team
needs.
</P>
<P>
   WORTH NOTING
</P>
<P>
   Joe Dumars, the low-key member of the Detroit Pistons'
``Bad-Boys'' championship teams of 1989-90, had his No. 4 jersey
retired by the team Friday. Dumars, a six-time National Basketball
Association All-Star, was the Most Valuable Player of the 1989 NBA
Finals, leading Detroit over the Los Angeles Lakers for the first
of two consecutive titles. During his 14-year career with the team,
Dumars compiled 16,401 points, 4,612 assists and 902 steals. The
36-year-old, who is the team's vice president of player personnel,
is the sixth Pistons player to have his number retired, joining
Dave Bing, Bob Lanier, Vinnie Johnson, Bill Laimbeer and Isiah
Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Lakers are moving into elite company with their
17-game winning streak. If they win No. 18 tonight at home against
Sacramento, they will tie three teams (1969 Knicks, 1982 Celtics,
1996 Bulls) with the third-longest streak in NBA history. If they
win Monday at Denver and Thursday at Washington, they will tie the
1971 Bucks with 20 consecutive wins. The record? 33 in a row by the
1972 Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Shandon Anderson was greeted by a chorus of boos during his
return to the Delta Center in Salt Lake City. Anderson, the former
University of Georgia star who played the first three seasons of
his NBA career with the Utah Jazz, left the team in the offseason
and signed with the Houston Rockets. Anderson scored 16 points, but
the Jazz ripped the Rockets 101-82.
</P>
<P>
   George Irvine said he does not want to coach the Detroit
Pistons, and he's not afraid to let anyone know it. After the team
fired Alvin Gentry on Monday, Irvine was moved from assistant to
interim coach. But he wants to remain an assistant, not a full-time
head coach. ``I just don't want to do this,'' Irvine said. ``I just
really don't want to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   MAKING HEADLINES
</P>
<P>
   Already established as a supernova, Vince Carter added to his
status with another game-winner, that game-winning three at the
Clippers. More significantly, Toronto ran its streaks to six
consecutive road wins and eight overall.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks corrected an error by releasing Dennis Rodman the
day after the enigmatic forward publicly criticized owner Mark
Cuban. Rodman lasted 29 days in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Isaiah Rider of the Hawks was late every home game and was
warned that he'd be suspended for three games if he shows up late
again.
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING AHEAD
</P>
<P>
   Sean Elliott, the starting small forward on San Antonio's
championship team last year, will make his return to the NBA
Tuesday against the Hawks after undergoing a kidney transplant
seven months ago.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey Nets forward Jayson Williams, out 11 months after
breaking his leg, has received clearance to begin practicing with
the team this week.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
