u p BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      03-11 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WINNING TICKETS? AN EARLY LINE  
 WAITING FOR PEROT MAY BE IN VAIN  
 FALWELL'S CRUSADE: VOTER REGISTRATION  
 ONE CANDIDATE'S WAY OF GETTING ATTENTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES JR.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE WINNING TICKETS? AN EARLY LINE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Though it now seems certain that Gov. George W. Bush of Texas
will be the Republican presidential nominee and Vice President Al
Gore will be the Democratic nominee, both men insist it is too
early to talk about running mates.
</P>
<P>
   But others are talking, toying with pairings that might win. It
is all pure speculation, but herewith, in no particular order
except by party, are some theoretical pairings, along with the
perceived pros and cons.
</P>
<P>
   Caveat emptor.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and ...
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain of Arizona: He could help heal the party rift
left by the primaries and bring in the independents and dissident
Democrats Bush failed to draw. But he insists No. 2 is not for him.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Colin L. Powell: He is still an unusually popular public
figure. But he has already rejected a shot at being No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole: She worked hard for Bush after dropping out of
the race herself and could help close the gender gap. But she is a
so-so stump performer.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania: He is a Bush friend from an
Eastern megastate, a former member of Congress and a good
fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki of New York: He helped deliver his megastate
to Bush in the primary, and his presence on the ticket in November
might force Gore to commit extra time and money to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman of New Jersey: She also could help with
the gender gap. But her support of abortion rights poses a major
problem for a ticket with an anti-abortion candidate at the top.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and ...
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey: He could help unify the
party. But his poor performance in the primaries exposed weakness
on the stump. And, anyway, he insists he is not interested.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Evan Bayh of Indiana: In heavily Republican Indiana, this
popular politician with an easygoing stump style has been elected
both governor and senator. So he has the potential to help the
Democratic ticket in the Midwest. But would the contrast between
his stump style and Gore's be too jarring?
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dianne Feinstein of California: She's been mentioned for
years as a possible choice for vice president and could help Gore
hang on to the women's vote nationally. Equally important, she
could help him lock in California.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of Energy Bill Richardson: He is Hispanic. And in the
Southwest and three of the biggest states _ California, Texas and
New York _ the Hispanic vote is beginning to make a big difference.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Kerry of Massachusetts: He worked hard for Gore after
deciding not to run himself. He is a Vietnam War hero.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gov. Kathleen Kennedy Townsend of Maryland: She is a long,
long shot. But since she is both a Kennedy and a woman, this
speculation started almost the moment she first signed up to run
for a public office.
</P>
<P>
   WAITING FOR PEROT MAY BE IN VAIN
</P>
<P>
   The drive to draft Ross Perot for a third run for president
seems to be making little headway.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Reform Party members who want him to be their
nominee rather than Pat Buchanan, the hard-right news commentator,
held news conferences in a dozen cities around the country. But the
coverage was minimal, with few reporters or Perot supporters
showing up.
</P>
<P>
   In Louisville, Ky., for example, the news conference turned out
to be a nonevent. Not one reporter showed up, only the state party
chairman, John Longmire. He lamented later that if Perot had
already declared himself a candidate, there would have been plenty
of coverage.
</P>
<P>
   In Perot's hometown, Dallas, four supporters showed up and vowed
to continue the draft-Perot effort.
</P>
<P>
   Perot offered them no encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would take something of a miracle to get him to run for
office again,'' Russell Verney, Perot's closest political aide,
said at the end of the disappointing day.
</P>
<P>
   A footnote: Friends of Buchanan say he is considering moderating
some of his hard-right rhetoric in an effort to broaden his
candidacy and thereby expand his impact on a Gore-Bush contest that
is shaping up as very close.
</P>
<P>
   FALWELL'S CRUSADE: VOTER REGISTRATION
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jerry Falwell is not turning the other cheek.
</P>
<P>
   ``In recent days,'' he writes in his latest weekly Falwell
Confidential letter, ``certain elements in both political parties
have made it clear that people of faith are persona non grata in
the American electoral process.''
</P>
<P>
   He then accuses Sen. John McCain of attacking him and says Vice
President Al Gore invented stories about him.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, he goes on, needs to reclaim itself as ``one
nation under God.'' And to help the process, he says, he and other
church leaders who helped him found the Moral Majority 20 years ago
plan to register 10 million new voters over the next seven months.
</P>
<P>
   Come Election Day, he says, those voters will be ``actively''
urged, along with other God-fearing voters, to ``fulfill their
Christian duty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously,'' Falwell writes, ``we will not endorse or oppose
any congressional, presidential or other candidates. This is not
allowed by law. If people of faith pray, God will, without doubt,
lead them in making good decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS: ONE CANDIDATE'S WAY OF GETTING ATTENTION
</P>
<P>
   In politics, when nothing else seems to work, why not a gimmick?
</P>
<P>
   So Michael Stafford, a Houston-area Republican facing an uphill
struggle in the Harris County district attorney's race, came up
with one _ a mail pamphlet that features a picture of O.J. Simpson
playing golf and a headline that reads: ``Exclusive! If Michael
Stafford had been the DA, O.J. would be busting rocks, not hitting
balls.''
</P>
<P>
   Prominent blacks say it is tasteless at best and racist at
worst, and county Republican leaders question what California
prosecutions have to do with Texas prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   Stafford says his point is that he would be a prosecutor who
would win the big ones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-00 1541EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
