<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4063 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-WOODY-CRUSADE-ART-     03-11 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WOODY-CRUSADE-ART-850(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NEW EFFORT, WOODY ALLEN SEES ATTACK OF SKYSCRAPERS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By JAMES BARRON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Woody Allen made a film last month that did not have
the romantic kookiness of ``Annie Hall,'' the tortured family drama
of ``Hannah and Her Sisters'' or the hot '30s jazz of ``Sweet and
Lowdown.'' This film was short _ 2 minutes, 53 seconds _ and went
into what Hollywood types would call extremely limited
distribution: about a dozen copies.
</P>
<P>
   The victim _ because every Woody Allen production has a victim _
is his neighborhood in the East 90s, which also happens to be where
he shot his 1996 musical misadventure ``Everyone Says I Love You.''
The villain is an apartment house: a 16-story tower that a
developer wants to build on top of a one-story bank branch at
Madison Avenue and East 91st Street.
</P>
<P>
   Allen and the opponents of the project, who asked him to lend
his fame to their fight, say the new tower would block their views
and leave their low-rise neighborhood feeling uncomfortably like a
high-rise canyon.
</P>
<P>
   In the famously nebbishy voice heard in critical favorites like
``Radio Days,'' Allen used words like ``huge'' and ``aesthetically
wrong'' as he described his worries about the building and what it
would do to the community.
</P>
<P>
   To the long list of things Allen has done or been _ boyhood
magician; stand-up comedian; clarinetist and band leader; disdainer
of Oscars; neurotic sex symbol _ add historic preservationist.
Allen said the film was the first he had ever made for a cause. The
dozen copies were for the Landmarks Preservation Commission, which
has the power to order the apartment building scaled down. The site
is in the Carnegie Hill Historic District.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrities have been pleading and marching for historic
preservation projects since before Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis
volunteered to help save Grand Central Terminal. In the 1980s, the
television commentator Bill Moyers joined opponents of a 42-story
tower just off Central Park West. More recently, Walter Cronkite
attacked Donald Trump's sixth-of-a-mile-tall tower near the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   In a neighborhood named for a VIP of a century ago, it is no
surprise that Allen is not the only high-wattage personality
opposing the apartment building. Sir Howard Stringer, the chairman
of the Sony Corp. of America, has been heard from.
</P>
<P>
   So has a marquee full of names recruited by Jurate Kazickas, who
lives with her husband, former Deputy Treasury Secretary Roger C.
Altman, a block from the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blythe Danner, you know, Gwyneth Paltrow's mother, used to
live two doors down,'' Kazickas said, explaining that they became
friends during a previous battle over construction in the
neighborhood. ``I call her up and go, `Here we go again.' She gave
me the phone numbers of Joanne Woodward and Paul Newman and Kevin
Kline. Bette Midler I knew. They're concerned citizens as well as
celebrities.''
</P>
<P>
   And Allen not only made his film, he also testified before the
landmarks commission at a standing-room-only public hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The effect of that kind of celebrity involvement ``is to turn a
hearing into theater,'' said Robert S. Davis, a lawyer for the
developers of the project, on 91st Street. ``When Woody Allen
walked into the hearing room, all eyes turned to the door he walked
in through and away from the historic preservation consultant who
was speaking on our behalf. He talked as if his major concern was
that he films in Carnegie Hill and doesn't want the backdrop for
his movies to be affected. He did not talk much about how he moved
into a property that backed up against it.''
</P>
<P>
   So if this were a film, those who are for the Madison Avenue
building would call it ``Everyone Has a Self-Interest,'' but in an
hourlong interview, Allen did not mention the closeness of his town
house to the building site.
</P>
<P>
   ``This I knew long before I moved there,'' he said in a
follow-up conversation. ``And regardless of what happens, it's fine
for me. If they build a tall building there, it's not a huge
problem for me, not nearly enough to have prevented me from moving
there. If you're in my house, if you look right straight out, you
see something else.''
</P>
<P>
   The self-interest he talked about had to do with his
professional life _ trying to make movies in a city he worries is
losing the pleasant-looking urban landscapes worth capturing on
film _ ``an older, more human New York,'' he called it. ``A more
charming New York.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a crime when you have to shoot a scene but can't
move the camera an inch to the right because there's a terrible
poured concrete building,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But a film about the Carnegie Hill brouhaha could just as easily
be called ``Dining Rooms with a View'' _ the architect can see the
site from his dining room, as can several of the opponents. Also,
one of the developers lives a couple of blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Building anywhere in New York is building in your own backyard
_ in this case, it's mine and Woody's,'' the architect, Charles A.
Platt, said. ``Part of my view will be taken. I think it will be
replaced by something that's wholly appropriate and certainly
reasonable.''  &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps a better title for a film about the the building would
be ``A Tale of Two Transactions.'' Both took place within the last
two years. In the first, Citibank sold the developer, the Tamarkin
Co., the right to build above its one-story branch at 1275 Madison
Avenue, a squat brick structure that went up in 1950. The owners of
a town house next door also sold Tamarkin their air rights,
allowing a five-floor increase in the height of the building.
</P>
<P>
   At about the same time, Allen was buying a six-story Victorian
town house on East 92nd Street. Allen moved there from a penthouse
in the East 70s he said he had outgrown after 30 years. ``I had a
child, I needed more room,'' he said. ``If I didn't have a child, I
never would have moved out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the hand of the gods, serendipity, having someone like
him move in,'' said Jane Parshall, a chairwoman of one of the
groups opposing the building, the CitiNeighbors Coalition of
Historic Carnegie Hill. ``It's not just because he bought this very
expensive house and may lose some sunlight on his back, it's that
he's made movies in this neighborhood for years and years and
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Cut to Allen, who is often described as reclusive but who has
been anything but reluctant to share his thoughts on the proposed
building and the landmarks commission.
</P>
<P>
   In January, he told opponents that he was willing to speak out
against the building, and they began calling reporters. He told The
New Yorker about the film before he had finished it; in an
interview three weeks later, he made many of the same points _
sometimes in the same words _ and then screened it. Some critics
would probably say the film _ in truth, a video _ is little more
than a simply made commercial with Allen talking and a Rogers and
Hart song playing in the background.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not against these developers, I just feel they've picked
the exact wrong street to put up a 17-story building,'' he said.
``I don't think the Citibank is any great treasure to look at, but
if they said they want to build a 10-story building, fine. But 17
stories _ and it's a tall 17, it's not a completely kosher 17
because some of those are double-height floors _ would just be
crushing to that neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   The principal developer, Carey Tamarkin, who is 42 and studied
architecture at Harvard, insisted that the building would be 19
feet 6 inches shorter than the 210-foot height allowed in the area
under city zoning regulations. William Coleman, the project
director of the Tamarkin Co., also noted that the red-brick bank _
on top of which the new building will be built _ will get a new
limestone facade to match.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Allen worries that if the building is built as planned,
it will make Carnegie Hill less an oasis for directors scouting
locations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had so much affection for the city in my movies over the
years,'' Allen said. ``As far back as `Manhattan,' there was a
scene where I was walking with Diane Keaton. I was saying these
things should be landmarked. I always felt that way. I wrote that
into the script.''
</P>
<P>
   For ``Hannah and Her Sisters'' (1986), Allen said, ``We did this
architectural look around New York. The thing that struck me was
this soul-crushing noncontextual architecture.''
</P>
<P>
   Tamarkin, who offered to meet with Allen, called the landmarks
commission hearing last month ``like having my head banged against
a wall for five hours continuously.'' Allen said it was no picnic
for him, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is always an effort to perform live or speak before a
group,'' he said. ``I would rather have been at a Knicks game or at
home in my bedroom, writing, but there are certain things there is
no way out of.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor was it Allen's first encounter with the commission. The last
time, several years ago, he was cast in the role Tamarkin is
playing now, though on a much smaller scale. Allen wanted to build
a pergola on the terrace outside his penthouse, which was in the
Upper East Side Historic District.
</P>
<P>
   To win approval for the project, his workers had to hold up the
boards they wanted to erect while someone from the commission stood
in Central Park. The idea was to see whether the 15-foot-square
pergola would encroach on the view from the park.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's verdict? ``I had to modify the design,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Allen called the process a ``pain in the neck.'' But he added;
``My God, somebody's looking out for the city. That's as it should
be.''
</P>
<P>
   So he hopes that the commission, which could issue a decision as
early as next month, will send Tamarkin back to the drawing board
to make his tower shorter and less massive. ``It just seems to be
like a no-brainer,'' Allen said. ``If you stop a cab driver in the
street, he'll say, `That's sad, it doesn't belong there, it will be
a monster thing jutting into the sky.' This doesn't require an
architectural genius.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-00 1551EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
