<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4065 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BOX-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NY     03-11 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: EX-BOXER FIGHTS `FALSE IMPRESSION' OF CARTER MOVIE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just in time for the Oscars, Denzel Washington rushes across the
ring and punches Joey Giardello silly, pounds his pale face into
raw hamburger. Denzel has the middleweight champion of the world
out on his feet, helpless against the ropes. But what do you expect
from white judges? Denzel loses the decision because he's black,
and you can see the rage and disillusion on his handsome face. It
will be a few more reels before he trusts America again, and then
only because a black teen-ager and his white Canadian friends make
justice prevail.
</P>
<P>
   What about poor Joey? At 69, he finally gets into a movie, and
Hollywood slaps him around as if he were just another pug out of
Brooklyn. He was the champ!
</P>
<P>
   He deserves his own movie. Here's the pitch: Bored with high
school, which he attended occasionally, 15-year-old Chubby Tilelli
goes Airborne using the name of a friend's cousin, Joseph
Giardello. In Army matches, the streetfighter becomes a boxer. In
1948, after his discharge, he moves to Philadelphia and becomes a
middleweight contender. He is arrested on an assault charge,
apparently because he's white; the theory at the time was that the
district attorney needed the black vote to become mayor. As soon as
he wins City Hall, he springs Giardello. Because there are always
rumors of mob involvement and his training regimen includes beer,
macaroni and not much running, Joey never quite gets the respect
that his speed, savvy and superb boxing skills deserve.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 14, 1964, at the Philadelphia Convention Hall, I covered
Giardello's title defense against Rubin ``Hurricane'' Carter, a
ferociously muscled 27-year-old who had won 20 of his 24 pro
fights, 13 by knockout. Carter had started boxing only three years
earlier. His manager, a deputy warden of the Hudson County (N.J.)
Jail, explained to me, ``He's been in college.'' But for all
Carter's anger at having spent so much of his life in jail, he was
cool, even ingratiating, during the buildup for the fight.
</P>
<P>
   In South Philly's dank and dirty Passyunk Avenue Gym, which was
Giardello territory, fans would call Carter ``monkey'' and ``bad
guy'' as he worked out.
</P>
<P>
   Once, someone yelled out, ``Joey's gonna knock you out,'' and
Carter smiled and said, ``Hope he does it early; hate to go 14
rounds and then get knocked out.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of that training session, locals were muttering that
with such a sense of humor he couldn't really be such a bad guy.
</P>
<P>
   Denzel brilliantly captures Carter's intense, edgy charm in
``The Hurricane.''
</P>
<P>
   And mounts a far better attack in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   In the fight that really happened, Carter dominated the early
rounds, moving the quicker Giardello around the ring and landing a
few solid rights to the head that he did not follow up.
</P>
<P>
   Joey was staggered in the fourth and cut over the left eye,
probably from a butt. By the fifth round, however, even while
protecting the eye, Joey began to take control. At 34, with 96
victories in 126 fights over 16 years, Joey was a survivor. I gave
him seven of the next 10 rounds, with one even.
</P>
<P>
   Joey clearly deserved his unanimous decision. Afterward, he said
that Carter ``isn't a bad fighter'' and admitted that Carter had
him confused early and ``never fell for any of my feints.''
Carter's failing was not attacking inside; ``He just kept looking
for that one shot to knock me out,'' Giardello said.
</P>
<P>
   Carter subsequently agreed that he lost by not bringing the
fight to the champion. In ``Lazarus and the Hurricane,'' a book
written by two of the Canadians, Sam Chaiton and Terry Swinton,
Carter was quoted as saying that he had consciously held back to
conserve his strength and stamina for the later rounds. The book,
which was one of the basic texts for the movie, had Carter losing
``a controversial split decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Giardello told me last week that he was shocked when he saw the
movie. I had called the Cherry Hill, N.J., phone number he gave me
36 years ago. He was in the same house with the same wife. Life was
good, he said. He talked about one of his sons, Carmine, who is
retarded, with the same rough-edged warmth I remembered; still
living at home, Carmine is ``the unofficial mayor of Cherry Hill.''
Giardello recently retired after 22 years as an inspector in the
state's Department of Weights and Measures.
</P>
<P>
   No hard feelings toward Carter, he said, and then he politely
asked if I would mind continuing the discussion with his lawyer,
George Bochetto of Philadelphia. They are demanding a jury trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a `false-light' suit,''' explained Bochetto. ``The
movie presents as true certain facts that create a false
impression, in this case which demean Giardello and rob him of his
legacy. He is used to further the theme of the movie, that Carter's
life was destroyed because of racial prejudice.''
</P>
<P>
   Although technically he is not allowed to set forth specific
dollar amounts in the complaint to federal court, Bochetto is
asking for a substantial judgment that smelled like millions over
the phone. Also, he wants attached to the movie and to any video a
clear explanation of what really happened, including scenes from
the real fight.
</P>
<P>
   The nonboxing inaccuracies in the film, which maintains that a
racist system railroaded Carter into prison for a triple murder,
have been commented on at length; among them, the Canadians
apparently received credit that should have gone to the dogged
investigators, reporters and lawyers. The boxing inaccuracies would
seem minor by comparison, except for their key to Carter's
motivation: If the Giardello decision really ended any dream of
justice, it would then not be so far-fetched to believe that
Carter, in a racist rage, gunned down three whites.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does ``The Hurricane'' distort history, it also loses
control of its own contrived story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
