<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELLIOTT SET TO RETURN FROM KIDNEY SURGERY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sean Elliott has a decent chance of stepping onto the court of
the Alamodome in San Antonio on Tuesday night, marking his first
appearance this season. Becoming the first professional athlete
known to resume his career after a kidney transplant, the Spurs'
32-year-old swingman will most likely receive a prolonged,
emotional ovation.
</P>
<P>
   But after that endearing moment, Elliott and the defending
National Basketball Association champions will have to negotiate
the rest of their turbulent season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just tried to be as objective and observant of Sean's
situation as I can possibly be, because I don't know what's going
to take place,'' Coach Gregg Popovich said by telephone on Friday.
``I don't know what certain players are going to think, how certain
players are going to react, what it's going to do to our flow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Or what it's going to do to the consistency we have going,
which, in my opinion, isn't much.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs face the Knicks Sunday in Madison Square Garden for
the first time since the finals; the two teams met in San Antonio
in January, and the Spurs won easily, 96-83.
</P>
<P>
   Last June when they last walked off the Garden floor, the Spurs
did so triumphantly _ carrying home the Lawrence O'Brien
championship trophy to San Antonio. Tim Duncan and his teammates
not only gave their city its first title by beating the Knicks in
five games; they gave the post-Jordan NBA a dignified and
professional bunch of torch-carriers.
</P>
<P>
   How their world has changed.
</P>
<P>
   Nine months later, San Antonio is trailing a proud, aging Utah
team in the Midwest Division. Almost unanimous preseason favorites
to repeat, the Spurs (40-22) are struggling to find cohesiveness as
the Lakers and the Trail Blazers vie for home-court advantage
throughout the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan, who was making a legitimate claim as the game's dominant
player, is having another superlative season. But the maturing of
Shaquille O'Neal and the explosion of Vince Carter have taken up
more of the viewing public's consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Elie and Jerome Kersey, who is starting at small forward,
have had major trouble adjusting to the new,
no-grabbing-and-chucking defensive rules. Minor dissension off the
floor and major discussion of roles and minutes on the floor have
also tested the chemistry of a team without turmoil a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of that is my doing,'' Popovich said, referring to the
different rotations he has used, ``and part of it is the fact that
we haven't found anybody to step up consistently.''
</P>
<P>
   It all began with the loss of Elliott. Unknown to his teammates,
Elliott, who had kidney problems earlier in his career, suffered
from worsening renal function during much of last season. Without a
transplant, doctors said he was bound for dialysis treatments.
Elliott's brother, Noel, became a donor and underwent surgery with
Sean last September.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott began the long road back. He was hospitalized in
December after complaining of fatigue, and has admitted that
recovery has been much slower than he had thought. Despite the
struggle to build up his cardiovascular strength, he began
practicing with the team regularly in February.
</P>
<P>
   His brother's kidney was surgically inserted behind Sean's
pelvic bone on his right side, meaning the organ has a
much-stronger natural shield than his abdomen would provide. He has
already signed a waiver exonerating the Spurs from any medical
liability should a kidney-related injury occur.
</P>
<P>
   Many coaches walk a fine line with players rehabilitating
injuries. On one hand, their regard for the player as a person
forces them to consider the ramifications of a comeback. On the
other, they need victories. In Elliott's case, Popovich said the
latter has not entered his thought process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not even an iota,'' he said. ``I could care less. We're going
to finish wherever we finish. I would not be bringing him back if I
thought there was a chance of danger. I've been very adamant about
that. It's taken all this time to get me to where the doctors have
convinced me they don't see any more risk in him than anybody else
out on the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``After watching him for the last month, I tend to agree. He's
got no pads. Nobody gives him any quarter. He just goes out there
and does what everybody else does. It's just a matter that maybe
his body can't compete for as long a time as everybody else's body.
But he's in a lot better condition and shape _ medically and
physically _ than he was last year during the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Popovich gets rueful when he thinks about what's happened since
his team won a title. ``I think we're a very good basketball team,
but we're definitely not as talented without Sean,'' he said. ``And
it is a shame that they were not able to continue on a roll and
come back and defend as the same team. I feel badly that these guys
were not able to do that. Having said that, tough. Who cares?
</P>
<P>
   ``This team has to be as good as they can possibly be. We're
still very confident that we can give anybody a lot of trouble and
do well. Now bringing Sean back, I think it exacerbates the
situation. Who knows what kind of rotation we're going to have? I'd
be blowing smoke to say, `Well, having consistency in the rotation
for playoff time doesn't mean anything.' We're going to have be
much more fortunate than we were last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether they repeat or not, he is happy for Elliott. ``He's
really challenge-oriented,'' Popovich said. ``I think everyone has
forgotten that for two years in a row he could not play because he
had knee operations. It's been like two continuous years of rehab.
And he played a year and now another season of rehab. So this guy
has been through an awful lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``These challenges are something he's accepted. Because of who
he is, he's decided he wants to overcome them. Frankly, I don't
think he's concerned with whether he plays 10 minutes a game or 30
minutes a game. He wants to be able to say, `I came back, I did it,
I beat it and I contributed to my team.'''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Marketing of Carter
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan's association with David Falk was mainly
responsible for Falk's reputation's as the NBA's best-known agent.
Though he only charges his clients hourly, Lon Babby's stature grew
significantly when Grant Hill and Tim Duncan hired the
Washington-based attorney to negotiate their contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Vince Carter, the game's next great economic force, is planning
on searching for a new representative this summer, and whomever he
chooses may significantly alter the league's landscape and a
certain agent's bank account.
</P>
<P>
   Carter has suspended ties with his current agent, Tank Black,
pending the outcome of Black's criminal trial. The agent has been
charged by the Securities and Exchange Commission with allegedly
defrauding National Football League clients out of millions of
dollars and also mishandling Carter's accounts. The players
association last week prohibited Black from representing any NBA
players during the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Although other representatives of Black's firm have continued to
pursue endorsement deals for Carter _ including a possible contract
with Ford Motor Co.'s Canadian outlet, according to Bloomberg News
_ the Toronto Raptors forward has indicated he will talk to
potential suitors after Aug. 1. About to sever ties with Puma,
Carter will most likely sign a new shoe contract in the next year
with either Nike, Adidas or Reebok.
</P>
<P>
   Whichever agent he chooses will assume the role of immediate
power broker in sports-business circles.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd certainly be an exciting person to represent,'' Babby
said. ``I saw that he doesn't want to talk to anyone before Aug. 1.
Whether I'm foolish or not by adhering to that, I don't know. There
are runners and go-betweens at all levels. But I won't approach him
until then.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the League
</P>
<P>
   Grant Hill continues to stick to his original premise regarding
free agency. He'll decide after the season. But after Coach Alvin
Gentry's firing last week, more and more signs point to Hill
leaving the Pistons if Detroit cannot turn its fortunes around
quickly. Hill will almost certainly exercise an option to become a
free agent in his contract this summer. While he can sign on for a
single season in Detroit and receive a deal in the neighborhood of
$80 million next summer based on his seven-year experience level,
Hill can also ask the Pistons to field offers for him and exercise
a sign-and-trade deal this summer. Unless the franchise can lure a
high-profile coach to Detroit and solve its problems at point guard
and center _ or at least give the appearance of a championship
contender _ Hill will be gone by 2001 at the latest. ... John
Starks, sent home by the Chicago Bulls until his request to become
a free agent is presented to a grievance arbitrator, will have his
case heard on Tuesday. The feeling among several observers is that
Starks may be declared a free agent, but that the arbitrator will
probably not make the decision retroactive to March 1 _ the day a
player must be on a team's roster to compete in the playoffs. In
short, Starks may get his wish to leave Chicago but probably won't
be able to play in the playoffs this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
