<DOCNO> NYT20000311.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4068 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-SURGEON-MISTAKES-6     03-11 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SURGEON-MISTAKES-600(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INQUIRY CREATES AURA OF DOUBT AROUND DOCTOR AND HOSPITAL
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To his supporters, Dr. Ehud Arbit is a brilliant
surgeon and a humanitarian, the one who takes on the hardest cases
when hope has been lost. To the New York State Health Department,
he is dangerously incompetent, working in operating rooms where
careless errors go unchecked and patients face grave risks.
</P>
<P>
   The state received complaints that Arbit, the chief of
neurosurgery at Staten Island University Hospital, had operated in
January on the wrong side of a patient's brain _ for the second
time in five years _ and learned of other accusations that his
mistakes had left patients maimed or paralyzed.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, state officials forced him to surrender his license
last month, pending an investigation, and fined the hospital
$80,000.
</P>
<P>
   Arbit, who lost his post as chief of neurosurgery at Memorial
Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center in 1995 after he was accused of
operating on the wrong side of a patient's brain, contends that he
has been unfairly haunted by the earlier case and victimized this
time by a conspiracy led by his colleagues. But he conceded that he
could not identify those who had complained to the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Malicious remarks have been made to hospital administrators
and the Department of Health about me that are completely false,''
Arbit said in a recent interview. His view is echoed by dozens of
his colleagues at the hospital, who have sprung to his defense in
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Staten Island hospital are defending Arbit's
practice and have accused the state Health Department of passing
judgment before thoroughly investigating. But state health
officials say their inquiry has involved many interviews and has
led investigators to conclude that the doctor's patients are
endangered.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Arbit's case is one of the clearest examples of the state
Health Department's ambition to spotlight cases for disciplining
doctors at a time when President Clinton is urging more disclosure
of medical errors.
</P>
<P>
   The agency's swift action is a striking departure from what has
traditionally been viewed as a lumbering, cautious investigative
process that some say leans overboard toward the medical
establishment.
</P>
<P>
   And its treatment of Arbit has prompted doctors and medical
officials to question whether the state health commissioner, Dr.
Antonia C. Novello, is on a crusade that might have overlooked the
internal disputes now becoming apparent at the Staten Island
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The state's continuing investigation may well uncover answers
that bridge the wide disparity between those who question Arbit's
surgical expertise and those who paint him as the victim of an
out-of-control professional rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   But his case also carries broader implications, for it has
damaged the credibility of the hospital, which is 10 years into an
aggressive, multimillion-dollar effort to stop the growing
population of Staten Island from defecting to Manhattan for complex
medical care.
</P>
<P>
   ``The community's confidence in this institution has been
undermined,'' Rick J. Varone, hospital president, said. Morale
among the staff members has plummeted, he said, and the doctor whom
Arbit blames for his downfall now says he will no longer take his
cases to the hospital, which sees about 28,000 patients a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Department of Health's intentions were 100 percent pure,''
Varone said of its initial inquiries, adding that before the state
became involved, the hospital had investigated Arbit's record and
decided that the accusations were unfounded. ``The difference
between me and the state is that I gave him his day in court,''
Varone said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Staten Island University Hospital, like hundreds of other
community hospitals around the country, has tried mightily to rise
to the level of a large, academic medical center. It has begun
clinical programs that a decade ago were unheard of in a hospital
its size _ a burn center and a microsurgery unit _ and it soon will
have a major heart center. It has built up existing programs like
cancer care and neurosurgery, hiring prestigious specialists and
investing heavily in equipment.
</P>
<P>
   To many health experts, these expansions pose daunting risks for
smaller hospitals. Support services for sophisticated new programs
in areas like cancer care and heart surgery might be substandard,
and existing doctors and other medical staff might lack the
experience and credentials of the department heads recruited to
supervise them.
</P>
<P>
   ``To reach the level of top-level hospitals, you can't just
bring in one big name and expect that all will go with it,'' said
Robert I. Field, the director of the graduate program on health
policy at the University of the Sciences in Philadelphia. ``The
trend now is to concentrate high-tech services into centers of
excellence and leave community hospitals in their appropriate
niche. So I think this is a risky strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   In an extensive interview, Varone tried to put the hospital's
history and growth into perspective. He said he became president in
1989, when the hospital was struggling to compete with others in
Manhattan and New Jersey. After a merger with Richmond Memorial
Hospital, Varone set into motion a plan to build programs to keep
Staten Island patients from seeking treatment elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Government reimbursement levels for patient care have dropped
ominously, partly because of managed care, so the hospital embarked
on an obvious course to find money sources, and surgery specialties
generate income. Further, Varone said, he was upset that 22 percent
of the patients there were traipsing to Manhattan for procedures he
thought should be offered by the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Buying equipment was easy. Attracting high-profile doctors was a
problem. ``Getting physicians here is difficult,'' Varone said.
``They tended not to want to be at the community level. They wanted
to be in an academic center.''
</P>
<P>
   So he offered doctors fat compensation packages and the chance
to build departments from scratch. He recruited a new head of
surgery from New York Hospital, who brought in a chief for plastic
surgery. Cancer and radiology experts came as well. ``Plastic
surgery cases were up 82 percent last year,'' said Dr. Arman
Kasabian, the new chief of the department. ``Everything they have
promised me they gave me.''
</P>
<P>
   Neurosurgery _ a small, lucrative field where the brightest
stars attract a huge percentage of the patients _ was trickier. The
existing department could not compete with departments like those
at New York University or Mount Sinai, Varone said.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1995, Varone received and acted on an attractive offer.
Rabbi Jacob Spitzer of Brooklyn, who has been a health care
advocate for Orthodox Jews and often gives them health care advice
and referrals, introduced him to Arbit after he had been dismissed
at Sloan-Kettering.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that Rabbi Spitzer recommended him was the only way
Dr. Arbit got through the door,'' said Varone, whose hospital has
cared for an large number of Orthodox Jews.
</P>
<P>
   The rabbi also cornered the state Health Department's deputy
commissioner at a breakfast meeting in Manhattan and urged him to
be thorough in his investigation of Arbit's conduct. Spitzer also
sent a letter of support for Arbit, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer had helped other displaced doctors at Staten Island. Dr.
Steven Swersky and his partner, Dr. Robert Klinger, both
obstetricians disciplined by the state and fired from Beth Israel
Medical Center in Manhattan, had a strong patient base in Brooklyn,
and Spitzer said he lobbied for them.
</P>
<P>
   Varone conceded that the timing of Spitzer's recommendation for
Arbit caused him trepidation. The brain surgery mistake at
Sloan-Kettering had been front page news. The state had mildly
disciplined Arbit, placing him on a year's probation. Others at
Staten Island had reservations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent a lot of time talking, and I admired him greatly,''
Varone said. ``He was tarnished by Memorial and he can't walk away
from that, but I went through months of evaluating him. He was
someone worthy of Memorial Sloan-Kettering, and as a human being he
was terrific. It was an agonizing process. And one looks back and
wonders if this Memorial thing follows him forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Varone said he decided to hire Arbit in 1995. By 1998, Varone
replaced Dr. Victor Ho with Arbit as head of the neurosurgery
department. By Varone's account, those of other doctors and Arbit,
the hospital staff did not welcome Arbit. His promotion, by many
accounts, worsened an uneasy situation.
</P>
<P>
   Arbit recalled one of his first operations at the hospital, in
which he placed the patient in a position that colleagues in the
operating room found unfamiliar. With the patient unconscious and
the doctor scrubbed and ready to go, the anesthesiologist halted
the procedure, Arbit said, arguing that the position was dangerous.
Arbit said he had to go to administrators to get clearance as the
surgical team stood by.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have done multiple operations in this position,'' he said.
``I had to convince them this was sound.''
</P>
<P>
   By Arbit's account, he was relentlessly badgered by colleagues,
a situation Varone confirmed. ``There was a faction of harmful
people who instigated against him,'' Varone said. ``I can't for the
life of me figure out why. The environment for him was difficult.
He has been undermined by a bitter colleague, but I don't know if
he is the one who created the furor,'' he said, referring to Ho.
</P>
<P>
   The state investigation derives from complaints from various
sources, although Arbit blames Ho's office. About a dozen other
current and former hospital doctors, most of whom would speak only
on the condition of anonymity, said that Ho complained about them
relentlessly to hospital administrators, engaged in petty antics
like refusing them equipment from his operating room, and made life
unpleasant in the department.
</P>
<P>
   ``Victor Ho is very abusive in the OR,'' said Dr. Barbara
Minkowitz, a pediatric orthopedist who once assisted with Ho's
former partners and works in an operating room next to his.
``People tiptoe around him so they don't have to deal with his
personality.'' Another surgeon who left the hospital said, ``I
didn't think my career would be helped working with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ho refused to be interviewed. His lawyer, Robert Asher, would
not say whether he had instigated the latest investigation of
Arbit. ``Dr. Ho will categorically deny that he has ever done
anything except for the betterment of patients,'' Asher said.
``People at the hospital don't like him because he is a
perfectionist. And that can be seen by the fact that the department
went downhill after he was replaced.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Responding to accusations that Ho frequently criticized his
colleagues' work, Asher said: ``If he's made complaints, so what?
It is the duty of a physician to inform the state about other
physicians that are not acting appropriately. If he has _ and we
are not conceding he has _ he is on the side of truth, justice and
the American way.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Nonna Datiashvili, an internist who has admitting privileges
at the hospital, decided to take her husband to Arbit to have a
brain tumor excised. Nurses tried to steer her to Ho, she said.
``The nurses don't like him,'' she said of Arbit. ``I think the
stigma of his past is huge. No one opened their heart to him.''
Asher said that the fact the nurses and anesthesiologists disliked
Arbit underscored the necessity of the Health Department's actions.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the hospital began pushing Ho to be on call for
emergencies, a step he has resisted since he came to the hospital,
and to submit his cases to hospital officials for review, as part
of a hospital agreement with the state to subject all neurosurgery
cases to institutional checks. Ho told hospital officials on
Thursday that he would no longer practice at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Arbit's troubles became a hospital concern in early February,
when Varone ran into another doctor who he said looked concerned.
``I asked him what was wrong and he told me, `We may have a
wrong-side case with Dr. Arbit.' I told him I wanted all the
information on it by the next day and that if what he was telling
me was true, he's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Arbit was called in the next day, Varone said, adding that he
had all intentions of suspending him from practice. Instead, Arbit,
using X-rays and textbooks, demonstrated that the surgery was not
mishandled, Varone said, because the X-rays depicted a tumor that
had grown into both sides of the brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next allegation by another anesthesiologist was that he
had made someone quadriplegic,'' Varone said. ``We went up to see
the patient, and the patient was walking. I was ready to blow him
out but I let him have his day. I don't know why the allegations
were made, but they may be a reflection on the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   But word of the brain surgery and other cases had already made
its way to state officials, although the identities of those who
complained have not been disclosed. By early February, the
Department of Health had begun its investigation, and Arbit
surrendered his license on the 18th. Varone insists that every case
the state accused Arbit of mishandling was investigated internally
by the hospital and found to be without error.
</P>
<P>
   The state Health Department disputes Varone's version. Its
spokesman, John Signor, said that 30 interviews conducted by state
investigators corroborated the wrong-side-of-the-brain procedure
and other errors, including that of a patient left partly
paralyzed, another who underwent surgery to have a plate attached
to her spinal cord along the neck and suffered complications
because the plate was installed incorrectly, and others who were,
according to the report, badly injured during surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We interviewed doctors, nurses, quality-assurance staff,
physician assistants, employees relevant to the complaints,''
Signor said. He added that the hospital's investigation, according
to the state's review of records, consisted merely of interviews
with Arbit.
</P>
<P>
   Other cases have marred Staten Island University Hospital's
reputation in the last year. In September, it agreed to reimburse
the state Medicaid program $45 million for improper bills it had
submitted over five years, and to provide $39 million in free care
for indigent patients in the next 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Datiashvili said she believed that Arbit was committed to
improving conditions at the hospital, to raising the quality of
medical care there. Others echo her sentiments, and more than a
dozen of Arbit's patients have described his lifesaving care.
</P>
<P>
   In person, Arbit seems a quiet, pleasant physician mystified by
the new accusations against him. He said he was innocent of every
medical error cited. In the Sloan-Kettering case, for example, the
state found that he operated on the healthy right side of the brain
of Rajeswari Ayyappan, the 59-year-old mother of a famous Indian
film star, Sridevi Ayyappan, instead of her left side where a
cancerous tumor was situated.
</P>
<P>
   To this day, Arbit blames ``systems problems,'' adding that the
staff did not bring the right patient's X-rays to the operating
room. In at least one case he is accused of mishandling at Staten
Island, he said, he was only aiding another doctor who was
foundering.
</P>
<P>
   His detractors say he is simply unable to accept his own
shortcomings, which they argue are serious. ``I think that from a
purely technical standpoint, he is thought to be a good surgeon,''
a member of the Sloan-Kettering staff said. ``But there is a whole
judgment piece, a blind spot. He doesn't see the whole patient. He
just sees tumors.''
</P>
<P>
   The state Health Department has demanded that the Staten Island
hospital present a plan of correction for each of the 40 violations
it has cited, and the hospital said it had taken several steps to
do so. For example, the state said that the hospital used physician
assistants inappropriately in surgery, and for now, they have all
been removed from the neurosurgery operating room. The hospital has
asked outside medical experts to review its care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am prepared to put this institution through greater
scrutiny,'' Varone said. ``This whole process will only make us
stronger. If we are held to an even higher standard, that is OK
with me.''
</P>
<P>
   And as to whether Arbit is a bad doctor out of control or a
victim of a vindictive colleague and overzealous Health Department?
``The truth will come out,'' Varone insisted. ``It is like a plane
accident. It may take time. But it will come out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
