<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4081 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-MUSEUM-PROTEST-NYT     03-11 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MUSEUM-PROTEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WHITNEY DROPS MUSEUM SUPPORT OVER NEW SHOW
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Wyo.)   (jw) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Angry over a planned exhibit at the Whitney Museum
linking Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and other political figures to the
Nazis, Marylou Whitney, the widow of Cornelius Vanderbilt Whitney,
said Saturday that she had withdrawn her financial support of the
museum and quit its national fund-raising committee.
</P>
<P>
   Whitney said that a work by Hans Haacke, a German-born New York
artist, planned for the Whitney's 2000 Biennial opening on March
23, would serve to belittle the Holocaust, politicize art and
violate the principles on which the Whitney was founded by her late
mother-in-law, Gertrude Vanderbilt Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gertrude would roll over in her grave,'' she said of the
Haacke work _ a wall of garbage cans with speakers blaring the
sound of marching jackboots, a reproduction of the First Amendment
and, in a medieval typescript favored by the Nazis, quotations from
Giuliani and others, including Sen. Jesse Helms, Patrick Buchanan
and the religious broadcaster Pat Robertson.
</P>
<P>
   News last week of the forthcoming exhibit and the Haacke work,
called ``Sanitation,'' recalled the fury over the First Amendment
issues raised by the ``Sensation'' show at the Brooklyn Museum of
Art last fall, when the mayor attacked some of the art as ``sick''
and tried to withhold city subsidies from the museum.
</P>
<P>
   The Whitney, which receives most of its funds from private and
corporate sources, was confronted with harsh criticism from the
Anti-Defamation League, which charged that the Haacke work
trivialized the Holocaust. Giuliani called the Haacke work
offensive, but said that the city would take no action.
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell L. Anderson, director of the Whitney, did not respond
immediately to messages left at the museum Saturday. Haacke, who
lives in Manhattan, was not immediately available.
</P>
<P>
   Whitney, in a telephone interview from her home in Saratoga
Springs, N.Y., said she had informed Anderson on Friday of her
decision to withdraw her support from the museum, which is on
Madison Avenue at 75th Street.
</P>
<P>
   She said she had told him she was perturbed with the Haacke work
itself, but was even more upset with the museum for what she said
was a violation of the trust Gertrude Vanderbilt Whitney had placed
in the institution she founded 70 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gertrude wanted to help American artists,'' Whitney said.
``That's why she called it the Whitney Museum of American Art. It's
not supposed to be for any foreign artists. I'm upset with the
museum for going against Gertrude's principles and I'm terribly
upset with this work. It's in such bad taste. And the museum should
not be used politically.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitney, whose family has been a bulwark of support for the
museum, said she planned to donate $1 million to the Whitney this
year but had decided to give it instead to the Whitney Gallery of
Western Art in Cody, Wyo., which was established by her husband on
land donated by his mother.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, she said she had resigned from the national
committee that raises almost half of the museum's $20 million
budget, a committee she joined more than 35 years ago. While she
refused to give details, she said that many of the committee's 30
members were also upset over the planned exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   Whitney, who was quoted by The New York Post on Saturday as
saying that the museum's name ought to be changed from the Whitney
to ``The Sensation,'' drew back from that suggestion. ``I didn't
really mean that,'' said the 73-year-old heiress to a $100 million
fortune built on railroads and oil.
</P>
<P>
   From its founding in 1930, the Whitney was financed almost
entirely by the family _ first by Gertrude Vanderbilt Whitney, who
left it $2.5 million of her $11 million estate, and after her death
in 1942 by her daughter, Flora Whitney Miller. Since the 1960s,
much of the museum's financing has come from earned income and from
private and corporate donations and grants from foundations, the
National Endowment of the Arts and the state and city of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Whitney said she was aware that her criticisms of the Haacke
work might ``turn him into a martyr,'' and ``cause people to line
up for six blocks to see this trash.'' Because of the controversy,
huge crowds turned out to see Chris Ofili's work at the Brooklyn
Museum, which included a rendering of the Virgin Mary that used
pornographic cutouts and elephant dung.
</P>
<P>
   But Whitney said she had no choice. ``I just feel you have to
stand up for what you believe,'' she said. ``I believe that
Gertrude wanted this museum to be something wonderful and
educational, but when they put up things you wouldn't want your
children or grandchildren to see. ...''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
