</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-STAR-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAR FRENCH CHEF IS HEADING TO MANHATTAN
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Alain Ducasse, the celebrated French chef who has
restaurants bearing his name and three Michelin stars in Paris and
Monte Carlo, is about to open his first restaurant in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Ducasse's restaurant, Alain Ducasse at the Essex House, will
replace Les Celebrites, a small but luxurious Art Deco dining room
in the Essex House hotel on Central Park South, which has been
closed for nearly two years. During that time, there were almost as
many rumors rippling through the food world about the fate of the
room as about Ducasse's plans.
</P>
<P>
   Ducasse, who arrived Friday in New York, said he expected the
restaurant to open before June 21 after about $1.5 million in
renovations. Ducasse said he would expand the kitchen and make
cosmetic changes in the 60-seat dining room to make it lighter,
fresher and more contemporary. The paintings by celebrities like
Elke Sommer, Phyllis Diller and Pierce Brosnan, for which the room
was famous, are being removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be colorful and very high-fashion but not as serious
or stiffly classic as Paris,'' Ducasse said. He said that a famous
designer, whom he would not name, was creating uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   As is the practice at many top restaurants in Paris _ but not in
New York _ Alain Ducasse at the Essex House will be open Monday
through Friday only, with just one seating for dinner, making it
likely to become the city's most exclusive restaurant. Lunch will
be served two days a week. Ducasse is also planning to offer
cooking seminars, in a kind of club, on weekday mornings when the
restaurant does not serve lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an argument that says you want all the richest talent
here in New York,'' said Drew Nieporent, who owns and manages
several New York restaurants. ``There's a saturation of restaurants
in New York now, but Ducasse is not going to do huge volume so I
think he'll pull it off.''
</P>
<P>
   Ducasse said the chef would be Didier Elena, a 31-year-old who
has worked with him for 12 years. His wine director, Gerard
Margeon, will oversee a list of what Ducasse called the ``great
wines of the world.'' Another 13 members of his staff will also
come to New York.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, just after Ducasse, who was based in Monte Carlo, took
over what had been Joel Robuchon's restaurant in Paris, skeptics
wondered how he would manage to juggle the responsibilities of
running two top caliber restaurants nearly 600 miles apart.
</P>
<P>
   He skillfully put any doubts to rest, and since then has added a
growing list of projects. Like Paul Bocuse, one of the first modern
celebrity chefs, whose renown Ducasse's now rivals, he is not
daunted by running a big inventory of restaurants, despite a
constant rumble of criticism from those who insist he has spread
himself too thin.
</P>
<P>
   He opened Spoon Food &AMP; Wine, a stylish but informal place in
Paris, which now has a branch in Mauritius and is to soon have
others in Tokyo and in Ian Schrager's new Sanderson Hotel in
London. For now, he is discounting rumors that there will be a
Spoon at the Royalton in New York.
</P>
<P>
   His Bar et Boeuf, a kind of surf and turf restaurant in Monte
Carlo, just received a Michelin star, and Il Cortile, an Italian
restaurant in Paris for which he is the consultant, also has a
Michelin star. He has two country inns in Provence, La Bastide de
Moustiers and L'Hostellerie de l'Abbaye de la Celle. He decided not
to pursue a restaurant in Las Vegas, in a small version of the
Eiffel Tower.
</P>
<P>
   So why did he finally decide to add a trans-Atlantic commute?
</P>
<P>
   ``The easy answer is that I wanted to give it a try,'' he said,
adding that he regarded New York as one of the Everests of his
profession because, like Paris, it is the most spectacular
restaurant city with the most discriminating public in the world.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Essex House restaurant would be the last one named
Alain Ducasse.
</P>
<P>
   Ducasse is not the first Michelin three-star chef to set up shop
in New York. Alain Senderens and Louis Outhier preceded him. But
the restaurants run by these chefs, also in hotels but on a
consulting basis, did not bear their names and the chefs eventually
severed their ties with them. Ducasse's arrangement is different,
more long-term and with greater involvement.
</P>
<P>
   While he has not set a schedule, he said he would be in New York
``as often as necessary.'' New Yorkers can certainly expect to see
him in August, when the Paris restaurant closes for vacation.
</P>
<P>
   As for the food he is planning, he said it would be extremely
high-end but different from both the luxuriously classic fare
served in Paris and the more Mediterranean cooking featured in
Monte Carlo. Like other chefs with multiple restaurant projects,
including Jean-Georges Vongerichten, who is based in New York, he
has managed to devise a distinctive cuisine for each property.
</P>
<P>
   He expects to show off American-grown products, which impress
him so much that he spent Saturday morning in the Greenmarket in
Union Square and is working on a book about American ingredients,
``Harvesting Excellence,'' with a French writer, Jean-Christian
Agid.
</P>
<P>
   The menu has not been worked out. ``The actual menu is the last
thing I think of,'' he said. New York restaurant goers who would
like to book a table, regardless of what's on the menu, may call
(212) 265-7300 starting Wednesday. Reservations are not being
taken, but a list of those interested is being assembled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
