<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4101 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-EX-YANKS-NYT &LR;      03-11 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-EX-YANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTSIDE THE BRONX, A PLACE ON THE FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUNEDIN, Fla. _ He's a utility player; he can't play every day.
</P>
<P>
   With those words, heard so often in baseball, a player can be
doomed to a career of backup duty. The label is especially damaging
when it is applied early in a player's career, preventing him from
ever getting a chance to prove otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I had passed that point already,'' Homer Bush said the
other day. ``There were a lot of people out there saying I couldn't
play every day. I think pretty much 90 percent of the people
figured I couldn't play every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten years older than Bush, Randy Velarde had endured a similar
experience as a major-league infielder. He was good enough to back
up at second base, shortstop and third, even play a little
outfield, but he was not a candidate for a regular job.
</P>
<P>
   Velarde and Bush both served in that utility role for the
Yankees. Both also left the Yankees and discovered there was life
after _ as starters, no less, both at second base. Bush had no
choice in his departure; the Yankees traded him to Toronto. Velarde
left as a free agent, lured by the California Angels' promise of a
steady job.
</P>
<P>
   The utility infielders, however, departed with one difference:
Bush had already earned a World Series ring; Velarde left just
before he could have had one, if not more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in the past, but yeah, it did hurt,'' Velarde said
recently at the Oakland Athletics' camp in Phoenix. ``The first
year after I left, they won the world championship. There were a
lot of tears of joy and tears of sadness. I wasn't there to be part
of it after spending so much of my career there, but at the same
time I was happy for all the guys who were able to be part of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Velarde, acquired as a minor-leaguer in a 1987 trade, played for
the Yankees for parts of the next three seasons, then for full
seasons from '90 through '95. In only three of those seasons did he
play 100 or more games. Bush, an extra in the trade that brought
Hideki Irabu to New York in 1997, played in a total of 55 games for
the Yankees in '97 and '98, and appeared in the 1998 World Series.
He wasn't around for last year's World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed but satisfied at the same time,'' said
Bush, 27, who went to Toronto with David Wells for Roger Clemens.
``Disappointed because it's like, man, I could be there, satisfied
because I got the opportunity to play every day. I knew I had to
give up something to get this opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Making the choice between the World Series and a regular job
poses a dilemma, Bush acknowledged, then added: ``But you really
can't make a living being a utility player. I have a wife, a
daughter, a mom who I want to do something for, and I just couldn't
do it being a utility player. When I think about all that, I accept
what has happened. I wish them the best. I know they wish me the
best.''
</P>
<P>
   Velarde, despite his ability to overcome a series of disabling
injuries and become a regular, still appears to have some regrets
about his decision to leave the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was offered more money to stay there, but it was as a
utility player,'' he said. ``I had been doing that for nine years.
If hindsight was what it was, I would have stayed there because the
next year they won the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   But whatever inclination he might have had to stay was eroded by
the departures of Buck Showalter as manager, Don Mattingly to
retirement and Mike Stanley to free agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew they were going to be decent, but not world
championship caliber,'' said Velarde, who at 33 years old did not
have long to gain credibility as a starter. ``To Mr. Steinbrenner's
credit, he went out and got players who made them world champions.
I wanted to go back, but here was a three-year offer on the table
from the Angels to be their second baseman. I saw it as an
opportunity of a lifetime, to be able to go out there and establish
myself as an everyday player, to prove I could play every day. I
was never given that opportunity in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Velarde still doesn't have a World Series ring, but his career
has taken a remarkable turn. A .268 career hitter, he played the
most he ever has (156 games) last season, amassed 200 hits and
batted .317 with the Angels and the Athletics. The Athletics say it
was his arrival that solidified their lineup and kept them in the
division race.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, starting 127 games for the Blue Jays, had a remarkable
season in his own right, batting .320 and stealing 32 bases.
Interestingly, though, he said the statistics were deceiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt that I really didn't play as well as my numbers
showed,'' Bush said. ``I felt I got a lot of breaks on infield
hits. I feel there's a lot of room for improvement, like with my
on-base percentage. A .320 batting average is pretty good for a guy
in his first year as a regular, but I don't think I hit a solid
.320. I think I basically ran .280 and hit 40 points.'' Bush's
on-base percentage was .353.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Blue Jays and the Athletics do not appear to be
World Series candidates this year, their second basemen eagerly
await their chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a consummate professional, you put on this uniform for one
reason _ to be a world champion,'' Velarde said. ``If you go for
anything else, you're in it for the wrong reason.'' But he added:
``Would I change my plans? I don't think so. I'm where I wanted to
be. I'm playing everyday. It's taken this long.''
</P>
</TEXT>
