<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4111 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-BELL-2TAKES-     03-11 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BELL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR METS' BELL, NUMBERS HAVEN'T MATCHED HIS POWER 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ They called him a monster, because that
is what boys call boys who look like grown-ups.
</P>
<P>
   He was 12 years old, 5 foot 9, and his feet kept outgrowing his
spikes. His coach had to carry his birth certificate at Little
League games, just to prove that Derek Nathaniel Bell was, in fact,
a kid.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Gooden grew up two houses away in Tampa, and his cousin,
Gary Sheffield, was Bell's teammate. Gooden laughs hard when he
pictures the young Bell. ``He did have a beard and mustache,''
Gooden said.
</P>
<P>
   Bell was known for the mustache, Sheffield said. That and the
home runs. Nobody hit them like Bell, who batted fourth for the
1980 Tampa Little League All-Stars, right behind Sheffield. It was
nothing special for the two to combine for five homers in a game.
They were local celebrities, with some games broadcast on radio and
the championship game on national television.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, when Bell was playing outfield for the Houston
Astros, he was in his hotel room when the phone started ringing. He
was on television, his teammates told him, and Bell first thought,
so what? It turned out a cable network was showing a Little League
World Series title game, and Bell was pitching for the USA. His
teammates couldn't get enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had that long face, those baggy eyes _ we gave him a hard
time,'' said Astros infielder Bill Spiers. ``It was funny. If you
would have seen it, you'd have been like, `Oh my God, he looks
exactly the same as he does now.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bell laughed, but the Mets' new right fielder still wonders how
his team lost. He remembers having to start his swing before the
Taiwanese pitcher released the ball, and that when the pitcher
threw curveballs, there was no way to stop swinging. Bell's team
lost twice in the final game, in 1980 and '81, and both times he
wept. The monster cared.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a crucial game, if they lost, he would be the only one
crying at the end of the game,'' said Bell's mother, Chestine. ``I
would try to console him and say, `It's OK,' but he was just so
hurt and upset. That's when I knew he was serious about baseball
and he was going to go all the way. I knew he wanted to get
somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell got to the majors with Toronto in 1991, the same season
Baseball America named him the minor-league player of the year. A
year later he was a reserve as the Blue Jays won the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   But the next year, Bell was traded to San Diego, because some in
the Blue Jays organization questioned whether he had the instincts
and the personality to stick in the major leagues. Two years later,
San Diego sent him to Houston. Last December, Houston shipped him
to the Mets in the deal that brought pitcher Mike Hampton to New
York. The Mets wanted Hampton; taking Bell got the deal done
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was going to hit with more power than he has,''
said Pat Gillick, the former Blue Jays general manager now with
Seattle. ``I thought he would be a 30-homer guy every year. I
really liked him. I thought he was a good player, a good person. He
was just a little different. He's not a bad guy, he just marches to
a different tune.''
</P>
<P>
   The words to that tune, the Mets have found out, are yo, yo and
yo. If Bell is not hollering ``Yo, yo, yo!'' in the clubhouse,
someone is saluting him by saying it. When he bounds in each
morning, General Manager Steve Phillips said, it is like a
hurricane blowing through. Bell has worn a different sports jersey
every day of camp, and before he enters the locker room _ as Steve
McNair or Chris Childs or whoever he is that day _ Bell gives the
coaches a fashion show.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just me,'' said Bell, 31. ``There ain't no walls
nowhere. When I'm on a team, the coaches, the players, everything
has got to be out in the open. There should be no walls nowhere
around here, except for the home run wall.''
</P>
<P>
   The home run wall cannot often contain Bell, who has always had
exceptionally quick wrists. As a Little Leaguer, he would hit balls
over the fence and across the street. For fun, Bell and Sheffield
would practice on a Senior League field, with major-league
dimensions. Sheffield barely reached the warning track. Bell
cleared the walls. ``That's stuff you've never seen,'' said
Sheffield, who now plays for the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   It's not much different now. Matter of factly, Bell lists all
the places he has reached with home runs: the third deck in
Houston, over the pavilion in Los Angeles, the second deck in San
Diego, the Big Mac sign in St. Louis. Sheffield said the only
difference between Mark McGwire's batting practice and Bell's is
that McGwire hits long home runs more consistently. For sheer
distance, nobody hits them farther than Bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not strong at all,'' said Jeff Bagwell of the Astros,
``but he can kill a ball with a baseball bat. He's special.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield has urged Bell to use his power to become a home run
hitter. Bell has never hit more than 22 homers in a season, and
last season he hit only 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``Derek has the most potential of anybody in the game,''
Sheffield said. ``I always try to push Derek to go for home runs.
He has the ability to hit home runs if he wants to, but Derek wants
to be an all-around player, and if home runs come, they come.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell does not consider the 1999 season a bad year _ the Astros
won their division, he said, and his job was to help the team win.
Bell missed his hitting coach, Tom McCraw, who was away for much of
the year after prostate cancer surgery, but his numbers were still
shocking. Bell, who spent some time on the disabled list with a
groin pull, batted .236, the lowest average in the National League
among regulars, and he struck out a career-high 129 times. Even Rey
Ordonez had a higher slugging percentage against right-handed
pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Though benched in the playoffs, Bell supported his teammates,
offering cash rewards for victories, saves and game-winning runs
batted in. Bagwell was in New York when Bell was traded to the
Mets, and was bothered by radio talk about the ``baggage'' Bell was
bringing. ``I wanted to call and say Derek is one of the nicest
guys and has one of the biggest hearts in the game,'' Bagwell said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Yet, there were problems in Houston. Larry Dierker, who managed
Bell the last three years, called him an enigma. Dierker said Bell
brooded over being mentioned in trade rumors for Roger Clemens last
spring, and his performance suffered. Bell wanted to bat second,
not sixth, and criticized Dierker the day the manager returned from
brain surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' manager, Bobby Valentine, has not decided on his
regular lineup. But Bell sees himself batting second, with Edgardo
Alfonzo third and Mike Piazza fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if I'm hitting .299 with 29 home runs and 99
RBIs,'' Bell said. ``If there's a man on second base, no outs, last
game of the season, last at-bat, and I can get the guy over to
third base for Alfonzo, Piazza, and those guys to tie the game or
win the game, I'm going to give myself up, because numbers don't
mean that much to me. I care about winning. I'm a team player, and
I want my teammates to know it.''
</P>
<P>
   But not all managers like to play for one run, especially in
today's game, Dierker said. Dierker did not want Bell to hit that
way, because, like Gillick and Sheffield, he thought Bell was
capable of more. But Bell wanted to be selfless.
</P>
<P>
   ``It says something about who he thinks he is,'' Dierker said.
``Bagwell is not a selfish player _ he wants to win as much as
anybody. But he doesn't try to get the guy over, he tries to get
the guy in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't ask Derek to get the guy over, either, but that's
the way he wanted to play. And that's OK; he was hitting second in
our lineup a lot, and that was his job a lot. But if he was hitting
fifth or sixth, which to me is what his talent suggests, he's a guy
who could drive in 100 runs.''
</P>
<P>
   To get the most out of Bell, said Gooden, who now plays for the
Astros, a manager must continually affirm that he needs him.
``Derek wants to be liked by everybody,'' Gooden said. ``He's an
easygoing guy, easy to get along with, but he's very sensitive. He
needs to know the team is behind him all the way. He's one of those
guys that needs to hear that constantly, especially when he's
struggling.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell is vowing to stay positive this year, whatever happens. He
can handle New York, he said, because he simply will not talk about
negative things.
</P>
<P>
   When something goes wrong, on the field or in life, Bell will
follow the same routine: retire to his home or hotel room and play
video games. The off-field troubles that have haunted others from
his neighborhood _ including Gooden, who has battled drug
addiction, and Sheffield, who has been shot _ have largely avoided
Bell. Gooden credits Bell's mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time he was an only child, and I kept him
shielded,'' said Chestine Bell, whose next oldest child is nine
years younger. ``Just go to school, play baseball and come home. I
would take him to practice, and I would be right there to pick him
up from practice. I'd be there at the games; nobody had to take him
there and bring him home. Being a single mom and raising a boy,
it's a little rough. You've got to try to keep him on the straight
and narrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell's mother is proud of him, and he is proud of himself. It is
up to others to wait for the monster talent to emerge.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as he's living up to his expectations,'' Sheffield
said, ``that's all that matters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
