<P>
   SPACE-WEATHER _ WASHINGTON _ Stormy weather in the Earth's
magnetosphere can interfere with television reception, cause pocket
pagers to go deaf, even threaten electric power grids. Yet
scientists know little about the enormous cloud of subatomic
particles that surrounds the Earth for thousands of miles into
space or about the solar winds that constantly whip across it.
IMAGE, a new satellite scheduled for launch March 18, will provide
them with the first opportunity to begin to understand ``magnetic
weather'' conditions around the Earth. (Nesmith, Cox News Service).
35. WITH PHOTO. A GRAPHIC SKEDDED EARLIER WILL NOT BE AVAILABLE.
</P>
