<P>
   DEAD-FAMILY _ On the Sunday before he died, 72-year-old Earl
Phillips rang the bell as usual at his beloved Cove Creek
Missionary Baptist Church near Waynesville, N.C., and greeted some
members with words still etched in their memories: ``If anyone
doesn't believe in God, all they need to do is look at these
mountains.'' But by the next Sunday, church members were wondering
why God would allow three generations of the Phillips family to be
slaughtered, allegedly at the hands of two marauding spree killers,
drunk and in a panic-stricken frenzy to outrun the law after having
already killed one person. (Scruggs, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   STARGAZERS _ GREEN BANK, W. Va. _ In isolated Deer Creek Valley,
where folks traditionally rely upon moonshine and timber for their
livelihoods, construction crews are nearing completion of a
gigantic radio telescope with an ``ear'' bigger a football field.
Weighing 17 million pounds and rolling on a 25-foot-thick
foundation of reinforced concrete, the Green Bank telescope will be
``one of the largest moving things on Earth,'' its builders
promise. Since 1958, an astronomy observatory has been located at
Green Bank precisely because it is so remote and surrounded by
mountains that block out all radio interference. About 130
scientists and engineers live near the rural community of Green
Bank, which is 100 miles from the nearest town. The scant populace
is an interesting mix of brainy stargazers and their down-to-earth
backwoods neighbors. (Dart, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
