<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINISHING-SCHOOL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANSWERING A CALL FOR ETIQUETTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By MATTHEW PURDY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RYE BROOK, N.Y. _ ``The next trick we're going to learn,'' Mrs.
Herbert Christopher Hoover Jr. told the 27 girls around the table,
``is how to use the telephone.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they knew something about telephones, just as they
knew how to walk straight, sip soup and hold a conversation. But
Manners 2000, The Etiquette Advantage _ a one-day total-immersion
finishing school _ teaches the proper way.
</P>
<P>
   For example, ``Who may I say is calling?'' is preferable to the
teen-age grunt. And if parents are not home or waving wildly to
signal that they don't want to talk, Hoover suggested saying
something like, ``My father is having a business conference and my
mother is entertaining.''
</P>
<P>
   Some parents, hearing a child utter that sentence, might think
about having her deprogrammed. But the manners makeover at the Rye
Town Hilton last weekend specialized in such unnatural acts: girls
sitting straight-backed, walking with rib cages erect, saying
quaintly, ``May I please be excused to go to the powder room?''
</P>
<P>
   Manners are making a comeback, appropriately understated, of
course, which may explain why you haven't noticed it at your dinner
table. In the booming economy, people are eager to not only be well
off, but also to appear so.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Hoover, a former Mrs. Philadelphia with long years as a
model and image consultant, and Mrs. Robert Stith-Williams, a
longtime impresario of society balls in New York and Europe. (They
use their husbands' names.) Theirs is a tiny industry promoting
renewed appreciation of the fish fork, polite children and social
courtesies now mostly seen in colorized movies.
</P>
<P>
   The premise is that proper conduct counts, and those who know
will know whether you know, and if you don't, will identify you as
the social equivalent of slurped soup.
</P>
<P>
   Hoover had helpful hints.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never blow our nose at the table. We excuse ourself and
leave the room if we have to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should not talk about yourself for more than a minute and
a half without throwing the conversation to someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoover (her late husband was a distant cousin of the president)
said manners and grace, which she wears naturally, give people
self-confidence, freeing them to focus on others and making them
more likely to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Stith-Williams declared America an etiquette disaster area. ``I
see bad things,'' she said. ``When I see a top CEO stabbing his
steak in a private club and sawing it in half, things are bad.''
</P>
<P>
   They have come to the rescue of executives, a restaurant staff
and mothers fed up with children's reducing conversation to two
expressions _ ``like'' and ``ya know.'' The mother of a girl
approaching her bat mitzvah has asked them to teach the girl ``how
to introduce herself to her relatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend's session cost $250 a girl, and included a
three-course luncheon to teach the sixth-, seventh- and
eighth-graders proper table etiquette. Sip soup from the side of
the spoon, they were told, and wait for your hostess to put her
napkin in her lap before doing so yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Between courses, one eighth-grader, sitting erect, muttered,
``My grandmother would have loved this.''
</P>
<P>
   Others found it relevant. ``My dad has lots of dinner parties
because he's the boss,'' said a sixth-grader named Mary. ``He had
to dine with the queen of Sweden. He thinks that will come up in my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Victoria, another sixth-grader, said, ``My grandparents are
having a 50th anniversary party in April at a really fancy place,
so my mother thought it would be good to know how to do
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Stith-Williams said language and manners went haywire 30 or 40
years ago. ``That's all from _ what's that thing they had in
upstate New York? _ Woodstock,'' she said. She hopes that the
popularity of her seminars means that people want the next
generation set straight. But frankly, she's not optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``America used to be a consomme,'' she said. ``Now we're a
bouillabaisse. And once you're a bouillabaisse, you'll never go
back to being a consomme.''
</P>
<P>
   But at least we can use the right spoon.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
