<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4124 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NY-APARTMENT-SHOPPING     03-11 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-APARTMENT-SHOPPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING TWO YEARS TO FIND JUST THE RIGHT CONDO
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By TRISH HALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Some people look at apartments the way they check out
melons in the supermarket. They might buy something, someday, but
if the feel isn't exactly right, they'll pass.
</P>
<P>
   Good brokers can usually tell which shoppers are seriously in
need of a new place and which ones are not. Figuring that their
time in this market is too valuable to waste, the brokers usually
find some way to give browsers the slip. Jill Meilus, a broker with
the Corcoran Group, always believed that Elizabeth Bibb and Michael
Yamashita would buy something. She just didn't know when. And so
for almost two years, she showed them places, probably 40 in all,
trying to fulfill their desire for a condo rather than a co-op, two
real bedrooms and good light, all for about $450,000.
</P>
<P>
   Bibb and Yamashita live in a colonial house in Mendham, N.J., in
Morris County, but like to keep a second place in the city. Bibb, a
former magazine editor now studying playwriting, and Yamashita, a
photographer for National Geographic, come to the city for work and
for fun, sometimes with their daughter, Maggie, 4.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two years ago, they decided to sell their one-bedroom
duplex on West 15th Street, which they had bought four years
earlier for $175,000. It didn't have a bedroom for their daughter,
and they figured it was the perfect time to sell. ``We thought we
had hit the height of the market,'' Yamashita said.
</P>
<P>
   Their apartment sold quickly for $390,000, then a building
record for one-bedrooms. Yamashita said that, encouraged by his
investment-banker brother, who believed the financial crisis in
Asia would provoke a similar one here, he expected that prices
would fall and that taking their time to buy would be prudent.
</P>
<P>
   That turned out to be wrong, and as the real estate market
simply continued to rise, rising 20 percent in 12 months in
neighborhoods like Greenwich Village and Chelsea, they found
themselves looking for something bigger even as prices kept
outpacing their budget.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, they wanted to restrict their search to Chelsea or
the Village, but their broker convinced them they had to look
elsewhere to find what they wanted. They were close to buying one
place, but they had to act quickly to get the requisite papers
together, and with a business trip to Europe that couldn't be
canceled, they didn't have time.
</P>
<P>
   A loft in TriBeCa seemed perfect, but they passed on it because
of strict subletting rules. Since they sometimes travel on business
for months, they want to be able to sublet easily.
</P>
<P>
   As the prices rose, they became increasingly concerned that if
they didn't buy, they would be forever priced out. But in early
December, with the holidays coming and the uncertainty about Y2K,
Bibb decided to suspend the search. ``I had just talked to Jill and
said we had given up on the hunt,'' Bibb said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she couldn't really stop looking. ``Because of my real
estate addiction,'' she said, ``I went to the Internet, and a thing
popped up in our price range. I said, `This must be a typo.'''
</P>
<P>
   Her broker checked and found that there was a contract out but
that it hadn't been signed, so they went to look at the place, a
two-bedroom condo with a wood-burning fireplace on East 31st Street
between Second and Third Avenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I walked in here, the first thing I saw were those
windows,'' Yamashita said. ``They look Japanese.'' The shape of the
windows, with walls jutting out at either end, will make them
perfect for the window seats and shoji screens they plan to
install. The windows look out on the church and its courtyard,
hardly the dramatic view that had been one of their nonnegotiable
demands. But the screens will create a translucent, pearlized light
that in its way is just as evocative as the World Trade Center view
from their old apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Bibb felt instantly at home. ``It had a very good vibe about
it,'' she said. ``There is something very cosmic about how one
chooses where to live. It felt like it could be home.'' The asking
price was $460,000, but to outbid the other interested party, they
offered $470,000, lured partly by what they considered manageable
monthly carrying costs of $730 and monthly taxes of $375. They
closed on Jan. 14, using the cash they had kept ready from the sale
of their old place.
</P>
<P>
   Although their place has the clean lines of a postwar apartment
building, it was actually constructed in 1902 as a school that was
part of the Episcopal Church of the Good Shepherd next door. An
addition was built in the 1960s after the school was sold and
turned into apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Their apartment's modernity is a pleasing contrast to their
18th-century house in New Jersey, Bibb said, with its three
bedrooms, barn, gazebo and 5{ acres. Yamashita has lived since 1982
in Mendham, a town he discovered when he was taking photographs for
an article on New Jersey. A native of Montclair, he was entranced
by the horse farms and rolling hills, which remind Bibb of her
Kentucky childhood.
</P>
<P>
   The apartment perfectly holds their more modern pieces, like a
chair by George Nakashima, the Japanese-American artist. Their new
living room is already decorated with some photographs by
Yamashita, including one of the moss garden at Kyoto taken in the
rain, and an aerial view of Mount Fuji. A specialist on Asia,
Yamashita took the photographs for ``In the Japanese Garden,''
published by Fulcrum; his wife wrote the text.
</P>
<P>
   Although they hadn't wanted to live so far east in Manhattan,
their block has turned out to be a ``weird little haven,'' Bibb
said, with church bells ringing, pigeons cooing and every food they
could want around the corner at Todaro's, a miniature Balducci's.
</P>
<P>
   Although Yamashita jokes that his wife, who did most of the
looking, was ``the client from hell'' for their broker, Meilus said
she always believed they would buy when they found the right thing.
Maybe the broker's confidence came from the fact that she had known
Bibb since they were college students spending a semester at the
London School of Economics.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Meilus said, she has had some clients who have taken
even longer. ``I have one who's 3{ years,'' she said. ``I'm seeing
her this afternoon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
