<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4126 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-NYT &LR;      03-11 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE MARS AND VENUS CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Sunday, March 12:
</P>
<P>
   And so it has come to pass that after a short but electrifying
primary election campaign, the choice for president in the year
2000 is between two attractive, earnest men of privilege who went
into the family business of politics, and who probably first
shouted at each other in the 1960s across a football stadium at a
Yale-Harvard game. Voters yearning for someone who did not claw his
way up like Bill Clinton should be pleased.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that for all their similarities and their shared
desire to command the center, Gov. George W. Bush and Vice
President Al Gore are waging a contest between two contrasting
visions long familiar in American politics.
</P>
<P>
   In his victory speech last week, Bush portrayed himself as the
tribune of honor and the individual. He wants lower taxes, more
money for the military and tough standards for schools combined
with greater choice for parents. He would use some of the surplus
to shore up Social Security, but replace it in part with a system
of investment accounts. He portrays Gore as a loyal defender of the
state for the solution to every problem, stifling freedom in the
process.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president sees Bush, on the other hand, as a servant of
the affluent and a candidate who would peel the state back from its
proper role in securing the environment, schools and health. The
state, for Gore, is not the enemy of the individual. It is there to
nurture, protect and ensure that Americans are treated fairly,
especially in their earliest years and old age.
</P>
<P>
   These terms should be familiar by now. With their tailored suits
and cowboy boots, the candidates may look alike and even talk
alike. But as a couple, Bush is from Mars and Gore from Venus.
</P>
<P>
   Of course in marriage as in politics, especially in good times,
Americans find some appeal in both visions. Bush is right that the
individual and the entrepreneur are at the center of the American
success story. But Gore is correct that the surpluses lying ahead
offer an extraordinary opportunity to pay down the debt and soften
the harsh inequities dealt by the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The polls show the race to be close. But at the moment they show
Gore as having the edge on the issues, especially on Social
Security, health, schools and the environment. That means that Bush
will have to flesh out what he means by the phrase ``compassionate
conservative'' with more programmatic detail.
</P>
<P>
   On taxes, the governor is surely right to say that the $1
trillion surplus projected for the next 10 years belongs to the
American taxpayers. But so does the $5.5 trillion federal debt, and
the obligation to provide for basic social needs. Bush's speech
after his big primary victories last Tuesday was notable for not
mentioning anything about health care and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   The governor also dwelled at length about honor, which he said
had been ``exiled'' from the White House for nearly eight years.
There was a theme of restoration about his address that will be
appealing to many Americans after the years of scandals. It cannot
help Gore to be reminded, as he was by recent news stories, of the
failure of the Justice Department to investigate the campaign
fund-raising abuses of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But honor is a tricky issue. Sen. John McCain drew voters to his
cause because he had a record that no one could dismiss. Bush must
overcome deep skepticism over whether the honor he stands for is
deserved, especially after a campaign of scurrilous attacks and his
own unrestrained fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   From their divergent positions, Bush and Gore will be looking
for ways to portray themselves as men of the center and their
opponents as from the fringes of this debate. Their records show
them both to be more nuanced in their approach to government than
the oratory suggests _ Gore as a fiscal conservative and
budget-balancer, Bush as an advocate for more spending on education
and poverty programs.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, however, the voters will probably decide which basic
impulse about government makes the most sense for a nation that is
prosperous and complacent, put forward by two men with backgrounds
more similar than not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
