<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4127 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-LEWIS-WITNESSES0312-1     03-11 2255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-WITNESSES0312-1STLEDE-C </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What did they see the night of the Buckhead slayings?
 &HT;    By Staff Writers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At least nine people have stepped forward to say what
they saw on the night after the Super Bowl, when a fight in
Buckhead led to a pair of fatal stabbings. Baltimore Ravens
football star Ray Lewis and two other men facing murder charges.
Here are the witnesses' statements, drawn from various sources.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Whitehead was at Cobalt, partying with a friends, and left
around closing time.
</P>
<P>
   Whitehead said he and a woman began walking towards Jelly Rolls,
a club just east of Cobalt, when they saw some men arguing and
shouting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recognized one person in the group, Ray lewis. Lewis was
clearly acting as a peacemaker with the individuals who were
arguing. All the individuals were shorter than Ray. I easily
recognized him, but not the others.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, the argument escalated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I continued down the street near a light pole past the Rose
and Crown Club and I stopped there to talk to this lady,''
Whitehead said. ``From this point I observed the same group next to
the back of the Navigator limousine, which was parked on the street
near some apartments. At that time I saw Ray Lewis restrain one of
the men and was attempting to get everyone from his group into the
limo.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he saw Lewis ``restraining an individual who I describe
as a shorter, fair-skinned black male. At no time did I see Ray
Lewis hurt or strike anyone. He only acted as a peacemaker in
restraining people from fighting. He tried to get people back into
the limo.''
</P>
<P>
   A second fight broke out on the street corner in front of the
limo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I then left the area and walked back towards the club where my
car was parked,'' Whitehead said. ``I was afraid of possible
gunfire since a previous murder had occurred in that vicinity the
prior Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Keith Ponder, who shot a video of celebrities at Cobalt that
night, described Lewis as a ``peacemaker'' who pulled a friend away
from an argument. Ponder, however, left the area before the two
victims were stabbed.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis was not involved in the argument but merely stepped over
to pull away a friend, Ponder said. ``He had one friend by the arm
and they went around to the back of the limo and got in the back,''
Ponder testified at Lewis's bond hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Ponder himself also stepped in to urge the participants to knock
it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll change the adjective, but I asked them to, `Let that mess
go, you guys. I just saw a kid last couple of weeks ago die across
the street from the same type stuff,' '' Ponder said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Richard Lollar and Jacinth Baker _ who moments later
were stabbed to death _ were verbally aggressive. ``They wouldn't
back down; they were yelling,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said one was about 5-foot-5 and the other shorter. (Baker was
5-foot-3, Lollar was 6-foot-3.)
</P>
<P>
   Ponder drove off before the stabbings. Seconds later, he heard
gun shots.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Keeler lives in a second-floor East Paces Ferry Road
apartment, her bedroom window looking down on the crime scene. She
was startled awake in the middle of the night Jan. 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard glass shattering and people screaming and yelling,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   She pushed aside her curtain and called 911. The scene unfolded
quickly and was lit by a street light and several business signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were two gentleman, the victims, who were getting beaten
up,'' she said. There were four or five men on them, and the
assailants were larger men, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I looked out the window, they were at least
trying to fight back,'' she said, ``and by the time the police get
there, they were already down.''
</P>
<P>
   As the police arrived, the men who had beaten the victims fled
on foot, she said.
</P>
<P>
   She saw a man trying to help one of the victims. Then a handful
of gunshots rang out and the crowd scattered, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ozonu pulled his cab into the intersection of East Paces
Ferry Road and Grandview Avenue and was stunned by what he saw. One
man was being pummeled, another was down and bleeding on the
pavement, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I saw was six guys beating up a guy,'' he said. ``There
was a commotion. That means it could have been more people. More
than six.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Two of the guys started running away (down East Paces Ferry
Road). A body was lying in the street, and a guy was pointing at
him. Talking, talking. His legs were spread, shoulder wide. He was
pointing, `I was warning you. I was warning you.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The other guy kept grabbing him, (saying) `Come on, come on _
let's go.' He was pulling him, (saying) `Let's go.'''
</P>
<P>
   The man standing over the body and pointing was about 6 feet
tall and looked like a weight-lifter, Ozonu said.
</P>
<P>
   Ozonu, who moved to Atlanta from Nigeria 20 years ago, was
interviewed by police at the scene and met again later that morning
with homicide detectives. He has returned to the crime scene with
district attorney's investigators; an investigator stopped at his
apartment to interview him recently while a reporter was there.
</P>
<P>
   Ozonu said he probably couldn't identify the participants, other
than to give a general description. One of those involved in the
beating was so fat he could barely run, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he drove down the block to seek help from a police
officer when he heard shots being fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every one of those people who left in the limo was involved in
this,'' Ozonu said. ``To me, if you weren't involved, why would you
run away?''
</P>
<P>
   He said he saw many people on the street, but only one who tried
to help.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' high school buddy, Kwame King met his friend in
Charlotte, N.C., en route to Atlanta. He rode with Lewis in the
Lincoln Navigator limousine and stayed with the football star at
the Georgian Terrace Hotel in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   King accompanied Lewis to the Sports Authority store in nearby
Duluth the day before the Super Bowl while Lewis signed autographs
for about two hours. King said another man went along with them _
supposedly Joseph ``Shorty'' Sweeting.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, King said, he went to a Super Bowl party with Lewis
at the home of one of the football star's friends. They returned to
the Georgian Terrace Hotel in downtown Atlanta at midnight. A short
time later, Lewis, King, two women and two other men piled into the
limousine Lewis had rented and headed to Cobalt.
</P>
<P>
   About 3:30 a.m., the music was turned off and King, Lewis and
their party headed back toward the limo, parked about a block and a
half away.
</P>
<P>
   As they approached the first intersection, King said two men
started to follow them closely. Another man with braids ran up
behind them.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis and Jaye Roberts (who also goes by the name Jessica
Robertson) were getting into the limo with a few other women. Once
inside, King said, he heard a crash, as if someone had been hit
with a bottle or other object. He did not see it happen, however. A
big scuffle started on the limo's passenger side. Lewis then tried
to help Sweeting get into the limo.
</P>
<P>
   King said he saw Lewis at all times and that Lewis continually
tried to get his group back into the limo. He said Lewis never
punched or stabbed anyone.
</P>
<P>
   King said there was still fighting outside the limo as they sped
off. Seconds later, they heard shots being fired at the vehicle and
everyone inside the limo ducked their heads. The right tire of the
limo was shot, so the driver of the limo pulled into a Holiday Inn.
</P>
<P>
   From there the limo passengers took taxis back to The Georgian
Terrace.
</P>
<P>
   Duane Fassett, who often drove for Lewis, told police he saw
Lewis involved in an altercation with one of the victims in front
of the limo at the intersection where the stabbings occurred?.
</P>
<P>
   Fassett said Lewis was walking back to the limo in a group of at
least three women and six men when one of Lewis' group started
arguing with another group of men.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis tried to shepherd Oakley, who Fassett knew as ``Derby,''
into the limo, and others from Lewis's group also got inside.
Fassett said three men from the second group approached the front
of the limo, intensifying the argument.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the men inside of the limo then poured out of the
vehicle and started fighting with the men, Fassett said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Lewis was fighting with one of the victims, as were
``Shorty'' (Sweeting) and Oakley, two men he often picked up at
Lewis's Baltimore home. The altercation ended and members of
Lewis's group rushed back into the limo and the vehicle sped away
as someone fired shots.
</P>
<P>
   Fassett said he drove to a nearby Holiday Inn. He told police
Oakley was bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   Police said ``a substantial amount'' of blood was found inside
the passenger compartment.
</P>
<P>
   Occupants from the limo were seen cleaning up in a hotel
bathroom, before leaving in various cabs.
</P>
<P>
   Jessica Robertson, a Houston resident who met Lewis during Super
Bowl week, told prosecutors that she, Lewis and several others left
Cobalt about 3:30 a.m. and were followed by six men as they walked
toward the limo. She also gave prosecutors nine garment bags of
Lewis's clothing that she said he had asked her o hold for him.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson told police that she, Lewis and the others climbed
into the limo when two men jumped on Sweeting and started fighting
with him near the front of the vehicle. She said Lewis walked over
and pulled the men off Sweeting and tried to get him back into the
limo.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson later said she thought the men were trying to rob
other members of her group because her companions were wearing a
lot of jewelry that night.
</P>
<P>
   In one statement she said a fair-skinned man hit Oakley on the
side of the head with a bottle. She said the assailant wore a blue
Cousey sweater and a black knit cap. In another statement, that
description is omitted.
</P>
<P>
   She said Lewis continued trying to get people into the limo and
she did not see him strike anyone. She said Lewis did not have a
knife.
</P>
<P>
   There were 13 people in the limousine and Lewis sat in the back
with Robertson next to him. He took off his mink coat and put it on
the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson's attorney, Akil Secret, said Robertson described the
limo ride from the stabbing scene as ``pure pandemonium.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were screaming at (the driver) Duane Fassett to `drive!
Drive!' It seemed like he froze,'' Secret said.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson said Sweeting sat in the seat next to the driver's
partition. Police said there was a ``substantial amount'' of blood
in the limo. But Robertson said no one talked of a stabbing while
in the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   As they drove off, she saw a large black man over 6 feet tall
with braids standing near a parked Honda with a gun in his hand. He
started shooting at the limo as it drove off.
</P>
<P>
   She said that later, back at Lewis' room at the Georgian Terrace
Hotel, Lewis, she and one of his co-defendants saw an early-morning
TV report saying two men had been shot or stabbed in Buckhead.
``You didn't stab anyone, did you?'' Lewis supposedly asked the
co-defendant (whom Secret would not name.)
</P>
<P>
   Chris Shinholster, 28, came to Atlanta from Akron, Ohio, to
party in the Super Bowl atmosphere and went to the Cobalt, where he
met his two hometown buddies who had moved to the area. Shinholster
said he saw no fight inside the club, but left moments before
Lollar and Baker came out of the bar.
</P>
<P>
   Shinholster said he walked past Lewis's stretch limousine, but
turned back when he heard Lollar and Baker arguing with Lewis's
friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to make peace,'' Shinholster said.
</P>
<P>
   He saw one of his friends hit Reginald Oakley over the head with
a Moet champagne bottle. A fight broke out and he turned to Lewis
to ask him to intervene, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't you get your boy?'' Shinholster asked Lewis. He said
Lewis was just standing there. Shinholster said he did not see
Lewis holding a knife.
</P>
<P>
   Just then, Lollar yelled, ``I've been cut!''
</P>
<P>
   Shinholster said he did not see the stabber. He has repeatedly
told his story to Atlanta police. ``I've been down to Atlanta three
times already. I'm tired of being interviewed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see who killed them,'' he said. ``I didn't see Ray
Lewis with no knife.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were my two dudes who died,'' he said. ``I knew them all
their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gwen, 25, is a rapper known as Chino Nino. He who came to
Atlanta for the Super Bowl parties and met his friends, Lollar and
Baker, at Cobalt.
</P>
<P>
   Gwen said he was walking on the sidewalk with them when the
fight with Ray Lewis's entourage erupted. Gwen, who is 6-feet-2 and
weighs 160 pounds, said he joined the fight to protect his friends,
who were smaller and outnumbered. He told police Lewis punched his
friends.
</P>
<P>
   But Gwen said he fled when he saw an opponent brandish a knife.
</P>
<P>
   A short time later, Gwen saw his friends lying bleeding in the
street. He ran back and cradled Lollar, crying, ``Wake up! Wake
up!,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tragedy I've got to deal with the rest of my life,''
Gwen said. He would not say who brandished the knives or who
stabbed his friends.
</P>
<P>
   He has, however, told police and prosecutors what he knows. The
next time he tells the entire story will be in court, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were my friends. Justice is gonna be served,'' Gwen
said.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writers Lyda Longa, Joshua B. Good, Mike Fish, Craig
Schneider, Bill Torpy, Bill Rankin and Dan Chapman contributed to
this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
