<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-POLICE-BIAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: HOW A BLACK MAN'S WALLET BECOMES A `GUN' 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BRENT STAPLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When my fiancee's teen-age son pleaded for a cell phone, his
mother and I came back with an emphatic ``no.'' Like most people
raising children, we want him to spend less time on the phone and
more on his studies.
</P>
<P>
   But we also reminded him that he is a black teen-ager in New
York City, where people of his description _ 6 feet 2, 200 pounds,
with braids and the currently fashionable baggy pants _ attract
disproportionate attention from wary citizens and the police.
</P>
<P>
   We do not want him mistaken for a drug dealer in the marginal
neighborhoods he passes through in his travels around Brooklyn. Nor
do we want him reaching into his pocket at some inopportune moment
for an implement that in the bad lighting of a subway entrance
might be mistaken for a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Call it paranoid if you like. But the safety issues surrounding
young black males in any big city are many and complex _ and
include the inevitable worries about disastrous encounters with the
police. These worries have risen sharply of late, given the
convergence in the press of three unnerving cases involving police
misconduct and brutality, all of whose victims are black and
Latino.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, the scene of the latest scandal, about 70
officers are under investigation for perjury, evidence tampering
and, in a few cases, attempting to murder suspects. New York has
just witnessed the conclusions of two sensational police trials,
one focused on the police torture of the Haitian immigrant Abner
Louima, the second involving the shooting death of an unarmed
African immigrant named Amadou Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   Black parents have always told their children to shut up, keep
still and keep their hands in plain view when approached by the
police. But as an immigrant from Africa, Diallo had received no
such preparation. When the police approached, he reached for his
wallet _ perhaps in an attempt to identify himself _ which turned
out to be the last move he made.
</P>
<P>
   In the days since the officers were acquitted of murder,
demonstrators in New York have waved billfolds in the air, chanting
``It's a wallet, not a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani _ most recently New Republic
magazine _ attributed Diallo's death to unequal enforcement of the
law through the city's ``stop and frisk'' program, in which
plainclothes officers sweep through minority neighborhoods,
rousting people whom they find ``suspicious.''
</P>
<P>
   That ``stop and frisk'' has faults was illustrated in a striking
report last December by New York state's attorney general that
showed that blacks were more than twice as likely to be stopped as
whites _ even when taking into account higher crime rates in
minority neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   An analysis of the reports filed by the officers after each stop
found that less than a third of those black people fit the
description of the suspect being sought. This suggests very
strongly that the officers were stopping black people at random,
based on race alone.
</P>
<P>
   Such disparities are clearly unacceptable. But it is just as
clearly true that fatal shootings of minority citizens were a
problem _ and an explosive political issue _ in New York long
before ``stop and frisk'' was instituted. In addition, this problem
has historically transcended localities, administrations and
schools of policing.
</P>
<P>
   The root of the problem is the tendency of white police officers
_ and white Americans generally _ to associate blackness with
criminality in the absence of any substantiating evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The psychologist Gordon Allport first showed this effect 50
years ago in his studies on ethnic prejudice. In a particularly
clever experiment, Allport would begin his lecture showing his
undergraduate class two pictures, one of a black man unarmed and
one of a white man holding a knife. At the end of the hour he asked
students to recall what they had seen. Often the knife had migrated
from the white man to the black man, driven by stereotypes that
connect race with criminality.
</P>
<P>
   The point was that racial categories are freighted with negative
meanings that sometimes make us view people as threatening without
cause and that sometimes get us to see things that do not exist.
</P>
<P>
   Diallo, for example, appears merely to have been standing in the
vestibule of his apartment building. One of the police officers
testified that he was ``slinking'' around that vestibule and said
that he was ``peering'' suspiciously out of the doorway as though
to avoid being seen. It was a short mental step from this sinister
view to seeing the wallet that Diallo pulled from his vest pocket
as a gun.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a crime to have preconceptions based on race. But to
paraphrase the Bronx district attorney, Robert Johnson, they can
indeed kill in the right circumstances. The way out of this problem
is to ensure that officers who police a community actually live in
that community, so that they can tell the difference between the
criminal and the innocent _ and one black person from another.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, those of us with black teen-agers to raise will
continue with our paranoid precautions _ understanding that we are
not really paranoid at all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
