<DOCNO> NYT20000311.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4130 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-INTERNET-REAL-1125(2T     03-11 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-REAL-1125(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THESE DAYS YOU CAN CALL IT REAL E-STATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Just five years ago, Internet sites relating to real
estate _ to the extent that such sites existed at all _ generally
contained small numbers of property listings, crude search
capabilities and, if the site was truly innovative, links to
mortgage lenders and brokers.
</P>
<P>
   Now there are hundreds of thousands of real estate sites on the
Internet, at least one with more than 1.3 million property
listings. Most sites can be searched and culled in myriad ways, and
many large sites also offer a cornucopia of added features,
including links to lenders, credit-reporting agencies, house
inspectors and surveyors.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the online loan calculators; appraisal reports;
sale-price histories; school-district statistics; crime reports;
tips for buying, selling and borrowing; and even social and
historical data on neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   What started as a simple tool for buyers has evolved into a
whole toolbox. But care must be taken. For instance, the best way
to search for a home may vary from site to site, and using the
wrong search strategy can limit the number of ``hits.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also possible that by responding to an online listing and
establishing a relationship with the listing broker, you may not be
able to use a different broker to negotiate for you if you decide
you want to buy. And applying for a mortgage online through several
mortgage brokers or lenders, whether out of curiosity or just
because it's easy, can have a negative effect on your credit
rating.
</P>
<P>
   For home buyers, though, the Internet is a powerful tool.
``Imagine being able to search for a home that is within 20 minutes
of your job and that has three bedrooms, two bathrooms and whatever
other amenities you prefer,'' said Nick Karris, a real estate
analyst for Gomez Advisors, an Internet research firm in Lincoln,
Mass. ``Well, you can go to any one of a number of sites on the
Internet and find every house that meets your criteria just by
pushing a button.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past two or three years, Karris said, a staggering amount
of real-estate-related information has become accessible.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, consumers who were looking to buy real estate
would get almost all of their information from brokers and from
classified ads,'' he said. ``But now they can get as much
information as they want before they ever even meet with an
agent.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley Inman, the founder of Inman News Features, a real estate
news syndication service in Emeryville, Calif., agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until fairly recently, most of the properties that were for
sale in most areas of the country were contained in databases owned
by Multiple Listing Services,'' Inman said. ``And in most cases,
the Realtors hugged their databases so closely that their customers
couldn't even get a peek inside.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Internet has leveled the playing field, Inman said.
Buyers can electronically cull the listings of most of the houses
for sale in a given area, and it's a rare real estate Web site that
does not also make it possible for buyers to get up-to-the-minute
mortgage rates, calculate mortgage payments for varying amounts at
various rates and then visit an online mortgage broker or lender to
get an application.
</P>
<P>
   ``After years of consumers' feeling frustrated and powerless,
the Internet has cracked open the box and let consumers look
inside,'' Inman said, explaining that today, most large Multiple
Listing Services either have their own site or have agreements with
at least one Internet listing site. And many brokerage concerns
also have sites that contain listings that may not be included in a
Multiple Listing Service because the broker has an ``exclusive'' on
the listing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, a broker can't afford not to have an Internet
presence,'' Inman said, ``because the first thing a seller would
say is, `Hey, how come my house isn't listed on the Web?'''
</P>
<P>
   That's why listings are the mainstays of most Internet real
estate sites. By all accounts, the site with the greatest number of
listings is homestore.com, the flagship of a family of
real-estate-related sites that include realtor.com, the official
site of the National Association of Realtors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the biggest database by far,'' said Stuart Wolff, the
chairman of Homestore.com, which operates the realtor.com site with
1.3 million listings and the National Association of Home Builders
site, homebuilder.com, with a listing of about 130,000 new houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're also one of the most visited networks in the world,''
Wolff said, explaining that during January alone more than
2,563,000 different users paid a visit to a homestore.com site.
</P>
<P>
   But having lots of listings provides no guarantee that the site
has all listings in a particular area.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a couple of areas of the country that are a little
out of whack,'' Wolff said. ``And New York is one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolff explained that most of the listings on homestore.com are
derived from Multiple Listing Services affiliated with the National
Association of Realtors, so that areas that do not have such pools
of listings from a number of brokers _ notably Manhattan _ may not
be fully represented on the site. Moreover, he said, since
different Multiple Listing Services use different categories, the
success of a search for a particular type of house will vary.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a search for all available single-family houses in
Rutherford, N.J., yielded 21 hits when the search used the
realtor.com's series of increasingly specific area maps. A second
search conducted using only the site's town and state fields
resulted in only three hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way to search our site is to use the maps,'' Wolff
said, explaining that because the local Multiple Listing Service
frequently uses the name of the region or a ZIP code rather than
the town name, using the maps will result in the greatest number of
listings. In fact, he said, many buyers prefer to search by
neighborhood rather than by town name anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some people, the neighborhood is more important than the
house,'' he said. And that is why one of the more popular services
on the site is its ``Find a Neighborhood'' service, which allows
buyers to focus on the type of neighborhood they want to live in by
comparing and weighing factors like the quality of the schools, the
age of the population, social and cultural services and the number
of families with children living nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``The service is particularly good for first-time buyers,''
Wolff said. ``They can find the kind of neighborhood they want to
live in, they can look for homes in that neighborhood, and then
they can find a professional to show them the homes they like.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
