<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4132 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-INTERNET-REAL-2NDTAKE     03-11 1579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-REAL-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: they like.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In fact, like other sites that use listings provided by a
Multiple Listing Service, realtor.com generally tries to steer
business to a professional, typically, the listing broker. The site
provides only the brokers' telephone numbers and the MLS numbers
online, but not the addresses of the houses.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that poses a problem for buyers who don't want to go
through the listing broker to see the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard enough for a buyer to play hardball in a seller's
market,'' said Ilyce R. Glink, the author of the newly revised
``100 Questions Every First-Time Home Buyer Should Ask'' (Times
Business Books). ``But it's even harder when the agent you're
dealing with is the listing broker.''
</P>
<P>
   Glink explained that since most people who are interested in an
Internet listing call or e-mail the listing broker, that could make
it difficult for buyer to later negotiate for the property through
another broker.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you e-mail five different listing brokers and establish
business relationships with them, you could be setting up five
different `dual agency' situations,'' she said, explaining that a
dual-agency situation occurs when a broker or agent represents both
the buyer and the seller in the same transaction. And that, Glink
said, can end up being a disadvantage for a buyer because the
broker cannot be an advocate for either party.
</P>
<P>
   So she advises prospective buyers to use their own brokers, who
will represent only their interests, instead of calling or
e-mailing listing brokers, and certainly before agreeing to being
taken to see a property by a listing broker.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Lessa, a broker at Irwin S. Balch &AMP; Associates Realty in
Mamaroneck, exclusively a buyers-only agency, said that it would be
unusual for a traditional broker to provide buyers with the address
of an Internet listing without having them come into the office
first.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's because they want to be the one to show you the
property,'' Lessa said.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out, however, that since most brokers in a given area
are probably members of the same Multiple Listing Service, a broker
representing the buyer can usually provide clients with the address
of an Internet listing from the MLS number usually included with
the listing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can then drive by the house to see whether or not it's
right for them,'' Lessa said, ``and if it is, we can get them in to
see it.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, one of the clearest benefits of the Internet is not for
buyers, but for brokers.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Corcoran, the chairwoman of Corcoran Group, the
Manhattan brokerage company, said that she has been tracking
Internet sales by her agents and brokers since the company first
started using the Internet in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we found is that a traditional buyer sees about 22
different apartments before making an offer,'' she said. ``But a
buyer who comes to us from the Internet only needs to see about six
apartments before making up his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Corcoran said, buyers who come into her office after
first culling properties on the Internet now account for one in six
of her sales. ``What happens is, most people first go to your Web
site as Peeping Toms, just to look around,'' Corcoran said. ``Then
they start sending you e-mail, and before you know it, they're your
pen pal. And once someone becomes a pen pal, they're probably going
to end up a client.''
</P>
<P>
   Since there is no Multiple Listing Service in Manhattan, and
since the only way to see most apartments, even with your own
broker, is to go through the listing broker, many Manhattan
brokerages will include whatever information they have on a
particular Internet listing, including, in some cases, the address.
</P>
<P>
   ``With most of my properties we give you the address, a
description of the property, floor plans, a photo of the building
itself, multiple photos of the interior, and even the views out the
windows,'' Corcoran said. ``And we've learned that customers find
having all that information very alluring.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, since the absence of a Multiple Listing Service in
Manhattan makes it difficult for Internet ``super sites'' to get
listings, buyers in Manhattan have to visit individual broker's Web
sites for listings or browse through the classified advertisements
in the newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   But even searching the classifieds can now be done online.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have between 3,000 and 4,000 listings on our site every
day,'' said Jason R. Krebs, a vice president and the general
manager of nytoday.com, an Internet site owned by Times Company
Digital, a division of The New York Times Co. ``We have all the
listings from the newspaper as well as the direct feeds of the
inventory available from most of the major brokers.''
</P>
<P>
   Krebs explained that prospective buyers who use the nytoday site
can enter search criteria to find apartments of a certain size,
type, price or location.
</P>
<P>
   When the search is submitted, he said, the site searches through
not only the classified ads currently running in The New York Times
newspaper but also through the databases of many of New York's
largest brokerage companies, including Bellmarc, Brown Harris
Stevens, the Corcoran Group, Douglas Elliman, Charles H. Greenthal,
Halstead and Stribling. The brokerage concerns' individual listings
can also be reached directly through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Other newspapers that have classified ads online include The
Daily News, Newsday, The New York Post and The Village Voice.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, nyrealty.com offers detailed profiles of about
500 co-op and condominium buildings, as well as maps, details about
recent sales and information about specific neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Another group of listings that will often not appear on sites
that depend on Multiple Listing Services for their inventory are
``For Sale by Owner'' listings, known as FSBO (pronounced fizz-BO)
listings. But that does not mean that such listings cannot be found
online.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this moment, we have about 20,000 FSBO listings
nationwide,'' said Hans Koch, the chief executive of Owners.com, a
San Francisco company. Sellers who pay $99 can submit a listing and
five photographs. For sellers who buy the $289 Premier Package, a
professional photographer will take pictures of the house, both
inside and out, and the photos are then posted on the Web site,
along with the listing, to provide buyers with an online ``virtual
tour'' of the property.
</P>
<P>
   Another part of the owners.com site that is useful to buyers who
choose not to use an agent is its ``Get Prequalified'' section,
which links buyers to online lenders. Once on a lender's site, Koch
said, a buyer can get an estimate of how much money they can
borrow. (The names and Web addresses of a number of sites offering
mortgages and financial services appear in the accompanying
listing.)
</P>
<P>
   But submitting prequalification applications to a number of
online mortgage sites can be counterproductive.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't realize that playing around on the
Internet can have an effect on their credit rating,'' said Stanley
Simon, a real estate lawyer and a partner in Allen, Morris, Troisi
&AMP; Simon in Manhattan. Simon explained that every time a person
applies for credit, whether for a loan, for an increase in a line
of credit or for a mortgage, the lender makes an inquiry about
credit worthiness with at least one of the major credit-reporting
bureaus.
</P>
<P>
   Those inquiries, he said, are then noted on the prospective
borrower's credit report. And since the reporting bureaus make a
record of each inquiry, but do not indicate whether credit was
ultimately extended, having a large number of inquiries may lower a
person's overall credit rating, Simon said. So it can be risky to
apply for lots of mortgages simply out of curiosity and because
it's easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``My advice to clients is to think twice before clicking that
`Submit' button,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how useful a tool the Internet is or eventually
becomes, it may never completely take over the role traditionally
performed by flesh-and-blood brokers and sales agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at hundreds of listings on the Internet and spent a
lot of time sorting through junk,'' said Mauro Calcano, a Manhattan
executive who with his wife, Isabel, recently searched online for
houses in the New York City area while they were still in London,
where they had lived for five years. ``My wife was diligent about
finding a place with the best school system possible. She was at it
for weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Calcano said, the couple stumbled upon Web site for
Irwin S. Balch, the buyers' agency in Mamaroneck that Lessa works
for.
</P>
<P>
   ``We e-mailed back and forth maybe 20 or 30 times a week,''
Calcano said, explaining that over a period of about a month the
agency had lined up a couple of dozen houses for them to see in
Westchester County, in and near Rye. But when the couple flew over
and and started looking at the houses, nothing clicked. That's when
Lessa's associate, Laurie Bell, decided to take the Calcanos to see
some new houses being built in Ridgefield, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at a set of plans, we looked at the development, and
that was all we needed,'' Calcano said, The couple are now under
contract to buy a five-bedroom house scheduled to be completed in
September.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing missing from the Internet is the human factor,''
Calcano said. ``Without those guys, we never would have found what
we were looking for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
