<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4133 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ZERO-DOWNPAYMENTS-REA     03-11 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZERO-DOWNPAYMENTS-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCING A HOME FOR ZERO DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)  (jw) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As many aspiring home buyers know, to their regret, the biggest
obstacle to ownership can often be the down payment. And while the
percentage needed for a mortgage has dropped in the last 20 years
from the traditional 20 percent to 10, 5 and in some cases even 3
percent, the prices of homes have doubled, tripled and even
quadrupled.
</P>
<P>
   Now some large lenders have started to offer zero down payment
mortgages that also allow financing of the closing costs. Some
lenders even make it possible for new owners to leave the closing
with more cash than they had when they walked in _ at the price of
course, of more debt.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Reddam, chief executive officer of DiTech.com, a mortgage
lender in Costa Mesa, Calif., says that what his company calls a
Dream Loan allows home buyers to obtain mortgages for up to 125
percent of the purchase prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``This loan is for people who have good credit and strong income
but who have never been able to save enough for a down payment,''
he said. ``It's also for people who feel they have a better use for
their money than tying it up in their home.''
</P>
<P>
   Reddam said that good credit generally referred to a credit
score of 660 or above. The credit score is calculated using factors
like the payment history on other loans, the number of open credit
lines and the type and amount of a person's indebtedness.
</P>
<P>
   ``A borrower with sterling credit would have a score above 700,
and a `B' borrower would have a score below 620,'' Reddam said.
``So a person with a score of 660 is in the middle of the range.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to having a good credit score, he said, a borrower
seeking a Dream Loan needs a somewhat better income-to-debt ratio
than normally required. In most cases, Reddam said, for a borrower
to qualify for a mortgage, total monthly expenses _ including all
recurring debt payments and the payment on the mortgage being
applied for _ cannot exceed about 38 percent of gross monthly
income. For Dream Loans, however, notwithstanding the
income-to-debt ratio, the borrower must have at least $2,000 a
month left after all bills are paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no application fee, and the actual cost of the loan
depends on the person's credit score and how much over 100 percent
they want to borrow,'' he said, adding that the interest rate also
depends on the amount of the loan, with the current rate for a 125
percent mortgage around 11 percent. The rate for a conventional
mortgage from DiTech, he said, averages around 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Another company aggressively marketing zero-equity loans is
Countrywide Home Loans in Calabasas, Calif. ``We give you a
choice,'' said Stephen Brandt, the company's senior vice president.
``You can get either a Zero Down Plus with PMI or an 80/20 No Down,
No PMI.''
</P>
<P>
   Brandt said that the Zero Down Plus mortgage is a 103 percent
first mortgage that requires private mortgage insurance. The 80/20
mortgage, he said, is actually two loans _ an 80 percent first
mortgage plus a 20 percent home equity loan.
</P>
<P>
   With the Zero Down Plus mortgage, he said, the extra 3 percent
usually covers the borrower's closing costs. Private mortgage
insurance, typically referred to as PMI, is required on first
mortgages for more than 80 percent of a home's value. The insurance
_ paid for by the borrower as part of the monthly mortgage costs _
provides the additional security needed for lenders to be able to
sell such loans to institutional investors on the secondary market.
</P>
<P>
   Brandt said that the principal and interest payments on a
$250,000 Zero Down Plus mortgage for 30 years at 8.875 percent _
the current rate _ would be $1,989 a month. Private mortgage
insurance on the part of the mortgage that exceeds 80 percent of
the home's value, he said, would add $203 a month, making the total
payment $2,192.
</P>
<P>
   The company's other zero-down offering works differently. Since
the 80 percent first mortgage is considered a conforming loan,
meaning that it conforms to the standards set by Fannie Mae and
others who buy the loans from the issuers, then repackage them in
pools of securities for purchase by investors, there is no
requirement for PMI. But while the interest rate charged on the
first mortgage is still 8.875 percent, the interest rate charged on
the second mortgage _ in essence, a home equity loan _ is 12.875
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The first mortgage, for $200,000 at 8.875 percent, would require
monthly payments of $1,591; the home equity loan, for $50,000 at
12.875 percent, would cost $559 a month. The total, $2,150 a month,
is $42 a month less than the mortgage that requires PMI.
</P>
<P>
   Brandt said that while the Zero Down Plus loan allows financing
of the closing costs, the PMI portion of the monthly payment was
not tax deductible. On the other hand, he said, with the 80/20
loan, in most cases the interest on both the first and second
mortgages would be deductible.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the catch?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think these loans can be extremely risky,'' said Gerri
Detweiler, education adviser for Credit Counselors of America and a
co-author with Marc Eisenson of ``Slash Your Debt'' (The Financial
Literacy Center, Kalamazoo, Mich., 1999). ``If the value of your
house drops, or even if it just doesn't increase, you could be in
big trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Detweiler said that since only a small portion of the monthly
payment is applied to the principal in the early years of a
mortgage, a homeowner could end up having to sell a house for less
than the outstanding balance on the loan. That could easily happen
with a home that has a 125 percent mortgage, she said, and is even
possible for a home with a 100 percent mortgage when the costs of
the sale are considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything happens to your income stream, or you have to move
unexpectedly, you're stuck,'' Detweiler said. ``You have no
breathing room. You may never get out from under.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
