<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4139 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-STRATEGY0312-COX     03-11 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-STRATEGY0312-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush campaign expected to expand for the fall
 &HT;    By Jena Heath
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gov. George W. Bush, shifting into general-election
gear, is exploring ways to expand his Austin campaign operation
even as he prepares to install a loyalist at the Republican
National Committee in coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Bush aide said Friday that the campaign will install a,
``general chairman type, obviously somebody senior and somebody
close to the governor,'' at the RNC, before turning its attention
to the Austin staff. The aide said such a move is customary for the
presumptive nominee, but declined to say whom who the RNC pick will
be.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home, Bush will ``expand the circle of advisers,
bringing in new people to fill new slots,'' the aide said. Changes
will include hiring one or more staffers to do formal, senior-level
outreach to coalitions across the country. The 1992 campaign of
Bush's father and Dan Quayle had a division devoted to reaching out
to teachers and other constituencies. That campaign also had a
congressional liaison, a position now unfilled on the Bush staff.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, losses in New Hampshire, Michigan and Arizona
prompted speculation about more substantial changes, specifically
about how campaign manager Joe Allbaugh, communications director
Karen Hughes and key political strategist Karl Rove would fare
after the primary season.
</P>
<P>
   The three stalwarts have formed Bush's inner circle since he
first ran for governor in 1994. Bush's recent victories vindicated
Rove's strategy of spending deeply, establishing campaign
operations in every state and never deviating from a deep tax cut
message reminiscent of the Reagan years.
</P>
<P>
   But victory came at a price. Anticipating trouble on the right
from millionaire publisher Steve Forbes, the campaign missed the
threat posed by Arizona Sen. John McCain, whose success with
moderates and Democrats posed the real challenge. McCain exploited
Bush's speech at Bob Jones University, an evangelical institution
with an anti-Catholic philosophy, drowning out his compassionate
conservative message.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has won the thing but he has won at a very high price,''
said Paul Begala, a former aide to President Clinton. ``He has
tacked much too far to the radical right. ... You will be seeing
television ads featuring Jerry Falwell praising Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   The McCain challenge also forced the Bush campaign to spend most
of its $70 million. Bush will soon turn his attention to a series
of scheduled fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Rath, the Republican National Committee member from New
Hampshire, said he expects the campaign to broaden its base of
advisers but does not anticipate ``a fundamental reshaping of the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they have always planned that this is going to be a
very, very close general election,'' Rath said. ``There is relative
prosperity in this country, peace abroad nationally. These make for
tough times to be the change agent.''
</P>
<P>
   Begala said he believes the campaign will have to rethink its
strategy as it goes up against Gore, a fierce competitor who ``went
through a very painful, wrenching period of change,'' and emerged
with ``one clear strategy designed to win the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that Bush has reinvented himself and placed himself in
the hands of whatever local there was in each state and let them
define him ...'' Begala said. ``You can't keep doing this.
</P>
<P>
   But Rath defends the results: ``Let's not forget that these guys
won. At the end of the day, that's what matters.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
