<SLUG> BC-BKN-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV SPORTS: SEEKING INSIGHT, NOT AN INTRUSION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The world did not end in 1997 when Fox Sports inadvertently let
the world hear Yankees Manager Joe Torre curse on national
television. It was the second season that Fox equipped managers and
coaches with miniature microphones, and a technician let the taped
comment slip onto the air.
</P>
<P>
   Torre felt betrayed _ he was told he wouldn't be embarrassed _
but after Fox's apology, he consented to be wired again and again.
</P>
<P>
   Almost exactly a year later, in a Yankee game against Boston,
Fox caught Torre narrating a Mo Vaughn fly ball: ``I don't think he
got all of it. I'm sure he didn't get all of it.'' When the ball
landed in the right field bleachers, he lightheartedly said, ``I'm
wrong, he got all of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The miking of players, coaches and officials has never been like
the National Security Agency listening in on private telephone
conversations. If there have ever been shocking remarks, I've never
heard them. Sometimes they illuminate, like demystifying the
manager-pitcher-catcher mound chats.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, they're ``ear candy,'' said Ed Goren, executive producer
of Fox Sports, like a first-base coach reminding a base runner not
to be picked off.
</P>
<P>
   So it's strange to hear National Basketball Association coaches
and players whine, as if they fear being subject to an illegal
search and seizure, about new league requirements that coaches wear
tiny microphones and that cameras show team locker rooms at
half-time on NBC and Turner Sports' telecasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it negatively impacts the coach, because you now have
to really monitor what you say,'' Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy said.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, these rules are turning into labor issues about
working conditions. Lighten up, guys. Keep your shorts on.
</P>
<P>
   NBC and Turner started wiring coaches and lead officials earlier
in the season on a voluntary basis, and not for every game. Some
coaches have resisted, including one who removed his mike during
the second half of a Turner broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever has been said is used only on tape, and nothing
with profanity or strategy is heard. That doesn't leave a lot for
delicate flowers to complain about or create grounds to change how
one speaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little window dressing and an inside look or listen,''
said Mike Pearl, executive producer of Turner Sports. ``When we go
to commercial and can show the locker room, it tells fans things
are still going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty five years ago, Pearl, then at CBS Sports, said the
network's hand-held cameras boldly joined NBA huddles during
timeouts. ``We got away with it for a while,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   NBC has so far wired coaches and referees for seven
regular-season games and the All-Star Game. Miraculously, the
league hasn't folded.
</P>
<P>
   During a Houston game, NBC's microphone on Rudy Tomjanovich
caught the Rockets' coach uttering something that sounded like
``Kapoya,'' his exuberant reaction to a three-point shot.
</P>
<P>
   But what began as an experiment in rightly enhancing telecasts
has gone too far. Starting Sunday, the league will require that
both coaches wear the microphones and will levy fines of at least
$100,000 if they refuse.
</P>
<P>
   The two-coach mandate is excessive and the fine ridiculous.
Baseball requires that team managers or coaches be wired for sound.
Those managers who don't want to be wired can hand the obligation
over to a coach who has nothing to say. Simple. Fines up to
$100,000 can be levied if everyone refuses.
</P>
<P>
   In wiring game participants, the networks understand the need
for propriety. If they don't use the taped sound bites carefully,
they can lose access.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes down to a level of trust with the league that we'll
be judicious,'' said Jed Drake, ESPN's vice president of remote
production.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than have a rigid policy on miking, the National Hockey
League works to accommodate the networks' requests to wire players,
coaches or officials.
</P>
<P>
   To hear an NHL linesman caution a goalie on ESPN, ``Watch that
stick or the next time, we'll call a penalty,'' is instructive.
</P>
<P>
   The National Football League is far more restrictive. No coaches
or players can be wired _ a privilege reserved for NFL Films
productions _ but one player on each team can be wired during
warm-ups, with the team's permission. Fox, CBS, ABC and ESPN are
also allowed into locker rooms before games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We grab a little footage and we're out in a few minutes,''
Goren said, ``just so you get a little feel for the atmosphere in a
locker room before a game.''
</P>
<P>
   The fruits of the access have been minimal and far from
revealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Behind-the-scene shots in the locker room are interesting, but
not particularly insightful,'' Drake said. ``But they show the
ordinary preparations leading up to a game.'' And they're recorded
without sound.
</P>
<P>
   Goren said he'd love to tape conversations between head coaches
and offensive coordinators to show how a play worked, or to tape
the coaches' booth to hear what a coordinator says after he has
called a play for a touchdown. ``There's got to be some emotion up
there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Drake said that wiring NFL players in warm-ups has yielded
insightful or amusing bits from Minnesota's John Randle and San
Francisco's Steve Young. On Fox, Goren recalls Darrell Green,
Washington's veteran cornerback, giving a pregame pep talk to a
rookie.
</P>
<P>
   So it's time for folks like Jeff Van Gundy to relax. Only
wealthy courtside denizens can really hear what you're saying. And
they don't have microphones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
