<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMERCIAL-REAL-880(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: USING WEB PAGES TO WEAVE AN INFORMATION NETWORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOHN HOLUSHA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In pressing to adapt their operating methods to the
opportunities presented by the Internet, real estate services
companies are finding themselves making use of some of the
techniques of the dot-com companies that have become their
important customers in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, technologies that seemed advanced just a few
years ago, such as e-mail, are being displaced by systems that
place on a World Wide Web site all the information needed to manage
property, describe available space or process transactions, with
passwords providing a hierarchy of access.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the Internet companies we deal with would laugh at us if
we wanted to fax a document,'' said Matthew P. Barlow, an executive
managing director at Julien J. Studley, a company that specializes
in representing office tenants. ``The pace of deals is faster
today, and we don't want to miss opportunities because of our
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Some companies are using their Internet capabilities as a
marketing tool. Insignia/ESG, a large commercial-services company
that also manages 65,000 condominium and co-op apartments in New
York, recently launched EdificeRex.com, a portal to Web pages. The
site enables residents of the apartments to access services that
include reserving tables at popular restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Insignia/ESG said it intends to broaden the portal to include
the commercial side of its business. Andrew I. Farkas, the
company's chairman, said the combination of technology and original
content can give a company a competitive advantage in businesses
like property management.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology itself is not necessarily the driving factor,'' he
said. ``The driving factor is combining technology with content to
create e-business models in every place where you are operating
traditional business models.'' He said developing the features of
EdificeRex was ``orders of magnitude'' more difficult than applying
it to the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Technology can be a marvelous filing cabinet. Cushman &AMP;
Wakefield, which manages 35 million square feet of property,
recently formed a joint venture with Business Integration Group of
Tempe, Ariz., to offer its clients a Web-based property management
service it is calling ``e-real estate.''
</P>
<P>
   John C. Santora, Cushman &AMP; Wakefield's executive managing
director for asset services, said the system is intended to reduce
confusion and duplication by placing all the information regarding
the company's management portfolio on one central database.
</P>
<P>
   Other people have packages to do preventive maintenance,
computer drawings and lease abstracts, he said, but ``none of them
talk to each other.'' Another problem, he said, was that local
offices measure things in different ways, so the data they produce
is often difficult to compare with the results from other
locations.
</P>
<P>
   The communications abilities of the Web permit all this data to
be stored in powerful computers called servers that can be accessed
from almost anywhere. ``You don't need any special programs, you
just go to the Internet and you are in,'' Santora said. ``Clients
in hotel rooms worldwide can get access to their information.''
</P>
<P>
   Although some clients might get uneasy knowing their
confidential financial information is in the same place as their
competitors', Ron Savage, the chief executive of the Business
Integration Group, said the company's fire-wall and password system
means that only authorized people have access. ``We have had two
audits and we work with the security people of the companies that
use the system,'' he said. ``It's like online banking.''
</P>
<P>
   Having a well-organized central database connected to the Web
allows brokers and other executives to concentrate on getting deals
done without having to keep track of paper or electronic files,
said Michael A. Cohen, director of leasing for Williams Real Estate
Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say you have an assignment to dispose of 100 properties from a
company that wants to get them off its balance sheet,'' he said.
``With a central repository, you have a separate folder for each
transaction, with photos of the property, floor plans, financial
analysis and so on. That information is available to the client and
the broker on the case anytime, anywhere in the world via the
Web.''
</P>
<P>
   Another advantage, he said, is that the systems can be designed
to keep track of documents and the sequence in which they have been
generated and how they have been altered. ``It can tell me if I
have a copy of the most recent offer on a property, which is
important if you are doing 50 to 100 transactions a year,'' he
said. ``And I don't have to ask for information. It's there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology is a tool that makes things work better,'' said
Heather Shively, chief executive of Capital Thinking, a New
York-based company that matches owners and brokers with mortgage
lenders through the Web. But she said that the heart of the
30-person company, which started operating this month, is real
estate professionals who know how to structure proposals in a way
that meets the underwriting standards established by lenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technology is not there to replace people,'' she said.
``We understand lenders and we have relationship managers who work
with them. We want them to see nice clean deals coming from us.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Executives at Studley have established a three-level electronic
communications system. One is an Intranet for internal company use;
another, called the Ultranet, is for use by brokers and clients;
the third is a public Web page to be used as a sales tool by
brokers.
</P>
<P>
   The public Web page, still in development, will feature
time-sensitive graphics, among other things. Someone visiting the
site in the middle of the night will see a home page that has a
nighttime sky with stars. Visitors at 6 a.m. will see dawn, those
at 6 p.m. will see dusk.
</P>
<P>
   But it is more than fancy graphics. The site will list property
for sale or lease and the space needs of clients. And it will be an
automated tip service for brokers. ``The Web site will be a
marketing tool for brokers,'' said Jeffrey D. Hipschman, chief
information officer for the company. ``It will send notification
back to the broker if a client visits the site looking for
information.''
</P>
<P>
   Hipschman said the company uses its Intranet to keep track of
employees, and as a way of storing an inventory of their skills.
``If we need an expert on land assembly, we can find one quickly
using the system,'' he said. He said the site contains information
on recent deals so brokers and executives can keep track of the
state of the markets in the cities where Studley has offices.
</P>
<P>
   But he said there has been an effort to keep the approach
light-handed to make the net attractive to people not weaned on
technology. One page is devoted to competitor information, often a
euphemism for rumors. ``People can post the latest rumor,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   A central repository for information, he said, is a step up from
e-mail, and is likely to replace it. ``This way everyone involved
can share information, rather than sending point-to-point
e-mails,'' he said. ``With this system, everybody is working off
the same page.''
</P>
<P>
   And having all the data on properties organized in files makes
it easier to find obscure but essential documents with a few clicks
of a mouse, said Santora of Cushman &AMP; Wakefield. ``I can drill into
a rent file to find the underlying legal documents,'' he said. ``In
New York a lease can run to 500 or 600 pages. I can click on rent
and go right to the lease file.''
</P>
<P>
   With information on space availability becoming much more
readily available, and with companies popping up offering to match
landlords with prospective tenants, some of the information that
has been jealously guarded by brokers seems to be slipping into the
public domain.
</P>
<P>
   But Cohen of Williams said brokers would not be replaced by
computers. Instead, he said, their role will change. ``More
information will be available, but it will not take out the need
for someone to negotiate a transaction,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think brokers will become more like consultants than people
whose job it is to find space,'' he said. ``They will help
companies plan their real estate strategies, the way lawyers and
accountants advise them now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
