<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BASEBALL-NOTES0312-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Realignment consensus not near
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kissimmee, Fla. _ For all the happy talk, commissioner Bud Selig
has some appeasing to do before his radical realignment plan comes
up for consideration next month.
</P>
<P>
   There is cronyism in the air as well as some short-sightedness.
Selig is returning some calls but not others. This issue hasn't
been settled easily in the past. It is worthwhile to remember that
the last time baseball re-sorted itself, Selig finally threw his
team, the Milwaukee Brewers, into the fire, jumping leagues just to
effect the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are several plans under consideration, in brief,
Tampa Bay would jump to the National League while Arizona would
move to the American. This would enable the Texas Rangers to move
into the geographically preferable AL Central. The NL's refitting
for four divisions would eliminate the wild card, somewhat odd
after MLB swooned over its effectiveness the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves would leave the NL East _ and the New York Mets _ for
a Southeast Division that might include Florida, Tampa Bay and
perhaps St. Louis. And here, things break down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm assuming it's a typo,'' Cardinals president Mark Lamping
griped. ``If you believe the thinking that regional rivalries are
important, how can you possibly separate the Cardinals and the
Cubs? You just don't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Selig agreed and let the Cards know in a phone call, intimating
that the Cardinals, Cubs and Brewers would remain in the same
division. USA Today, which printed the new alignments, mistakenly
reversed Cincinnati with the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Colangelo is still watching his phone. The Arizona
Diamondbacks general managing partner, Colangelo is working hard to
prevent his club from being uprooted, primarily because Phoenix
likes things the way they are. An Arizona poll of season ticket
holders and single-ticket buyers shows that between 65 to 85
percent of people attending Diamondbacks games want the team to
remain in the NL.
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo, who counts Selig as a friend, has heard nothing from
the commissioner, hardly the best way to build consensus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support it and I particularly support it because it does
away with the wild card in the NL,'' Cincinnati general manager Jim
Bowden said, whose club lost a one-game playoff to New York. ``Last
year we had the problem that if you tie, you don't know where
you'll play the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``And one team would make it and one wouldn't for various
reasons. Some nuances I didn't like. It's just better if a team has
to win the division to get into the postseason.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like it's every team for itself, except for the expansion
franchises, which can be moved without their permission. The vote
comes up at baseball's quarterly meeting April 18 in Houston. A
simple majority in both leagues is required for passage, that being
the solution's only simple part.
</P>
<P>
   THE PHILLIES' BIG QUESTION
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia second baseman Marlon Anderson (.252, 11 errors)
has become the biggest question mark in the Phillies daily lineup.
Although management says he is the second baseman of the future
until proved otherwise, Anderson's every play is being scrutinized
this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Asked his opinion, third base coach John Vukovich recalled an
opinion first issued by former Phillies manager Paul Owens. ``It's
like Pope used to say,'' Vukovich said. ``You can lead a horse to
water. But you can't make him float on his back.''
</P>
<P>
   JIMYWOCKY
</P>
<P>
   Then there is this from Boston manager Jimy Williams, after
observing that Japanese pitcher Tomo Okha was rushing his delivery
last week when he gave up six hits and six runs while retiring just
one hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had 45 seconds in his minute,'' Williams said. ``Kind of
like a New York minute, but he's from Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   NOT READY FOR PRIME TIME
</P>
<P>
   New Indians owner Larry Dolan observed Cuban defector Danys Baez
at Cleveland's Winter Haven camp and could see for himself that his
$14.5 million investment is hardly ready for the majors. The
22-year-old might open the season at Class AA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Danys is just getting broken in,'' said Indians manager
Charlie Manuel, having returned to the team after colon surgery.
``This is a great experience for him. He has a lot of potential,
but he's going to have to develop more consistency with all his
pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI AGENDA
</P>
<P>
   Reds captain Barry Larkin, who a year ago was asking to be
traded, has already seen enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not a matter of whether we will win the division,'' he
said. ``It is a matter of by how many games.''
</P>
<P>
   ETC.
</P>
<P>
   Former Braves left-hander Kent Mercker arrived in Anaheim to
find himself a savior. He is the only Angels starter with a winning
1999 record (8-5). The rest of the projected rotation _ Ken Hill,
Tom Candiotti, Ramon Ortiz and Jerrod Washburn _ was a combined
22-30.... Pittsburgh's Jason Kendall has been so impressive in his
comeback from a shattered ankle that manager Gene Lamont ditched
his plan to play him every other day in the early stages of camp.
He started three games in a row last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks' Omar Daal might be the only man to find a
benefit from the December flooding in his native Venezuela. Limited
to one inning of winter ball because of the disaster, Daal hit camp
with a very fresh arm. ``As soon as I threw in the bullpen three
times, I feel more power in my body and more relaxed,'' he said....
In the Rangers camp, Tom Evans is beating out prized prospect Mike
Lamb in the scramble for Todd Zeile's vacated spot at third
base....
</P>
<P>
   Cubs management has all but conceded that right-hander Kerry
Wood will open the season on the disabled list. He began throwing a
curve only last Monday (50 feet, flat ground) and his first spring
start has been delayed to next weekend. Target comeback date: April
18-20 in Montreal.... The New York Mets expect to get third baseman
Robin Ventura back on the field late this week but progress from
shoulder surgery is slow. Ventura has been used thus far strictly
as a DH.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
