<SLUG> BC-BKC-ACC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUKE HITS LONG NOTES TO REACH THE FINAL
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By BARRY JACOBS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ Duke built one of modern college basketball's
most successful programs on the strength of its defense. But
Saturday afternoon it was a 3-point shooting barrage in the second
half that carried the Blue Devils to a hard-fought 82-73 victory
over Wake Forest in the semifinals of the 47th annual Atlantic
Coast Conference tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The top-seeded Blue Devils, who improved to 26-4, made 13 field
goals in the second half, nine of them 3-pointers, as they held off
repeated challenges by fifth-seeded Wake Forest, which fell to
17-14.
</P>
<P>
   The victory put Duke into Sunday's 1 p.m. championship game,
where it will face the winner of Saturday's second semifinal
between North Carolina State and Maryland, the only ACC team to
defeat the Blue Devils in the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Wake Forest held a 41-36 lead with 18 minutes 50 seconds to go
on a layup by guard Robert O'Kelley. But Duke, sluggish and
frequently short on its shots, came alive offensively and took
control for keeps.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils mounted a 14-2 run, culminating in a 50-43 lead
on a free throw by the all-conference forward Chris Carrawell with
12 minutes 15 seconds to go. Wake Forest, which began forcing
shots, was still within 55-51 midway through the half when Duke
again erupted.
</P>
<P>
   This time the Devils pushed their edge to 63-53, their largest
of the game, on a 3-pointer by forward Nate James, who had 14
points and played tenacious defense.
</P>
<P>
   Wake Forest responded with 5 unanswered points, closing to 63-58
on a 3-pointer by guard Josh Howard with 7:34 left. But the Duke
barrage continued, as five of its players scored in double figures,
including guard Jason Williams, who had 16 points and 11 assists.
</P>
<P>
   Wake Forest, winner of three straight, showed uncommon poise
against the Blue Devils, and led by 37-36 at halftime. Duke had
previously been 3-3 when trailing at the half.
</P>
<P>
   The Deacons quickly took the lead as all five starters scored in
the opening four minutes, and kept the Blue Devils off balance with
rugged defensive play inside. Forced to the perimeter, Duke, the
ACC's most accurate 3-point shooting club, missed five of its first
six attempts from long range. For the half, the Blue Devils made
only 37.1 percent from the floor, while Wake Forest hit 53.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Duke remained within a basket for the game's first six
minutes. Then Wake Forest went on a tear, scoring on seven of its
next 11 possessions, capped by a penetrating jumper by Howard to
push the lead to 28-20 with 7:29 remaining in the first half. That
matched the Deacons' biggest lead of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils responded by turning to guard Mike Dunleavy and
forward Shane Battier, who led his team with 18 points. With each
scoring inside and out, Duke went on a 12-2 run. The burst was
capped by a Dunleavy layup at the 4:44 mark, giving the nation's
second-ranked team a 32-30 advantage, its first since the game's
opening basket.
</P>
<P>
   Dunleavy, a freshman reserve who returned to action on Thursday
after missing four games because of mononucleosis, led all scorers
with a dozen points in the half.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike in its first two meetings with the Blue Devils, which
it lost by an average margin of 16 points, Wake Forest took the
blow, kept its composure and regained the lead, 37-34, on a
3-pointer by Howard with 1:38 left in the half.
</P>
<P>
   Duke finished first outright in the conference during the
regular season for the fourth consecutive year, a feat matched only
once in ACC history _ by Vic Bubas' Blue Devils of 1963-66, led by
Art Heyman, Jeff Mullins, Jack Marin and Bob Verga.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Mike Krzyzewski's Blue Devils also won the ACC tournament
last season. Not since David Thompson and Tom Burleson starred for
North Carolina State in 1973 and 1974 has a program won the
regular-season race and the league tournament two years in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Finishing first earned Duke a day's rest under the format
adopted by the ACC in 1998. On Thursday, the Blue Devils defeated
ninth-seeded Clemson, 94-63, setting a tournament record by hitting
17 of 29 attempts from 3-point range.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
