<HEADLINE>
AFTER ANOTHER OPERATION, ANOTHER COMEBACK FOR CANSECO
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Ask Jose Canseco about home runs, and he
talks about health. Ask him about his place in the batting order,
and he talks about health. Ask him about the weather, and he talks
about health.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to be healthy and play every day,'' said Canseco,
35. ``I don't think about numbers. I think about staying healthy.
I'm healthy. That's my main concern.''
</P>
<P>
   For good reason. Injuries have wreaked havoc on Canseco's
career. He has hit 431 home runs, but he has missed 30 percent of
his teams' games the past 11 seasons, since he was the American
League's most valuable player in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you have to do is a little mathematics,'' Canseco said.
``I'd have about 550 home runs right now.''
</P>
<P>
   But Canseco, now Tampa Bay's designated hitter, immediately put
his projection in perspective. ``There are a lot of players in
history probably that would have had more stats if they hadn't been
injured,'' he said. ``But injuries are part of the game, and part
of this game is if you have the talent and ability, you have to
stay injury free. You have to be in the lineup every day and pile
up those numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Canseco had 31 home runs when he had to undergo back surgery in
the middle of last season. Sammy Sosa had 32 home runs at the time,
Ken Griffey Jr. had 28, Mark McGwire had 27. Canseco could have
been right with them in pursuit of McGwire's record, but he does
not lament his fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was hard for me to accept,'' he said, discussing his
injuries, ``I wouldn't be able to bounce back the way I bounce back
or have the urge to play the way I play. I'm just happy I have the
ability to come back as I have and to have been able to put these
numbers together as I have. If I get 500 or 600 home runs, I'll
probably go down with the most home runs compared to the most
surgery.''
</P>
<P>
   Canseco is the opposite of Cal Ripken Jr. ``I can't fathom Cal
Ripken Jr., who's my size and who plays a position that's so
demanding,'' he said. ``I can't imagine that streak he had. To me,
that's impossible. That's not of this planet. I have enough trouble
staying healthy for one year.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Canseco thought of his former brother in bashing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I truly believe if Mark McGwire were healthy, he'd hit a
thousand,'' he said. McGwire has had his own run of injuries.
Without them, he, too, would have many more home runs, as if 522
isn't an impressive number itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be one of the superstars in the game,'' Canseco said, ``I
think one criteria has to be health. McGwire's probably one of the
few who have ever overcome that.''
</P>
<P>
   What About Quinn?
</P>
<P>
   Sign of an improving team: Mark Quinn cannot break into the
Kansas City Royals' outfield.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn is a 25-year-old rookie who won minor league batting
titles each of the past two seasons, then staged a spectacular
three-week performance with the Royals last September. After
hitting .360 for Omaha of the Class AAA Pacific Coast League, Quinn
batted .333 in the major leagues, hitting six home runs in 60
at-bats and producing an astronomical .733 slugging percentage.
</P>
<P>
   But the Royals' outfield is filled with Jermaine Dye in right,
Carlos Beltran in center and Johnny Damon in left. What to do with
Quinn?
</P>
<P>
   ``Quinny would have to make the club as a designated hitter or
part-time designated hitter,'' Manager Tony Muser said. ``I'm not
in favor of sitting Quinny on the big league level. I think he's
still on the development side. He's hit everywhere he's been. He
had a nice September with us last year. I want him to keep working
hard, push his way into that outfield defensively.''
</P>
<P>
   Muser said he was reluctant to have a player as young as Quinn
be the DH.
</P>
<P>
   ``Labels are funny in this game,'' he said. ``All of a sudden,
boom, you're a designated hitter. I've seen Mark improve his
defense dramatically over the last two years. If he DH's and
doesn't play much in the outfield, that progress is probably going
to come to a halt. We'll have to see how this plays out. We know we
have a talented offensive guy there.''
</P>
<P>
   What about first base? The Royals do not have a natural first
baseman. Why not teach Quinn that position?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've thought about that,'' Muser said. ``I told him to bring
a first baseman's glove to spring training. But we've got one
project under way right now with Sweeney. For right now, two
projects would be a little too much for us to handle. I'm not
saying he couldn't do it. I'm just saying we've made a commitment
to Michael and we'll stay with that commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Sweeney had been a part-time catcher for the Royals until
they decided they had seen enough of him behind the plate and made
him a first baseman for the last four months of last season. He
solidified his presence there by batting .322 and driving in 102
runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds' Lament
</P>
<P>
   The Cincinnati Reds lost the wild-card spot in last year's
National League playoffs in a 5-0 loss to the Mets in a playoff
game. Or did they? Jack McKeon, the Reds manager, cited not the
last game of their season but the first series of the season as the
reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that opening series against the Giants, we had the lead
every game,'' McKeon recalled. ``One game it was a six-run lead and
our bullpen couldn't hold it. They walked everybody. Here we had a
bunch of young kids who had performed a little bit the year before.
But now opening day they go out and they don't want to get hit.
They're afraid and they walk everybody and blow the leads.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look back and say if we had won just one of those games we
would have been in the playoffs. Now those same guys have the
experience. Opening series this year, you won't see us walk those
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Moving Would Be No Bargain
</P>
<P>
   If a realignment plan under consideration is adopted, there
would be good news and bad news for the Tampa Bay Devil Rays. They
would be leaving the American League, meaning they wouldn't have to
play their division-mate Yankees 18 times (good news), but (bad
news) they would go to the National League, be in the same division
with the Atlanta Braves and play them 20 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to be one of the better teams in baseball, you're
going to have to beat teams like that.'' Larry Rothschild, the
Devil Rays' manager, said. ``When I was with the Marlins in '97, we
beat the Braves. It's the way the game is. That's the way it should
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Happy to Oblige
</P>
<P>
   Tom Kelly, the Minnesota Twins manager, said that managers
received a memo earlier in the spring from Sandy Alderson, the
chief of baseball operations in the commissioner's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told us to make sure that when we had road games we took
enough regulars,'' Kelly related. ``I was going to send him an
e-mail telling him if he would tell me who my regulars are I'd be
happy to take enough of them for each game.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials Investigate Conflict
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner's office is looking into a potential conflict
that would arise with a pair of pending acquisitions by Clear
Channel Communications. The conflict centers on Tom Hicks, owner of
the Texas Rangers, and his role as vice chairman of a company that
represents players, including about half a dozen of his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some concerns about it,'' a baseball official said.
</P>
<P>
   The players association also has concerns. ``It raises some
interesting questions,'' Donald Fehr, head of the association,
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks, who also owns the Dallas Stars of the National Hockey
League, said he would address baseball's concerns. ``I can see the
potential for conflict,'' he said, ``but we'll set it up where
there is no conflict.'' He also noted that no conflict currently
exists because neither deal has closed.
</P>
<P>
   Clear Channel, which owns and operates radio stations and
outdoor advertising properties, is acquiring SFX Entertainment and
AMFM Inc. As chairman and chief executive officer of AMFM, Hicks
will become vice chairman of Clear Channel.
</P>
<P>
   In the nine months preceding its agreement with Clear Channel,
SFX purchased three agencies that represent baseball players:
Speakers of Sport (Jim Bronner and Bob Gilhooley), Hendricks
Management (Alan and Randy Hendricks) and Tellem &AMP; Associates (Arn
Tellem).
</P>
<P>
   The agents, who for years have been competitors, gathered in
Phoenix last week for their first ``team'' meeting. An unexpected
topic of discussion was the Hicks matter. One person involved with
the group said the agents had made known their concerns to SFX
officials.
</P>
<P>
   The agents represent Rafael Palmeiro, Royce Clayton and Justin
Thompson, among other Rangers. They also represent Juan Gonzalez,
Roger Clemens, Pedro Martinez, Mike Mussina, Kerry Wood, Albert
Belle, Mariano Rivera, Moises Alou, Vladimir Guerrero, John Rocker,
Al Leiter, Nomar Garciaparra, Ben Grieve and Mike Lieberthal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assuming our deal closes and the SFX deal closes sometime this
summer,'' Hicks said, ``our firm would be the largest shareholder
and I'd be a director and own two teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks said the agent part of Clear Channel's business represents
about 1 percent of the company's total business, about $25 million
out of $2.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to Gary Bettman the other day,'' Hicks said,
referring to the National Hockey League commissioner, ``and I said,
if need be I'd recuse myself from any board actions relating to
that 1 percent line of business.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had not spoken to anyone in the baseball
commissioner's office but said he would make the same pledge,
including having nothing to do with the day-to-day operations of
the sports agency business. ``I think it's a nonevent,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   However, an agent who has no link to SFX said it was not a minor
matter. ``There are a lot of things that have been in a gray
zone,'' he said, ``but there's nothing gray about that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
