<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEARY KNICKS ARE INSPIRED BY SPURS REMATCH
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The shot arched from Latrell Sprewell's fingertips like a
desperate flare that quickly fizzled and faded as it plunged short
of the rim. At that instant, the San Antonio Spurs began dancing
around as unified as a string of paper dolls, using the pinwheel
ceiling of Madison Square Garden as the backdrop for their
championship celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the chaos on that June evening, Patrick Ewing loped away in
a suit while a dilapidated Larry Johnson shuffled numbly to the
locker room. At the point of his playoff injury in the semifinals,
Ewing had asked of his team, ``Get me my ring.'' In his effort to
deliver, Johnson pushed through pain and conjured up a 4-point
magic potion against Indiana during a surreal playoff journey.
</P>
<P>
   They were so close to punctuating spectacular careers. But it's
clear that neither aging superstar has many more opportunities left
in their bodies. While Ewing can still summon the star power out of
his 37-year-old frame at times, the legs are not there for every
occasion now. While Johnson is two days short of his 31st birthday,
his chronic disc pain will likely force him to have minor back
surgery over the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Their bodies are like scrap metal, their time is short. It's
about now for Ewing and Johnson. What better measure of their hope
than to face down their demons Sunday at the Garden. In their first
appearance in town since they hoisted the trophy on the Knicks'
stage, the Spurs will seek to put their opponents in their place _
again. Last June, they won the title four games to one. In January,
a month into Ewing's return from his Achilles' injury, Tim Duncan
crushed the Knicks' spirits as an encore to the finals, 96-83.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kicked our butt the last time we were out there,'' Ewing
said. ``We'll be ready for them Sunday. David Robinson is a great
player. Tim Duncan is a great player. Naturally, when you play
against people who are good, you want to go out and perform your
best.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing sounded just like the stubbornly proud star of yesteryear.
He did not play in the finals, and let it be known that the outcome
might have been different if he had.
</P>
<P>
   Those thoughts were only reinforced Friday night when he
delivered a game-winning shot in Philadelphia to give the Knicks
only its second victory on the road in 10 games. One good victory,
and the Knicks were oozing the confidence of a team bound for
another finals clash with the Spurs, Lakers or whomever stands in
their way. One good victory, and the Knicks seemed refocused on the
task at hand. Have they snapped out of it? Or will the Spurs send
them spiraling into another funk?
</P>
<P>
   ``San Antonio is coming into the house knowing what happened
last year,'' Johnson said. ``We can't have no letdowns against
anyone. When we play good teams, you see a different ball club.
Being veterans, we should see that and know that's not the way
you're supposed to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Chicago won all those titles, they went out and destroyed
teams from the get go. They just put it on them from the start.
They destroyed the other team's confidence and then cruised from
there. We tend to try to wait and see how hard we need to play to
win. There should be one way we play all the time. We have to get
over the mental block.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the way we've been struggling on the road, this game
on Sunday isn't about how we played in the finals last year. Hey,
we've got teams nipping at our heels in our own division. We have
to play hard every game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, the comparisons with how we played them in the
finals last year is definitely going to be there,'' Johnson said,
referring to the Spurs. ``We know that.''
</P>
<P>
   They know the Spurs uncovered the Knicks' weaknesses last year.
Maybe Ewing would have put a roadblock in the paint that Robinson
and Duncan lorded over in the finals. Maybe a healthy Johnson could
have helped slow the duos runaway dominance. In January, neither
backed up that theory, as both struggled to score 12 points a piece
while Duncan came up with 33.
</P>
<P>
   What could have possibly changed since then? If Ewing had not
hit the shot to beat the 76ers on Friday night, if Johnson had not
come through with 6 straight points in the fourth quarter, they
might not have been emotionally prepared for the Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both Patrick and Larry played great,'' Coach Jeff Van Gundy
said. ``Too often, everyone will judge Patrick on shooting. That's
always the talk _ the kind of shots, the number of shots _ but
Patrick means a lot more to us than that.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, he and Johnson meant the difference as younger
stars like Allan Houston and Sprewell floundered around them. Out
of that effort, the Knicks have hope _ whether foolish or founded _
that they can overcome both the daunting task of returning to the
finals and taking down giants like the Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   `'We're ready for that one,'' Chris Childs said. ``We need to
let San Antonio know that last year was last year, and this year
it's going to be a different story.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as Houston and Sprewell are called upon to carry the
burden, Johnson and Ewing will have a lot to say about how the
story ends for their careers as Knicks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
