<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOAT-MACARTHUR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR A BRITISH WOMAN, AT 23, THE WORLD IS NEXT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Suspended in space some eight stories above an America's Cup
waterfront scene in Auckland, New Zealand, that for the last
several months had been home to some of the world's top sailors,
the elfin British solo skipper Ellen MacArthur took in a much more
commanding view than her 5-foot-2 frame normally affords.
</P>
<P>
   MacArthur was harnessed to the carbon-fiber masthead of her
striking new Open 60, Kingfisher, performing a routine rig
inspection before the boat's inaugural overnight sail. Having taken
delivery of the yacht from a local builder just days earlier,
MacArthur was beginning to forge some imperative bonds with the
vessel aboard which, later this year, she will hitch her dream to
race alone around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Back on deck after a rapid descent, she offered a technical
observation to a helper in fluent French _ a handy skill for an
offshore single-handed sailor, whose discipline is dominated by
Frenchmen _ and then returned to her native tongue for a broader
take on the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at this boat and I ask myself if this is really
happening to me,'' she said. ``It sometimes feels too good to be
true.''
</P>
<P>
   Her twinkling eyes in contrast to the flat light of a drizzly,
calm Auckland morning, MacArthur looked even younger than her
remarkable 23 years. But it was a morning for dichotomies, for
MacArthur's youthful appearance belied her vast experience, and the
still harbor gave no indication of the violent gales and stormy
seas that await on the multistaged, self-appointed mission ahead of
her.
</P>
<P>
   MacArthur's ultimate goal with the 60-foot Kingfisher _ named
after the European retail giant that proffered 2 million pounds for
title sponsorship of the campaign _ is to compete in this
November's fourth running of the quadrennial Vendee Globe race, a
solo, nonstop sprint around the planet and whose signature
masochistic allure is a death-defying charge across the frigid
Southern Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's daunting, but it's something I've wanted to do for a long
time,'' MacArthur said. ``A lot of the sailing decisions in my life
have almost been subconscious. It's like they were meant to be. And
the Vendee was meant to be now.''
</P>
<P>
   Though MacArthur's march to the sea in hindsight seems
inevitable, in reality her nautical fate was far from
predetermined. Raised by her school-teacher parents far from the
water in the only-in-Britain village of Whatstandwell, she was
introduced to sailing by an aunt at the age of 8, and almost
immediately realized she had discovered a life-long pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   Funneling her lunch money into a secret boat-buying fund, she
purchased her first dinghy at 13 and traded up twice by 17, at
which time she refit and sailed her latest acquisition, a husky
21-footer, on a five-and-a-half-month solo cruise around Britain.
</P>
<P>
   She parlayed that experience into jobs working on boats and
teaching sailing, and into a pair of crewed trans-Atlantic
crossings. But she began to make a name for herself when, at 20 and
the youngest of 56 competitors, she finished 17th in the wild Mini
Transat race, a solo transAtlantic contest aboard radical,
stripped-out 21-foot rockets.
</P>
<P>
   The experience led to the unavoidable questions about age and
gender, to which MacArthur replied, ``I can't describe how it feels
to be the youngest sailor and a girl. It's like asking me how it
feels to be a 40-year-old bloke. I'm just an ocean sailor, like
everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but not many ocean sailors have enjoyed the run
MacArthur is currently on. She followed the Mini Transat with a
class triumph in the double-handed Round Britain and Ireland Race.
Then, she made her true breakthrough in the 1998 solo Route du
Rhum, yet another French torture test in which she again won her
class, for 50-footers, while vanquishing many of the 60-foot
skippers in the process.
</P>
<P>
   For the British, who in recent years have not managed to scrap
together an America's Cup effort nor been able to beat the French
in the solo offshore game, which they essentially invented, the
MacArthur package was too good to be true. The marketing people at
Kingfisher agreed, and opened their coffers.
</P>
<P>
   True to form, MacArthur continues to do it her way. She built
her boat in New Zealand, rather than Europe, so she could shake it
down on a homeward delivery via the Southern Ocean and accrue her
first crucial high-latitude Southern Hemisphere miles. In June, she
will compete in the solo trans-Atlantic race from England to
Newport, R.I., as a further shakedown.
</P>
<P>
   The big test will come in the fall. For MacArthur, it is just
another tipped domino in a reeling procession of events. ``You
don't have to have massive goals, just steady ones,'' she said.
``You knock one off and you go from there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
