<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4151 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKW-BC-GOTTSTEIN-NYT     03-11 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-BC-GOTTSTEIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
B.C. SEEKS NATIONAL STAGE 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By ANDREW R. TRIPALDI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHESTNUT HILL, Mass. _ The sidelines had started to feel like a
prison for Boston College forward Becky Gottstein as she spent six
weeks on the bench nursing a stress fracture in her right ankle.
So, understandably, she felt liberated when she returned to the
lineup, just in time for the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Out of action since Jan. 18, Gottstein, a 6-foot-1 sophomore,
took the floor once again last weekend for the Big East tournament
opener against West Virginia. It was a relatively quiet return for
Gottstein, who scored 7 points and grabbed 9 rebounds in a 70-53
victory. But she was elated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to play so bad,'' Gottstein said. ``I was hoping
the rust would fall off quick. I was just excited to get here and
have a uniform on again.''
</P>
<P>
   Gottstein averaged 16.9 in the Big East Tournament, propelling
Boston College (25-8, 12-4 conference), to its first appearance in
the semifinals since 1990. In the quarterfinal victory over
Georgetown, she shot 6-11 from the field for 18 points, and
followed with 19 points and seven rebounds in a 79-54 loss to
UConn.
</P>
<P>
   Gottstein's return not only injected renewed hope and confidence
into the Boston College coaching staff and her teammates, her
presence also makes the No. 17 Eagles a legitimate dark horse in
the National Collegiate Athletic Association tournament picture.
The women's draw takes place Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Boston College got off to a flying start at the beginning of the
season with a 15-4 record, including a 12-game winning streak. With
a starting lineup of Gottstein, the senior guard Cal Bouchard, the
sophomore guard Brianne Stepherson, the senior forward Alissa
Murphy and the junior center Jamie Cournoyer, the Eagles had a
solid blend of experience and youth.
</P>
<P>
   But when Gottstein was hurt, the picture looked bleak. Boston
College Coach Cathy Inglese juggled her personnel, fielding six
different starting lineups during Gottstein's absence, and the
Eagles managed to finish out the regular season 8-4.
</P>
<P>
   Inglese said that the production of the 6-3 Cournoyer,
especially while Gottstein was out, was crucial to Boston College's
success during the critical juncture.
</P>
<P>
   Cournoyer has started every game, averaging 11.7 points and 5.9
rebounds per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been feeling more and more confident in what I am
doing,'' Cournoyer said. ``With Becky out, I felt I had to do more
and play a bigger role.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, finally at full strength again, Boston College awaits word
Sunday night as to its seeding, bracket and first-round opponent in
the NCAA Tournament, which begins Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Inglese is hoping the selection committee, after taking into
account Boston College's strong overall record and impressive Big
East conference record, rewards the Eagles with a first-round home
game at Conte Forum.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles qualified for the tournament for the first time last
year, defeating Ohio State, 72-59 in the first round and losing to
Tennessee in the second round, 89-62.
</P>
<P>
   This season Boston College was only 1-4 in the regular season
against teams now ranked in the top 25, and detractors contend that
the Eagles seem to fall to earth against upper-echelon opponents.
</P>
<P>
   But three of those four losses occurred during Gottstein's
absence: 84-77 at No. 1 UConn (28-1) on Jan. 26, 72-59 at No. 5
Notre Dame (25-3) on Feb. 5, 73-51 at No. 8 Rutgers (21-6) on
Feb.23.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing to the Final Four may or may not be a realistic goal
for the Eagles, but Inglese believes her team, with a healthy
Gottstein, is ready to attain national prominence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been very pleased with our team because we have been
playing better and doing more good things,'' Inglese said. ``I
think we are taking very good shots, and I am pleased with our
execution. We have shown a lot of growth in the last few games. We
have just got to keep it up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
