<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4153 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TOME-SCHOOL-REAL-NYT &LR;      03-11 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOME-SCHOOL-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: DISPLACING THE GHOSTS OF STUDENTS AND SAILORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Md.)  (jw) 
 By MAUREEN MILFORD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT DEPOSIT, Md. _ Perched on steep cliffs above this curious
little riverside town, which is just a mile long and 500 feet deep,
is a ghostly granite-and-limestone group of buildings that have
preoccupied residents for decades.
</P>
<P>
   The former Tome School for Boys, with its sweeping views of the
Susquehanna River, was considered one of the most beautiful
boarding-school campuses on the East Coast at its peak in the
1920s. Named for Jacob Tome (the last name rhymes with home), a
Port Deposit lumberman and banker and Cecil County's first
millionaire, the beaux-arts campus was designed by the New York
firm of Boring &AMP; Tilton, which also designed the main building on
Ellis Island and the Heights Casino in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the school has become a symbol of the town's past,
particularly its heyday a century ago as a ``port of deposit'' for
goods moving by boat and rail between the Susquehanna Valley and
the Chesapeake Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the school became part of the Bainbridge Naval Training
Center, etched in the memories of tens of thousands men and women
who served there, from 1942 until its closing in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Flanked by the river to the west and cliffs to the east, Port
Deposit, in the northeast corner of Maryland, about 35 miles from
Baltimore, has a population of about 800.
</P>
<P>
   Main Street recalls the town's commercial prominence in the 19th
century with Georgian, Greek Revival, Federal, Victorian and
Italianate structures built well above street level to avoid damage
from floods, which are usually controlled by Conowingo Dam six
miles upstream. The entire town is on the National Register of
Historic Places.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy did little to alter the symmetry of the Tome School
campus. The dozen buildings that lined the quadrangle in a
century-old drawing _ the gymnasium, dormitories, classroom
buildings, dining hall and headmaster's house _ are completely
recognizable today. The row of two-story clapboard houses built for
teachers, the heating plant, sidewalks, roads, drinking fountains
and even street signs give the impression of a town deserted very
suddenly.
</P>
<P>
   Only deterioration of the buildings and the untrimmed grounds,
including an overgrown terraced garden and a nine-hole golf course,
provide clues that the last class graduated from the Tome School in
1941 and that the Navy closed the base in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the weedy 1,200-acre tract is facing a new life as
development plans, sponsored by the state of Maryland, get under
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``A shadow of our history is up there,'' said Erika Quesenbery,
a curator at the Paw Paw Museum, named for bushes that once graced
the museum entrance. ``People feel an amazing sense of pride about
it _ and an amazing sense of loss.''
</P>
<P>
   The school was built in 1900 with about $1 million of the $3
million bequeathed by Tome. The trustees in charge of the bequest
set about creating an exclusive preparatory school, but its
prestige was short-lived, and during the Depression, the school
fell on hard times financially.
</P>
<P>
   Robert T. Jones Jr., 77, a retired funeral director who lives in
Newark, Del., went to the school in the late 1930s, and he
remembers how he liked to stand on the bluff and watch storms
whipping up on the Susquehanna.
</P>
<P>
   On Sundays, he recalled, the boys would troop into town to
church, descending the steep cliffside steps they called ``Jacob
Tome's ladder.''
</P>
<P>
   At the outbreak of World War II, the Navy came looking for
recruit training sites, and the school was sold to the government
for $900,000. The entire campus was incorporated into the new naval
base, and since 1942, the property has been off limits to most
civilians, although drivers crossing the Susquehanna on Interstate
95 can glimpse the elegant headmaster's house and the clock tower
of the main classroom building.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Navy closed the base, residents of Cecil County worked
for years to reclaim the property. In 1991, the 125-acre Tome
School section was annexed by Port Deposit. Then last year, the
Navy agreed to transfer the entire site to Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   In a military ceremony last month, attended by Tome graduates,
former sailors and local officials, the Navy formally transferred
the parcel to the Bainbridge Development Corp., an agency set up by
the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people can understand what the significance of
that day was to us,'' said Mayor Wayne L. Tome Sr., a
great-great-great-nephew of Jacob Tome. ``We've been sitting there
looking at that site. It's been a thorn in our sides.''
</P>
<P>
   The development corporation, whose board is made of area
residents, is charged with developing and marketing the property.
Possible uses for the Tome campus include a conference center,
retirement community or university extension campus, and the rest
of the site could be devoted to recreation, home sites, office
buildings or light industry. Development is expected to take place
over the next 15 to 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The first order of business is to create a master plan for the
entire parcel, said Harland Graef, a retired DuPont executive who
is the development corporation's chairman. A study is also under
way to determine the best way to establish a modern water and waste
treatment system, and the corporation is now applying for grants to
pay for necessary repairs to keep the historic Tome buildings from
deteriorating further.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to restoring the buildings, the development
corporation will have its work cut out for it. Vandals made off
with much of the ornamentation on the Tome buildings, inside and
out. Even the weather vane on the clock tower of Memorial Hall was
stolen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was demolition by neglect,'' Tome said. ``Vandals stripped
out plumbing for the copper and chipped out the marble steps.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-00 1748EST &QL; 
