<DOCNO> NYT20000311.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4155 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OUTDOORS-SEAFARMING-N     03-11 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-SEAFARMING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEA-FARMING INDUSTRY IN PERIL FROM INFECTIOUS VIRAL DISEASE
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By PETE BODO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As little as a decade ago, the nascent but rapidly growing
aquaculture industry was hailed by most conservationists and
recreational anglers as the magic bullet in the battle to halt the
precipitous decline of the wild Atlantic Salmon. But today, the
brief history of salmon aquaculture is best read as a cautionary
tale about the hazards of tampering with the natural order.
</P>
<P>
   This message was reinforced most recently by the discovery of a
previously unknown viral disease, infectious salmon anemia, which
is ravaging the salmon aquaculture industry, and appears to be
present in wild salmon as well.
</P>
<P>
   The disease causes hemorrhages in the kidneys, spleen, and other
organs, eventually leading to death, according the Dr. Fred
Whoriskey, vice president of research and environment for the
Atlantic Salmon Federation. There is no known cure or antidote for
the salmon anemia, and it is not considered a threat to humans. But
if the salmon anemia spreads significantly among wild fish, it will
further imperil a threatened and severely depleted species, and
make aquaculture appear to be more of a Trojan horse than a magic
bullet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aquaculture is not the main reason for the decline of wild
salmon,'' said Bill Taylor, president of the Atlantic Salmon
Federation, the organization leading the battle to save the wild
fish. ``But it has proven to be a real problem wherever large
numbers of sea cages are present. On the Bay of Fundy off Canada,
which has the highest concentration of salmon farms in the world,
and in the Gulf of Maine, aquaculture is having a major, negative
impact on wild fish. The irony in this is terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Aquaculture, or sea-farming, has in the span of a single
generation burgeoned into a worldwide, $45 billion industry. Sea
farms produce, among other things, seaweed, shrimp, catfish and
salmon. Most consumers probably aren't even aware that the vast
bulk of salmon they eat is fish raised en masse in coastal pens,
genetically as different from their wild cousins as a Butterball
turkey is from a wild bird.
</P>
<P>
   The only telltale sign of a farm-raised fish is the distinct,
white lines of fat in the cross-section of a typical salmon steak,
markings that suggest rich feed, rapid growth and lack of exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Before sea-farming, wild salmon were a gourmet delicacy that
often fetched more than $7 a pound. Aquaculture promised a win-win
situation: if salmon were ``farmed'' in large quantities, at a cost
with which the gear and labor-intensive high-seas fishing fleets
could not compete, consumers would be satisfied for a better price
and the overfished wild salmon populations would rebound.
</P>
<P>
   The salmon federation itself was so intrigued that it made an
alliance with the budding industry and developed strains of salmon
suitable for fish-farming. But while the price of salmon has
plummeted to just over $2 a pound, aquaculture has created a host
of problems _ even before the salmon anemia outbreak _ including
pollution and the genetic threat to wild stocks posed by the
unexpectedly large numbers of salmon that escape from the cages.
</P>
<P>
   The escapees behave much like wild salmon, seeking out rivers in
which to spawn. But they are not genetically designed for life in
the wild, and by breeding with wild fish they corrupt the gene
pool. The first serious signs of the failing marriage between
aquaculture and the conservation establishment emerged when large
numbers of escapees began turning up in rivers that held indigenous
populations of wild fish. And then came the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Whoriskey and other biologists believe that the inevitable
stress inflicted on fish held in cages in large numbers either
created the disease, or helped it grow exponentially. Additionally,
outbreaks of the disease appear to be triggered by the cold water
(50 to 60 degrees) that is considered ideal for salmon-farming.
</P>
<P>
   When fish become infected with the salmon anemia, they shed
viral particles that are then spread to other fish in their
proximity, or borne on ocean currents. Thus, infected fish farms
are de facto virus factories: in just six years from its first
appearance in Norway in 1984, the salmon anemia spread to a total
of 101 fish farms there. The disease appeared on this side of the
Atlantic in 1996. Just two years later, more than one million
infected aquaculture fish were destroyed by the government of
Canada, at a cost of more than $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   The most disturbing news of all emerged from the Magaguadavic
River in southern New Brunswick, where Whoriskey and other
scientists regularly conduct field studies on wild fish and
aquaculture escapees. Every year since 1992, the number of escapees
from nearby Bay of Fundy sea-farms has eclipsed the number of wild
fish, whose numbers have declined in reverse proportion. In 1999,
the salmon anemia was present in 14 percent of the escapees found
in the Magaguadavic and, most alarmingly, almost 75 percent of the
wild fish captured by biologists.
</P>
<P>
   In response, researchers have developed new, closed-loop
technologies that replace crude, unreliable sea cages with large
bags that are much more effective in preventing escapees, catching
effluents that currently pollute the ocean floor beneath sea cages,
and may also lessen the spread of diseases like salmon anemia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Responsible, environmentally acceptable aquaculture is not
rocket science, but it's a more expensive proposition than sea
cages,'' said Taylor, whose salmon federation office is situated in
Charlotte County, New Brunswick, where one in every four jobs is in
aquaculture. ``We have to pursue that vigorously, because it's
clearly too late to put the genie back in the bottle.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
