American bald eagle, has run a sanctuary at his parents' farm in
Grafton for birds that have been injured or are no longer wanted.
By his count, Dubacher, 51, cares for 1,700 birds - including 15
eagles, 2 peregrine falcons, and 19 emus - in a maze of greenhouses
and wooden pens. (David Jennings/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- March 11, 2000 -- BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN -- Erick
Barkley, who scored 7 points in St. John's victory in the Big East
semifinals Friday, made a stunning announcement afterward. After
the exhilarating 1-point victory, Barkley, dejected and near tears,
told reporters he was taking a leave of absence. (Chang W. Lee/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) TAMPA, Fla. -- March 11, 2000 -- BBA-YANKS-JETER --
Derek Jeter, the Yankees 25-year-old shortstop, is such a good
hitter that even when fooled, he is capable of hitting a pitch just
above his shoes or off the outside corner and dumping a single into
right field. But he is also apt to swing at a bad pitch and ground
out to second base. If Jeter amassed another 15 seasons at his
current rate of success, he would approach 4,000 hits and 2,000
runs scored. But there is room for improvement. (Barton
Silverman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- March 11, 2000 -- NY-WOODY-CRUSADE-2 --
Woody Allen has made a short film for the Landmarks Preservation
Commission to oppose a new tower in Carnegie Hill, saying it would
ruin the character of the neighborhood, which he has used as a
backdrop in longer works. Allen and the opponents of the project,
who asked him to lend his fame to their fight, say the tower would
leave their low-rise neighborhood feeling uncomfortably like a
high-rise canyon. (Fred R. Conrad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- March 11, 2000 -- NY-WOODY-CRUSADE-1 --
Woody Allen has made a short film for the Landmarks Preservation
Commission to oppose a tower above a Citibank branch in Carnegie
Hill, saying it would ruin the character of the neighborhood, which
he has used as a backdrop in longer works. In his famously nebbishy
voice, Allen used words like ``huge'' and ``aesthetically wrong''
as he described his worries about the building and what it would do
to the community. (Fred R. Conrad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) SEATTLE -- March 11, 2000 -- MCCAIN-VOTERS -- Beyond
their allegiance to Sen. John McCain and a somewhat vague banner of
reform, there seems to be virtually nothing that amounts to a
common bond in his supporters' political views. ``I'm still kind of
shocked at myself,'' Holly Hamilton, left, a high school teacher,
said about her first-ever Republican vote. Troy Miller, a
purchasing agent, center, said ``If I had to vote right now, I
think I'd write in somebody like Pat Paulsen.'' ``My vote's
completely up in the air,'' said Kris Lenning, a phone company
technician. (Peter Yates/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- March 11, 2000 -- IMMIG-EDUC-2 -- Immigrant
youths with limited literacy have been coming to the United States
for centuries. But, for the first time, cities are collecting data
on their numbers, researching their needs and creating programs to
teach them first-grade material in a high school context. Ancelmo
McBean, 16, from Panama, got help with a New York subway map from
Kathleen Sampson in a beginning literacy class in Manhattan.
(Rebecca Cooney/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- March 11, 2000 -- IMMIG-EDUC-1 -- Immigrant
youths with limited literacy have been coming to the United States
for centuries. But, for the first time, cities are collecting data
on their numbers, researching their needs and creating programs to
teach them first-grade material in a high school context. Amina
Simba, left, Ma Bich Ngqc and Liu Weng Fang in a high school
literacy class in Manhattan. (Rebecca Cooney/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) KOSOVSKA MITROVICA, Yugoslavia -- March 11, 2000 --
KOSOVO-DILEMMA -- Washington and NATO are split on strategy for
Mitrovica, now effectively partitioned. Serbs returned home after
visiting a Serbian cemetery in the Albanian section of the city
under United Nations guard. (Andrew Testa/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) ZAMORA, Mexico -- March 11, 2000 -- SUB-MEXICO-POLITICS-2
-- With the Mexican presidential election nearing, ``people are
realizing I can win,'' said Vicente Fox, the presidential candidate
of the National Action Party, of recent advances that give him a
better chance at the post than any other opposition figure since
the Mexican revolution. Fox, a former Coca-Cola executive who
usually wears cowboy boots, was on the campaign trail in the town
of Zamora in Michoacan State. (Wesley Bocxe/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) TARCUATO, Mexico -- March 11, 2000 -- MEXICO-POLITICS-1
-- Vicente Fox Quesada, the presidential candidate of the National
Action Party, has made advances that give him a better chance at
the presidency than any other opposition figure since the Mexican
revolution. Fox addressed voters in Tarcuato, an Indian village in
Michoacan State. (Wesley Bocxe/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- March 11, 2000 -- MANHATTAN-COWBOYS --
Cowboys were in town Friday promoting the new Wrangler Pro Rodeo
Tour, which the sport's business sages believe will push calf
roping, steer wrestling, bull riding and barrel racing into the
entertainment mainstream, following attractions as diverse as stock
car racing, arena football and professional wrestling. Last year,
26 million fans attended the Professional Rodeo Cowboys
Association's 700 sanctioned events. (Ruby Washington/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) FAIRFIELD, Iowa -- March 11, 2000 --
TRAVELING-HABERDASHER-3 -- Tim DeFord, 43, likes to keep the
customer satisfied, but he has to find him first. So this traveling
haberdasher packs up his station wagon and drives from town to Iowa
town. ``People in my business are better off if they don't have a
memory,'' he said, talking about earlier times, when people dressed
to the nines. ``I could put my inventory on the sidewalk with a
sign that says `free' and half the people in the town would walk
right past it.'' (Rodney White/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) FAIRFIELD, Iowa -- March 11, 2000 --
TRAVELING-HABERDASHER-2 -- As Americans have gone to casual attire,
small-town shops offering options for the well-dressed man have
been closing. Leland Gookin examined swatches of fabric as Tim
DeFord, 43, a traveling haberdasher from Fairfield, Iowa, looked
on, hoping to make a sale. Gookin (46 short) proved an indecisive
customer, and ultimately did not buy a sport coat on this visit.
(Rodney White/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) FAIRFIELD, Iowa -- March 11, 2000 --
TRAVELING-HABERDASHER-1 -- Tim DeFord owns Lord's Fine Men's Wear
in Perry, about 30 miles northwest of Des Moines, a store that
would have closed long ago, meeting the fate of so many small-town
shops, if DeFord did not keep his business alive by traveling to
customers in places where men's shops have disappeared. DeFord, 43,
fitted Leland Gookin at his home. (Rodney White/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
