<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4162 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-FLA-PRIMARY0312-COX     03-11 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-PRIMARY0312-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Personal and political issues abound in Florida primary
</P>
<P>
   By Brian E. Crowley
</P>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ In a corner office in suite 417, Jillian
Inmon is working with walking pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel terrible,'' she says in between answering the
constantly ringing phone. Going home is out of the question because
nothing right now is more important to Inmon than making sure that
Texas Gov. George W. Bush wins Florida's 25 electoral votes in
November.
</P>
<P>
   Like her partner in this endeavor, Brett Doster, she is a
political workaholic who worked on Jeb Bush's 1998 campaign for
governor. Doster has been with Bush even longer, cutting his young
political teeth as Bush's personal assistant in 1994 and again in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   For them, the idea of losing Florida to Vice President Al Gore
would be almost the same as losing a family member. If it is true,
and it is, that it is virtually impossible for Bush to lose his
home state of Texas, then it is equally true that for his younger
brother there could be no more dreaded political and personal
defeat than for Gore to win Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Inmon, 31, and Doster, 28 , are the vanguard of the effort here.
They occupy the same offices they used in Jeb Bush's successful
governor's race. On Inmon's desk is a bright yellow folder, with
``JEB'' scrawled across it, standing in the midst of less colorful
folders. Inside, are the constant requests from national news
organizations for interviews with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in the coming campaign is intense, and Gore is letting
it be known he believes he can embarrass the Florida Bush brigade
by winning the Sunshine State. Just to prove his point, Gore won't
spend primary night at home in Tennessee, he's going to be in
Tallahassee Tuesday under the glare of Jeb Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is being guided here by Attorney General Bob Butterworth,
who has become more than the usual token big name state chairman.
He's working it like a field director, said one top Gore official.
</P>
<P>
   Among those working with Butterworth is Karl Koch, a veteran
Democratic strategist who worked for the late Gov. Lawton Chiles
and former Lt. Gov. Buddy MacKay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We absolutely believe we can win Florida,'' said Koch. ``The
campaign would not spend the time it has if that weren't true.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past 12 months, Gore has been to Florida five times, and
Bush has been here three. Gore's count will go up to seven this
week when he comes to Miami tonight, leaves Florida Monday
afternoon and then returns Tuesday evening for a rally in
Tallahassee. While in Miami, Gore is tentatively scheduled to visit
Jackson Memorial Hospital. Bush will make his fourth visit with a
stop today in Plant City to attend the Strawberry Festival.
</P>
<P>
   As the campaign unfolds in Florida, Democrats are going to
portray Bush as a lightweight governor too willing to pander to
extremists in his party when it is politically expedient.
Republicans will tag Gore with the Clinton scandals, suggesting
voters should be weary of the Clinton-Gore show.
</P>
<P>
   While there are abundant political issues that separate the two
candidates, the question of character could be the turning point
for Florida's 1.3 million independent voters who make up 15 percent
of the state's more than 8 million voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you belong to a party, you tend to identify with the
issues that are important to that party,'' said Tre Evers, a
Republican strategist. ``The independents and the undecided voters
are aware of the issues, but in that group you can find people who
are pro-gun and anti-gun who support the same candidate. They seem
to lean more toward the question of character.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the case in 1992, when 20 percent of Florida voters
backed Ross Perot who in the beginning of the campaign was viewed
as a solid, honest, patriotic businessman. As that view unraveled,
Perot's support dropped to 9 percent of the vote in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Independent voters in other state primaries were very supportive
of Republican Sen. John McCain of Arizona and Democrat Bill
Bradley. Polls have suggested the character issue was a major
reason independents supported them.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are voters who usually don't make up their mind until
the final weeks of a campaign,'' said Jim Kane, a political analyst
for the independent Florida Voter, which studies voting trends.
``These also are the voters who help decide elections.''
</P>
<P>
   There are host of other intangibles that will affect the
outcome, from debate performances to excitement that would be
generated if Gore picked U.S. Sen. Bob Graham as his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida has 25 electoral votes, and Al Gore is not going to
just give them to George Bush,'' Koch said. ``Bush will have to
fight for them.''
</P>
<P>
   After finally seeing a doctor, Inmon is feeling a little better,
although she refuses to get the bed rest she was told she needed.
Gore is going to be in Tallahassee, and Inmon vows not to rest
until she is sure that the only trips Gore will be making to
Florida next year will be as a tourist.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
