<SLUG> BC-CHILE-PRESIDENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LEADER ASSUMES POWER IN CHILE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile _ Pledging to improve the free-market economy
while helping the poor, Ricardo Lagos took power Saturday as
Chile's third democratically elected leader since the end of
military rule, and as the first socialist president since Salvador
Allende was overthrown in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Lagos made his name opposing General Augusto Pinochet's military
dictatorship. He faces decisions on whether to curb the influence
of the armed forces and on whether to support efforts to try
Pinochet on human rights charges.
</P>
<P>
   Lagos was handed the presidential red, white, and blue sash by
outgoing President Eduardo Frei in the Pacific port of Valparaiso.
Lagos, an economist who studied at Duke University, then swore in
his Cabinet, which includes several Ivy League-educated
technocrats.
</P>
<P>
   Chile is ranked among Latin America's top economies, but it has
struggled recently because of financial crises in Asia and Latin
America. Much of Lagos's economic platform seeks to continue
Chile's free-market path.
</P>
<P>
   Lagos has also vowed to assist Chile's poor, who make up about
20 percent of the country's 15 million residents _ a low figure for
Latin America, but a sore spot for Chileans who feel left out of
the economic growth during the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Among several inaugural activities, Lagos made a campaign-like
stop in the city of Concepcion and took a ride around working-class
neighborhoods of Santiago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chile has made great strides during the last 15 years to
expand development, telephones, roads and airports, but now we have
to reach even further,'' Lagos said to cheers at the University of
Concepcion. ``Our first objective . . . must be to integrate every
region of Chile to the rest of South America and the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaders from more than 50 countries attended the inauguration,
including a US delegation led by Attorney General Janet Reno. US
officials said they welcomed the new administration as another
healthy sign of consolidating democracy in Chile.
</P>
<P>
   Lagos's narrow victory in a January runoff against a rightist
candidate, Joaquin Lavin, was a milestone. Not since Allende had a
socialist candidate been elected president in Chile.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a decade of democratic politics since the end of
military rule, Chile is still struggling to shake off the memories
of its 17 years under Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
   Isabel Allende, daughter of the late president, attended the
inauguration. ``Obviously, I'm reminded of my father, but I'm
convinced that this will be a very good government and that Chile
will finally strengthen its democracy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lagos was an apprentice of Allende's and a fierce opponent of
the military government, which is believed to have abducted,
tortured, or killed several thousand people. In the late 1980s,
Lagos became a leader of a national campaign to remove Pinochet
from office and return to democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts expect Lagos to be a moderate leader, balancing
economic and social needs while being firm but diplomatic with the
country's armed forces, whose leaders remain loyal to Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the attention on Lagos's new term was stolen with the
return March 4 of Pinochet, who flew home after 16 months of house
arrest in Britain. The former general was allowed to leave Britain
after authorities there declared him unfit on health grounds to
stand trial in Spain for human rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Absent from the inaugural was Pinochet, who secured the title of
senator for life, and with it, immunity from prosecution, as he
prepared to leave office. The general spent the day on a family
estate in the Andean countryside. An appellate judge recommended
last week that Pinochet's immunity be revoked. If it were, he might
face more than 70 lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than focus on the Pinochet controversy, some Chileans
said Saturday that they preferred to look ahead to the Lagos
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is coming into a very complicated situation,'' said Lucia
Boyens, a 28-year-old art gallery worker in the Providencia section
of the capital. ``I wish him well, but the people are going to
demand a lot from him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-00 1831EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
