<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-TEXT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXCERPTS FROM GORE INTERVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
  (With GORE-INTERVIEW) 
(mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Following are excerpts from an interview Saturday with Vice
President Al Gore aboard Air Force II, as recorded by The New York
Times:
</P>
<P>
   Q. How are you going to contrast yourself with Governor Bush?
</P>
<P>
   A. There are so many contrasts that will come out in this
campaign. One is the issue I discussed with Governor Ventura this
morning _ the need for campaign finance reform. I'm still waiting
for Governor Bush's answer on my call to eliminate soft money from
this campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Q. You know he's not going to do that.
</P>
<P>
   A. That's the conventional wisdom. But I think some people are
underestimating how strongly John McCain feels about that and
underestimating the fact that the Republican Party at the
grassroots level doesn't necessarily support Governor Bush's
position on this. The support Senator McCain attracted was in part
fueled by a grassroots desire to get rid of soft money, and it
comes from Republicans as well as independents and Democrats....
</P>
<P>
   Experience is one of the biggest issues in this campaign. And,
frankly, if you look at Governor Bush's economic plan, you have to
wonder whether he has the experience to be president. I mean, you
really have to wonder. He would spend more than a trillion dollars
in excess of the non-Social Security surplus. Not only the entire
surplus, but a trillion dollars more than the surplus. And in John
McCain's words, put the Social Security program at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Now when you see a proposal like that, you have to wonder: Does
Governor Bush have the experience to be president? When you look at
the fact that his tax scheme is much larger than the one that was
proposed by the congressional Republican leadership that was
overwhelmingly rejected by the country. Again you have to wonder,
does George Bush have the experience to be president?
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why not refuse to be part of those soft-money fund-raisers,
just as a symbolic move, if nothing else?
</P>
<P>
   A. I am not going to unilaterally disarm, and I don't think that
anybody who thinks about it for more than two seconds has a problem
understanding that. All he has to do to ban soft money is to say
yes. One syllable, three letters, one word. It's not complicated:
yes, Y-E-S. And then soft money is completely eliminated from this
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   I have learned from my mistakes. Like John McCain, I bring the
passion that comes from personal experience to the battle for
campaign finance reform. And he has not given me any evidence that
he has learned from his mistakes. I think it's a mistake to be
against banning soft money. I think it's a mistake to allow
billionaires to funnel special-interest, secretly funded attack ads
into the last days of the primary election and embrace the message
of those so-called independent expenditures. I think it's a mistake
to bust out of the traditional campaign finance law and raise $70
million with more to come.
</P>
<P>
   And again, that is the reason why he is putting forward this
risky tax scheme that is rejected by the American people but is
strongly supported by his own special-interest, soft-money donors.
If you look at that group _ here's the striking contrast. You talk
to that group, that is their No. 1 priority. You talk to the
American people, that is their lowest priority. In fact, they want
to keep the prosperity going and they don't want to put Social
Security at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What specifically were your mistakes?
</P>
<P>
   A. The '96 campaign, where both parties pushed the limits. I
made a mistake going to that Buddhist temple. I made a mistake in
making telephone calls from my office. And I have learned from
those mistakes. And I am passionate about the need for campaign
finance reform, because so long as there is this current system,
you're going to see the kind of thing that George Bush did in the
New York and Ohio and California primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you have any credibility on this issue? The Republicans
are already raising your ``no controlling legal authority.'' You
can see the ads already. How do you overcome that? And new reports
in the last few days....
</P>
<P>
   A. That's old news.
</P>
<P>
   Q. It's still a political problem.
</P>
<P>
   A. I have acknowledged my mistakes, I have learned from my
mistakes. I have a passion for campaign-finance reform that is
fueled in part because of the pain of those mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Like John McCain, I took from my personal experience a deeper
commitment to the battle for campaign finance reform, and I think
this is the year it's going to happen. They've been writing it off
from the very start, but it is intricately linked to this Bush
risky tax scheme, which would devastate funding for education and
environment and health care. It is closely linked to Bush's record
of creating the worst pollution in America, in the state of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Why do you think that he has made the decisions that lead Texas
to be No. 1 in air pollution, No. 1 in water pollution and No. 1 in
land pollution? It's because of his ties to this old-politics,
special-interest campaign funding.
</P>
<P>
   He would be better off if he made a clean break from it and
joined me in making this campaign the first in American history
where there was no soft money. He would be freer to break from his
past of doing what the polluters want, doing what the fat cats
want, and he would be freer to join in debates and joint town-hall
meetings and start responding to what the American people want.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What about Leon Panetta saying you listened attentively,
there are photographs _ does this trigger your memory?
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't know what is in that particular paper and I can't
comment on something that hasn't been publicly released that I
haven't seen. But I've said previously that I made a mistake in
pressing the limits in '96. I think that we need campaign finance
reform.
</P>
<P>
   Q. When there were lingering questions about Whitewater,
President Clinton called for an independent counsel. Given the
lingering questions about your involvement in the fund-raising
problems, is there any conceivable way you would call for an
independent investigation on this, to reassure the public?
</P>
<P>
   A. (Laughs) This was all reviewed three years ago. You'll have
to decide what he says. But what does he say about the present?
What does he say about the soft money right now? What does he say
about evading the campaign-finance limit, with $70 million, right
now? What does he say about the Wyly secretly financed attack ads
against John McCain?
</P>
<P>
   Q. But he's raising questions about you.
</P>
<P>
   A. I have acknowledged my mistakes in the past, and I am
applying the lessons of those mistakes to a call for change now, so
that this campaign and all future campaigns will be conducted
differently. What is his response to my call for eliminating soft
money from his campaign? What is his response to my call for
eliminating the 30-second and 60-second ads and debating twice a
week? What is his response to my call to join me in joint town hall
meetings before undecided voters?
</P>
<P>
   Q. You're talking with the passion of a convert....
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, that's right.
</P>
<P>
   Q. ...and usually a convert has had some kind of epiphany or
experience that prompts the conversion.
</P>
<P>
   A. The pain of making the mistake in '96. Bear in mind, in my
first term in Congress, I called for full public financing of all
federal elections. I sponsored or co-sponsored a dozen campaign
finance reform bills over my career. I supported the
McCain-Feingold bill in the Congress.
</P>
<P>
   I had a passion for this before, but the passion became stronger
in the wake of the '96 campaign, when both parties pushed the
limits. I don't want to see any other campaigns conducted like
that.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What is the ``pain'' that you felt?
</P>
<P>
   A. Making mistakes and acknowledging them. When you acknowledge
a mistake, that is an opportunity for learning and growth. And that
is what I experienced.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
