<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4169 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-POPE-APOLOGY-BOS &LR;      03-11 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-APOLOGY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE'S LENTEN MESSAGE TO SET TONE FOR MIDEAST PILGRIMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Pope John Paul II will deliver Sunday what Vatican
officials say will be a dramatic and sweeping apology for a long
list of Roman Catholic sins that are as ancient as the Crusades and
as modern as the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   This Lenten message of repentance comes a week before the pope
makes a historic pilgrimage to the Holy Land, a personal journey
intended as the culmination of his papacy and his drive for
dialogue and reconciliation among Judaism, Christianity, and Islam.
The message will have many here listening intently to see whether
he goes beyond previous apologies for the individual actions of
Catholics to address the institutional role of the church.
</P>
<P>
   The pope's journey, threading through modern-day Jordan, the
West Bank, and Israel, will follow the path of the historical Jesus
from his birth in Bethlehem, to his childhood in Nazareth, his
ministry in Galilee, and his crucifixion in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   But along this path, the pope will also walk a land where
Crusader armies slaughtered Muslims, Jews, and Eastern Orthodox
Christians, pillaging their communities in the name of reclaiming
the Holy Land for the Roman Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul will be the first pope in 36 years to set foot in
Israel, a nation founded on the ashes of the Nazi Holocaust, and to
meet with people who survived its horrors. One of them will be
Israel's chief rabbi, Yisrael Lau, who was interned in a forced
labor camp and who lost most of his family in death camps.
</P>
<P>
   The two men share an intimate bond to a terrible past. Both were
born in villages near Krakow, Poland, where about 1 million Jews
were killed in the Nazi camps. After World War II, Karol Wojtyla
became the bishop of Krakow, who was made pope.
</P>
<P>
   The pope has chosen the powerful and haunting setting of Yad
Vashem, Israel's Holocaust memorial, to deliver a speech for the
March 20-26 trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is his initiative to deliver a speech at Yad Vashem, to
speak of forgiveness'' Lau said. ``It is the appropriate place and
time for a man who faced the Holocaust with his very own eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Lau has repeatedly praised the pontiff's efforts at
Jewish-Catholic reconciliation and his statements that Judaism is
the ``elder brother'' of Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting with reporters, Lau said this pope and Pope John
XXIII, who launched a reexamination of Roman Catholic doctrine in
the early 1960s, ``sympathize with the tragedy of the Jewish people
during the Holocaust more than any other leader in Europe, at least
in the last century.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Catholic officials call Nazism a ``pagan ideology,''
the church has expressed regret for Catholic teachings that may
have influenced ``anti-Jewish prejudices embedded in some Christian
minds and hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Lau said, the pope's repeated expressions of sorrow for
the acts of individual Catholics _ prominently in the landmark 1998
document ``We Remember: A Reflection on the Shoah'' _ fall well
short of a full recognition of the church's responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Lau and others have said, the church must examine
the role played by Pope Pius XII, who has been criticized by some
historians for his near silence, some say complicity, in the
Holocaust. That history, and the possibility that Pius XII may be
canonized, have caused outrage in Israel and deep divisions in the
Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is impossible to correct a crime of the past without any
mention, for example, of Pius XII when he stood on the blood of the
victims and did not say a word,'' Lau said.
</P>
<P>
   It is with these thoughts in mind that Lau and others will
listen Sunday as the frail, 79-year-old pontiff, if all goes as
expected, drops to his knees at St. Peter's Basilica in Rome for
the Day of Pardon Mass. In his homily, he is expected to pray for
20 centuries of Catholics' ``faults of the past,'' including
silence on slavery, oppression of women, doctrinal antipathy to
Jews, and inhumanity toward those tortured and killed during the
Inquisition's search for heretics.
</P>
<P>
   The text of the homily had not been released as of Saturday, but
its outline, Vatican officials said, was laid out in a 32-page
document prepared by an international group of Catholic theologians
and released last week in Paris to mark the beginning of Lent.
</P>
<P>
   Lent, the 40-day period of contemplation and repentance leading
to the celebration of Christ's resurrection at Easter, began
Wednesday. But the pope has said this entire ``Jubilee Year,''
which also marks 2,000 years of Christianity, should be devoted to
reflection on the past and a sense of where the church will go as
it begins its third millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Michael McGarry, a Paulist priest and head of the
Vatican's Tantur Ecumenical Institute in Jerusalem, said the pope
is continuing the process begun by the Second Vatican Council
convened by Pope John XXIII, when ``the church set out to change
the direction of how it saw itself and how we see others.''
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic doctrine until then _ that Jews were responsible
for the death of Jesus _ was ``the linchpin of anti-Semitism,''
McGarry noted.
</P>
<P>
   Building on that step, he said, John Paul II has undertaken a
revolutionary transformation of the relationship between Catholics
and Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``This pope has done more for Catholic-Jewish relations than the
church had done in the previous 2,000 years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although he stressed that the pope's trip to the Holy Land is a
spiritual pilgrimage, McGarry said that it is also a culmination of
John Paul II's work to heal the wounds between Catholicism and
Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi David Rosen, director of the Anti-Defamation League in
Jerusalem and a theologian who has met with the pope to shape the
emerging dialogue between the two faiths, agreed. ``This creates a
new era, a new paradigm shift in the way the Catholic Church views
Judaism,'' the rabbi said.
</P>
<P>
   The pope's efforts to come to terms with past sins began at
least five years ago when he announced his intention to make the
pilgrimage that begins March 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like five years of Yom Kippur,'' said Ron Kronish,
director of the Interreligious Coordinating Council in Jerusalem,
referring to the Jewish day of atonement. ``This is a very
significant development in Catholic-Jewish relations. It is a
genuine spirit of repentance.''
</P>
<P>
   A Gallup poll commissioned by Kronish's council found that more
than 60 percent of Israeli adults view the trip positively and only
12 percent see it negatively.
</P>
<P>
   Some extremist elements in the ultraorthodox Jewish community
have publicly protested the visit, however, and in some quarters of
Jerusalem there are posters calling the pope an ``enemy of the
Jews.'' Many other Israelis seem largely indifferent to the event
but view it as an opportunity to promote interfaith dialogue and
understanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of European Jews who came to Israel out of the
context of the Holocaust will have a hard time with it,'' Kronish
said. ``But the majority of Israel and Jews worldwide can and
should accept the church's efforts and say, `Hey, this is something
good, and a good way to move forward.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
