<P>
   BIG12-TOURNEY: KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Big 12 basketball
tournament has been something that everyone in Kansas City took for
granted as a local mainstay. After next year, it will be taking a
turn in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   By RANDY COVITZ and BLAIR KERKHOFF. 1,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   EDISON-SCHOOLS: KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Kansas City school
Superintendent Benjamin Demps Jr. wants the private sector to take
over more of the district's worst-performing schools to improve
achievement and compete with charter schools. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the school board approves, the move would push the district
further into one of the most controversial trends in education.
Proponents believe that private-management companies, compelled by
competition and a sharp focus on the bottom line, will bring to
public schools the efficiencies of free markets. By squeezing
administrative costs and using economies of scale, they say they
can spend more in the classroom and still pocket a profit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By ERIC PALMER and PHILLIP O'CONNOR, 1,500 words. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FISHER-BOWLING: LAWRENCE, Kan. _ Larry Woydziak admits he isn't
much of a bowler. A recent score of 87 out of 300 confirms that. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So why is he a minor celebrity when he rolls into some Kansas
town, walks into the bowling alley, and steps up throw his
occasional gutter ball? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Larry Woydziak, 45, a Lawrence Fire Department captain with 22
years of service, is on a quixotic quest: He wants to send the ball
he bought for $1.95 at a garage sale spinning down the lane in
every Kansas county that has a bowling alley. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By JIM FISHER. 1,000 words.
</P>
