<SLUG> BC-GORE-VENTURA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE DISCUSSES REFORM WITH VENTURA 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also GORE-INTERVIEW) 
(mk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ They looked like twins, in their blue jeans,
cowboy boots and black shirts. But Vice President Al Gore pointed
out the big difference between them _ Gov. Jesse Ventura's boots
were tan ostrich and Gore's were black leather. The governor said
the ostrich camouflaged the dirt.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said, ``That makes them cooler.''
</P>
<P>
   There was another difference, too. Ventura is widely perceived
as a legitimate critic of the campaign finance system, one that has
embroiled the vice president in controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he wanted to meet with the famously independent
governor not to seek his endorsement but to talk about how to
overhaul the campaign finance system.
</P>
<P>
   And he was no doubt hoping that some of the luster that Ventura
_ as well as Sen. John McCain of Arizona and former Sen. Bill
Bradley _ brought to the issue would rub off on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to raise that banner higher,'' Gore told reporters.
``Not only because of the obvious political reason that I want to
give a home for those voters who were strongly supporting Senator
McCain and Senator Bradley because of that issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I acknowledge that's part of what's going on here. But also
because I believe in it.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, the Minnesota governor said he would give a pass
to the vice president on the issue, even though Gore narrowly
escaped being the subject of an independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to play within the game,'' Ventura said. ``You
can't really criticize someone for playing within the set of rules
that you got to play the game within.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-00 1906EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000311.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4177 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKC-AMERICA-EAST-NYT &LR;      03-11 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-AMERICA-EAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOFSTRA WINS SPOT IN NCAA TOURNEY BY BEATING DELAWARE, 76-69 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RON DICKER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ They began the game as tense as an archery
bow. They loosened up when the pressure was at its greatest. And
then the Flying Dutchmen of Hofstra celebrated.
</P>
<P>
   It was just your usual, every-23-years event. Hofstra (24-6)
earned an automatic bid to the NCAA men's basketball tournament
Saturday by holding off Delaware, 76-69, in the America East
tournament championship game before 5,124 screaming fans at a
packed Hofstra Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Students rushing the court nearly engulfed the Dutchmen as the
buzzer sounded. And the player most responsible for getting them
there, Speedy Claxton, who was named the tournament's outstanding
player, stood on top of the scorer's table to take in the
adulation.
</P>
<P>
   Claxton earned it. He had 24 points, eight assists and seven
rebounds. He carried the cold-shooting Dutchmen on his
5-foot-11-inch frame in the first half, then nurtured them through
an 8-point deficit early in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the perfect way to go out,'' Claxton said. ``I've had
a great career here. I can leave here happy, knowing I've
accomplished what I needed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Claxton was not alone, though. Norman Richardson, the silky
forward who has so often turned in big performances in big games,
overcame his own early cold shooting to notch 26 points _ 20 in the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   The offense stalled for one agonizing stretch before Hofstra's
coach, Jay Wright, commanded his team to get Richardson the ball.
Richardson lighted up with confidence as the feeds started coming
and the net began rippling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't imagine it would be this exciting,'' Richardson said.
``This is the best feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Gittens put Hofstra ahead for good, 67-66, with a free
throw at the 3-minute 32-second mark. Gittens' burst to the basket
drew a fifth foul from Delaware's best player, Mike Pegues, who
scored 19 points.
</P>
<P>
   Gittens already had done his most important work on defense,
limiting Pegues to one measly left-handed scoop shot during the
Dutchmen's comeback from a 49-41 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to to stay in front of him and outwork him,''
Gittens said.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson scored 7 points and Claxton 5 points in a 12-2 surge
that vaulted Hofstra in front, 64-59. Delaware (24-7) tied the
score at 66-66 on Billy Wells' 3-pointer before the Dutchmen went
ahead for good to end Delaware's two-year reign as the conference's
representative in the NCAA field of 64.
</P>
<P>
   ``The better team won today,'' Pegues said.
</P>
<P>
   Without Pegues, the Blue Hens did not have the firepower to
catch Hofstra in the final minutes. They closed to within a point
once on a free throw by Wells (13 points), but Claxton responded
with a darting layup and then flicked a pass to Danny Walker for an
easier layup to put Hofstra up, 72-67, with 46 seconds to go.
</P>
<P>
   As the final seconds ticked off, Claxton thought, ``Finally.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright, who has built Hofstra from an also-ran into a contender
in six years, said he felt relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that if we didn't win this game, people would say we
can't win the big game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And the crowd, which had seen Hofstra win 25 straight less
significant games on its home floor, truly enjoyed No. 26.
</P>
<P>
   This was not a made-for-TV celebration. Students and alumni had
a lot of time to make up for, being followers of the little school
that couldn't. Now that the little school could, folks were seizing
the moment. Fans lingered on the court for more than a half-hour
with players and coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Hours earlier, at the start of the game, the Flying Dutchmen had
oozed tension, especially when they were shooting. Hofstra made
only four of its first 12 field-goal attempts. At times they stood
around on offense, waiting for Claxton to beat his man off the
dribble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't worried,'' Claxton said. ``It was a matter of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, the jubilant Dutchmen were cutting down the net,
and Claxton got the last loop.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a dream,'' Wright said. ``I know Speedy Claxton would
have been crushed if he had left without going to the tournament.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
