   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   GORE _ WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore believes the turning
point in his presidential campaign was his decision last summer to
halt his constant calculations about what was best for the Clinton
administration and to start speaking ``straight from the heart.''
``I made a big change in my priorities,'' Gore said during an
interview in which he took stock of his bumpy but successful
campaign for the Democratic nomination and his general election
strategy against
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas. (Shepard, Cox News Service).
Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-PRIMARY _ Tablesetter for Tuesday's Florida primary. Length
and interest depend on the outcome of the Super Tuesday votes.
(Crowley, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-STRATEGY _ WASHINGTON _ Gov. George W. Bush, shifting into
general-election gear, is exploring ways to expand his Austin
campaign operation even as he prepares to install a loyalist at the
Republican National Committee in coming weeks. A senior Bush aide
said Friday that the campaign will install a, ``general chairman
type, obviously somebody senior and somebody close to the
governor,'' at the RNC, before turning its attention to the Austin
staff. The aide said such a move is customary for the presumptive
nominee, but declined to say whom who the RNC pick will be. (Heath,
Austin American-Statesman). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS _ WASHINGTON _ Check the mailbox, there's a form in your
future and it could change your life. Every 10 years, the
government conducts a head count of America. It may sound like a
dull exercise, but the results help determine how your are
represented in Congress and the state legislature and how federal
and state money is distributed to your city and school district.
(Holmes, Cox News Service). MOVED TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
