<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-OLIGARCHS _ MOSCOW _ While experts agree that Russia's
popular acting President Vladimir Putin could be the runaway winner
in this month's presidential elections, many experts warn that none
of his efforts will matter unless he does what his predecessor
Boris Yeltsin failed to do: rein in Russia's oligarchs. Reform or
no reform, they say that Russia's woes will continue while the
robber barons retain their power. But while Putin would certainly
win about 100 percent of the vote if he did crack down on these
moneyed plutocrats, he would lose their financial backing _ crucial
to his success. (Coke, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH box attached to end of story.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Friday, March 10.
</P>
<P>
   COX-LATAM-MCKAY _ WASHINGTON _ The view from Buddy MacKay's
office is of the White House. Behind his desk is a map stretching
from the southern United States to the tip of South America. This
is MacKay's world. For the past year, the former Florida governor
has been President Clinton's special envoy to the Americas _ a
territory covering the entire Western Hemisphere, including Canada.
The job has taken MacKay, 66, to an average of two countries a
month _ listening to their leaders and communicating their problems
on at least a weekly basis to the president of the United States.
Sometimes, communications break down. (Lipman, Cox News Service).
WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Wed., March 8, in (i) International and (w)
Washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-WITNESSES _ ATLANTA _ We'll start with a 10-inch intro,
then run in vignette style, the eight witness accounts we have of
what happened in the early morning hours after the Super Bowl when
two men were murderd in a popular Atlanta entertainment district
and Batimore Ravens' All-Pro lnebacker Ray Lewis was subsequently
charged in their slayings. Most statements give Lewis a small, if
any role in the killings. (Staff, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
70.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (s) Sports categories.
</P>
<P>
   STARGAZERS _ GREEN BANK, W. Va. _ In isolated Deer Creek Valley,
where folks traditionally rely upon moonshine and timber for their
livelihoods, construction crews are nearing completion of a
gigantic radio telescope with an ``ear'' bigger a football field.
Weighing 17 million pounds and rolling on a 25-foot-thick
foundation of reinforced concrete, the Green Bank telescope will be
``one of the largest moving things on Earth,'' its builders
promise. Since 1958, an astronomy observatory has been located at
Green Bank precisely because it is so remote and surrounded by
mountains that block out all radio interference. About 130
scientists and engineers live near the rural community of Green
Bank, which is 100 miles from the nearest town. The scant populace
is an interesting mix of brainy stargazers and their down-to-earth
backwoods neighbors. (Dart, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Monday in (a) national and (l) lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   RACE-FIRSTPERSON _ WASHINGTON _ Growing up in Liberia, I was not
aware of the racism that plagued America, even though my country
was founded by freed slaves from the United States. It wasn't until
I came to the United States at age 10 that I learned about slavery
and racism in America, which was a shock at first. I also heard the
word nigger for the first time when I got here. My recent visit to
Selma, Ala., gave me a new perspective on the civil rights movement
and American race relations. (Ismail Turay Jr./Cox News Service).
20. WITH MUG SHOT. MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   US-TAIWAN _ WASHINGTON _ (Tentative). Since the United States
sent warships into the Taiwans Straits four years ago to quell a
potentially fiery situation between China and Taiwan _ and show our
support for the latter _ the Clinton administration has
incrementally backed away from its iron-glove handling of relations
with the mainland. So much so, that many Asia observers are now
asking ``Would the United States wage a war a world away to save
Taipei from an aggressive Beijing seeking to re-unify China _ at
all costs? We poll the administration, as well as the presidential
candidates. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Tentatively moving Fri., March 10, in (i) International and
(k) Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ After just about every notorious new, senseless
shooting spree _ most recently the death of that six-year-old girl,
those five shot by a Pennsylvania man in anti-white rage _ my wife
asks how many more must die before we get sensible gun control. The
question is only rhetorical, of course. It has to be because the
answer is already in: the numbers do not matter because the powers
resisting gun control simply don't care about them. There is no
elusive, magical body count out there that will trip legislative
action.(Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers.)
MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ This appears to be the Year of the Apology.
Seemingly, everyone is apologizing for something or being asked to
apologize. (Howard Kleinberg is a columnist for Cox News Service.)
MOVES THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   MURRAY-COLUMN _ LUFKIN, Texas _ I was coming out of a cafe the
other morning when a fellow came up out of nowhere, introduced
himself and, allowing that he was a conservative and knowing I was
a liberal, proceeded to tell me how he felt about gun control.
Truth is, I am not so much a liberal on all subjects. I am very
conservative, for instance, about discussing such things as gun
control in a cafe parking lot with somebody who has just introduced
himself. (Murray, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ (Andy Glass is a columnist for Cox News Service
in the Washington bureau.) MOVES THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   LAPIDUS-PROFILE _ MIAMI BEACH _ Profile of Miami architect
Morris Lapidus. When he retired in 1982, Lapidus was so bitter
about his rejection by critics and peers that he threw away most of
his drawings and blueprints. He was widely ridiculed for his
kitschy resort hotels; one wit said they gave her ``the
Fountainblues.'' Well, she's dead and he ain't. At 97, Lapidus is
back in vogue, his curvy, voluptuous designs all over the place.
And he's working again; a restaurant of his design just opened in
South Beach. We visit him there, in Lapidusland, and tour the
fantasy world he created as we look back on a life that began in
Russian poverty and came to embody American pizazz. (Auchmutey,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 80. WITH PHOTOS and LAYOUTS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TEENMUSIC-STYLES _ Pop princesses' racy lyrics and revealing
clothes have American girls shopping and some of their parents
fretting. (Allmon, Waco Tribune-Herald). 40. WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   AGING-PARENTS _ Watching your parents get old is never easy.
Caring for a sick, elderly mom or dad is even tougher. But it's a
grim _ often debilitating _ situation more baby boomers are forced
to face. In fact, Time magazine recently noted that 33 million
Americans _ an unprecedented 13 percent of the population _ are
over 65. (Thompson, Palm Beach Post). 30. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BINGO _ Who didn't really believe this was just a weird fad that
would fade? Instead, almost every fund-raising group has a bingo
night. Players come armed with their own blotters, and bingo has
spawned a quirky little subculture all its own. (Sauer, Grand
Junction Daily Sentinel). 30. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BINGO-LORE _ Bingo lore side to go with bingo story. (Sauer,
Grand Junction Daily Sentinel). 10. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   STARGAZERS _ GREEN BANK, W. Va. _ In isolated Deer Creek Valley,
where folks traditionally rely upon moonshine and timber for their
livelihoods, construction crews are nearing completion of a
gigantic radio telescope with an ``ear'' bigger a football field.
Weighing 17 million pounds and rolling on a 25-foot-thick
foundation of reinforced concrete, the Green Bank telescope will be
``one of the largest moving things on Earth,'' its builders
promise. Since 1958, an astronomy observatory has been located at
Green Bank precisely because it is so remote and surrounded by
