<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-GORDON0312-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With a new crew and altered car, Jeff Gordon's results have been
subpar
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The smiles were broad and bright Friday as Jeff Gordon
eased the No. 24 Chevrolet into the garage stall after his
qualifying run at Atlanta Motor Speedway. That sudden breeze was
the collective sigh of his beleaguered race crew.
</P>
<P>
   After two humdrum practice sessions (23rd and 27th fastest), the
mood of Gordon's team changed quickly, like the bright sunshine
that chased away the gray storm clouds an hour earlier.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so it was only qualifying, and Gordon isn't on the pole for
today's Cracker Barrel 500, but his seventh-fastest lap of 191.947
mph puts him close enough to challenge on a track where he's won
two of the past three races.
</P>
<P>
   A new pit crew, new crew chief and new body style on the Chevy
have conspired to rob Gordon of his old results. He's off to an
uncharacteristically dreadful start.
</P>
<P>
   Misfortune has been riding shotgun in the 24. An oil leak early
in the Daytona 500 dropped Gordon four laps down, and he finished
34th. A week later at Rockingham, he lost two laps early and
finished 10th. At Las Vegas last week, Gordon wrecked in practice,
then lost a lap when he made a long pit stop for an adjustment
early in the race and finished 28th.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon has gone eight races without a top-five finish, the
longest drought of his 226-race Winston Cup career.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't take things for granted,'' Gordon said. ``We can't
expect to just go out there and be the best every weekend.
Certainly, the last couple of weeks have been humbling enough to
prove that to us. I think that's going to make us stronger in the
long run.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the pressure is falling on Robbie Loomis, who has
replaced Ray Evernham as Gordon's crew chief. ``I'm not sleeping,''
Loomis said. He learned about pressure working for a bona fide
legend, Richard Petty.
</P>
<P>
   ``On days when you weren't getting your job done,'' Loomis said,
``that cowboy hat and sunglasses made him look like he was about
100 feet tall.''
</P>
<P>
   Surely, no one in the Cup garage believes the 24 team's best
days are over because of three bad races.
</P>
<P>
   ``It must be every driver's dream to be in a position where you
lose three races and everybody is starting to ask questions about
`whatever happened to...?''' said Kenny Irwin, driver of the No. 42
Chevy. ``They might be having a little bit of a slump, but it's not
over.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an old saying _ the sun don't shine on a hound dog all
the time,'' Michael Waltrip said. ``They'll be back. It's like one
of those Halloween movies. You might think the guy is dead, but he
always comes back, usually when you least expect it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's way too early to declare Gordon dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three races is pretty early, no matter how horrible those
three races are,'' Gordon said. ``Certainly, the way we're looking
at it, we've got some steps to take before we start saying we're
going to win the championship. Finishing races competitively is
what's on our mind right now, not what we've done the last couple
of weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon said he is leaning on lessons learned in his early racing
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't know times when I've struggled. They all
think I've just won races and been competing for a championship
every year. There have been times when I've struggled, when I lost
a ride, when I was wrecking every weekend and wasn't going fast
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   It happened when Gordon was 18, racing sprint cars. And how
would you feel being the guy who fired Gordon, who grew up to be a
three-time Winston Cup champion?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he feels good because I was costing him a lot of
money,'' Gordon said. ``The greatest thing that happened to me is I
started running USAC (midgets) after that and started winning right
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went through a period of time where I (was thinking), man, I
don't know how to drive this race car. It's me. I went on to do
some pretty great things and realized when the car was right, when
I could tell them to do the right things, that we won races. That's
the thing I've always got to remember: a lot of getting that car
right is a lot of what I say and how I say it.''
</P>
<P>
   But it hasn't been all communication.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm certainly not happy with the finishes that I've had,''
Gordon said. ``I think we all are a little bit frustrated, some
with where we're finishing, some with this new Monte Carlo. We were
hoping and expecting it to be a lot better than it was.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing we've been lacking is finding the setup,''
Loomis said. ``Stuff has changed a lot with this new body style. We
really haven't found the setups that we need under it. The hard
part right now is we're having to test when we're under the clock.
We've got 10 races in a row. We're doing a lot of our development
from week to week.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Gordon is trying to put on a positive spin. ``I
don't think it's a bad thing to go through what we're going through
right now,'' he said. ``I've had it pretty good, things have gone
really well for us on this team. I think this will truly tell us
what we're really made of. That's not a bad thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
