<SLUG> BC-BIG12-TOURNEY-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY LOOKS FOR LONG-TERM BASKETBALL TOURNAMENT SOLUTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BLAIR KERKHOFF and RANDY COVITZ  
c. 2000 Kansas City Star
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The human history of the Big 12 men's
basketball tournament sits together in Section 106, about halfway
up on the aisle.
</P>
<P>
   Four women, the youngest 77 years old, take in every moment of
action at Kemper Arena, even though their favorite team, Kansas
State, lost in the opening round.
</P>
<P>
   Fran Schletzbaum, Jane Weingart and Jean Householder of
Atchison, Kan., and Mary Harmon of Lawrence, Kan., have attended
all 24 Big Eight or Big 12 tournaments at Kemper. Householder's
days as a spectator date to Big Seven tournaments in Municipal
Auditorium and even NAIA tournaments in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years in Kemper, their seats have been moved from
midcourt to the front row behind the baseline to their current
location, halfway up the end zone. That last shift occurred when
the Big 12 was formed four years ago and it reassigned ticket
holders. Fans who didn't see the women in their familiar seats and
saw them with binoculars made it a point to stop by.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came up and told us they remembered us sitting there and
wondered if they'd see us again this year,'' Schletzbaum said.
``That was nice of them. We wouldn't think of not coming to the
tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   But the group will have a difficult decision in two years. After
the 2002 men's tournament at Kemper and women's tournament at
Municipal, the events move to Dallas. For the first time since
World War II, Kansas City will be without a tournament that did not
start with ``Big'' and end in ``Six,'' ``Seven,'' ``Eight'' or
``12.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be as if a longstanding relationship is over but the
person still sits next to you in class. Can we still be friends?
</P>
<P>
   That is where Kansas City and the Big 12 tournament find
themselves this weekend. The breakup was one-sided, with the
conference making the announcement last October. The tournament
returns to Kansas City in 2005, but after that, no rotation has
been set. Cities such as Oklahoma City and San Antonio are expected
to make pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City is already thinking beyond 2005. Maybe not planning,
but thinking. Renovating Kemper some more, re-inventing the West
Bottoms and getting serious about a new arena are all ideas
expressed by city leaders in this year's tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a wonderful run with the Big Eight and Big 12,''
said Bill Nelson, retiring president of the Bank of America Kansas
City region and a civic leader. ``We didn't get this by birthright.
We need to compete and earn it.''
</P>
<P>
   For most of basketball's history, Kansas City did not have to
worry about its future as a tournament town. With events that date
to the days of former University of Kansas professor James
Naismith, Kansas City was a major basketball destination.
</P>
<P>
   A world championship was staged in Kansas City in 1905. An
original Olympic qualifying tournament in 1936. And the second NCAA
championship in 1940 financially salvaged what has become the
organization's crown jewel, the NCAA Tournament. Kansas City has
been home to more Final Fours and NCAA Tournament games than any
other city. Kansas City's place in basketball lore is secure.
</P>
<P>
   But a building that has not kept up with the times and an
expanded conference have put an end to what had once seemed an
infinite tournament time line.
</P>
<P>
   Kemper Arena opened in 1974 and sits in the largely undeveloped
West Bottoms. When the men's tournament moves to Dallas, it will
operate in the new American Airlines Arena, complete with the
amenities of most modern structures and located near the city's
trendy West End.
</P>
<P>
   ``To a fan, patron amenities are sometimes more important than
the caliber of play,'' said Chris Plonsky, Texas senior associate
athletic director. ``During the Big Eight days, when the caliber of
play was fantastic, people cared about coming and seeing three days
of great ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things have changed. The discretionary sports fan with his
corporate ticket wants more.''
</P>
<P>
   Things that Kemper does not provide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wider concourses, wider seats, cup holders are the type of
amenities people are getting in the major-city new arenas,'' said
Tim Allen, Big 12 associate commissioner. ``If you're a fan intent
on watching basketball, you may overlook them, but those are things
people are starting to take into consideration more and more.''
</P>
<P>
   Those amenities are or will be available in Dallas, the new
arena in Oklahoma City and in every other major city in the Big 12
that has an eye on playing host to the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to show that kind of progress as this event
goes to Dallas, because the new arena in Dallas will be a
spectacular arena, one that our schools will be impressed with,''
said Kevin Weiberg, Big 12 commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   A new arena for Kansas City is a never-ending subject. But
without a major-league sports tenant, the city struggles with
feasibility and need.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kemper is great for now,'' said Nelson, a proponent of
building a new arena. ``But we need to think in terms of our
competition for conventions. We're told over and over again that
major conventions are looking for a major gathering hall and an
arena that would fill that need with a capacity to seat 18,000 to
20,000 people.''
</P>
<P>
   But new arenas, at least the ones in NBA cities, cost more than
$100 million, although the new arena in Oklahoma City, expected to
open in 2001, cost $82 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take a lot of money and fortitude,'' said Gil
Bourk, chairman of the Kansas City Organizing Committee, which
works with the Big 12 host committee. ``No one has been able to
prove to me that it makes sense.'' (MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-00 1924EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000311.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4185 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-BIG12-TOURNEY-2ND-TAK     03-11 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIG12-TOURNEY-2ND-TAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 KANSAS CITY, Mo.: that it makes sense.''  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Big 12 says it is not forcing the issue. The league,
however, requested and received improvements to Kemper and
Municipal four years ago when the Big 12 was formed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conference does not want to be put in a position of
telling Kansas City, `Build a new building or else,''' Allen said.
``That's a decision that the community has to make. The real
question is, can the community afford not to build a new
building?''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Gray, president of the Greater Kansas City Sports
Commission, said the city should strengthen its position by looking
beyond any improvements to Kemper.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing other communities have is an entertainment
district,'' Gray said. ``There's a lot of land by Kemper.''
</P>
<P>
   And a plan to develop it. Bill Haw, president of National Farms
Inc., owns the Livestock Exchange Building and 25 acres around it
at the West Bottoms. He is talking about major development and
multilevel parking in the area in hopes of being able to ``create a
hospitable, festival atmosphere around the Kemper.''
</P>
<P>
   But all the improvements will not change the notion that the
tournament needs to move around for competitive balance. Travel is
more difficult for the distant Texas schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't discount the people to whom it means the most, the
players and coaches,'' Plonsky said. ``It's a flat-out competitive
issue. That's been lost in the discussion. People point south and
say people don't care about basketball in Texas. That's not true.
It has to be given a chance to be seen in other parts of the
conference. Like football.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yes, football. Kansas City is losing the basketball events
after 2002, but in 2001 the city will hold the championship
football game and basketball tournaments. The city has little
college football tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the economics of football and all the
benefits to the community...you're talking about 80,000 fans,
national television and all that,'' said Gray. ``If we get into the
position of having football and or basketball every year, that's a
huge victory for this community.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as the Big 12 sees cultivating basketball in Texas as being
a big victory for the conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is going to help this conference more than a strong
fan base in our largest state,'' Allen said. ``If Baylor fans go to
the tournament in Dallas and have a good experience, that's a
tremendous marketing tool for them and the entire conference. Right
now, we're marketing our product in one city.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's a city, mind you, that many think cannot be topped as a
tournament site. The tournament historically has rivaled others at
the gate, and this year's men's and women's events could be the
best from a competitive standpoint. Six men's teams are hopeful of
NCAA Tournament bids, which would be a league record. The women
also are making a push for six bids, which would tie the number
they got in the conference's first season.
</P>
<P>
   The men sold out in advance for the first time since the
inaugural tournament in 1997, thanks to a new policy that allowed
Chiefs season-ticket holders to buy tickets returned by the
schools.
</P>
<P>
   As a bonus, Iowa State, whose fans traditionally follow the
basketball team in great numbers, has the top-seeded teams in both
tournaments. As many as 5,000 fans have come to Kansas City to see
the Cyclones play. If they had their druthers, they'd play here
every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not happy the tournament is moving,'' said Bill Fennelly,
Cyclones women's coach. ``People take vacations in Ames (Iowa
State's home) and come to the tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Won't they vacation in Dallas or elsewhere?
</P>
<P>
   ``They will,'' Fennelly said. ``But we'll have people who jumped
in the car Saturday morning and said, `What the heck, let's go
watch the game (in Kansas City).' You can't say, `What the heck,
let's go watch the game in Dallas.' Not unless you have a private
plane.''
</P>
<P>
   In three years, however, David and Joy Oates, Texas Tech fans
from Brownsfield, Texas, will like the tournament's proximity to
their home.
</P>
<P>
   Joy Oates, while at the women's tournament at Municipal, said:
``Dallas has so many people who graduated from the Texas schools
that they'll support it.''
</P>
<P>
   Support doesn't naturally mean good atmosphere. Missouri coach
Quin Snyder, who played and coached at Duke, remembered an electric
feeling when the Atlantic Coast Conference tournament was in the
hoops-frenzied cities of Charlotte and Greensboro, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when it moved to Atlanta or Landover, Maryland, the
feeling wasn't the same,'' Snyder said. ``It lost something.''
</P>
<P>
   That feeling has never been a problem in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you come to Kansas City, you feel like you're coming to a
special event,'' Weiberg said. ``From the time you step out of the
airport _ banners, signs. You get a feeling the city is focused on
the event. That will be a great challenge for a city like Dallas.
(It) doesn't have a history of putting that kind of focus on a
single event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's possible to grow that kind of interest. I look at
the success of the (Dallas Stars' NHL) hockey franchise as an
example of how interest can be generated, something that folks
thought wouldn't draw that much support.''
</P>
<P>
   Will the women in Section 106 go to Dallas?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're thinking about it,'' Householder said. ``We haven't made
up our minds, and we have plenty of time to decide. It is
basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   (30)
</P>
</TEXT>
