<HEADER>
A4186 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-FISHER-BOWLING-KAN &LR;      03-11 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHER-BOWLING-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER KANSAS TOWN MEANS ANOTHER BOWLING ALLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM FISHER  
c. 2000 Kansas City Star LAWRENCE, Kan. _ Larry Woydziak admits he
isn't much of a bowler. A recent score of 87 out of 300 confirms
that.
<TEXT>
<P>
   So why is he a minor celebrity when he rolls into some Kansas
town, walks into the bowling alley and steps up to throw his
occasional gutter ball?
</P>
<P>
   Woydziak, 45, a Lawrence Fire Department captain with 22 years
of service, is on a quixotic quest: He wants to send the ball he
bought for $1.95 at a garage sale spinning down the lane in every
Kansas county that has a bowling alley.
</P>
<P>
   So far Woydziak, a member of an outfit called Kansas Explorers,
has concentrated on the northeast part of the state _ around
Hiawatha, Marysville, Atchison. But in the far reaches of Kansas he
has pinpointed other alleys _ St. Francis, Sterling, Caldwell,
Beloit and more, 117 in all, just waiting for the thump of his
mother-of-pearl ball on the lane, the hum of its rotation as it
rolls, and the clatter as the pins go flying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus I've heard of a private alley in a church in Kansas City,
Kansas,'' said Woydziak, ``and there's the old Seelye Mansion in
Abilene that had alleys built into it. And I want to look into the
one in a recreation center in Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does sound a little nutty, doesn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   Not really. Marci Penner, of the Kansas Sampler Foundation in
Inman and who keeps track of such things, says Woydziak, as one of
the group's 1,500 Explorers, is like many members who pick out a
theme for their travels through the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's one who plans to jog through every town in Kansas,''
said Penner. ``There another who wants to go to every sale barn in
the state and eat at the sale barn restaurant.''
</P>
<P>
   Others have made up their minds to photograph as many grain
elevators as they can; a few are fascinated by silos or that
specific variety of silo that has a tree growing inside; unique
graveyard statuary has grabbed others; a bunch love old barns, both
round and square; old railroad depots have turned a handful into
zealots; and, of course, there are those resolved to visit every
county courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   For an Explorer, said Penner, ``Larry's pretty average.''
</P>
<P>
   Woydziak has never bowled on a regular basis. The $1.95 ball
pretty much sums up his attitude toward equipment. Nor is he a
devotee of bowling shirts. So, why bowling?
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to thinking about Rose Hill (Kan.), where my wife,
Connie, and I grew up,'' he said. ``I remember how tough it was for
a small businessman to make it in a place like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I remembered that in my drives through Kansas you'd see
these little bowling alleys in these small towns and you'd think,
`Now that's something, a bowling alley way out here.' And I thought
that bowling alleys might be a way to meet some nice people.''
</P>
<P>
   Using the Internet, telephone books and city directories,
Woydziak located bowling establishments in all but 26 of the 105
counties in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Once in touch with the owners, Woydziak has been delighted to
find himself invited to visit and hear statements like: ``Let us
know when you're coming; we'll open up special, and we'll even have
people for your to bowl with.'' That's country friendliness, he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Woydziak expected a dearth of alleys in western Kansas, but he
says he's been surprised at the number of counties in the eastern
part of the state that are bereft of facilities for what is still
America's most popular participant sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``The saddest thing is to get a number, call it, and hear that
it's been disconnected,'' he said. ``Right there you know there was
a bowling alley but it's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   The closures, Woydziak said, signal the slow demise of something
special _ the heyday of the small-town bowling center.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get the feeling a lot of them are just holding on,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Time was, said Mark Jensen of Wichita, director of the American
Bowling Congress in Kansas, bowling lanes in small towns were akin
to community centers.
</P>
<P>
   Bowling then, said Jensen, was the recreation. Oh, there was
snooker down at the beer joint. Or old men playing checkers or
dominoes. Maybe a rodeo in the summer. But aside from church and
the PTA, it was bowling that brought a lot of people together.
</P>
<P>
   He said bowling was something an entrepreneur could get into
fairly cheaply, what with financing deals offered by the big
bowling suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember back in the 1950s and 1960s bowling alleys were so
popular they were open all night and you'd have to actually shoo
people out just to clean up,'' said Jensen.
</P>
<P>
   But then, he said, came cable TV, multiplex movies in nearby,
bigger towns, stock car racing, the Internet, power boats, dirt
bikes, golf, jogging, casino gambling, professional sports teams,
kids' soccer and baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Johannes, whose family has been in the bowling business for
decades in Kansas City, said bowling had changed with electronic
scorekeeping, video monitors carrying all sorts of sports, lanes
made of composite materials, keno games, sports bars, restaurants,
kid's play areas and a plethora of other amenities.
</P>
<P>
   With such conveniences, said Johannes, bowling is thriving in
big and medium-sized cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``But out in the country, six or eight lanes isn't going to make
it. The cost of all the new stuff is just too high. There aren't
enough people.''
</P>
<P>
   There are enough for Woydziak. Without crowds, he said, you get
to see the little things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in this one eight-lane alley, and I was talking to the
proprietor,'' he said. ``And in came this women's league to bowl.
One of the women has a baby, the next thing to newborn.
</P>
<P>
   ``And she walked over and handed it to the woman I was talking
to. They didn't say a word to each other. But you could tell from
their eyes that there was total trust. The proprietor rocked the
baby and talked to me. The new mother went over and bowled and that
was that.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't see things like that in big towns or cities. That's
why this is worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how long his quest will take or how much it'll cost is
something Woydziak isn't even thinking about. The payoff, if there
is such a thing, will be his journal, detailing every bowling alley
he visits and every proprietor, bowler, and stranger he meets.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, what we leave behind is mostly just a bunch of
forms,'' said Woydziak. ``I hope someday my kids and grandkids and
their kids can pick this up and enjoy reading about the old man who
went around Kansas with a bowling ball _ crazy as it seems.''
</P>
<P>
   (30)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-00 1930EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000311.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4187 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-EDISON-SCHOOLS-2NDTAK     03-11 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDISON-SCHOOLS-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ herself doing payroll.  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   In January, School Futures notified Richey she was removed from
her duties for making unauthorized purchases, exceeding the budget
and failing to recruit enough students. Richey has been put on a
paid leave, but her dream, for now, has been snatched away.
</P>
<P>
   School Futures has declined to discuss Richey.
</P>
<P>
   Others have found the relationship with School Futures more
productive.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert Guerrero, education director of Alta Vista Charter
School, said School Futures is providing $120,000 to renovate the
West Side school and help with fund raising, staff training and
student testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, it's been a good partnership,'' even while dealing
with the financial uncertainties that continue to buffet charter
schools, Guerrero said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Richey's removal soured some in the charter-school
community on private management firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be a role for the management companies, but I would
say we are wary of it,'' said Laura Friedman, who helped draft
Missouri's charter school law and advises many of the schools. ``We
tell prospective operators to ask a lot of questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Judy Morgan, Kansas City teachers union president, said she
wanted to see results before any more district schools were turned
over to private operators.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real hard for me to accept people making a profit on our
children's education,'' Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bartman, Missouri education commissioner, poses the
pivotal issue for many who have watched the district's students
fall behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the fact that the Kansas City system is not serving its
students well, we all have to be open to new possibilities,''
Bartman said. ``If they can get the job done of educating the kids
and educating them well and they can get a profit, more power to
them. '' Where's the payoff?
</P>
<P>
   Despite the pingpong rhetoric over philosophical merits of
private companies educating students, there is an economics problem
yet unciphered. Can they make money running schools? Most of the
companies are private businesses and do not report their financial
performance. The two companies that are publicly traded have had
huge losses and uninspiring stock results.
</P>
<P>
   TesseracT Group of Scottsdale, Ariz., is being restructured
after reporting a $10.6 million loss for the six months that ended
Dec. 31, and the Nasdaq exchange delisted the stock for failing to
meet minimum results.
</P>
<P>
   Edison Schools was founded in 1991 by Whittle, who believed
business had to be able to do a better job than the academic
bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   Edison, which brought on former Yale University President Benno
Schmidt as chairman, had invested $160 million in its projects as
of last November but reported a $50.4 million loss last year on
$133 million in revenues. It lost $2,068 for each of its 23,900
students and just reported a $14 million loss for the first six
months of this fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   The company predicts it will be profitable in 2004, when it
projects it will run 400 schools with about 260,000 students and
have $1.8 billion in revenue. It now has 79 schools and 38,000
students. Edison's stock, which was priced at $18 a share when it
went public in November, is now trading around $18.
</P>
<P>
   Whittle said Edison would become profitable as it achieved
economies of scale. Merrill Lynch, which handled Edison's stock
offering, predicts that Edison's administrative costs will drop to
6 percent from about 17 percent and that it eventually will bear a
7 percent return on investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have hundreds and thousands of schools to spread our
costs across,'' Whittle said. ``We are negotiating with a computer
company to buy 250,000 computers. We can do that because we have a
national system.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch touts big potential for school management. Its
research says the country spends about $360 billion a year on
elementary and secondary education, ``but our return on investment
is woefully inadequate.'' According to Merrill Lynch, if Edison
captured a 1 percent share, it would have $3.6 billion in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   But some financial analysts say these projections are
misleading. Most of America's schools are performing well, making
them unlikely candidates for privatization.
</P>
<P>
   If there are profits to be had, they are more like McDonald's
than Microsoft _ very small, said Thomas Toch, a Brookings
Institution scholar who is writing a book on the subject. ``They
will have to get very big and then have to operate very
efficiently.''
</P>
<P>
   Some educators watching the privatization trend say economies of
scale may be trickier to achieve in education than in other
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I look at education, it doesn't benefit much from economies
of scale. The largest districts and largest schools are the most
inefficient in terms of cost and outcomes,'' said Henry Levin, an
economist and director of the National Center for the Study of
Privatization in Education at Columbia University, which is
evaluating the movement. ``My own view is, the answers are out on
how well they will do, and there are no assurances that they will
be profitable.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City may benefit from hiring Edison while the company is
young and investing heavily in schools in hopes of attracting more
customers, Levin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Edison is probably a good buy for your school district because
Edison is putting in more than they're getting out right now.''
</P>
<P>
   (30)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
