r a BC-EDISON-SCHOOLS-2TAKES     03-11 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDISON-SCHOOLS-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS STILL SURROUND PRIVATELY MANAGED PUBLIC SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER and PHILLIP O'CONNOR  
c. 2000 Kansas City Star KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Kansas City School
District Superintendent Benjamin Demps Jr. wants the private sector
to take over more of the district's worst-performing schools to
improve achievement and compete with charter schools.
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the school board approves, it would push the district further
into one of the most contentious trends in education.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents believe that private management companies, compelled
by competition and a sharp focus on the bottom line, will bring to
public schools the efficiencies of free markets. Supporters say
that by squeezing administrative costs and using economies of
scale, private companies can spend more in the classroom and still
pocket a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Currently a dozen school-management companies operate about 200
schools nationwide with about 100,000 students. Merrill Lynch
analysts estimate that private companies eventually will manage 20
percent to 30 percent of public schools. While school companies
have yet to make much, if any, money, they promise that both
students and investors will profit from their experience.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptical educators, however, say there is no evidence that
business brings anything special to the operation of schools.
Pointing to health care, they warn that market incentives bring the
temptation to cut corners and wring larger returns. Academics and
economists studying the movement say there is no assurance of
long-term profitability and wonder what will happen to students in
privately operated schools that fail.
</P>
<P>
   A public debate has erupted over claims by school-management
companies that they have produced significant learning gains.
Education researchers say it is simply too early to tell. Teachers
union leaders and other detractors also express philosophical
reservations about for-profit education and believe any savings
extracted from the system should benefit students and not be paid
to shareholders and owners.
</P>
<P>
   H. Christopher Whittle, chief executive of Edison Schools, the
country's largest school-management company, sums up the debate
this way:
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is: How do you run a good school and make a
profit? Critics will say that what we will do is dramatically
decrease what we offer in the classroom. But we don't do less; we
do more. If we didn't, we couldn't stay in business.'' Looking for
options
</P>
<P>
   As test scores of students in districts like Kansas City have
fallen behind national averages, many parents have tired of the
public school monopoly. They have turned to charter schools as an
alternative, and some charter schools have turned to private
enterprise for help. So has the Kansas City district, which
contracts with Edison to operate Woodland Elementary. The New
York-based company also manages two of the city's 15 charter
schools, including one overseen by the district.
</P>
<P>
   Charter schools are publicly funded but operate free of many
local and state regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Longer school days and school years, more teacher training,
proven curriculum and heavy use of computers are ways private
management companies hope to improve on what is done in public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Eugene S. Ruffin, president of School Futures Research
Foundation, a San Diego-based nonprofit management firm, said there
were some simple but dynamic differences between privately run
schools and their public counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (charter) law allows you to remove many of the barriers
about what you should teach, when you should teach and how you
should teach,'' Ruffin said. ``It allows you to choose who works
for you, both administrators and teachers. Our teachers are paid
according to the performance of children in their class. They get
bonuses and raises based on performance, not the degrees they have
earned or tenure.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruffin concedes that the first year is chaotic as the staff
adapts to a business model, being accountable for budgets as well
as grades. Banneker Charter Academy of Technology, run by School
Futures, illustrates that poignantly. Broken dreams
</P>
<P>
   Esther Richey, a former Kansas City School District principal,
recruited School Futures when she desperately needed money to fund
her dream of opening a charter school. She persuaded the school's
board to hire the company, and she became an employee.
</P>
<P>
   For 7 percent of the money the school received, School Futures
covered building costs and promised to run the business side of
Banneker, leaving Richey free to oversee education.
</P>
<P>
   The school immediately ran into problems, Richey said.
</P>
<P>
   Classrooms were scattered among three central city buildings,
transportation fell apart, cafeteria costs ran over budget, bills
went unpaid, and Richey found herself doing payroll.
(MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
