<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWO-PATHS-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROTHERS TAKE TWO PATHS IN LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON KANDEL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sammy and Danny Batres play on the same worn and
rutty streets of suburban Pacoima. They wear identical toothy
grins, and walk with the same swagger. They share a bunk bed in the
same converted garage.
</P>
<P>
   But the brothers are headed down different paths.
</P>
<P>
   It's as clear as two papers affixed to the family refrigerator:
One is an award 10-year-old Danny got for perfect attendance at
Vaughn Next Century Learning Center, where he was ``student of the
week.''
</P>
<P>
   The other note is a probation report 14-year-old Sammy received
for getting caught with a knife at school.
</P>
<P>
   Sammy is a gang member who already has taken a bullet. Danny is
a good student at a renowned charter school and wants to become a
scientist and study volcanoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned that I don't want to get into gangs,'' Danny said.
``I want to go to college, get a job and have a fine wife.''
</P>
<P>
   For Sammy, the world of gangs seems inescapable, even at his
age.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't straighten out,'' he said. ``This is my life. This is
my world.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the Batres brothers are emblematic of families
across the San Fernando Valley and Los Angeles who struggle to keep
their children out of gangs. These youths' paths raise a key
question for parents: Why do some children inexorably stray toward
trouble, while others do well in school and excel?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's quite a few stories like this,'' said Steve Martinez,
a former member of a Pacoima gang and now the associate director of
Communities in Schools, a dropout prevention and youth intervention
program in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times we run into older brothers who don't want their
younger brothers to go through what they are going through because
they understand the danger the danger of being shot, of being hurt.
But more than likely, the younger brother follows in the footsteps
of the older brother.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Maritza Hernandez said she feels helpless as she watches her
sons take different paths. Five men in the family uncles and
cousins have joined gangs. One is dead.
</P>
<P>
   The 33-year-old Salvadoran said she fears for Sammy's life in
their neighborhood, which police have declared is affected by
gangs. Crime there is down 3.3percent, but still 84 serious crimes
were logged in the small neighborhood hard against the 118 Freeway,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   So out of desperation, Hernandez decided in recent days to send
Sammy to live with his father in Ohio, from whom she is separated.
A short, stocky woman with strands of gray hair covering black,
Hernandez, who earns just $12,000 a year making wooden reeds for
clarinets at a local warehouse, hopes a heavy hand of guidance and
encouragement will keep Danny on the right path.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to do,'' she said recently, tears welling.
``I keep telling him, `If this is the way you are, then Danny might
start going in the same path. I want the gang life to stop here.'''
</P>
<P>
   The family lives in a $400-a-month converted garage, divided
into the boys' bedroom and a living room, where their mother sleeps
on the couch.
</P>
<P>
   The only place for Danny to do his homework is on the small
kitchen table, with its Winnie the Pooh place mats and the
occasional cockroach.
</P>
<P>
   In better days, the three used to drive downtown to the Hungry
Bear restaurant every Saturday for barbecue, but then Sammy got
older and began hanging out with friends more. No time for family,
he would say.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Sammy, I can't sleep,'' she said. ``I keep thinking he is
going to get killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether sending Sammy to live with his father will turn him
around, no one knows. Hernandez can only hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``My boys are my whole life.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on his experience as a counselor, Martinez worries that it
might be too late for Danny.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a good move by taking (Sammy) out of it,'' he said.
``But the fear now is that the image of his older brother might
stay there.''
</P>
<P>
   Danny already feels the allure of gang life. He and his friends
are enamored of graffiti, some of which was scrawled by his big
brother around the neighborhood. They spend countless hours after
school admiring gang tags on walls, on abandoned homes, and in
gutters.
</P>
<P>
   Like many youngsters, Danny doodles on his schoolwork. But
instead of drawing cars or people, Danny practices his tag.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL 2ND TAKE FOLLOWS.)  &UR;
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Check it out,'' he said. Then he added, ``I tag on paper at
school every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Danny stays a little closer to home than his brother, but
sometimes strays into the gray haze of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   He and his friends say they enjoy throwing rocks, lemons and
eggs at passing cars. Sometimes they tie rocks to the ends of
fishing poles and break car windows. Other times they play with BB
guns.
</P>
<P>
   Sammy wanders a little farther. A popular spot several blocks
away is the ``Backwall,'' a series of large walls cutting an
embankment between the Ronald Reagan Freeway and an industrial
complex along Paxton Street.
</P>
<P>
   This spot is the gangsters' canvas, where they spray-paint their
names and cross off rivals' names in all colors, shapes and sizes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took my brother here one time,'' Sammy said as cars could be
heard whizzing by on the freeway above. ``He was like, `Whoa, this
is cool.''' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The thrill for Danny extends only so far, though.
</P>
<P>
   When his brother came home crying and bleeding from a gunshot
wound to the calf one November night, Danny began to think hard
about where he wanted to go in life.
</P>
<P>
   The attack occurred when Sammy and some friends had gathered on
the sidewalk in front of a friend's house after a wedding. A car
pulled up to the curb and someone inside shouted, ``Where you fools
from?''
</P>
<P>
   Then someone in the car drew a gun and started firing. Everybody
scattered. A bullet struck Sammy in the calf.
</P>
<P>
   It became his mark of manhood, a badge of courage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bullet went up into the back of my knee,'' he said
recently, displaying the wound.
</P>
<P>
   But to Danny, the wound was a mark of stupidity.
</P>
<P>
   ``After he got shot, I told him, `If you get shot one more time,
you're not going to be my brother anymore,' '' he said. `` `You're
going to be dead.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sammy, who spent a week in Juvenile Hall for his
knife-possession offense and is on probation until he is at least
18 in California, does not condone his gangster lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``If my brother did that,'' Sammy said, ``I'd knock him
around.''
</P>
<P>
   But no one so far has been able to persuade Sammy that the life
of a gangster is no life at all. He brags about what he sees as
perks: girls, for one.
</P>
<P>
   He said he has seven girlfriends, displaying pictures of them
recently at his home. ``These two are sisters,'' he said of two
young, good-looking dark- haired girls.
</P>
<P>
   He hangs with his friends, smoking pot and drinking. ``I like
the high,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He claims he gets respect. ``We're known around the Hall''
</P>
<P>
   the Hall being Juvenile Hall.
</P>
<P>
   No one can tell him otherwise, not even Carl Cruz, 26, Sammy's
uncle and a man who has acted as a mentor. A former member of a
Pacoima gang, Cruz blames a big part of the problem on Sammy's lack
of a father figure at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no structure,'' said Cruz, who joined Victory
Outreach, a group working to cut gang violence in the Northeast
Valley. ``There's no discipline. Sammy dominates the home.''
</P>
<P>
   Cruz also knows how easy it is for a younger brother to follow
in his older brother's footsteps. He followed two older cousins
into gangs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever he is doing, you want to do,'' he said. ``It is hard
for a younger brother to detach from that and make his own
decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   There might be hope for Sammy, though, Cruz says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he wants to change, but the structure at home doesn't
allow that,'' he said. ``He's smart. He has a lot of talent. But he
needs a strong hand on him so he can shape up.'' &UR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-00 1953EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
