<SLUG> BC-BKN-WOLF-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAZERS' FUNK IS NO HIT IN PORTLAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Imagine a city where there is no pro football, no
pro baseball and no pro hockey. Or, to put it another way, one
where even the Arena Football League team moved to Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Portland, where the Blazers occupy the attention of
the average sports fan about 99.9 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fish-bowl mentality that can be wonderful when things are
going great, but also create a level of scrutiny that few NBA
players endure. Take last week's loss to the Lakers at the Rose
Garden. It was such a devastating defeat, the Blazers lost three
straight this week and four of their past five games.
</P>
<P>
   They are not only losing ground to the Lakers, they could fall
behind Indiana and finish with the third-best record in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Need a scapegoat? Blame L.A. (who else).
</P>
<P>
   ``Without question, we're in a funk,'' said guard Greg Anthony.
``We've played very bad basketball since the Lakers game.''
</P>
<P>
   A funk is an understatement. The Blazers went from the
team-most-likely-to-finish-with-the-best-record, to getting
embarrassed in a 19-point home loss to Toronto, and losing to the
New Jersey Nets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say it's a slump,'' said coach Mike Dunleavy. ``I
mean, we haven't played very well at times, so I would consider it
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Damon Stoudamire, who usually is more concerned about
himself than anything else, has become concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what's going on. We need to quit worrying about
who's ahead of us and behind us in the standings and just play our
game,'' Stoudamire said. ``I hate the fact that we're so focused
on, `Did the Lakers win tonight? Who lost?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the mental strain of keeping pace with the big bad
Lakers, the Blazers are also fighting serious injury problems.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Grant is bothered by an inflamed fascia in his right foot,
and is beginning to wonder how effective he will be in the playoffs
if he doesn't get better soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this is the way it's going to be until the end of the
season, then I have to do something,'' Grant said. ``Because if we
hit the playoffs and I'm playing like this, then I'm not going to
help the team.''
</P>
<P>
   And Stoudamire has been slowed by a sore knee he hurt in the
Lakers game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's going to be 100 percent for a while,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   On the bright side, Dunleavy can be grateful that he has
something to worry about besides Rasheed Wallace's next technical
foul, or when Scottie Pippen will experience his next bout of
sullen behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway bashing: Miami point guard Tim Hardaway was bothered by
NBC announcer Bob Costas' comment during last Sunday's Lakers-Heat
telecast that ``You could make a case for Vince Carter replacing
him on the Olympic team,'' because of Hardaway's lack of quickness
due to injuries and advancing age.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm on the team, and there's nothing they can do (about it),''
Hardaway snapped back in response to Costas.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, it shows that Costas may be able to wax poetic
during the 20 seconds he gets to pontificate between pitches on
baseball, but basketball sometimes brings out the worst side of
him.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone loves to berate NBA stars when they talk about taking
the summer off instead of playing for their country. So Hardaway
spent last summer loyally representing Team USA during Olympic
qualifying in Puerto Rico. His reward? Now he's being targeted for
removal by the great Costas.
</P>
<P>
   Draft threat? According to the Vancouver Province, agent Tank
Black told the Grizzlies in 1998 to bypass forward Vince Carter
because a shoe deal with Puma would be nullified if Carter were
drafted by a team in a ``small market.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a relatively moot point, because the Grizzlies were settled
on Mike Bibby with the No. 2 pick, and would have taken Michael
Olowokandi if the Clippers had passed on the unspectacular center.
</P>
<P>
   It's only today that every NBA GM will tell you that Carter was
the top player in the draft, although few had him rated among the
top two or three picks at the time.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, Carter's dealings with Black and Puma have both been
shattered this season. He said he would leave Puma a couple months
ago, and suspended his relationship with Black last week. Black is
currently facing fraud and money-laundering charges.
</P>
<P>
   In demand: St. John's coach Mike Jarvis has reportedly drawn
interest from the Nets, Pistons, Wizards and Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets are expected to fire Don Casey sooner or later, while
the Pistons have an opening and nobody is quite sure what Michael
Jordan's plans are from day to day. As for the Celtics, it seems
Rick Pitino's tirades/bad trades may finally be catching up with
him.
</P>
<P>
   Owner testimonial: Hornets coach Paul Silas, who formerly
coached the Clippers, gave one of the strongest endorsements in
league history on Clippers owner Donald Sterling in an interview
with the Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not a bad fellow at all. He's a charming guy that I have
a lot of respect for,'' Silas said. ``The only thing I can't
understand is why,with all his resources, won't he step up to the
plate and really make that franchise something special.''
</P>
<P>
   Ready for work: Now that Sixers assistant John Calipari has
finally taken the Memphis job, former Pistons coach Alvin Gentry
and former Wizards coach Garfield Heard are the top two candidates
to replace him on Larry Brown's staff in Philadelphia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-00 2001EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
