<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4203 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT     03-11 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR CARTER, COMPARISONS ARE JUST BEGINNING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ He has the same name as Gomer Pyle's commanding
officer, which is a miserable coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   His hang time is the envy of all above-average bats.
</P>
<P>
   His maneuvers are a bit less flamboyant than Richard Simmons
after a head-on collision with caffeine.
</P>
<P>
   So it seems simple enough to define second-year Toronto Raptor
Vince Carter on these remarkable credentials.
</P>
<P>
   But he happens to stand about 6-foot-6, and invested three
seasons in the basketball program at the University of North
Carolina, which is to individuality as the Amish are to tattoo
parlors.
</P>
<P>
   Then he became Rookie of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   His sophomore season has not been compromised by jinx. The last
month has been nutty.
</P>
<P>
   After an astonishing effort in the NBA's Slam Dunk Contest,
Carter dropped 51 points on Phoenix, cooked Boston with a 3-pointer
at the buzzer, and duplicated the game-ending heroics last
Wednesday vs. the Clippers at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Such ESPN bait leaves us with the unavoidable comparisons to You
Know Who.
</P>
<P>
   For perspective, we impose upon the wisdom of Clippers assistant
coach Dennis Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was employed by the Boston Celtics when You Know Who
left a couple of permanent creases in his face during a 63-point
playoff performance 14 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``(You Know Who) has six championships, so it's kind of unfair
to both of them,'' Johnson said of the comparison before digging in
to advance it. ``But he (Carter) would be the only player I would
pay to go watch. I think NBC was wise to add a few Toronto games to
the schedule; the NBA really needed someone like this to come along
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, a six-time member of the NBA's first-string,
all-defensive team, said the biggest difference between Carter and
You Know Who can be measured by their comparative ferocity when the
other team has the ball.
</P>
<P>
   You Know Who was a nine-time member of the NBA's all-defensive
crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vince is becoming much better defensively,'' Johnson said.
``But when you compare him to (You Know Who), he's lacking just a
little bit. There are times, though, when he shows that swagger,
looks like he wants to lock you down.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said the comparison also is skewed a bit by the
subjective variable of supporting casts.
</P>
<P>
   In You Know Who's first two seasons, his Chicago Bulls teammates
would have had difficulty covering the spread at a Gus Macker
Tournament. While the Raptors aren't exactly threatening an
overflow at Springfield, Mass., Carter does get to play alongside
two talented thugs Charles Oakley, Antonio Davis and gifted kid
cousin Tracy McGrady.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vince, I'm sure, is going to get there commercially,
financially,'' Johnson said. ``and more importantly ...
basketball-wise. But he has to keep it in the proper order. (You
Know Who) always knew he had to care of business out here.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is pointing toward the basketball court, a place where
greatness is required before the marketing can fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``And what set (You Know Who) apart was something more than
desire,'' Johnson said. ``A lot of guys have great desire. But what
(You Know Who) had was the desire to always want the ball when the
game was on the line. He learned early that, along with being a
hero, you have to not be afraid about being the goat.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm already seeing some of that in Vince. By just saying
that, it means he's surpassed all of the next (You Know Who's)
we've seen before.''
</P>
<P>
   Shot-clock violations
</P>
<P>
   Now that garage sales have allowed the Chicago Bulls and Orlando
Magic to become major threats in the free-agent mall, expect the
tactic to be repeated. According to league sources, the next
franchise to throw a few salaries overboard could be Atlanta. The
Hawks, who (as of Saturday) had the league's sixth-worst record,
owe the Clippers two first-round picks. One of those originally
belonged to Toronto and is lottery protected; the Raptors are
playoff-bound, so the Clips will have it this summer. The other
(the Hawks' original pick) is protected though the first nine
selections, but the Hawks may attempt to give it to the Clippers
this year, anyway. Atlanta may be just as bad (or worse) if it
moves salary this off-season, and next year's draft may be much
more tempting. ...
</P>
<P>
   The broken leg of Cincinnati's Kenyon Martin (the projected
first pick) provides enough karma for us to believe the doomed
Clippers will win the lottery. Martin is expected to make a full
recovery, but nobody will be able to work him out before the June
28 draft. And the lottery may be even worse than expected. Chris
Mihm, the 7-foot junior center from Texas, Maryland junior forward
Terence Morris, and LSU sophomore forward Stromile Swift all are
threatening to stay in school. All three are projected top-five
picks. But one scout close to the LSU program said Swift could
change his mind when he discovers just how impressed the NBA is
with his ability to run fast and jump high. The first five rotation
also may be sabotaged by the questionable health of Loren Woods,
the 7-1 Arizona junior center who has back problems. ...
</P>
<P>
   According to several NBA watchdogs, the most talented player in
this draft will be Fresno State shooting guard Courtney Alexander.
He also may be the worst defender. ... A recent Sports Illustrated
story on junior college hotshots did not mention Chris Massie, a
6-8, 250-pound power forward who averaged 19 points per game at
Oxnard. Massie, who didn't even attend high school in his hometown
of Houston, reportedly was impressive enough to inspire a scouting
visit from the Lakers. ... Friends of second-year Laker Tyronn Lue
said the 5-10 point guard loves L.A. and hates not playing enough
to welcome a trade to the Clippers. ...
</P>
<P>
   We'll support attaching microphones to the lapels of NBA coaches
when NBC rolls tape of commissioner David Stern's next chat with
players' union emcee Billy Hunter. ... Rumor has it that Clipper
Tyrone Nesby made an honest mistake in not guard Vince Carter on
Carter's game-winning shot. Clips coaches told Nesby to ``stay on
Carter,'' so Nesby made a beeline toward Butch Carter, the Toronto
coach.
</P>
</TEXT>
