<HEADLINE>
`TRAUMA' TRAINS CAMERA ON ER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - Scooter Alpert bopped around the corner of the nurses'
station, his eyes flashing as he removed his surgical cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just in the operating room watching some guy get his
scalp sewn back on,'' he said, sounding like a kid at Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Alpert is no ghoul. He's a producer for Trauma: Life in the ER,
the Learning Channel's highest-rated show. He and a couple of
cameramen (one is a woman, actually) are spending March at the
emergency and trauma center at Phoenix's Good Samaritan Regional
Medical Center, filming more than 200 hours of footage for two
one-hour episodes scheduled to air sometime this fall.
</P>
<P>
   And make no mistake _ a man getting his scalp reattached is good
TV.
</P>
<P>
   Not ER TV, not exactly. Trauma: Life in the ER, now in its
fourth season, is the real McCoy. It's gripping, no matter whether
it's filmed in your local hospital or someplace across the country.
It strips away the romantic entanglements and office politics of ER
_ a show Alpert has never seen, amazingly _ and gives viewers the
bare-bones workings of a trauma center. I love ER, but this is
plenty dramatic enough.
</P>
<P>
   Trauma's cameras go everywhere _ no emergency is off-limits, no
matter how disturbing _ and although they don't ignore the blood
and guts of emergency medicine, they don't flaunt it either.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to focus on the people who help people, as
opposed to the gore,'' Alpert said.
</P>
<P>
   That would be people such as Robinelle Schroder, a nurse and
trauma coordinator at the Phoenix hospital, who will spend much of
the month with a camera following her.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a teaching facility,'' she said. ``We're used to
people watching us.''
</P>
<P>
   Every trauma, in fact, is taped for later review anyway. Of
course, those cameras aren't literally in people's faces. Trauma's
are.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, a helicopter flew in a man thrown from a car in an
accident near Buckeye. Alpert and Ed George, one of the cameramen,
met the helicopter on the roof of the hospital, tape rolling.
</P>
<P>
   They followed the victim into the trauma center, side by side
with the paramedics. (They film first and ask for consent from the
patient later. If it's not given, the footage isn't used.)
</P>
<P>
   Once inside, Alpert stepped back; George stood toe to toe with
the doctors and nurses, taking in everything through his lens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of intuition, I think, staying out of the way,''
George said of the most obvious danger. ``You sort of assess the
situation, and it allows you to instinctively know where to move.''
</P>
<P>
   Midway through, Liz Tynes began her shift behind the camera. She
and George tag-teamed the trauma from there; George moved back for
wider shots while Tynes moved in close, sometimes quizzing doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I find it really difficult,'' Tynes said of such
close shots. ``To get the good stuff _ to really be there _ you
have to get close. You can't stay back and use the zoom. You need
that immediacy.''
</P>
<P>
   We _ viewers _ do. As for the hospital staff, well . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on what I'm doing,'' said Dr. Dustin Reid, a
resident whose easygoing manner gives him a natural TV appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they're following me on rounds and we're not doing
anything that important, I totally notice them. And they'll ask me
questions like `What are you doing now?' and I just feel ridiculous
answering the questions with them right on camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in the middle of traumas, in the operating room, I don't
even notice they're there.''
</P>
<P>
   The size of the cameras _ no bigger than the camcorder you film
your child's first steps with _ helps. So does the experience of
the people behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's told me I was in their way yet,'' George said. ``I'm
sure (I have been), but they're very nice about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, probably not.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in each other's way all the time,'' Schroder said. ``It
hasn't been a problem. Nurses, especially, who work in the area,
are very assertive. We have no problem telling someone to get the
hell out of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   No one has taken to wearing pancake makeup to work, although
Schroder did wear her ``least-wrinkled scrub,'' she said, and Reid
got a haircut.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get traumas at 2 a.m. and you've been asleep for an
hour or two, then you get up. . . . My hair was getting a little
bit long, and it was sticking up all over the place,'' he said.
``So I got it trimmed down.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trauma crew has been busy from the get-go _ hours after
setting up shop the first day, six children were brought to the
hospital, victims of a car accident. Filming kids is especially
tough, Tynes said. But much like the doctors, she and George stay
so busy working that they keep an emotional distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're looking through here,'' George said, pointing to the
camera, ``it doesn't bother me at all, seeing right into somebody.
It's kind of fascinating actually.''
</P>
<P>
   It is. It's a life-or-death dance playing out on camera. Who
could look away?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very eye-opening to see how on the ball these people
are,'' Alpert said. ``If I get sick, I want it to happen here.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach Goodykoontz at Bill.Goodykoontz(at)ArizonRepublic.com or
(602) 444-8974. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
