<HEADLINE>
RELAUNCH MAY BE SWAN SONG FOR `FREAKS AND GEEKS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
(UNDATED) - I swear to God this is our last relaunch. That is
because we have only one other option: our funeral.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   When your show's been yanked during consecutive sweeps rat ings
periods, you deserve to be a little fatalistic. In a note to TV
critics, Paul Feig and Judd Apa tow certainly sound like they are,
and who can blame them? Not long after rescheduling their bril
liant-but-low-rated show, Freaks and Geeks, NBC pulled it for the
February rating period - just like it did in November.
</P>
<P>
   The show returns Monday, March 13, instead of sending a preview
tape for just that episode, Feig and Apatow also included the last
epi sode of the season, just in case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are we sending this last episode so early?'' they write.
``Because we like it, and if you don't tell people we exist, nobody
will see it but you.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider it done. (For more along this vein, check out
www.freaksandgeeks.com. Geez, even the Web site is good.)
</P>
<P>
   Monday's episode is, by the way, fantastic, both heartbreak ing
and hilarious. Of course, if you're one of the discriminating TV
types who watches Freaks and Geeks, that's what you ex pect. If
you've never seen it, do yourself a favor and tune in.
</P>
<P>
   And then dash off a letter to Garth Ancier, President, NBC En
tertainment, 3000 W. Alameda Ave., Burbank, CA 91523, beg ging the
network not to cancel the show.
</P>
<P>
   Or don't. But never, ever com plain again that there isn't any
thing good on TV. There is. You just have to watch it.
</P>
<P>
   You've got to figure that the seven NBC affiliates around the
country that refused to air God, the Devil and Bob because of its
subject matter did so without seeing it. At least, you've got to
hope that they did.
</P>
<P>
   The animated series, about a Detroit autoworker trying to prove
mankind is worth saving, premiered Thursday and begins its regular
run Tuesday. It won't replace the King James version of the Bible,
but it's thoughtful, funny and, yes, irreverent. Better still, it
actually makes you think. It doesn't present religion in a
traditional way, but what's wrong with that?
</P>
<P>
   Tell people you're a TV critic and their response is always the
same (before reading further, place nose in air):
</P>
<P>
   ``Well. I don't watch TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Is that so? According to the Television Bureau of Advertising,
most adults spend 128 minutes a day listening to the radio, 45 min
utes online, 30 minutes reading the newspaper, 19 minutes read ing
magazines - and 253 minutes watching TV.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the bureau isn't ex actly a disinterested third party,
but the numbers are convincing enough to lead one to believe that
all the folks who claim to be reading Proust might be squeez ing a
little WWF Smackdown! into their lives, as well.
</P>
<P>
   As for us TV critics, well, it's always nice to feel needed. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach Goodykoontz at Bill.Goodykoontz &LR; ArizonaRepublic.com or (602)
444-8974. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
