<SLUG> BC-RAC-FLORIDA-DERBY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DREAM GOES ON FOR AN 88-YEAR-OLD OWNER-TRAINER  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALLANDALE, Fla. _ The saga of Hal's Hope added a chapter of
storybook drama Saturday when the 3-year-old colt won the Florida
Derby by a head over the favored High Yield, and advanced one
milestone closer to the Kentucky Derby with Harold Rose, his
88-year-old owner, breeder and trainer.
</P>
<P>
   Hal's Hope, who came from a barn filled mainly with claiming
horses and ran second to High Yield in the Fountain of Youth Stakes
three weeks ago, dueled dramatically with High Yield down the
homestretch in their return match, but did not flinch.
</P>
<P>
   They will travel on to the next prep race for the Kentucky Derby
with totally conflicting scenarios: High Yield, a son of Storm Cat,
trained by D. Wayne Lukas, the master trainer who has won the Derby
four times; Hal's Hope, a son of Jolie's Halo, trained by a man who
underwent quadruple heart-bypass surgery last summer and came back
because ``I knew I had a horse in the barn who needed me.''
</P>
<P>
   They shared the stage Saturday with two other stars of racing,
Jerry Bailey, who rode six winners (but finished eighth in the
Florida Derby aboard Elite Mercedes), and Bill Mott, who trained
four of Bailey's winners. The jockey rode in eight of the 13 races
on the program but fell one victory short of his record total of
March 11, 1995, when he rode seven winners but lost the Florida
Derby aboard Suave Prospect by a nose to Thunder Gulch.
</P>
<P>
   The winning jockey in Saturday's landmark race, by contrast, was
Roger Velez, who has never even seen a Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been to the Kentucky Derby,'' Velez said, ``but it
looks like we're going this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose, however, has been to the Derby. In 1984 he got there with
Rexson's Hope, who ran 10th. But at 88, Rose is distinguished by
youthful optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last time I went to the Derby with a long shot,'' he said.
``This time I'm going with a contender.''
</P>
<P>
   Hal's Hope became a contender after winning the Holy Bull Stakes
at Gulfstream at odds of 40-1. Then, at 10-1, he ran second to High
Yield in the Fountain of Youth. And finally, he went off in the
Florida Derby at 6-1, and once more confounded the experts.
</P>
<P>
   He got the jump on High Yield at the start, and held the lead,
but never by more than half a length until they hit the
homestretch. Then Pat Day made his move aboard High Yield,
collaring the leader briefly as they raced down the stretch with
the crowd of 28,033 roaring. But High Yield could not put Hal's
Hope away.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's in front,'' Rose said, ``he won't let another horse
pass him. I didn't think they could outrun him. My expectations
have been realized.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Velez put it, ``The good Lord gave him a horse to keep
him going.''
</P>
<P>
   Hal's Hope ran the mile and one-eighth in 1:51 2/5, paid $15.80
for a $2 bet to win and earned $450,000 for his biggest payday, and
Harold Rose's. The top pair raced far in front of their eight
rivals: the nearest, Tahkoda Hills, ran third, 10 lengths away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we had it entering the stretch when Pat looked
back,'' Lukas said with regret. ``But you have to give it to the
other horse, he ran a tremendous race. It looks like these two
horses are way above the other horses here in Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   And even Lukas said: ``This is a kind of happy ending.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
