<HEADLINE>
`HISPANIC' SEEMS TO BE GIVING WAY TO `LATINO' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY LAURA TRUJILLO  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - When Gil Trejo was a kid, everyone just called him
Mexican. Later, he was called a Latin American and Chicano. In the
1970s, the term changed to Hispanic. And now, he says, it seems
he's a Latino.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, is it Hispanic now or Latino?'' asks the
73-year-old retired teacher and coach from west Phoenix. ``I don't
know which one everyone is using.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a question heard more often as Arizona Latinos, or
Hispanics, search for ways to describe themselves, especially as
more people move here, bringing preferred labels with them.
</P>
<P>
   Those who were Hispanic for years suddenly say they're Latino.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the census will add Latino to the
Hispanic/Spanish category. Hispanic magazine regularly refers to
people as Latino. And recently, the Diablos, Arizona State
University's Hispanic alumni association, switched to the ASU
Latino alumni association.
</P>
<P>
   After all, popular culture has declared a ``Latino Revolution,''
led by Ricky Martin, Jennifer Lopez and Christina Aguilera.
</P>
<P>
   Even quepasa.com is taking a poll, with billboards asking,
``Hispanic or Latino?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a healthy debate,'' says Jose Ronstadt, quepasa.com's
senior vice president of content. ``Because in the end, everyone
under the umbrella is of a very rich cultural heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   Since November, 5,000 people have voted on quepasa.com, with 37
percent choosing Latino, 31 percent Hispanic and the rest choosing
others, wanting to be called, Mexican, Cuban, or whatever their
national origin.
</P>
<P>
   The labels change in different parts of the country. In
California, it's Chicano or Latino. No one is Hispanic in New York,
they're mostly Cuban or Puerto Rican.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona, it seems, is one of the last places to find Hispanics,
experts who study such things say.
</P>
<P>
   Many see the term ``Hispanic'' as a Richard Nixon-government
imposed label.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to name themselves, using a Spanish word,'' says
Everardo Martinez-Inzunza, director of multicultural student
services at the University of Utah, who has followed the debate for
the past few decades. ``If I call myself Latino, I have a longer
history, not one created by a government agency.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal government coined the term ``Hispanic'' in the early
1970s when trying to categorize Spanish-speaking people.
</P>
<P>
   Others say Hispanic is too general or too hiccupy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't tell me anything about a person,'' says Jose
Martinez, 25, who works for the advocacy group Chicanos Por La
Causa. ``It waters down the identity.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost 30 years ago, the federal government decided to create
new ethnic labels.
</P>
<P>
   It took six months of meetings, debates, arguments and surveys,
remembers Grace Flores-Hughes, then a 25-year-old Mexican-American
from Texas who helped lead the meetings.
</P>
<P>
   She remembers her committee talking about Latino, but when taken
literally, it could include Italians and others of Latin origin.
She also worried that it sounded too masculine, excluding women.
They also pitched ``Spanish-Americans'' (too limiting) and
``Spanish-speaking Americans'' and ``those with Spanish surnames''
(too encompassing).
</P>
<P>
   ``(Hispanic) just seemed to be the only one that encompassed all
of us,'' says Flores-Hughes, who is credited _ or blamed, depending
on who's talking _ with coining the name.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years later, Flores-Hughes stands behind the label.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of it, still loyal to it,'' she says. ``You know,
you still can be Cuban or Mexican or whatever and be Hispanic.
Here's a term to best serve our community.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacqueline Bosque, vice president and general manager for Radio
Unica, also prefers Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   A typical day on her Valley Spanish-language station starts with
a Cuban psychologist, then a Dominican discussing telenovelas
(Spanish-language soap operas), followed by a Mexican on an
immigration show, and a Uraguayan and Mexican talking sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're diverse and our audience is diverse. But we're all
Hispanic because we all speak Spanish. Todos somos Hispanos,''
Bosque says. ``We're all Hispanics.''
</P>
<P>
   As a Cuban, Bosque feels alienated by the term ``Latino,''
saying it seems to include only those from Latin America. She
prefers to say she's ``Hispanic of Cuban-American descent.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people also prefer Hispanic as a way to set themselves
apart from new immigrants, says David Gutierrez, a history
professor at the University of California at San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a more hifalutin, high-toned label. People will say it to
mean, `We're not Mexicans, we're Hispanics,' '' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Cecilia Herrera, 28, was born in Mexico and came to Arizona when
she was 2. ``I always say Mexican,'' she says. ``I didn't know I
was Hispanic until I started school, then I had to check a box.''
</P>
<P>
   Herrera, a secretary for the Department of Public Safety, says
her younger sister considers herself a Chicana and her friend, from
Venezuela, always says Latina.
</P>
<P>
   Now, many notice, it's the younger generation embracing Latino.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each generation wants to name itself,'' quepasa.com's Ronstadt
says. ``They want to identify themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what many old-timers say, seeing the names change as each
generation labeling itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see, I was a Mexican, a Mexicano they called me,'' Trejo
says. ``And then all the others, Chicano, Latin American, or I
can't remember the order. Then, Hispanic, and now they say Latino.
They change the monikers, but I am who I am.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Laura.Trujillo(at)Arizona Republic.com or
(602) 444-8891. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Latino or Hispanic? The question comes more often as people search
for ways to identify themselves. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
