<HEADLINE>
PEREZ NOT GREAT, BUT NOT TERRIBLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUPITER, Fla. - Dodgers left-hander Carlos Perez threw 73
pitches and allowed four runs - three earned - in three innings
against the St. Louis Cardinals on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In most instances, that's called terrible. In this case, it's
called progress.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Dodgers and Perez - one of baseball's most expensive
works-in-progress given he's owed $12.6 million over the next two
seasons - are looking for any morsel of hope that he could be in
the rotation by opening day.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Orel Hershiser will be the fifth starter, Perez will
likely be in the minors and the Dodgers' bullpen will be weakened.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said he saw good signs from Perez,
whose velocity on his fastball was consistently 87 to 90 mph. Perez
also threw some good change-ups, but had one crushed 400 feet by
Craig Paquette.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was missing, but he wasn't missing bad,'' Johnson said.
``He was right around the plate. He's still cutting the fastball a
little more than you'd like to see him do it. He was overthrowing a
little bit, coming open a little bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``All in all, he threw the ball a lot better. He threw (73)
pitches, which tells you that's not the way he pitches. He
(usually) goes after guys. He missed a lot of pitches. He still has
a tendency, I guess from last year, to come flying open a little
bit and trying to make it up with his arm. His rhythm is not there
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is Perez never found his rhythm in `99, which is why
every start now is subject to scrutiny. He went 2-10 with a 7.43
ERA last season, and after a winter of work allowed five runs in
his first inning this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``My arm strength is good and my velocity is good,'' said Perez,
who has a 14.40 ERA this spring. ``I had a little trouble with my
fastball away. The homer, it was one of the better pitches I threw.
It was low and away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about what the people are saying. I want to be
consistent, throw fastball, fastball, fastball. Like I said before
and I'll say it all the time, this season isn't going to be like
'99. I feel my mind is clean. Every day I feel more comfortable,
more happy, compared to last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Comfortable Cora: After a shaky start in which Alex Cora fought
jitters in the field and had poor at-bats, he's settled down the
last four or five days and played well at shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   Cora, 24, said he relaxed after talking with his brother, Joey,
a former big-leaguer and now a minor-league coach in the Chicago
Cubs organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning I wasn't playing relaxed,'' Cora said. ``I
thought it was going to be easier. I felt the pressure a little
bit. I learned from it. (Joey) called me and we had a little chat,
about 45 minutes, and he told me to have fun and play hard. That's
all I can control.''
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Lefty Onan Masaoka pitched a perfect inning of
relief and doesn't appear to be far behind, despite missing two
weeks with a sprained ankle. ``He threw the ball real good,''
Johnson said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
DODGERS vs. ST. LOUIS
</P>
<P>
   When/Where: 11:05 a.m., Holman Stadium, Vero Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: Ch. 5; XTRA-AM (1150).
</P>
<P>
   Today's game: Trying to do his part in the battle to join the
rotation, Dodgers right-hander Orel Hershiser faces the Cardinals.
He pitched three hitless innings in his last outing. St. Louis
counters with righty Darryl Kile, acquired in an offseason trade
with Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's result: Dodgers pitchers continued to get hit hard in
a 9-6 loss to St. Louis, dropping their record to 1-10. Five
pitchers allowed eight earned runs as the Dodgers' team ERA climbed
to 6.99. Devon White hit a two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   -Brian Dohn
</P>
</TEXT>
