<HEADLINE>
YANKEES TAKE INTEREST IN EDMONDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. -- With left fielder Ricky Ledee struggling at the
plate and the team off to a slow start this spring, the Yankees are
intensifying their efforts to acquire Angels center fielder Jim
Edmonds.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees apparently are willing to part with Ledee as part of
a package for Edmonds, but so far have been reluctant to give up
either pitcher Ramiro Mendoza or infielder Alfonso Soriano.
However, Yankees owner George Steinbrenner has held numerous staff
meetings lately and could order a deal to be made.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night in Sarasota, Fla., Mendoza pitched against the Reds
in front of Angels scouts, and gave up two runs and five hits in
three innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees want to keep Soriano because they plan to use him as
bait in their pursuit of Twins starter Brad Radke. And if Mendoza
goes in a deal to the Angels, the Yankees would want to fill that
void in the pitching created by his departure.
</P>
<P>
   If they do acquire Edmonds, the Yankees would consider putting
Edmonds in center and moving Bernie Williams to left, provided
manager Joe Torre could convince the sensitive Williams it would be
best for the team.
</P>
<P>
   While the Yankees would prefer Edmonds, they also have interest
in Expos outfielder Rondell White.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Scott Schoeneweis and utility player Benji Gil made
strides Saturday in their efforts to make the team out of spring
training.
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis, competing with numerous pitchers for a spot in the
starting rotation, started Saturday's 7-3 win over the Colorado
Rockies. He gave up one run and four hits in four innings, striking
out two (including Larry Walker) and walking none.
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis made the team out of spring training last season as
a reliever, but later was demoted to triple-A Edmonton and sulked
while in the minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an experience,'' Schoeneweis said. ``Now I know I can
get big league hitters out. When I was sent down I didn't handle
myself very well. Hopefully I won't have that cloud hanging over
me.''
</P>
<P>
   It won't as long as he continues to pitch like he did Saturday.
Schoeneweis primarily throws a hard sinker and relies on getting
hitters to hit ground balls.
</P>
<P>
   Gil had only one hit Saturday, but that hit was an
inside-the-park grand slam. It was a linedrive to center that
skipped past center fielder Juan Pierre and rolled to the fence.
</P>
<P>
   Though his offense will definitely help his cause, winning a
spot as a utility player will be based on defense, and in
particular his ability to play shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me that's my easiest position,'' Gil said. ``I've played
there all my life. I've learned to play second, third and the
outfield the last two years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For Benji, shortstop is his natural position, so he feels
comfortable there,'' Scioscia said.
</P>
<P>
   ANGELS vs. SEATTLE
</P>
<P>
   WHEN/WHERE: 12:05 p.m. at Peoria Sports Complex
</P>
<P>
   RADIO/TV: KLAC-570, XPRS-1090
</P>
<P>
   TODAY'S GAME: Angels at Mariners. Jason Dickson starts for
Anaheim against Seattle's John Halama. Dickson has shown his
shoulder is healthy since coming off surgery, but has been unbable
to find his command.
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY'S GAME: Starting pitcher Scott Schoeneweis gave up one
run and four hits in four innings, and infielder Benji Gil hit an
inside-the-park grand slam as the Angels improved to 5-4 in Cactus
League play with a 7-3 win over the Rockies.
</P>
</TEXT>
