<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0312-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Special treatment, not special prosecutor?
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   VOTES CAST IN ARIZONA; CAUCUSES HELD IN MICHIGAN, MINNESOTA AND
NEVADA
</P>
<P>
   Computer glitches might have frustrated some Arizona voters in
Saturday's Democratic primary, but early numbers still indicated
that a record vote turnout was expected as the party completed the
first binding election for public office using the Internet.
Computers terminals and traditional paper ballots were offered at
most of the state's 124 polling sites Saturday. More than 35,000
people had already cast Internet votes when early computer voting
ended Friday. A total of 270 Democratic delegates were being
selected this weekend in voting, which include the Arizona primary
and party caucuses held in Michigan, Minnesota and Nevada. Results
for the caucuses weren't expected until Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   GORE TO FOCUS ON CAMPAIGN FINANCE REFORM
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore said Saturday that he would make
overhauling the campaign finance system a central theme of his
Democratic presidential bid. In an interview with The New York
Times on Saturday, Gore brushed aside questions about his conduct
in raising money, saying that he had learned from past mistakes and
therefore had become passionate about the issue. Gore made it clear
that he viewed his heightened zeal for campaign finance not only as
a draw for the independent voters who had flocked to Sen. John
McCain of Arizona but as an organizing principle for his campaign
against Gov. George W. Bush. He asserted that Bush's economic
proposals are unworkable because of his ties to special interests,
and ``fat cats'' who have financed his campaign, and expect a break
on their corporate taxes. Gore also repeatedly said that Bush lacks
the experience to run the country. ``You
</P>
<P>
   have to wonder, does George W. Bush have the experience to be
president?'' Gore asked as he flew to Minneapolis to campaign.
</P>
<P>
   GORE ELIMINATED BUSH'S LEAD, POLL SHOWS
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by surging support among moderates and independent
voters, Vice President Gore has eliminated Republican Gov. George
W. Bush's lead in the presidential race, a new Washington Post-ABC
News Poll released
</P>
<P>
   Saturday shows. The survey of 1,218 adults interviewed Thursday
through Saturday, found that Gore leads Bush by 48 percent to 45
percent among registered voters _ a statistical tie. The poll has a
3 percentage
</P>
<P>
   points margin of error. Six weeks ago, Bush held a double-digit
advantage over Gore, and in a Post-ABC News poll two weeks ago,
Bush still clung to a 6-point lead. In a hypothetical three-way
race, Gore and Bush are tied at 37 percent, with 23 percent for
John McCain who halted his campaign Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The statistical dead heat appeared duplicated in another poll,
released Saturday by Newsweek, which gave Bush a 47 percent to 44
percent edge over Gore. The poll, based on 803 voters surveyed
Thursday and Friday, had a 4-percentage-point margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   GORE'S ELDEST DAUGHTER STUMPS FOR PAPA
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Vice President Al Gore's eldest daughter rolled
across western Tennessee on a bus tour Saturday to get out the vote
for her father three days before Tuesday's Southern primaries.
``He's a visionary, he's a principled fighter, and he's a policy
pioneer. If you need a fourth, hes a really great dad,'' Karenna
Gore Schiff said at a union hall. She ridiculed Republican critics,
who have called Gore the ``Ozone Man'' because of his views on
environmental protection and global warming. He talked about the
environment before it was a ``cool'' thing to do, said Schiff, 26,
a third-year law student who lives with her husband and 8-month-old
son in New York City. Tennessee along with Texas, Florida,
Louisiana, Mississippi, and Oklahoma hold presidential primaries
Tuesday. Schiff stumped in western Tennessee in place of her
mother, Tipper Gore, who stayed home in Washington, D.C., to tend
to Schiff's younger brother who injured an ankle.
</P>
<P>
   NOWHERE TO PARTY
</P>
<P>
   The popular South by Southwest Music and Media Festival held in
Austin, Texas, in mid-March has forced Republican presidential
contender Gov. George W. Bush to scramble to find a place to
celebrate what is likely to be a smashing victory in Tuesdays
Southern primaries. The music festival, which attracts thousands of
people nationwide, already had reserved most of the city's large
centers and hotels. So Bush was forced to schedule his party for
the gymnasium of the Dell Jewish Community Center located in the
northern Austin suburbs. ``Downtown
</P>
<P>
   options were limited because of South by Southwest,'' said
campaign spokesman Scott McClellan. ``So we looked for a location
that could accommodate a large crowd, and lots of national media
including the satellite trucks.''
</P>
<P>
   DON'T WRITE OFF MCCAIN
</P>
<P>
   Republican Sen. John McCain says he's not ready to ride off into
the sunset just yet, and he won't give up fighting to preserve
Social Security and reform big money politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not bitter. I'm not going to indulge in recriminations.
There's no point to it,'' McCain told The New York Times in an
interview published Saturday, two days after he bowed out of the
race, ceding the GOP presidential nomination to George W. Bush.
Still, McCain said he is hesitant to release his block of 247
Republican delegates to the Republican presidential nominating
convention until he can figure out how to push his proposals to
reform campaign financing and use budget surpluses to pay down the
national debt and boost Social Security centerpieces of his
suspended White House bid. ``The main idea is to go slow. There's a
long time until (the) November (general election),'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
