<SLUG> BC-TRANSIT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRANSIT BID RIDES ON 62 VOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY MARY JO PITZL  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - In a city of 1.2 million, Tuesday's, March 14, Phoenix
transit tax comes down to a race for 62 votes.
</P>
<P>
   That's the size of the swing in the city's last transit
election, in 1997, when a proposed transit tax lost by 122 votes.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of Proposition 2000 are calling for more bus service
- more frequent buses, longer hours of operation and Sunday service
- and the introduction of electric light-rail commuter trains. They
are wooing voters with appeals to quality of life, projections of
traffic gridlock and a barrage of radio and TV ads.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the measure want to keep swing voters in their
camp, warning that more transit won't make a dent in congestion,
and with promises that there are cheaper ways to curb traffic.
</P>
<P>
   With 1997's debate over a transit tax still fresh for many
voters, the struggle is to capture those who didn't show up last
time to vote, or those who may be waffling.
</P>
<P>
   Both opponents and proponents predict Tuesday's vote will be
close, even if the campaigns being waged are lopsided.
</P>
<P>
   Transit 2000, which backs the tax, has $1.4 million, paid
consultants and the backing of the business establishment as well
as environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   The De-Rail the Tax Committee has less than $10,000, street
signs and a scrappy band of volunteers. They also have the easier
sell: no tax.
</P>
<P>
   Transit proponents, despite their apparent muscle, must convince
voters that better transit is worth a 0.4 percent sales tax
increase, or 4 cents for every $10 purchase. The transit expansion
tax would raise the total sales tax in Phoenix to 7.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix officials say they're back with a new proposal, just 30
months after a narrow defeat, because Phoenix's continued growth
will lead to increasingly dire traffic conditions unless commuters
are offered other ways of getting to work.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, if voters approve local matching funds now, the federal
government is prepared to pay for at least half of the light-rail
system.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Skip Rimsza calls this a ``just-in-time election,''
suggesting that transit improvements made now may save the city
from gridlock.
</P>
<P>
   Rimsza says this transit election could be another
transportation breakthrough; as pivotal as the successful 1985 vote
to fund Valley freeways.
</P>
<P>
   Becky Fenger, chairwoman of De-Rail the Tax, calls Proposition
2000 a ``trolley folly'' because of its price. It would cost $1.2
billion to build, plus $454 million to operate. And Fenger predicts
the costs will rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you have this white elephant, it needs a hell of a lot of
hay,'' she told a neighborhood group recently.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 2000 would expand Phoenix's bus system across the
city, resume Sunday service for the first time in six decades, and
add more express buses during rush hours.
</P>
<P>
   The bus fleet would grow 50 percent, with 210 new buses added
over 20 years. The cleaner-fuel buses would pile up 22 million
miles a year by 2020, a 140 percent increase over current levels.
Buses would run longer hours, more frequently, and on major streets
where there currently isn't service.
</P>
<P>
   Dial-a-Ride service for the disabled and elderly would double
within the year.
</P>
<P>
   Electric-rail service would come to town, with an initial
12-mile line running from near Chris-Town Mall, down Central
Avenue, and out to Tempe by 2006.
</P>
<P>
   Included in the plan are 500 bus pullouts on city streets, 100
miles of new bike lanes and left-turn arrows at every major
intersection.
</P>
<P>
   The transit tax is expected to raise $2.9 billion over 20 years.
Combined with existing local and state revenues, as well as
matching federal funds, the transit plan would cost $4.8 billion
over the next two decades.
</P>
<P>
   The tax would end in 2020. Voter approval would be required to
authorize a renewal.
</P>
<P>
   Transit backers say Phoenix's rail lines would be the start of a
regional system, enabling other Valley cities to fund their own
links and eventually benefit commuters Valley-wide.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 2000 promises to build 24 miles of light rail by
2016. Only the first 17 miles have been defined; the remaining
miles would be picked later, transit planners say, when demand
became clear.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, they envision 64 miles of rail if the system
expands. Those lines would generally follow freeway corridors, with
a spur running on South Central Avenue to Baseline Road. A segment
along Interstate 10, west of Interstate 17, would jog south near
27th Avenue and run past the state Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   The transit debate kicked off with name-calling that got worse
as the campaign progressed.
</P>
<P>
   Rimsza and his supporters have belittled the opposition as
``naysayers.'' Last week, they passed out fliers calling the
De-Rail panel CAVE people: Citizens Against Virtually Everything.
</P>
<P>
   The opponents have fired back, calling Rimsza and his crew
``liars'' and labeling their transit plan a ``dirty proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, bus driver Mark Meyer said he's pursued his
drive to close the 122-vote gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to register 122 people to make up for what we lost by
last time,'' Meyer said. ``I got 350.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether those people will vote in a single-issue election
remains to be seen. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at MaryJo.Pitzl(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or (602)
444-8963. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The campaign for the Phoenix transit tax has come down to an effort
to sway 62 votes as supporters and opponents argue over whether
more buses and the introduction of rail service will help move
people around town. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
