<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME FOR ARIZONA TO MAKE GROWTH PAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY SHAUN MCKINNON  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - After gritting their teeth through crowded highways,
dirty air, long lines at the MVD - all the ills of an
ever-expanding population - Arizonans finally can cash in on
growth.
</P>
<P>
   All they have to do is be counted.
</P>
<P>
   The half-hour or less it will take most people to fill out the
2000 census questionnaire will help Arizona collect as much as $20
billion in federal aid over the next decade, win the state probably
two new seats in Congress and provide information to plan future
roads, parks and schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot at stake, a lot of money and a lot of essential
city services our residents have come to depend on,'' said
Avondale's Debbie Kohn, one of the dozens of city employees around
the Valley assigned to the census.
</P>
<P>
   Missing just 2.4 percent of the population, the rate reported by
the Census Bureau for 1990, would cost Arizona as much as $200
million in direct federal aid over 10 years, according to a report
released Friday by the accounting firm PricewaterhouseCoopers.
Local officials say the total could surpass $400 million.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans will receive their census forms by mail this
week. The average form asks six questions of each household member,
with two additional for the head of the household. A longer form,
sent to one in six homes, adds 47 more questions designed to elicit
details about income, energy use, transportation and, yes,
plumbing. &QL; 
FAMILY PORTRAIT &QL; 
The results will paint 21st-century America's first family
portrait. More important, they will determine how the federal
government spends more than $2 trillion from now to 2011, and they
will reshape lawmaking bodies from Congress down to the smallest
town councils.
</P>
<P>
   This high-stakes head count has galvanized cities, counties,
community organizations and special interest groups.
</P>
<P>
   The Maricopa Association of Governments estimates that each
person generates at least $350 each year in state and federal
funding for various programs. Phoenix puts the number at a slightly
higher $415. Multiplied by the latest population estimates, that's
as much as $1.2 billion a year in Maricopa County and about $2
billion statewide.
</P>
<P>
   The money is spent on school lunch programs, employment
services, housing assistance, hospital services, programs for the
poor and elderly and more.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every Phoenix area city has created complete count
committees to find as many ways to persuade residents to complete
their forms and return them by April 1, Census Day. &QL; 
MULTIMEDIA CAMPAIGN &QL; 
 &QL; 
Phoenix has created a multimedia campaign and is saturating the
airwaves with public service announcements and in-studio
interviews, with special emphasis on Spanish-speaking radio
stations. Officials also have enlisted the aid of community-based
organizations, who benefit from the federal money and who are often
more trusted on a neighborhood level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those groups know when it comes to dollar allocation, a lot of
funding they receive is from grants,'' said Margie Emmerman, an
aide to Gov. Jane Hull and co-chairwoman of a Phoenix outreach
committee.
</P>
<P>
   The census is used to reapportion the 435 seats in the U.S.
House of Representatives and draw new district boundaries for the
90 seats in the state Legislature and most elected city and county
boards. Arizona's growth almost certainly will earn the state two
new seats in Washington, according to the Washington-based Election
Data Services.
</P>
<P>
   The scramble will come when it's time to redraw congressional
districts, which is why both major parties would like to increase
their influence in the state Legislature, the holders of the
reapportionment pen.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers also will adjust the lines of their own districts,
another highly partisan process. Maricopa County is expected to
strengthen its position in the state House and Senate, but Mohave
and Yavapai counties have grown at faster rates and may be able to
wrest power from other parts of the state.
</P>
<P>
   State and local agencies rely on census figures to plan schools,
roads, parks, utility lines and, most critically, fire and police
services. Businesses use the data to plot expansion and investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The census becomes the base from which we do all our
forecasts,'' said Harry Wolfe, socioeconomic program manager for
the Maricopa Association of Governments. ``Clearly, if the base is
an underestimate, it can have a spiraling effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Cities and towns worry most about planning for public safety, a
costly chunk of the annual budget. An undercount could leave newer
neighborhoods less protected.
</P>
<P>
   This year as never before, minorities and special-interest
groups are looking for ways to take advantage of the census. Black,
Hispanic and Native American organizations are flooding their
communities with promotional materials, talking up not only the
money involved, but the potential to flex political muscle with
bigger numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were definitely undercounted last time,'' said Pete Garcia,
president of Chicanos Por La Causa, a statewide Hispanic advocacy
group. ``We are working hard this time to allay people's fears of
being counted.''
</P>
<P>
   Chicanos Por La Causa has joined with the Mexican American Legal
Defense and Educational Fund to educate Latinos about the census.
</P>
<P>
   Several lesbian and gay groups are trying to further push the
census envelope by encouraging gay couples to check the ``unmarried
partner'' box when asked to describe their relationship. Though the
information would be unofficial, the groups hope to use it just as
others do.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are not counted, we lose out on federal funding for
research, funding for community services and passage and
implementation of laws that benefit our community,'' said Paula
Ettelbrick, family policy director for the National Gay and Lesbian
Task Force. &QL; 
THE COMMON ENEMY
</P>
<P>
   Lurking behind the campaigns is a common enemy: the undercount.
The U.S. Census Bureau acknowledged missing more than 4 million
people in 1990, 1.6 percent of the population. Some non-government
census experts say the numbers are higher.
</P>
<P>
   In Arizona, the undercount was 2.4 percent; a lower 1.8 percent
in Maricopa County, a considerably higher 10 percent in Apache
County. Minorities fared the worst: The census missed more than
32,000 Hispanic Arizonans, 4.5 percent of the total, and 22,000
Native Americans, or nearly 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   More than half the uncounted Native Americans were under age 18,
which alarms family groups who fear children on Indian reservations
will be shortchanged.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau concedes Native Americans mistrust the federal
government. To try to allay fears, the agency will not mail census
questionnaires to most reservation homes, but will instead deliver
them in person.
</P>
<P>
   Fear and mistrust also undermines the count among
Spanish-speaking immigrants, legal and otherwise. In that
community, the federal government often means only one thing: La
Migra, the Immigration and Naturalization Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Realistically, we know we are speaking sometimes to an
undocumented population,'' Emmerman said. ``We have to make sure
the message is for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Arizona has one of the nation's fastest-growing Hispanic
populations, an undercount of even 3 or 4 percent could create
funding shortfalls that multiply as each year progresses.
</P>
<P>
   But even as they narrow the message, officials say the core idea
is the same for everyone:
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one time when every person should be counted,
regardless of residency or documentation status,'' Emmerman said.
``For now, they shift from `citizen' or `resident' to just
`person.' '' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Shaun.McKinnon(at)Arizona Republic.com or
(602) 444-7116. &QL; 
 &QL; 
It's time for all the talk about how we've grown to end and the
counting to begin. With the receipt of census forms this week,
Arizonans will participate in a process that will earn the state
billions of dollars in federal money, two more seats in Congress
and official bragging rights as the 20th largest state in the
union. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
