<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAST IS ALIVE FOREVER ON A BIT OF TAPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
(UNDATED) - Ten years ago today, I did a terrible thing. I secretly
recorded a telephone con versation with my parents.
<TEXT>
<P>
   I know. I can hear my mother now. ``Eddie, really?''
</P>
<P>
   It began innocently enough. I'd been doing an interview with a
man who supported a baseball program for kids by selling con
cessions at spring training games. When the interview ended, I
forgot to turn off the tape machine.
</P>
<P>
   The next call I made was to my parents in Pittsburgh. It was
their 46th wedding anniversary and my father's 69th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing unusual about the call is that it's been frozen
in time, like a piece of wedding cake. I spoke with my parents
often. Even special occasions were filled with small talk, though
it doesn't seem so small these days.
</P>
<P>
   As always, my mother an swered the telephone, and we talked for
a few minutes before my dad got on the other line. He'd say hello,
then listen while the two of us talked.
</P>
<P>
   They were having a quiet day, my mother said. They'd been to
church and then went out for lunch. Now, she was cooking spaghetti
and had some clothes in the washer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine, I'm cooking and doing laundry on my anniver sary,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   It's exactly what anyone who knew her would have imagined.
</P>
<P>
   The previous day, they'd taken one of my aunts to a new shopping
mall across the state line in Ohio. They wandered around for 4{
hours, my mother said.
</P>
<P>
   By now, I had realized the tape machine was still record ing. I
could have reached down and switched it off. I didn't.
</P>
<P>
   My mother told me one of my cousins had a friend in Phoenix who
mailed one of my ``write-ups'' back to Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked her which one,'' my mother said, ``and she told me, `I
don't know which one, but it was good.' ''
</P>
<P>
   I made a wisecrack about calling the fire department to douse
all the candles on my dad's cake. He said this birth day didn't
bother him much but the next one would.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you hit 70 you go downhill,'' he told me.
</P>
<P>
   I could have turned the tape off any time. The button was right
there in front of me.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, I let the machine re cord them telling me about a
grandson's upcoming confirma tion; about how excited they were to
have my family visit them the following summer; about how some of
my cousins had visited my father while he worked at the St. Titus
Church weekly fish-fry.
</P>
<P>
   That sort of thing.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, I listened to the tape for the first time since re
cording it. It was a week or so after my father's funeral, a year
or so after my mother's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   I'd kept the tape in a desk drawer through all the anniver
saries and birthdays in be tween, not noticing how my parents'
laughter gradually lost its fullness, or how conversa tions about
the neighbor's dog or my brother's family or the miniature Easter
baskets my dad made for my daughter's grade school class slowly
turned into talk of test results and medications and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere along the way, I stopped getting Pittsburgh Stee ler
critiques and gnocchi reci pes and even weather reports.
</P>
<P>
   So, today, on what would have been my parents' 56th wedding
anniversary and my father's 79th birthday, I'll do a terrible thing
_ again. I'll eavesdrop on a conversation I should not have
recorded in the first place. Something I never told my par ents
about. And never erased. And never will.
</P>
<P>
   I know.
</P>
<P>
   I can hear my mother now.
</P>
<P>
   Really, I can hear my mother. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach Montini at &QL; 
Ed.Montini &LR; Arizona &QL; 
Republic.com or (602) 444-8978. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
