<HEADLINE>
KINGS CAN BE TOUGH ON LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO - Only one Western Conference team has a winning
regular-season record against the Lakers over the last two seasons.
It's not the Spurs, the Jazz or the Trail Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   It's the pesky, freewheeling Sacramento Kings, who roll into
town today and perhaps have a better chance than anyone of stopping
the Lakers' 17-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings have beaten the Lakers in three of the last four
meetings a feat no other Western foe can claim.
</P>
<P>
   For added intrigue, these teams are currently matched up for a
first-round playoff series, and play one another three times in the
next four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more of a mindfulness when we're playing against this
team ... because you know that you might face them in the
playoffs,'' said Kobe Bryant. ``You kind of have to try to get a
grasp of what they like to do, what kind of rhythm they play with,
just in case you do play them in the playoffs, you'll be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   The teams have met just once this season, a 103-91 Kings victory
at Sacramento in December that ended the Lakers' seven-game winning
streak. But that was Bryant's first game in the starting lineup
after returning from a broken hand, and the Lakers have come a long
way since.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that game's kind of like eons ago,'' he said, ``because
we were such a different team. We were just getting started with
(coach Phil Jackson's) system, with the players, everybody kind of
finding their own little niche. So the team that they're going to
face (today) is going to be very different from the team that they
faced.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Kings present unique challenges that have given the
Lakers fits.
</P>
<P>
   ``They play at a different pace than everybody else that we've
played so far. They just run the ball down your throat,'' Bryant
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said it's a benefit that the Lakers will see the Kings
three times between now and the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a team that presents the type of challenges that (are
tough),'' he said. ``An outside-shooting center (Vlade Divac), a
screen-roll game, small guards (Jason Williams, Darrick Martin)
that can break your defense down, 3-point shooters ... I think that
(Chris) Webber creates a problem, is a matchup problem for us,
outside-inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive: The Lakers are holding opponents to a league-best
.410 field-goal percentage and threatening to break the franchise
record of .432 - set by the 1971-72 team that won the championship.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson noted the Lakers force teams to take low-percentage
shots, but he also credited their cavernous new home, the Staples
Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's an easy place to shoot,'' he said. ``I
think if you took our home (statistics) versus our road, we
probably have a lower percentage at home than we do on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right. Laker opponents are shooting .397 at Staples, .427
everywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   LAKERS vs. SACRAMENTO Tipoff: 6:30 p.m., Staples Center
TV/Radio: Fox Sports Net; KLAC-AM (570) Lakers (51-11) update: They
a row. The Lakers head to Denver on Monday to begin a five-day,
eight-game trip. They play 14 of their last 20 games against probab
coming out of the All-Star break but have rebounded nicely, winning
their last four in a row. The streak includes an overtime win at
However, the Kings are just 12-19 away from Arco Arena and have
lost six of their last seven road games. -Howard Beck
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
