<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-11 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4428 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-GIULIANI-CLINTON-N     03-11 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON ASSAILS NEW YORK MAYOR ON SCHOOLS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Seizing on what she said was the prime issue in the
race for U.S. Senate, Hillary Rodham Clinton assailed Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani's stewardship of public education in New York Saturday,
asserting that he had resorted to ``gimmicks'' to rescue a school
system that she portrayed as on the brink of collapse.
</P>
<P>
   In her sharpest attack yet on what Clinton's aides believe is
one of the mayor's biggest political liabilities, Clinton mocked
Giuliani's education initiatives, including a proposal to give
parents vouchers to pay private-school tuition and a plan to sell
the Board of Education's headquarters in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   And for the second day in a row, Clinton linked Giuliani to
George W. Bush, the presumptive Republican nominee for president,
as she asserted that Republican policies would harm the public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to education, we do have real problems that
demand action, not political posturing,'' the first lady said in a
speech to teachers' union members at the New York Hilton in Midtown
Manhattan. ``We must ask our leaders what kind of solutions do they
offer? Will you spend more time firing people or fixing our
schools? Will you sell off the school board building, or invest in
our children's education? Will you resort to teacher bashing, or
engage in problem solving? Because real leadership means rolling up
your sleeves and getting to work _ not pointing your fingers or
clenching your fists.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's choice of where to speak _ a United Federation of
Teachers convention for teachers' aides _ underscored her
increasingly deep ties to the powerful union, which has regularly
battled with Giuliani and has emerged as one of her most prominent
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, through a spokeswoman, would not comment on either
Clinton's education proposals or the criticism of his education
record. Instead, the spokeswoman, Kim Serafin, sought to turn the
discussion to an unreleased report on the fund-raising practices of
the Clinton White House. She called on the Clinton administration
to release the report, by a former Justice Department official,
which is critical of President Clinton, Mrs. Clinton and Vice
President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lunchtime arrival at the ballroom at the Hilton set
off a flurry of excitement, as audience members leapt from their
chairs and scurried to the front of the room, lining up for a
photograph of Clinton, who seemed a little startled.
</P>
<P>
   To this friendly luncheon audience _ representative of
supporters whose enthusiasm is central to Clinton's political hopes
_ the first lady offered an appealing menu of proposals. She
called, for example, for higher salaries for teachers, and signing
bonuses for new teachers. She restated her support for the
centerpiece proposal of Sen. Charles Schumer's campaign two years
ago, to provide four-year college scholarships to teachers who
promise to work in inner-city schools. She called for more federal
spending to hire teachers and to repair run-down schools.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton gave no hint of how much she thought all this would
cost, or how it might be financed.
</P>
<P>
   She also assailed vouchers, which Giuliani has presented as a
tool to help parents in New York City assure a good education for
their children, but which Clinton and the teachers' union say would
lead to a flow of money and students out of the public school
system.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton noted her advocacy of higher standards, in the form of
testing, for teachers and students in Arkansas in the 1980s, when
she led a panel on education set up by Bill Clinton, who was then
governor. But she linked those standards to increased spending on
public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot raise standards without increasing the resources
needed to meet those standards,'' Clinton said. ``Yes, we need to
end social promotion. But what good does it do to raise the bar if
we don't lift up our young people to be able to vault across it?''
</P>
<P>
   Social promotion is a policy under which students are graduated
with their peers to the next grade, even if they have failed
academically.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's speech wove together a number of different threads of
her campaign. It allowed her to criticize Giuliani's record on
education (polls show education is one of the top two concerns of
New Yorkers). It also allowed her to reprise an older campaign
theme by raising questions about Giuliani's temperament, while
returning to a new line of attack, attaching Giuliani to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Clinton firmly latched her own fortunes to
those of the presumptive Democratic nominee, Gore. ``I will be by
his side as we fix our crumbling schools, as we put more teachers
in our classroom to lower class size, as we improve the quality of
education,'' she said. ``And I think we know that that is not the
priority of the Bush-Giuliani team. That other team, they want to
talk about gimmicks like vouchers.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, once again, as she discussed the state of schools in New
York City, the first lady sounded as if she had set her sights on
City Hall, rather than the United States Capitol; indeed, some of
her remarks were evocative of the attacks Ruth Messinger, the
Democratic candidate for mayor, made against Giuliani when she
challenged him in 1997. Clinton lamented the physical condition of
New York City classrooms she had viewed, worried about an impending
teacher shortage, and warned of overcrowding in public schools with
the start of the next school year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been to schools where the ceiling plaster's falling
down, where corridors are barred off, where the windows are broken,
where children are going to class in hallways and closets,'' she
said. ``I know that in many of our schools in this city, the
overcrowding has gotten to such an extent that we don't know where
we're going to put the children next September.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
