<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-CAPITALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CAPITALS TAKE THE DEVILS RIGHT BACK DOWN TO EARTH  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Minutes after their nine goals in Atlanta on Friday
night, the Devils were talking about what a severe test awaited
them Saturday night against the Capitals. The Devils were eager to
see how they measured up against a good team after an outing that
looked more like a scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   The answer was rather discouraging for the Devils, who suffered
a 4-2 loss to the Capitals. The defeat for the Devils means that
they have just that one victory _ that ludicrous game against
expansion Atlanta _ in their last five games during their longest
trip of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Brodeur allowed two quick goals to Chris Simon and Joe
Murphy in the early stages. The Devils tied it on two quick goals
of their own, by Deron Quint and Scott Gomez, before Ulf Dahlen
scored the winner for the Capitals early in the third period and
Steve Konowalchuk secured the victory with an empty-net goal.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur, who had such an easy night at the office 24 hours
earlier in Atlanta, found himself on his heels in the early stages
as the Capitals came out with enthusiasm and scored twice before
the game was 4 minutes 31 seconds old.
</P>
<P>
   Simon opened the scoring with his 24th of the season, 3:26 after
the opening face-off, when he beat Brodeur from the bottom of the
left circle after a pass by Adam Oates from behind the goal to the
right of Brodeur.
</P>
<P>
   The Capitals doubled their lead 65 seconds later. Murphy beat
Brodeur over the left skate on a slap shot from the bottom of the
right circle after a pass by Peter Bondra. Brodeur's left leg got a
piece of the puck, but not enough to stop it from trickling across
the line.
</P>
<P>
   But the Devils did not get discouraged by Washington's early
lead and tied the score about three and a half minutes later on
goals by Quint and Gomez to quiet the sellout crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Quint scored just 38 seconds after Bondra. Paired on defense
with Vladimir Malakhov, Quint was making his Devils debut after his
acquisition from Phoenix this week in a trade for defenseman Lyde
Odelein. The goal was his fourth of the season and it came when he
rushed the net on the left side and converted Malkahov's diagonal
pass.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez tied the score with his 18th of the season at 8:02 when he
beat Olaf Kolzig over the glove from the right side after a pass by
Sergei Nemchinov, who made two good plays to keep the puck in
Washington's zone.
</P>
<P>
   Nemchinov was in the middle of the most exciting play in the
scoreless second period. With 8:20 left in the period, Nemchinov
was awarded a penalty shot after he was pulled down on a breakaway.
But Kolzig denied Nemchinov's move from right to left by stretching
out his right leg.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
