<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-PENGUINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEPLETED PENGUINS PULL AHEAD OF RANGERS IN RACE FOR PLAYOFFS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ The Pittsburgh Penguins had won once in their
previous nine games. They had not scored in more than seven periods
and Saturday night were playing without their top two scorers,
Jaromir Jagr and Robert Lang.
</P>
<P>
   The Jagr-less Penguins were easy pickings, right? Wrong. And the
Rangers are in danger of missing the playoffs for the third
consecutive season.
</P>
<P>
   Behind goals from German Titov, Rob Brown and Robert Dome, the
Penguins embarrassed the Rangers, 3-1. Dome's redirection of a Pat
Falloon pass from just off the crease at 9 minutes 53 seconds of
the third period was just Dome's second goal of the season, but it
sealed the Rangers' fate.
</P>
<P>
   With the victory, the Penguins (70 points) leap-frogged the
Rangers into the eighth and final playoff spot in the Eastern
Conference. With 12 games remaining in their regular season, the
Rangers (69 points) are on the outside looking in.
</P>
<P>
   Ottawa General Manager Marshall Johnston was at the game
Saturday night. The National Hockey League trading deadline is
Tuesday at 3 p.m., and Johnston said the Senators are looking for a
forward. Johnston could also be looking for a potential off-season
trade involving Ottawa's holdout center, Aleksei Yashin.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are more concerned about this season, however. They
acquired the 32-year-old right wing Rob Dimaio on Friday from
Boston for right wing Mike Knuble, and their newest player arrived
in time for Saturday's morning skate.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night the Rangers faced a depleted Pittsburgh team that
had not scored in a week.
</P>
<P>
   The Penguins were able to end that streak just 5:36 into the
contest, on a German Titov goal. The score was set up by Aleksei
Kovalev. Thus, after going 151:42 without a goal, the Penguins had
the first goal of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers Coach John Muckler had planned to have Tim Taylor's line
shadow Straka's every chance he could. But the Rangers could not
get the Taylor line out quick enough on the goal. And Taylor's
reunion with Dimaio proved to be short-lived.
</P>
<P>
   With 3:04 remaining in the first period, Taylor was tossed from
the game for spearing Darius Kasparaitis in the midsection with the
blade of his stick. Taylor was assessed a game-misconduct penalty,
and the Rangers played the rest of the game one man down.
</P>
<P>
   The Penguins managed just two shots on goal during the
five-minute major to Taylor. But 22 seconds after it ended, at
17:42 of the second, Rob Brown swept a backhand shot of a Tyler
Wright rebound behind Mike Richter to give the Penguins a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   It took the Rangers nearly eight and a half minutes to register
their first shot on goal in the second period. And after they
slumbered through the first three and a half minutes of a double
minor, Pat Falloon was assessed for high sticking Mike York and it
looked as if the Rangers had packed it in for the night.
</P>
<P>
   But Muckler sent out a new line of Alexandre Daigle centering
Valery Kamensky and Dimaio for the rest of the power play. Kamensky
hammered home the rebound of a Dimaio shot from the slot from off
the left post for his first goal in 14 games, and the Rangers
headed into the second intermission trailing by just 2-1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-00 2326EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
