<HEADER>
A4449 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKC-OKLAHOMA-TEXAS-TE     03-11 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-OKLAHOMA-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUMPED SOONERS DUMP TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Perhaps it was a Freudian slip.
</P>
<P>
   After discussing his team's loss to Iowa State in Saturday's
first Big 12 men's basketball semifinal game, Oklahoma State coach
Eddie Sutton predicted a spirited championship matchup between the
Cyclones and Oklahoma _ 15 minutes before Texas would take the
floor against the Sooners in the second semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Sooners came back from Friday's late, late show
victory over Missouri to outhustle and embarrass a rested Texas
team that showed all the emotion of a PBS landscape-painting show
in losing to OU, 81-65.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton's inadvertent slip illustrates the kind of respect the
Longhorns don't get in these parts after bowing out of the
proceedings for the second consecutive year in the tournament
semifinals, playing from the No. 1 seed last year and the No. 2
seeds Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any question you have to give the credit
to Oklahoma,'' Texas coach Rick Barnes said. ``They played harder
and longer, and I am disappointed in our mental makeup _ the way we
handled the situation. We had guys who played outside their roles
and didn't have the kind of defensive effort we needed to have.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank goodness we've got another game and another tournament
(the NCAA) to see what we're really made out of. But today, there
were not a lot of things to like about our basketball team.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas, which prides itself on defense, was clipped by the
Sooners. OU pounded in 48.2 percent of their shots and repeatedly
outhustled the Longhorns to loose balls and rebounds. UT's guards
also did not respond offensively, hitting 10 of 32 shots.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns led after a less-than-intense first half, 32-30,
as center Chris Mihm scored 14 points. But after banking in a
jumper to open the second-half scoring, Mihm did not connect on
another field goal until a put-back with 1:09 to play and just
didn't get many touches. He finished with 20 and was unable to
explain the team's lack of intensity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know (why),'' Mihm said. ``But that's exactly what the
game boiled down to. They came out intense and fired up and it
seemed like we were just playing to play. If things went well and
we won, we won. If they didn't, no big deal. We were lackadaisical
in the second half and you can't let your guard down against
Oklahoma. We were expecting good things in the second half, but
they jumped on us and we didn't respond.''
</P>
<P>
   Eduardo Najera, who scored only 13 in OU's thrilling overtime
victory over Missouri on Friday night, buried Texas with 31. He
said he wasn't surprised that the Sooners' emotion outshone that of
the Longhorns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not surprised at all,'' he said. ``That's the reason we beat
them in Norman pretty bad (83-59), because we played with a lot of
emotion. We knew if we did the same thing today, it would be the
same way. Once we got that lead (39-36 at 17:02 of the second half)
and played with enthusiasm, we knew they would give up on us.
That's what happened today.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
