<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DINNER-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WISH FOR A SENATE RIVAL: BREAK A LEG  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After more than a year of shunning each other,
Hillary Rodham Clinton and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani shook hands
before sitting down to the annual Inner Circle dinner show Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton arrived in the ballroom of the New York Hilton about
8:20 p.m., stopped briefly at Giuliani's table, shook his hand, and
told him she was looking forward to seeing him perform in the
evening's program, which parodied politicians and the news media.
</P>
<P>
   The two had not been in the same room since beginning their
campaigns for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   They were the star attractions at the annual show of the Inner
Circle, an organization of present and former City Hall reporters.
This year's event _ a musical called ``Livin' La Rudy Loca''
performed by reporters lampooning the mayor, followed by Giuliani's
rebuttal with the cast of the Broadway show ``Saturday Night
Fever'' _ was attended by more than 1,000 guests. (Organizers said
sales of the $400 tickets for the black-tie charity event were
about 10 percent higher than usual.) Guests have typically
complained about the length of the not-always-fabulous shows. Often
the evening has stretched past 1 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Senate race and Clinton's appearance added a welcome
frisson of excitement, even though Clinton did not appear on stage.
By Inner Circle tradition, only the mayor is allowed a rebuttal to
the lampooning.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's entry into New York politics did give reporters
plenty of material for skits that could not have been easy viewing
for the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   In one scene of ``Livin' La Rudy Loca,'' according to the
script, a reporter playing Clinton was to find herself in jail with
reporters playing Sean Combs and Jennifer Lopez. When a reporter
playing President Clinton arrived with a bag of money, he was to
bail out Lopez but not his wife. ``I think Jennifer Lopez has
suffered enough,'' the script had the president saying, as he
walked off the stage arm-in-arm with Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   Another act was to include Gabe Pressman, a political reporter
for WNBC-TV, singing a song called ``Mild Thing'' about Gov. George
Pataki.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-00 2351EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000311.0257 </DOCNO>
