A4453 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-LEGENDRE-NYT &LR;      03-11 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-LEGENDRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERTRUDE LEGENDRE, 97, SOCIALITE, HUNTER, AND WAR CAPTIVE  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ENID NEMY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Gertrude Sanford Legendre, an unlikely debutante of
the 1920s who forsook society to become a big-game hunter and then
to work during World War II for the Office of Strategic Services,
predecessor of the Central Intelligence Agency, died on Wednesday
at Medway, her historic 6,800-acre plantation near Charleston, S.C.
She was 97 and also had a home on Fishers Island, off Long Island's
northeastern end.
</P>
<P>
   Gertrude Sanford was still in her teens when she took a hunting
trip to the Grand Tetons of Wyoming and shot her first elk. For
some years afterward, she pursued big game throughout Africa,
India, Iran and Indochina, and contributed rare specimens to
museums, including the American Museum of Natural History in New
York, the Peabody Museum at Harvard and the Smithsonian
Institution.
</P>
<P>
   In her later years, her love of hunting evolved into a love of
nature, and she took an active role in environmental issues. She
established the Medway Environmental Trust for educational purposes
and to make sure that Medway would forever be managed as a nature
preserve. In the last decade, she granted conservation easements on
her landmark house to the Historic Charleston Society and on most
of the property to the Wetlands America Trust.
</P>
<P>
   Legendre began her wartime career as a secretary with the OSS in
Washington. But within a year, in 1944, the agency transferred her
to Paris and gave her a WAC uniform and paperwork identifying her
as a second lieutenant.
</P>
<P>
   She became the first American woman captured in France when, on
a visit to the front northeast of Paris with several military
friends, she found herself pinned down by German sniper fire and
was forced to surrender.
</P>
<P>
   Held as a prisoner of war for six months, she then escaped and
made her way by train to Switzerland. The train stopped just short
of the border, and, as she made a frantic dash to the frontier, a
German guard ordered her to halt or be shot. She continued, though,
and reached the border.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Legendre helped a German prison guard who had
been kind to her emigrate to the United States. She also
established the Medway Plan, a relief organization, to provide
medical help and drugs to countries devastated by the war.
</P>
<P>
   Legendre was born in 1902 in Aiken, S.C., the youngest of three
children of John and Ethel Sanford. She, her brother, Stephen
Sanford, an internationally recognized polo player known as Laddie,
and her sister, Sara Jane Sanford, were said to have been the
inspiration for Philip Barry's 1929 play ``Holiday,'' made into a
classic movie starring Katharine Hepburn and Cary Grant. She wrote
two autobiographies, ``The Sands Ceased to Run'' (1947) and ``The
Time of My Life'' (1987).
</P>
<P>
   Legendre was reared in upstate Amsterdam, N.Y., where her father
managed the family carpet business and his horse-breeding farm, and
in a Manhattan town house on East 72nd Street now occupied by the
Lycee Francais. She was educated at the Foxcroft School in
Middleburg, Va., and made her debut after her graduation in 1920.
</P>
<P>
   She met her husband, Sidney J. Legendre, on one of her big-game
hunting trips to Africa. They married in 1929. He died in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   Legendre is survived by two daughters, Bokara Legendre of
Manhattan and Mill Valley, Calif., and Landine Manigault of
Stonington, Conn.; four grandchildren, and three
great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Known as one of the grand dames of Charleston, Legendre gave a
New Year's Eve costume party that was a tradition for half a
century. At one of the last of those parties, she offered a toast:
``I look ahead. I always have. I don't contemplate life, I live it.
And I'm having the time of my life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-11-00 2352EST &QL; 
