A4468 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-USC-LADN     03-11 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC WINS, HOPES FOR NIT BERTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They won't be huddled around a television set
watching the NCAA Tournament Selection Sunday show at Heritage
Hall, but the USC basketball team will have its own waiting game
today.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans will be anxiously awaiting a phone call tonight,
which is the unglamorous, low-tech approach necessary for teams
eager to make the National Invitation Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to get a call on Sunday, because I still have
an unfinished taste in my mouth,'' USC forward Brian Scalabrine
said. ``The season's over, but I want to keep on playing. It looks
like we'll get in, but you never know.''
</P>
<P>
   At least the Trojans feel they did their part to make the
tournament, after routing Washington State, 82-63, before 3,350 at
the Sports Arena on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   USC (16-14, 9-9) believed it needed two commanding victories
this week to make the NIT, but won't find out until tonight if it
was right.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's out of our hands now. We've done what we can do and we'll
take it from there,'' USC coach Henry Bibby said. ``I thought the
deciding factor was getting Sam Clancy back (the past four games)
and winning a couple games decisively. Hopefully, (his return) is
part of the attention we will get when they start to decide who
makes it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the team knew what we had to do for us to get in the
NIT. We had to win convincingly.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans certainly did that, opening a 30-11 lead over the
hapless Cougars (6-22, 1-17) in the first half and basically
coasting to victory. Jeff Trepagnier had 20 points, six rebounds
and four steals while David Bluthenthal added 18 points and 13
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to win by more than normal because they were 1-16,''
Trepagnier said. ``We had to beat them big.''
</P>
<P>
   For Bluthenthal, there was an added bonus to an otherwise
unremarkable game. He finished the season as the Pacific-10
Conference's leading rebounder with 9.9 per contest.
</P>
<P>
   Bluthenthal knew he needed eight rebounds to surpass Stanford's
Mark Madsen, and played all 40 minutes just to make sure. He was
actually disappointed, however, because he just missed averaging 10
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really trying to get one last rebound,'' Bluthenthal
said. ``I was so close.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Bluthenthal's chase for the rebounding title, though,
the only locker room topic was the NIT.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be a little disappointing if we don't get in,''
Trepagnier said. ``If we don't get in, we did it to ourselves.
Hopefully, we did get in. We're pretty confident.''
</P>
<P>
   The return of Clancy from a broken right foot has boosted the
confidence of the Trojans, who believe they could reach the
semifinals in Madison Square Garden if they play in the NIT.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a complete team again,'' Bluthenthal said. ``With Sam
back, there's no reason we can't get to New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Clancy's presence might also make the Trojans yearn for a Pac-10
Tournament, which the conference discontinued in 1990. They are
finally close to being healthy, for the first time since late
January, which is when they were tied for first place with a 6-1
record.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had a conference tournament, it would be great,''
Trepagnier said. ``In the Pac-10, anybody can get beat. That would
be fun. With Sam back, everything goes good. He gives us a spark
off the bench.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: USC coach Henry Bibby said that injured senior forward
Jarvis Turner (broken left ankle), who was honored before the game,
is unlikely to return for at least two more weeks, meaning his
career is probably over.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's at least two weeks away until he starts running again,''
Bibby said.
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Brandon Granville has 248 assists, which is the
third-best single-season mark in Pac-10 history.
</P>
